⸻

1) Strip / Timeline / Pointer bucket

Use when the problem lives on a single sequence.

Brute Force Method

Usually:
	•	try every start/end
	•	compare every pair
	•	scan repeatedly
	•	rebuild every candidate segment

BF Complexity Vis.

The visual metaphor is:
	•	too many windows
	•	too many pair lines
	•	repeated rescans of the same strip

How to Draw BF

Draw one long array/string strip, then:
	•	draw every possible subarray as brackets
	•	or draw many pair connections
	•	or restart a scan from each index

This should look crowded on purpose.

Optimised Pattern

Usually becomes:
	•	Two Pointers
	•	Sliding Window
	•	Binary Search on array
	•	One Pass Scan
	•	Prefix/Suffix scan
	•	Partition logic

Opt Vis. Technique

The metaphor is:
	•	“don’t restart”
	•	“carry a moving boundary”
	•	“one sweep with live markers”
	•	“shrink only when invalid”

Dry Run (Opt)

Show time as frames:
	•	frame 1: L=0, R=0
	•	frame 2: expand R
	•	frame 3: constraint breaks
	•	frame 4: move L
	•	frame 5: answer updates

How to Draw (Opt)

Draw:
	•	one strip
	•	2–3 markers max
	•	shaded active region
	•	one small note for validity

Best template:
	•	indices below
	•	pointers above
	•	current answer box on side

Opt Complexity Vis.

Visual metaphor:
	•	one sweep line
	•	each pointer moves at most once
	•	no restarting from scratch

Draw Opt Complexity

Draw the strip and underneath it:
	•	one arrow for R
	•	one arrow for L
	•	note that each only moves forward

That proves O(n).

Mem Vis (BF)

Memory picture:
	•	lots of saved substrings/subarrays
	•	many temporary candidate copies
	•	repeated local states

Mem Vis (Opt)

Memory picture:
	•	only pointers
	•	maybe one map/set beside strip
	•	constant or linear helper memory only

⸻

2) Lookup-table / Bucket bucket

Use when the algorithm remembers facts.

Brute Force Method

Usually:
	•	compare current value against all previous values
	•	count by rescanning whole input
	•	regroup repeatedly
	•	search linearly for matches

BF Complexity Vis.

The metaphor is:
	•	every element asks the whole array a question
	•	repeated global rescans
	•	same facts rediscovered again and again

How to Draw BF

Draw:
	•	input strip on left
	•	many repeated search arrows across the strip
	•	no external memory board yet

It should feel wasteful.

Optimised Pattern

Usually:
	•	Hash Map
	•	Hash Set
	•	Frequency Table
	•	Bucketization
	•	Canonical Signature Map

Opt Vis. Technique

The metaphor is:
	•	“store once, reuse forever”
	•	“turn searching into direct lookup”
	•	“remember counts instead of recomputing”

Dry Run (Opt)

Show:
	•	current value enters
	•	arrow into map/set bucket
	•	lookup succeeds or fails
	•	count updates

How to Draw (Opt)

Best template:
	•	source strip on left
	•	map/bucket table on right
	•	current element highlighted
	•	one arrow into key bucket
	•	optional result/complement box

Opt Complexity Vis.

Metaphor:
	•	one pass through input
	•	one constant-time board lookup per step

Draw Opt Complexity

Draw:
	•	one stream of elements entering the board
	•	each step touches one bucket
	•	no full rescans

Mem Vis (BF)

Memory picture:
	•	little or no explicit helper memory
	•	but hidden repeated work everywhere

Mem Vis (Opt)

Memory picture:
	•	visible side table
	•	keys and counts/indexes
	•	cost becomes explicit and controlled

⸻

3) Grid / Board bucket

Use when position in 2D matters.

Brute Force Method

Usually:
	•	start search from many cells
	•	explore paths repeatedly
	•	check rows/cols/regions over and over
	•	recursive explosion on board states

BF Complexity Vis.

Metaphor:
	•	branches spreading everywhere
	•	many overlapping path trees
	•	same cells revisited repeatedly

How to Draw BF

Draw:
	•	full board
	•	many branching arrows from multiple starts
	•	repeated cell visits
	•	cluttered path overlays

Optimised Pattern

Usually:
	•	BFS on grid
	•	DFS flood fill
	•	2D DP
	•	mark visited
	•	row/column precompute

Opt Vis. Technique

The metaphor is:
	•	“paint each cell once”
	•	“frontier expands layer by layer”
	•	“reuse solved neighbors”
	•	“mark and never come back”

Dry Run (Opt)

Show:
	•	current cell/frontier
	•	next neighbors
	•	visited marks appear
	•	dp value fills into next cell

How to Draw (Opt)

Best template:
	•	clean board
	•	blocked cells marked
	•	current layer or current cell highlighted
	•	only essential arrows shown

Opt Complexity Vis.

Metaphor:
	•	each cell touched once
	•	or each transition processed once
	•	no repeated boardwide restarts

Draw Opt Complexity

Draw the board with:
	•	one pass wavefront
	•	each cell numbered once
	•	note m x n cells

Mem Vis (BF)

Memory picture:
	•	many recursive branches
	•	path copies
	•	repeated call stacks

Mem Vis (Opt)

Memory picture:
	•	visited matrix
	•	queue/stack frontier
	•	DP table if needed
	•	one explicit board-sized helper state

⸻

4) Node-link / Tree-list-trie bucket

Use when the structure is linked.

Brute Force Method

Usually:
	•	rebuild paths repeatedly
	•	convert structure into arrays
	•	compare subtrees/list segments again and again
	•	recurse without caching

BF Complexity Vis.

Metaphor:
	•	branching recursion tree
	•	repeated subtree work
	•	pointer chasing without organization

How to Draw BF

Draw:
	•	full linked structure
	•	many recursive branches
	•	repeated highlighted subtrees
	•	duplicated paths

Optimised Pattern

Usually:
	•	Linked List pointer rewiring
	•	Tree DFS
	•	Tree DP
	•	Trie traversal
	•	Postorder aggregation
	•	Dummy node logic

Opt Vis. Technique

The metaphor is:
	•	“carry local pointers”
	•	“solve children, combine upward”
	•	“reuse shared prefix path”
	•	“rewire instead of rebuilding”

Dry Run (Opt)

Show:
	•	one pointer move or one recursive return at a time
	•	current node
	•	child answers returning upward
	•	list links changing shape

How to Draw (Opt)

Best template:
	•	3–5 visible nodes only
	•	one current node
	•	one or two active links
	•	dummy/head/tail marked clearly

Opt Complexity Vis.

Metaphor:
	•	each node visited once
	•	each edge traversed once
	•	one downward/upward pass

Draw Opt Complexity

Draw:
	•	tree/list with each node checked once
	•	arrows only on active traversal path
	•	note n nodes, one visit each

Mem Vis (BF)

Memory picture:
	•	repeated subtree copies
	•	deep uncontrolled recursion
	•	extra rebuilt arrays/lists

Mem Vis (Opt)

Memory picture:
	•	recursion stack only
	•	small pointer set
	•	trie nodes or DP memo if explicit

