1. First-pass triage heuristics

1.1 Ignore the story

Translate the prompt into pure math/data.
	•	“rob houses” → max sum with adjacency constraint
	•	“robot on grid” → grid traversal / shortest path / DP
	•	“accounts merging” → connectivity / grouping
	•	“banana speed” → monotonic feasibility / answer-space search

1.2 Read constraints before pattern selection

Constraints eliminate bad engines first.
	•	n <= 20 → backtracking / subset search / bitmask often allowed
	•	n <= 10^2 or 10^3 → O(n^2) / O(n^3) may be acceptable
	•	n ~= 10^4 to 10^5 → usually need O(n) or O(n log n)
	•	n huge / answer range huge → binary search, math, formula, logarithmic methods
	•	graph with large V, E → think O(V + E) traversals, not repeated rescans

1.3 Ask what the output is

The return type is a clue.
	•	boolean/existence → hashing, search, invariant checking
	•	count of ways → DP, combinatorics, counting
	•	minimum/maximum value → DP, greedy, binary search on answer
	•	actual path/order/list of solutions → DFS/backtracking/BFS with parent tracking
	•	top K → heap / bucket sort / quickselect
	•	grouped result → hash map / sorting / union-find / SQL group by

