MAKE IN DEPTH


Yes — here is the in-depth version.

What you asked for is not just a list of pattern hints.
It is a full heuristic operating system for reading, classifying, solving, debugging, and explaining LeetCode problems.

The right way to understand heuristics is:
	•	they are not proofs
	•	they are not pattern tags
	•	they are not guarantees
	•	they are decision shortcuts under uncertainty

A strong solver uses heuristics in layers:
	•	first to eliminate bad approaches,
	•	then to rank likely engines,
	•	then to define state/invariant,
	•	then to verify the choice by brute force and complexity.

⸻

1. What a heuristic really is

A heuristic is a rule like:

“If the problem says shortest path in an unweighted graph, try BFS first.”

That does not mean BFS is always right.
It means BFS is the highest-priority first suspect.

So every heuristic has 4 parts:

Signal

The clue in the prompt.

Suspicion

The pattern it points toward.

Reason

Why that pattern fits.

Failure mode

When that clue is misleading.

That is the correct way to use heuristics.

⸻

2. The master solving stack

When you open a new problem, run this sequence:

Layer 1 — Translation

Convert story into structure.

Ask:
	•	What is the input really?
	•	What is the output really?
	•	What is the hidden math version of the story?

Example:
	•	“Thief robbing houses” → max sum over array with no adjacent picks
	•	“Rotting oranges” → multi-source shortest-time spread on grid
	•	“Koko eating bananas” → monotone feasibility over integer answer range

⸻

Layer 2 — Budget

Read constraints and eliminate impossible runtimes.

Ask:
	•	What is the largest input size?
	•	What time complexity is even affordable?
	•	Is exponential allowed?
	•	Is quadratic acceptable?
	•	Is one pass expected?

This is the first hard filter.

⸻

Layer 3 — Shape

Identify the data world.

Ask:
	•	Is it linear?
	•	Is it branching?
	•	Is it spatial?
	•	Is it relational?
	•	Is it implicit state space?
	•	Is it pure math?

This narrows the available engines.

⸻

Layer 4 — Goal

Identify the task type.

Ask:
	•	existence?
	•	counting?
	•	optimization?
	•	shortest path?
	•	all solutions?
	•	range queries?
	•	dynamic updates?
	•	ordering?

This narrows the engine family further.

⸻

Layer 5 — Brute force

State the naive solution explicitly.

Ask:
	•	What would the dumb complete search do?
	•	What repeated work makes it slow?
	•	What bottleneck dominates?

This reveals the correct direction of optimization.

⸻

Layer 6 — Engine choice

Pick the main pattern.

Ask:
	•	Which engine directly attacks the bottleneck?
	•	Which engine matches the data shape and budget?

⸻

Layer 7 — Variation

Choose the subtype.

Ask:
	•	fixed vs variable?
	•	single-source vs multi-source?
	•	exact search vs boundary vs answer-space?
	•	1D / 2D / tree / interval DP?

⸻

Layer 8 — Composite helper

Add supporting structures.

Ask:
	•	Do I need memory?
	•	ordering?
	•	counts?
	•	feasibility check?
	•	range structure?
	•	memoization?
	•	hashing?

⸻

Layer 9 — State and invariant

Formalize correctness.

Ask:
	•	what exactly is the current state?
	•	what must remain true after each step?
	•	what is updated?
	•	what is never violated?

⸻

Layer 10 — Physics

Compute cost.

Ask:
	•	what is the dominant loop/state/edge/query count?
	•	what is the memory footprint?
	•	is this within budget?

That is the full architecture.

⸻

3. Constraint heuristics in depth

Constraints are the strongest early heuristic because they eliminate impossible approaches before you get seduced by a clever-looking pattern.

If n <= 20

Strong prior:
	•	backtracking
	•	subset enumeration
	•	bitmask search
	•	exponential DP
	•	meet-in-the-middle sometimes

Why:
	•	2^20 or 20!-style search may still be barely feasible if pruned or partially compressed.

Failure mode:
	•	sometimes even n <= 20 hides a polynomial DP or math trick, so do not force brute force if structure is obvious.

⸻

If n <= 100

Possible:
	•	O(n^3)
	•	interval DP
	•	Floyd-Warshall
	•	dense graph reasoning
	•	matrix DP

Why:
	•	cubic may still be acceptable here.

Failure mode:
	•	if there are many test cases, cubic may still be too slow.

⸻

If n <= 1000

Possible:
	•	O(n^2)
	•	2D DP
	•	pair comparisons
	•	LIS DP
	•	graph traversals on moderate dense inputs

Why:
	•	one million-ish operations to a few million is often okay.

Failure mode:
	•	if inner logic is heavy or multiple dimensions multiply, this may break.

⸻

If n <= 10^5

Strong prior:
	•	O(n)
	•	O(n log n)
	•	hashing
	•	sliding window
	•	two pointers
	•	sort + sweep
	•	heap
	•	BFS/DFS on sparse structures

Why:
	•	brute-force pair loops die here.

Failure mode:
	•	occasionally O(n sqrt n) or heavy constants may still work; sometimes integer bounds allow math shortcuts.

⸻

If values are huge, but count of items is small

Do not confuse value range with input size.

Example:
	•	nums[i] up to 10^9 does not force logarithmic algorithms if n is only 10^4.
	•	But if the answer range is huge and monotone, answer-space binary search becomes attractive.

⸻

If graph says V, E

Use graph-native budgeting.
	•	BFS/DFS: O(V + E)
	•	Dijkstra: O((V + E) log V) typically
	•	repeated graph traversals are suspicious if E is large

⸻

4. Data-shape heuristics in depth

Data shape tells you what kinds of movement are natural.

Arrays / sequences

Natural movements:
	•	scan
	•	prefix accumulation
	•	local transitions
	•	left/right boundaries
	•	sorted pairing

Most likely engines:
	•	sliding window
	•	two pointers
	•	prefix sums
	•	hashing
	•	greedy
	•	DP
	•	binary search if sorted or monotone

False positive:
Many people overuse DP on arrays.
If the state is just a moving boundary or running memory, window/two-pointers/hash may be enough.

⸻

Strings

Strings are arrays plus symbol constraints.

Natural additions:
	•	frequency tables
	•	character counts
	•	parsing states
	•	prefix matching
	•	suffix/pattern matching

Likely engines:
	•	sliding window
	•	hash map / count array
	•	two pointers
	•	DP
	•	trie
	•	rolling hash / KMP / Z

False positive:
Not every substring problem is sliding window.
If nonlocal alignment matters, it may be DP.

⸻

Linked lists

The shape is not random access.
That changes everything.

Natural actions:
	•	chase pointers
	•	rewire next/prev
	•	split/merge
	•	reverse
	•	cycle detection

Likely engines:
	•	fast/slow pointers
	•	dummy node pointer work
	•	reversal
	•	stack if reverse order is needed

False positive:
Beginners often try to “convert to array” too early. That is legal sometimes, but often misses the intended in-place pointer logic.

⸻

Trees

Trees naturally suggest recursion because the structure is recursive.

Natural actions:
	•	descend
	•	aggregate upward
	•	process by depth
	•	search subtree
	•	compare left/right information

Likely engines:
	•	DFS
	•	BFS level order
	•	tree DP
	•	recursion + return value
	•	binary search only if BST or monotone property

False positive:
Not every tree problem is plain DFS; many are really DP on subtrees.

⸻

Graphs

The crucial heuristic is: are you solving connectivity, order, or distance?
	•	connectivity → DFS / BFS / union-find
	•	dependency order → topo sort
	•	unweighted shortest path → BFS
	•	weighted shortest path → Dijkstra / 0-1 BFS / advanced methods

False positive:
People overapply DFS to shortest path problems. DFS explores, but shortest path often needs BFS/Dijkstra.

⸻

Grids

A grid is often just a graph wearing a 2D costume.

Questions to ask:
	•	Are cells nodes?
	•	Are moves edges?
	•	Is the goal distance, region counting, or DP accumulation?

Likely engines:
	•	BFS
	•	DFS
	•	visited marking
	•	2D DP
	•	multi-source BFS

⸻

Intervals / coordinates

This shape is really about order on a line.

Likely engines:
	•	sorting + sweep
	•	greedy
	•	heap of active intervals
	•	binary search
	•	prefix difference arrays
	•	geometry transforms

Key question:

Is this about overlap, ordering, coverage, or nearest span?

⸻

SQL / relational

Here the shape is rows/columns, not loops and pointers.

Likely engines:
	•	join
	•	group by
	•	having
	•	window functions
	•	partition/rank
	•	filtering

Key question:

Are rows being matched, grouped, or ranked?

⸻

Object / design / API

The shape is hidden internal state.

Likely engines:
	•	map + linked list
	•	heap + map
	•	queue/stack simulation
	•	lazy state maintenance
	•	buffer reuse

Key question:

What internal state must survive across operations?

⸻

5. Goal heuristics in depth

The same input shape can produce very different engines depending on the goal.

Existence

“Does there exist…?”

Typical engines:
	•	hashing
	•	binary search
	•	DFS/BFS reachability
	•	invariant check
	•	set membership

Why:
Existence is often easier than optimization.

⸻

Count

“How many…?”

Typical engines:
	•	DP
	•	combinatorics
	•	counting map/array
	•	prefix-state counting
	•	graph traversal counting components

Why:
Counts often require accumulation over states.

⸻

Optimization

“Maximum”, “minimum”, “best”, “least”.

Typical engines:
	•	DP
	•	greedy
	•	binary search on answer
	•	heap
	•	shortest path

Key heuristic:
Optimization questions split into:
	•	directly construct optimum
	•	search feasible threshold
	•	accumulate best subproblem answer

⸻

Enumerate all answers

“All valid combinations”, “return every path”.

Typical engines:
	•	backtracking
	•	DFS
	•	recursion with undo
	•	pruning

⸻

Ordering / ranking

“Top K”, “kth”, “smallest/largest among changing values”.

Typical engines:
	•	heap
	•	quickselect
	•	sorting
	•	window ranking / SQL window functions

⸻

6. Brute-force heuristics in depth

Brute force is not a waste. It is diagnostic.

A strong solver asks:

What would brute force do?

Examples:
	•	check all subarrays
	•	try all subsets
	•	compare every pair
	•	explore all paths
	•	recompute every range
	•	recurse every choice

Why is it too slow?

Common bottlenecks:
	•	repeated rescans
	•	repeated subproblems
	•	repeated best-element search
	•	repeated connectivity tests
	•	repeated range queries
	•	repeated validity checks

What structure kills the repetition?

This is the optimization leap:
	•	repeated rescans → prefix sum / hashing / preprocessing
	•	repeated subproblems → memo / DP
	•	repeated min/max → heap / monotonic structure
	•	repeated boundary search → binary search / monotonic stack
	•	repeated membership checks → set/map
	•	repeated connectivity merges → DSU

That is the real heuristic:
optimized solutions are reactions to brute-force waste.

⸻

7. Pattern heuristics in depth

Sliding window

Strong signals
	•	contiguous region
	•	longest/shortest valid substring/subarray
	•	target condition based on current contents
	•	left/right can both move only forward

Deep requirement

Window state must be incrementally maintainable.

That means:
	•	adding rightmost element is easy
	•	removing leftmost element is easy
	•	validity can be tested from maintained state

Failure mode

If removing the leftmost item destroys information you cannot update cheaply, plain sliding window may fail.

⸻

Two pointers

Strong signals
	•	sorted input
	•	pair/triple conditions
	•	compare from both ends
	•	merge two ordered sequences
	•	in-place compaction
	•	linked list slow/fast

Deep principle

Pointer motion itself encodes progress.

Failure mode

If no monotone relationship justifies pointer moves, two pointers can become guesswork.

⸻

Prefix sum

Strong signals
	•	many range sums
	•	cumulative balance
	•	subarray condition transformable into prefix relation
	•	parity / remainder / difference tracking

Deep principle

Move work from query time to preprocessing time.

Failure mode

Prefix sum alone is not enough under updates; then you need BIT/segment tree.

⸻

Binary search

Strong signals
	•	sorted data
	•	boundary where false becomes true
	•	minimum feasible / maximum feasible
	•	monotone property over answers

Deep principle

You are not searching values; you are searching an ordered decision boundary.

Failure mode

No monotonicity = no binary search.

⸻

BFS

Strong signals
	•	shortest path in unweighted state graph
	•	nearest target
	•	minimum steps
	•	layer expansion
	•	simultaneous spreading processes

Deep principle

BFS proves minimal step count because it explores by distance layers.

Failure mode

Weighted edges break plain BFS.

⸻

DFS

Strong signals
	•	component exploration
	•	subtree logic
	•	path existence
	•	recursive structure
	•	all-paths baseline

Deep principle

Go deep, return with information.

Failure mode

DFS is often the wrong choice when nearest/shortest is required.

⸻

Backtracking

Strong signals
	•	all configurations
	•	place/choose/undo
	•	constraints prune invalid states
	•	solution space is a choice tree

Deep principle

Backtracking is DFS + reversible state mutations.

Failure mode

Using backtracking without strong constraints or pruning when n is large.

⸻

DP

Strong signals
	•	repeated recursion
	•	best/count over structured choices
	•	overlapping subproblems
	•	state compression possible
	•	sequential or structured dependency graph

Deep principle

Name the repeated state and solve it once.

Failure mode

Using DP when greedy or direct math already collapses the problem.

⸻

Greedy

Strong signals
	•	locally best action looks globally safe
	•	ordering transforms problem
	•	proof via exchange argument or invariant seems natural

Deep principle

Greedy is not about speed; it is about correctness under local choice.

Failure mode

Picking greedy because it “feels intuitive” without proof.

⸻

Heap

Strong signals
	•	repeated top-k
	•	dynamic minimum/maximum
	•	scheduling with changing candidates
	•	best-first expansion

Deep principle

You need the best active item many times, not just once.

Failure mode

If you only need one final sort, a heap may be unnecessary.

⸻

Monotonic stack

Strong signals
	•	next greater/smaller
	•	nearest boundary with order constraint
	•	histogram/temperature/span type problems

Deep principle

Maintain ordered candidates so each element enters/leaves once.

Failure mode

Using stack when no nearest-boundary relation exists.

⸻

Union-find

Strong signals
	•	repeated merges
	•	component counting
	•	connectivity under added edges
	•	equivalence/grouping

Deep principle

Path discovery is irrelevant; only connectedness matters.

Failure mode

If actual paths/weights/orders matter, DSU is insufficient.

⸻

8. Variation heuristics in depth

Variation is where many learners get stuck.

They recognize the family but not the subtype.

Sliding window variations
	•	fixed-size: exact k
	•	variable-size: satisfy condition while shrinking/growing
	•	variable-size + frequency: maintain counts of symbols
	•	at-most K / exactly K: often convert exactly K into at-most K trick

Binary search variations
	•	exact target
	•	first/last occurrence
	•	lower/upper bound
	•	rotated array logic
	•	answer-space search
	•	partition-based search

BFS variations
	•	single-source
	•	multi-source
	•	bidirectional
	•	0-1 BFS
	•	implicit-state BFS

DP variations
	•	1D sequence DP
	•	2D grid/string DP
	•	interval DP
	•	tree DP
	•	bitmask DP
	•	digit DP
	•	memoized DFS vs tabulation

Greedy variations
	•	local-choice greedy
	•	sort-then-greedy
	•	heap-assisted greedy
	•	constructive greedy
	•	greedy feasibility inside binary search

Heuristic:
first identify the family, then ask what subtype of movement/state the problem requires.

⸻

9. Composite heuristics in depth

Hard problems are often composites.

Common composite patterns

Sliding window + hash map

For substrings with frequency/distinctness constraints.

Prefix sum + hash map

For subarray sums / balances / remainders.

Binary search + greedy check

For minimum feasible capacity/speed/threshold.

DFS + memoization

For recursive search with repeated states.

DP + bitmask

For subset-state optimization.

Greedy + sorting

When order creates safe local choices.

Hash map + heap

For top-k frequency or dynamic best-by-key.

Tree DFS + prefix accumulation

For path sum and ancestor-dependent queries.

BFS + visited set/state compression

For implicit-state shortest path problems.

Heuristic:
If one pattern gets you close but cannot maintain validity/efficiency alone, add the missing helper.

⸻

10. Canonical-link heuristics in depth

Canonical links are memory anchors.

They answer:

“What known prototype is this a mutation of?”

This is extremely important because broad labels like “DP” are too vague.

Examples:
	•	House Robber II → mutation of House Robber
	•	Minimum Window Substring → mutation of variable-size frequency window
	•	Partition Equal Subset Sum → mutation of knapsack
	•	01 Matrix → mutation of multi-source BFS
	•	Target Sum → mutation of subset-sum counting DP
	•	Top K Frequent Elements → mutation of count + heap selection

Heuristic:
always try to connect a new problem to a known ancestor, not just a broad family.

⸻

11. State heuristics in depth

A state is the minimum information that determines future behavior.

Good state:
	•	small
	•	sufficient
	•	non-redundant
	•	transition-friendly

Examples:
	•	dp[i]
	•	dp[i][j]
	•	(node, mask)
	•	(index, remaining_sum)
	•	(left, right)
	•	(node, parent)
	•	(i, used_mask, carry)

Bad state:
	•	too much history
	•	duplicated information
	•	vague “current situation” descriptions

Heuristic:
if you cannot write the state in one sentence, you do not yet understand the solution.

⸻

12. Invariant heuristics in depth

The invariant is the correctness backbone.

Examples:
	•	window is always valid after shrinking
	•	stack is monotonic
	•	all elements before i are settled
	•	heap top is the best active candidate
	•	BFS queue contains current frontier in nondecreasing distance
	•	DP transitions only use solved states

Heuristic:
before coding a loop, state what remains true every time the loop header is reached.

This is one of the strongest debugging tools you have.

⸻

13. Complexity heuristics in depth

Do not just label complexity after coding. Use it to design the solution.

Ask:
	•	What is the unit being processed?
	•	How many times can each unit move/enter/leave?
	•	Is there a nested structure?
	•	Is there sorting?
	•	Is there a state table?
	•	Are transitions per state constant or expensive?

Examples:
	•	sliding window: each pointer moves at most n times → O(n)
	•	monotonic stack: each element pushed and popped once → O(n)
	•	BFS/DFS: each node/edge bounded visits → O(V+E)
	•	DP: states × transitions
	•	binary search on answer: O(check_cost * log answer_range)

Heuristic:
derive complexity from movement/state counts, not from surface syntax alone.

⸻

14. Memory heuristics in depth

A lot of solutions fail not on time, but on hidden memory decisions.

Ask:
	•	Am I storing full paths unnecessarily?
	•	Can I store summaries instead?
	•	Can I mutate in place?
	•	Is recursion depth safe?
	•	Is memo table too large?
	•	Is copying strings/vectors causing hidden blowup?

Common memory upgrades:
	•	full DP table → rolling arrays
	•	storing strings → store indices or signatures
	•	storing whole paths → store parent pointers
	•	repeated object copies → use references/iterators carefully

Heuristic:
explicit memory is often cheaper than repeated recomputation, but uncontrolled memory kills scalability.

⸻

15. Ambiguity-resolution heuristics

Sometimes multiple patterns fit. Resolve conflict like this:

Case: Sliding window vs prefix sum
	•	contiguous + dynamic validity → sliding window
	•	many static range totals / prefix-difference relation → prefix sum

Case: DFS vs BFS
	•	any path / component / subtree → DFS
	•	shortest steps / nearest layer → BFS

Case: DP vs greedy
	•	if local choice needs proof and future tradeoff exists, suspect DP
	•	if sorted/local decision can be proven safe, greedy may win

Case: binary search vs two pointers
	•	sorted pair scanning with monotone pointer moves → two pointers
	•	boundary/target/feasible threshold search → binary search

Case: hash map vs sorting
	•	need instant lookup / counts / preserve unsorted relation → hash map
	•	need global order / interval merge / greedy proof → sort

This is important:
pattern selection is often comparative, not absolute.

⸻

16. Failure-mode heuristics

Each pattern has signature traps.

Sliding window traps
	•	exact-K vs at-most-K confusion
	•	forgetting to remove left contribution
	•	using it when validity is not incrementally maintainable

Binary search traps
	•	wrong monotonicity assumption
	•	off-by-one in boundaries
	•	stopping too early on boundary search

DFS traps
	•	revisiting nodes
	•	stack overflow
	•	forgetting parent/visited logic

BFS traps
	•	marking visited too late
	•	using BFS on weighted graphs incorrectly
	•	forgetting layer semantics

DP traps
	•	wrong state definition
	•	base cases incomplete
	•	fill order invalid
	•	transition double counting

Greedy traps
	•	intuitive but unproven local choice
	•	counterexamples lurking

Heap traps
	•	forgetting lazy deletion issues
	•	using heap when sorted list or monotonic structure is enough

⸻

17. Debugging heuristics

When stuck, do this:

Step 1

Make the smallest nontrivial example.

Step 2

Solve it manually.

Step 3

Track what your brain is really doing.

Step 4

Write the state.

Step 5

Write the invariant.

Step 6

Dry run line by line.

A huge number of algorithm bugs are not syntax bugs.
They are:
	•	wrong state
	•	broken invariant
	•	bad boundary conditions
	•	wrong variation choice

⸻

