5. The state-invariant model

This is the most important advanced layer.

A lot of people can say:
	•	“this is DP”
	•	“this is sliding window”
	•	“this is DFS”

But the real line between beginner and advanced is:

Can you state the state and the invariant precisely?

State

The minimum information that determines future behavior.

Good examples:
	•	left, right, char_count
	•	dp[i]
	•	dp[i][j]
	•	node, parent
	•	node, used_mask
	•	prefix_sum_so_far
	•	current_min, current_max

Bad state:
	•	vague descriptions like “the current setup”
	•	redundant history
	•	unnecessary full-path storage

Invariant

The unbreakable rule that remains true each loop / recursive layer.

Examples:
	•	the current window is valid
	•	all items before i are finalized
	•	the stack remains monotonic
	•	the heap top is the best active candidate
	•	all DP dependencies for this state are already solved
	•	the queue contains nodes in nondecreasing distance
	•	union-find parent links represent the current components

That is the real correctness framework.

If you can write:
	•	the state,
	•	the transition,
	•	the invariant,

you usually already know the solution.

