	•	“The optimized solution processes window boundaries, each pointer moves at most N times.”
	•	“The optimized solution processes candidate answers, there are log(range) guesses, and each guess runs a linear checker.”
	•	“The optimized solution processes DP states, each state is computed once with constant transitions.”
	•	“The optimized solution processes heap operations, each insert/remove touches only a log-height path.”

Now underline the proof shape:
	•	one sweep
	•	monotone pointer movement
	•	constant work per item
	•	sort then cheap scan
	•	halving
	•	checker × halving
	•	one visit per structural unit
	•	states × transitions
	•	push once / pop once
	•	log-height maintenance
	•	preprocess once / query many
	•	local-touch object update

That proof shape chooses the bucket.

⸻

The master decision tree

Q1. Is the runtime proved by one forward pass over units?

Clues:
	•	one scan
	•	one traversal over the input
	•	one pass
	•	single sweep
	•	no restart
	•	each element processed once

Yes

Go to Q1a.

Q1a. Is it literally just one straight pass, with no tricky amortization?

Yes
Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 1 — Single Linear Sweep

Proof shape
	•	one line
	•	one arrow
	•	one conveyor

Complexity style
	•	O(N)
	•	O(M+N)

Best for
	•	one-pass scans
	•	simple counting
	•	prefix/suffix precompute
	•	direct greedy scans

Runtime sentence

“Each unit is processed once in one sweep.”

⸻

No — there are multiple markers/boundaries moving

Go to Q1b.

Q1b. Are the boundaries/pointers monotone?

Clues:
	•	L and R
	•	expand/shrink
	•	inward pinch
	•	each pointer never resets backward

Yes
Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 2 — Bounded Pointer Movement / Amortized Window

Proof shape
	•	strip
	•	two arrows
	•	each arrow moves at most N times

Complexity style
	•	amortized O(N)

Best for
	•	sliding window
	•	two pointers
	•	merge pointer sweeps
	•	some deque/window methods

Runtime sentence

“Even though there are two loops conceptually, each pointer only advances a bounded number of times.”

⸻

Q2. Is the runtime basically one scan plus constant-time helper work?

Clues:
	•	hash map lookup/update per item
	•	set membership per item
	•	O(1)-ish frequency update per step
	•	current pass + tiny side operation

Yes

Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 3 — Linear Sweep + Constant-Time Side Operation

Proof shape
	•	main horizontal scan
	•	tiny side-box per step

Complexity style
	•	O(N)
	•	linear with constant helper work

Best for
	•	hash map / set scans
	•	frequency counting
	•	prefix-state hashing
	•	direct lookup problems

Runtime sentence

“Each unit is scanned once, and each step performs only constant helper work.”

⸻

Q3. Is there a one-time sort that dominates, followed by cheap work?

Clues:
	•	sort first
	•	then sweep/merge/check once
	•	post-sort logic is linear or near-linear

Yes

Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 4 — Sort Once, Then Sweep

Proof shape
	•	big sort box
	•	small linear arrow after it

Complexity style
	•	O(N log N)

Best for
	•	interval merge
	•	sort-then-greedy
	•	two pointers on sorted input
	•	ranking/order problems

Runtime sentence

“The expensive part is ordering once; everything afterward is cheap.”

⸻

Q4. Is the runtime proved by repeated halving?

Clues:
	•	binary search
	•	lower/upper bound
	•	halve the search interval
	•	logarithmic search space shrink

Yes

Go to Q4a.

Q4a. Is it just searching a sorted/ordered space directly?

Yes
Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 5 — Logarithmic Halving

Proof shape
	•	shrinking interval blocks
	•	N, N/2, N/4, ...

Complexity style
	•	O(log N)
	•	O(log range)

Best for
	•	standard binary search
	•	boundary search
	•	logarithmic lookup in ordered structures

Runtime sentence

“Each step halves the remaining search space.”

⸻

No — each guess runs a checker

Yes
Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 6 — Halving + Feasibility Checker

Proof shape
	•	halving blocks on top
	•	linear/greedy/check bar under each guess

Complexity style
	•	O(check_cost × log range)

Best for
	•	answer-space binary search
	•	Koko-type problems
	•	minimize maximum / maximize minimum
	•	threshold feasibility problems

Runtime sentence

“There are logarithmically many guesses, and each guess runs a bounded checker.”

⸻

Q5. Is the runtime proved by one visit per structural unit?

Clues:
	•	visit each node once
	•	process each edge once
	•	mark each cell once
	•	traversal with visited/finalized semantics

Yes

Go to Q5a.

Q5a. Is the structure a tree, graph, or grid, and the proof is literally bounded visits?

Yes
Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 7 — One Visit per Node / Edge / Cell

Proof shape
	•	check-marked nodes/cells
	•	traversal wave
	•	edge touches bounded

Complexity style
	•	O(N) for trees
	•	O(V+E) for graphs
	•	O(MN) for grids

Best for
	•	DFS/BFS
	•	flood fill
	•	tree traversals
	•	graph traversal
	•	component counting

Runtime sentence

“Each structural unit is finalized or visited only a bounded number of times.”

⸻

Q6. Is the runtime proved by states × transitions?

Clues:
	•	DP
	•	memoization collapsed to unique states
	•	recurrence
	•	fill each cell/state once
	•	bounded predecessors/transitions

Yes

Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 8 — State Count × Transition Count

Proof shape
	•	DP table/grid
	•	arrows into each state
	•	“solve once” emphasis

Complexity style
	•	O(states × transitions)
	•	examples: O(N), O(MN), O(N^2), O(2^N × N)

Best for
	•	1D DP
	•	2D DP
	•	edit distance
	•	interval DP
	•	tree DP
	•	memoized DFS
	•	bitmask DP

Runtime sentence

“The runtime is the number of unique states times the work per state.”

⸻

Q7. Is the runtime proved by amortized push/pop lifetime?

Clues:
	•	monotonic stack
	•	deque
	•	inner while loop that looks scary
	•	push once, pop once
	•	lazy transfer between containers

Yes

Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 9 — Amortized Push-Once / Pop-Once

Proof shape
	•	elements entering a stack/deque
	•	each element tagged with one entry and one exit

Complexity style
	•	amortized O(N)

Best for
	•	monotonic stack
	•	monotonic deque
	•	stack-based simplification
	•	lazy-transfer queue/stack tricks

Runtime sentence

“Each unit may trigger pops, but every unit itself can only be pushed and popped a bounded number of times.”

⸻

Q8. Is the runtime proved by log-height ordered maintenance?

Clues:
	•	heap
	•	balanced tree
	•	priority queue
	•	ordered set/map
	•	insert/delete/extract-min on a tree-like structure

Yes

Go to Q8a.

Q8a. Is the main cost one operation touching only a log-height path?

Yes
Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 10 — Log-Height Ordered Structure

Proof shape
	•	heap tree / ordered tree
	•	one root-to-leaf or leaf-to-root path highlighted

Complexity style
	•	O(log N) per operation
	•	total often O(N log N) or (V+E) log V

Best for
	•	heap problems
	•	Dijkstra
	•	top-K selection with heap
	•	active interval heaps
	•	ordered map/set maintenance

Runtime sentence

“Each update/query touches only the height of the ordered structure, not the whole structure.”

⸻

Q9. Is the runtime proved by a range hierarchy or powers-of-two decomposition?

Clues:
	•	segment tree
	•	Fenwick tree
	•	sparse table
	•	binary lifting
	•	query decomposes into blocks
	•	jump by 2^k

Yes

Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 11 — Hierarchical Range / Jump Decomposition

Proof shape
	•	interval tree
	•	block hierarchy
	•	powers-of-two ladder
	•	few blocks covering a range

Complexity style
	•	O(log N) per query/update
	•	O(N log N) preprocess sometimes
	•	O(1) sparse-table query after preprocess sometimes

Best for
	•	segment tree
	•	BIT/Fenwick
	•	sparse table
	•	binary lifting / LCA

Runtime sentence

“The raw range/path is replaced by a small number of summarized blocks or jumps.”

⸻

Q10. Is the runtime proved by preprocess once, then answer many cheaply?

Clues:
	•	build prefix sums once
	•	precompute first/last positions
	•	build index/summary table
	•	many queries after setup
	•	query time much smaller than build time

Yes

Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 12 — Preprocess Once, Query Many

Proof shape
	•	one large preprocessing box
	•	many small query arrows afterward

Complexity style
	•	build O(N) / O(N log N)
	•	query O(1) / O(log N)

Best for
	•	prefix sums
	•	lookup precomputation
	•	sparse tables
	•	indexed query systems
	•	repeated question-answer settings

Runtime sentence

“Pay the heavy cost once, then amortize it over many cheap queries.”

⸻

Q11. Is the runtime proved by constant-state arithmetic/invariant maintenance?

Clues:
	•	small scalar state only
	•	carry
	•	xor/parity
	•	direct formula
	•	per-digit or per-item accumulator
	•	no large side structures

Yes

Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 13 — Constant-State Formula / Invariant Update

Proof shape
	•	small variable boxes
	•	simple per-step update
	•	no expanding structure

Complexity style
	•	O(N) over items
	•	O(log N) over digits/bits
	•	sometimes O(1)

Best for
	•	arithmetic digit problems
	•	xor/parity
	•	running min/max invariants
	•	direct formula scans

Runtime sentence

“The algorithm keeps only a tiny invariant and updates it directly per unit.”

⸻

Q12. Is the runtime proved by local-touch updates inside a persistent object/system?

Clues:
	•	design problem
	•	cache
	•	iterator
	•	API operations
	•	buffer leftovers
	•	internal map/list synchronization
	•	each call updates only small internal region

Yes

Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 14 — Local-Touch Object / Process Path

Proof shape
	•	object box
	•	internal sub-boxes
	•	one operation path through only affected components

Complexity style
	•	O(1) or O(log N) per operation
	•	amortized O(1) in buffered systems sometimes

Best for
	•	LRU/LFU
	•	Read4/buffer problems
	•	iterator wrappers
	•	stateful API design
	•	async/process state maintenance

Runtime sentence

“Each operation touches only a tiny local portion of the maintained internal state.”

⸻

Q13. Is the runtime proved by component compression / near-constant merge-find behavior?

Clues:
	•	union-find
	•	connectivity merges
	•	path compression
	•	repeated finds/unions
	•	components collapse over time

Yes

Use:

OPT Complexity Bucket 15 — Component Compression / DSU Flattening

Proof shape
	•	component trees flattening
	•	roots merging
	•	compressed parent chains

Complexity style
	•	near-linear total
	•	amortized almost constant per find/union

Best for
	•	union-find problems
	•	connectivity merging
	•	dynamic components

Runtime sentence

“Path compression and root-based merging make repeated connectivity operations nearly constant on average.”

⸻

The compressed version

If the optimized runtime is proved by…
	•	one pass → Single Linear Sweep
	•	two monotone boundaries → Bounded Pointer Movement
	•	one pass + O(1) helper work → Linear Sweep + Constant Side Operation
	•	sort once then process → Sort Once, Then Sweep
	•	halving → Logarithmic Halving
	•	halving + checker → Halving + Feasibility Checker
	•	visit each node/edge/cell once → One Visit per Structural Unit
	•	states × transitions → State Count × Transition Count
	•	push once / pop once → Amortized Push-Once / Pop-Once
	•	log-height container maintenance → Log-Height Ordered Structure
	•	range/jump hierarchy → Hierarchical Range / Jump Decomposition
	•	build once, answer many → Preprocess Once, Query Many
	•	small scalar invariant → Constant-State Formula
	•	touch only local internal pieces → Local-Touch Object / Process
	•	component flattening → Component Compression / DSU

That is the whole system.

⸻

The best practical method

Use this 4-step workflow on any problem.

Step 1

Write the runtime proof sentence:

“Each ___ is processed ___ times, plus ___ overhead.”

Examples:
	•	“Each element is processed once, plus constant hash updates.”
	•	“Each pointer moves at most N times.”
	•	“Each DP state is solved once with constant transitions.”
	•	“Each query touches only log N blocks.”
	•	“There are log M guesses, and each guess scans N items.”

Step 2

Underline the proof shape:
	•	once
	•	twice but monotone
	•	constant side work
	•	sort first
	•	halve
	•	log-height path
	•	state count
	•	push/pop once
	•	preprocess once
	•	local internal touch

Step 3

Map that proof shape to the bucket.

Step 4

Draw the smallest geometry that makes that proof obvious.

That is the cleanest real workflow.

⸻

The tiebreaker tree

Sometimes more than one bucket seems plausible. Use this order.

If the proof’s heart is monotone movement

Prefer:
	•	Single Sweep
	•	Bounded Pointer Movement

If the proof’s heart is reused memory without extra multiplicative cost

Prefer:
	•	Linear Sweep + Constant Side Operation
	•	Preprocess Once, Query Many

If the proof’s heart is shrinking search space

Prefer:
	•	Logarithmic Halving
	•	Halving + Checker

If the proof’s heart is structural bounded visitation

Prefer:
	•	One Visit per Node/Edge/Cell
	•	Component Compression / DSU

If the proof’s heart is state reuse

Prefer:
	•	State Count × Transition Count

If the proof’s heart is amortized lifetime

Prefer:
	•	Push-Once / Pop-Once

If the proof’s heart is ordered maintenance

Prefer:
	•	Log-Height Ordered Structure

If the proof’s heart is range decomposition

Prefer:
	•	Hierarchical Range / Jump Decomposition

If the proof’s heart is persistent object locality

Prefer:
	•	Local-Touch Object / Process

That resolves most ambiguity.

