HOW TO DRAW INPUT,OUTPUT VARIABLES ETC IN DEPTH GUIDE


Yes — this is the missing layer.

Until now, we covered:
	•	what world to draw
	•	what brute force looks like
	•	what optimized state looks like
	•	what runtime proof looks like

Now we need:

how to draw the input, output, variables, helpers, and state labels clearly

Because a lot of bad algorithm diagrams fail for a simple reason:
	•	the world is drawn,
	•	but the variables are floating in space
	•	the input/output is unclear
	•	and the viewer cannot tell what each box means

So this guide is about the visual grammar of algorithm diagrams.

⸻

1) The deepest rule

Draw algorithms like a machine diagram

Every good visual should make these visible:
	•	Input
	•	Working state
	•	Helper structures
	•	Output
	•	Variables
	•	Update flow

That means the best mental model is:

Input → State Updates → Output

And all variables should belong to one of those three.

⸻

2) The 5 visual roles everything belongs to

Every symbol you draw should belong to one of these roles.

A. Input

What the problem gives you.

Examples:
	•	array
	•	string
	•	linked list
	•	tree root
	•	graph edges
	•	grid
	•	SQL table
	•	API calls
	•	integers n, k, target

B. Output

What the algorithm returns.

Examples:
	•	index
	•	boolean
	•	count
	•	max/min value
	•	resulting array/string/list
	•	path
	•	tree/list root
	•	grouped table
	•	object behavior

C. Live variables

What changes during execution.

Examples:
	•	i, j
	•	L, R
	•	sum
	•	carry
	•	ans
	•	curr
	•	prev
	•	dist
	•	indegree
	•	mask

D. Helper structures

What the algorithm maintains externally.

Examples:
	•	hash map
	•	set
	•	queue
	•	heap
	•	stack
	•	prefix array
	•	visited matrix
	•	memo table
	•	parent array

E. Derived state / invariant labels

What explains the meaning of the variables.

Examples:
	•	“window valid”
	•	“best so far”
	•	“seen values”
	•	“distance from source”
	•	“dp[i] = min cost to reach i”
	•	“heap top = smallest active candidate”

That is the complete vocabulary of diagram objects.

⸻

3) The universal diagram layout

For almost every problem, use this spatial layout:

Left = Input

Put the original data on the left or top.

Center = Active state

Put the current working state in the middle.

Right = Output / answer

Put the result or answer box on the right or bottom-right.

Side = Helper structures

Put helper structures on the side:
	•	map
	•	heap
	•	queue
	•	stack
	•	DP table
	•	visited set
	•	prefix array

Small labels = Variables / invariants

Put changing variables:
	•	close to the object they control
	•	not floating randomly

So the cleanest layout is:

Input | Active State | Output
with helper structures beside the active state.

⸻

4) How to draw INPUT in depth

The input should always answer:
	•	what shape is the data?
	•	what are its labels?
	•	what parts are relevant?
	•	what values or symbols are important?

4.1 Arrays and strings

Draw them as:
	•	horizontal boxes
	•	indices below
	•	values/characters inside

Example

nums = [2, 7, 11, 15]

Draw:
	•	four adjacent boxes
	•	values in boxes
	•	indices 0 1 2 3 under them

Add parameters nearby

If the input also has:
	•	target = 9
	•	k = 3
	•	x = 15

put these in small labeled boxes above or to the side.

4.2 Linked lists

Draw:
	•	node boxes
	•	arrows between nodes
	•	optional head label

If values matter, put value inside node.

If structure matters, draw:
	•	next
	•	prev
	•	dummy node if relevant

4.3 Trees

Draw:
	•	root on top
	•	children downward
	•	values inside circles/boxes

If BST property matters, preserve left/right order clearly.

4.4 Graphs

Draw:
	•	nodes as circles
	•	edges as lines/arrows
	•	weights next to edges if weighted

If adjacency list is input rather than a visual graph, you may still draw the graph if it better matches the algorithm.

4.5 Grids

Draw:
	•	matrix cells
	•	row/column labels if helpful
	•	blocked/open cells visibly different

4.6 SQL tables

Draw:
	•	table name above
	•	columns as headers
	•	a few sample rows only

Never draw 50 rows. Just enough to show the idea.

4.7 Scalar inputs

Draw scalars in mini-boxes:
	•	n
	•	k
	•	target
	•	start
	•	capacity

These should be visually smaller than the main data structure.

⸻

5) How to draw OUTPUT in depth

The output should always answer:
	•	what form does the result take?
	•	where is the answer stored?
	•	is it being updated live, or returned at the end?

5.1 Scalar output

Use an answer box.

Examples:
	•	ans = 3
	•	max_len = 5
	•	count = 12
	•	found = true

Draw:
	•	one labeled box, usually on the right

5.2 Index/range output

If output is:
	•	an index
	•	pair of indices
	•	interval [L, R]

Draw:
	•	answer box with range
	•	or highlight the range on the input itself

Example:
best = [2,5]

5.3 Sequence output

If output is:
	•	merged array
	•	reversed list
	•	new string
	•	topological order

Draw:
	•	a separate row/chain/table for result
	•	arrows from source to result if construction matters

5.4 Structure output

If output is:
	•	a tree/list root
	•	grouped buckets
	•	connected components
	•	object state

Draw:
	•	the final structure itself
	•	not just a scalar label

5.5 Query output

If output is per query:
	•	show one output box per query
	•	or show one repeated answer channel from preprocessing system

⸻

6) How to draw VARIABLES in depth

Variables are the hardest part, because most diagrams either:
	•	omit them,
	•	or dump too many of them.

The key rule is:

only draw variables that change the algorithm’s behavior

Do not draw every variable in code.

⸻

6.1 Variable categories

A. Position variables

Examples:
	•	i, j
	•	L, R
	•	mid
	•	row/col pointer
	•	current node

Draw them attached to the object they point to.

Bad:
	•	i = 3 floating in a random corner

Good:
	•	arrow labeled i pointing to index 3

⸻

B. Accumulator variables

Examples:
	•	sum
	•	count
	•	ans
	•	best
	•	currMax
	•	carry

Draw them as small state boxes.

Best placement:
	•	near the relevant working area
	•	not inside the input unless they are physically attached

⸻

C. State-definition variables

Examples:
	•	mask
	•	dist[node]
	•	dp[i][j]
	•	visited
	•	indegree
	•	parent

These are usually not just variables — they are part of the helper structure.

So draw them:
	•	as a table
	•	as labels on nodes
	•	as small side arrays
	•	as colored marks on cells

⸻

D. Temporary pointer variables

Examples:
	•	prev
	•	curr
	•	next
	•	tail
	•	node

Draw these only if the motion depends on them.

For linked-list drawings, these are essential.

⸻

7) Where to place variable labels

This is extremely important.

Rule 1

A variable that points to a location should be drawn as a pointer label near that location

Examples:
	•	L
	•	R
	•	mid
	•	curr

Rule 2

A variable that stores a quantity should be drawn as a small labeled box

Examples:
	•	sum = 12
	•	carry = 1
	•	count = 3

Rule 3

A variable that summarizes many things should be drawn as a helper structure

Examples:
	•	count_map
	•	dp
	•	visited
	•	dist
	•	parent

Rule 4

A variable that defines meaning should be drawn as text next to the diagram

Examples:
	•	dp[i] = best score ending at i
	•	window valid
	•	heap top = smallest active

⸻

8) The 8 main variable-drawing styles

Style 1 — Pointer arrow

Use for:
	•	i
	•	j
	•	L
	•	R
	•	mid
	•	curr

Style 2 — Scalar state box

Use for:
	•	sum
	•	count
	•	ans
	•	carry
	•	best

Style 3 — Table/array label

Use for:
	•	dp
	•	prefix
	•	suffix
