13) The biggest mistakes

Mistake 1

Listing edge cases without explaining the invariant.

Mistake 2

Writing assumptions that are not actually used by the algorithm.

Mistake 3

Confusing assumptions with edge cases.
Example:
	•	“sorted” is an assumption, not an edge case.

Mistake 4

Making the invariant too vague.
Bad:
	•	“things stay correct”
Good:
	•	“window contains at most k distinct elements”

Mistake 5

Hiding the correctness panel far away from the active state.

⸻

14) The deepest one-line rule

Draw the correctness panel as the place where the algorithm earns trust.

That is the best compression.

Because:
	•	assumptions say what you are allowed to trust,
	•	edge cases say what you are not allowed to forget,
	•	invariants say why the machine remains correct.

