how to draw dry runs / iteration frames / execution snapshots in a consistent storyboard format.



Yes — this is the layer that turns a static diagram into a teaching sequence.

A dry run is not just “show a few steps.”
A good dry run is a storyboard:

Input state → frame-by-frame updates → invariant preserved → answer emerges

That is the mental model.

The purpose of a dry run is to answer four questions:
	•	What changes each step?
	•	What stays the same each step?
	•	Why is the update legal?
	•	How does the answer evolve?

So the deepest rule is:

A dry run should show state transitions, not code lines.

You are not animating syntax.
You are animating the machine state.

⸻

1) What a consistent storyboard format is

A consistent storyboard means every frame has the same anatomy.

Each frame should contain the same zones:

A. Frame number

Example:
	•	Frame 0
	•	Frame 1
	•	Frame 2
	•	Final

This gives the run a timeline.

B. Trigger

What action happened between the last frame and this frame?

Examples:
	•	R expands
	•	L shrinks
	•	push 7
	•	pop smaller elements
	•	visit neighbors
	•	fill dp[3]
	•	relax edge (u,v)
	•	attach node
	•	carry propagates

This is the “event label.”

C. Main world

The main canvas stays visually stable across frames:
	•	strip
	•	grid
	•	tree/list
	•	graph
	•	table
	•	DP board
	•	formula board
	•	process box

This is the stage.

D. Live state

The variables and helper structures at this frame:
	•	pointers
	•	counters
	•	queue
	•	stack
	•	heap
	•	map
	•	DP cells
	•	visited marks
	•	carry
	•	mask
	•	object internals

This is the moving cast.

E. Invariant label

One short sentence:
	•	window valid
	•	stack decreasing
	•	frontier = current BFS layer
	•	dp prefix solved
	•	heap top = best active candidate

This is the logic anchor.

F. Answer box

Show:
	•	best so far
	•	current output
	•	final result when ready

This is the payoff channel.

That is the consistent frame skeleton.

⸻

2) The universal dry-run frame template

Use this exact structure for any problem:

Frame k

Trigger: what just happened?

World: same base canvas

Live state: current variables + helper structures

Invariant: one-line rule still true

Answer: current best/current output

This is the universal storyboard template.

A compact version looks like this:

Frame 3
Trigger: expand R to index 5
World: string strip
Live state: L=2, R=5, freq={a:1,b:2,c:1}
Invariant: window contains at most 2 distinct chars
Answer: best_len = 4

That format works across almost all patterns.

⸻

3) The six storyboard laws

Law 1 — Keep the world fixed

The input world should not be redrawn from scratch every frame unless necessary.

The array stays the same.
The tree stays the same.
The grid stays the same.

Only the live state changes.

This reduces noise.

⸻

Law 2 — Show only meaningful changes

A frame should exist only when something important changes:
	•	pointer move
	•	state update
	•	branch decision
	•	queue layer shift
	•	pop/push event
	•	answer update
	•	invariant restoration

Do not make a frame for every uninteresting increment.

⸻

Law 3 — One frame, one event

Each frame should emphasize one main event.

Bad:
	•	move L, move R, update answer, update map, shrink, expand, pop all in one frame

Good:
	•	Frame 4: R expands
	•	Frame 5: window invalid
	•	Frame 6: L shrinks
	•	Frame 7: answer updates

This makes the logic digestible.

⸻

Law 4 — Keep variable locations consistent

If best is in the top-right box in frame 1, keep it there in frame 2, frame 3, frame 4.

If the queue is on the right side, keep it there.

Consistency matters more than style.

⸻

Law 5 — Distinguish “changed” from “unchanged”

Use one of these:
	•	highlight changed cells
	•	bold changed values
	•	arrows from old → new
	•	color/state change markers
	•	fade unchanged context

A frame should let the viewer instantly see:

what changed since last frame?

⸻

Law 6 — The invariant must appear more stable than the variables

Variables move.
The invariant stays.

So visually:
	•	variables/arrows move
	•	invariant box remains steady

That helps explain why the updates are safe.

⸻

4) The four-frame minimum model

Almost every dry run can be taught with these four frame types:

Frame 0 — Setup

Show:
	•	input
	•	parameters
	•	initial state
	•	base invariant
	•	initial answer

This is the starting machine.

Frame 1..k — Progress frames

Show:
	•	one important event per frame
	•	current state
	•	answer evolution

This is the working loop.

Penultimate frame — Turning point

This is where the key insight becomes obvious:
	•	window shrinks correctly
	•	stack pops reveal answer
	•	BFS layer reaches target
	•	DP recurrence locks in
	•	heap top becomes final choice

Not every problem has a dramatic turning point, but most do.

Final frame — Output

Show:
	•	final state
	•	answer box
	•	brief explanation of why algorithm stops or why result is final

This is the closure frame.

⸻

5) How many frames to use

Use this rule:

Use the smallest number of frames that makes the state transition obvious.

Usually:
	•	3 to 6 frames for simple patterns
	•	5 to 8 for medium logic
	•	8 to 12 for complex DP/graph/design problems

Too few frames:
	•	viewer misses the update rule

Too many frames:
	•	it becomes a trace log, not a teaching storyboard

The right number is determined by conceptual turning points, not loop count.

⸻

6) The best frame-to-frame notation

Use these notation styles consistently.

A. Pointer motion
	•	L ->
	•	R ->
	•	mid = 4
	•	curved arrow showing move

B. Value update
	•	sum: 8 -> 13
	•	best: 3 -> 5
	•	count[a]: 1 -> 2

C. Push/pop
	•	push(7)
	•	pop(4)
	•	crossed-out popped element

D. Queue/BFS
	•	dequeue A
	•	enqueue B,C
	•	next layer boxed

E. DP fill
	•	highlight new cell
	•	arrows from source cells
	•	show formula/result briefly

F. Graph relax
	•	dist[v]: inf -> 8
	•	edge highlighted

G. Rewire
	•	old link faded
	•	new link bolded

H. Invariant check
	•	✓ window valid
	•	✓ stack monotonic
	•	✓ all deps solved

These are the visual verbs of dry runs.

⸻

7) The storyboard panel layout

The cleanest layout is:

Top

Frame label + trigger

Middle

Main world canvas

Side

Helper structures and variables

Bottom or right

Invariant + answer box

Example layout:

Frame 2 | Trigger: push current value
------------------------------------
[ main world canvas here ]
             | map/stack/queue here
------------------------------------
Invariant: ...
Answer: ...

That is the most stable storyboard layout.

