5. Arrow system

A. Motion arrow

For movement through the world.
	•	pointer moves
	•	sweep direction
	•	traversal direction
	•	frontier spread

Example:
L ->, R ->, sweep left to right

B. Update arrow

For one value changing another.
	•	recurrence
	•	scalar update
	•	answer update
	•	edge relaxation

Example:
sum -> sum + x

C. Dependency arrow

For “this is used to compute that.”
	•	DP predecessor
	•	subtree contribution
	•	formula dependency

Thin arrow, usually quieter than motion arrows.

D. Pointer arrow

For variables referencing positions or nodes.
	•	curr
	•	prev
	•	next
	•	head
	•	tail
	•	mid

The label lives on the arrow, not floating somewhere else.

E. Expansion arrow

For one state generating many.
	•	recursion branching
	•	BFS frontier spread
	•	neighbor generation

F. Merge arrow

For many becoming one.
	•	interval merge
	•	grouped rows
	•	union-find merge
	•	aggregate computation

G. Return arrow

For information bubbling back.
	•	recursion return
	•	subtree result
	•	memoized answer return

Usually curved or upward.

