Part III — The transformation layer

This is the missing bridge most learners never formalize.

A problem becomes solvable when you can say:

“The brute force wastes time here.

This optimized engine removes exactly that waste.”

That is the transformation layer.

I’ll give it as a library of bottleneck-to-pattern transformations.

⸻

Transformation 1 — Repeated range rescans -> Sliding window

Brute force

Enumerate every subarray/substring and recheck each one.

Waste

Overlapping contiguous ranges are re-read many times.

Transformation

Maintain one live range and update it incrementally as boundaries move.

Conditions required
	•	contiguous region
	•	add/remove updates are cheap
	•	validity can be maintained from current state

Canonicals
	•	Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters
	•	Minimum Window Substring
	•	max-sum fixed window

⸻

Transformation 2 — Repeated range totals -> Prefix sums

Brute force

For every queried range, recompute the sum or balance from scratch.

Waste

Same prefixes are recomputed repeatedly.

Transformation

Precompute cumulative state once; derive range result from differences.

Conditions required
	•	target property decomposes over prefixes
	•	queries are repeated or range-based

Canonicals
	•	Range Sum Query
	•	Subarray Sum Equals K
	•	2D rectangle sums

⸻

Transformation 3 — All-pairs scan -> Hashing

Brute force

For each item, scan all earlier/later items for a match.

Waste

Repeated existence checks through previously seen data.

Transformation

Store relevant past facts in a map/set and retrieve in O(1)-style time.

Conditions required
	•	lookup key can be defined
	•	you only need memory of prior/active items

Canonicals
	•	Two Sum
	•	Contains Duplicate
	•	Group Anagrams

⸻

Transformation 4 — All-pairs scan -> Sorting + Two pointers

Brute force

Check every pair in unsorted data.

Waste

No order, so you cannot discard regions.

Transformation

Sort once, then use monotone pointer movement to rule out impossible pairs.

Conditions required
	•	order makes the condition monotone
	•	reordering is allowed or answer doesn’t require original order without recovery

Canonicals
	•	Two Sum II
	•	3Sum
	•	Container With Most Water
	•	interval merge variants after sort

⸻

Transformation 5 — Exponential repeated recursion -> Memoization / DP

Brute force

Recursive branches revisit same subproblems again and again.

Waste

Overlapping subproblems.

Transformation

Name the state, cache it, or tabulate it once.

Conditions required
	•	future depends only on a small state
	•	same state reappears across branches

Canonicals
	•	Climbing Stairs
	•	Coin Change
	•	House Robber
	•	Word Break DP versions
	•	Edit Distance

⸻

Transformation 6 — Path explosion in unweighted space -> BFS

Brute force

Try many paths and compare lengths.

Waste

Explores all route lengths without layer discipline.

Transformation

Expand uniformly by steps so first arrival is shortest.

Conditions required
	•	edges all same weight or step cost
	•	shortest number-of-steps objective

Canonicals
	•	Rotting Oranges
	•	Word Ladder
	•	shortest path in unweighted grid

⸻

Transformation 7 — Repeated component searches -> DSU

Brute force

After every merge/query, run DFS/BFS again.

Waste

Connectivity is recomputed from scratch.

Transformation

Maintain components explicitly with parent roots.

Conditions required
	•	only connectivity/group membership matters
	•	not full path details

Canonicals
	•	Accounts Merge
	•	Number of Provinces
	•	Redundant Connection

⸻

Transformation 8 — Repeated best-element search -> Heap

Brute force

Each time you need current best/worst, scan all active candidates.

Waste

Repeated extrema search over changing set.

Transformation

Keep active candidates in a heap.

Conditions required
	•	best candidate changes dynamically
	•	repeated selection matters more than one global sort

Canonicals
	•	Top K Frequent Elements
	•	Kth Largest Element
	•	Meeting Rooms II
	•	Dijkstra

⸻

Transformation 9 — Repeated nearest-boundary scans -> Monotonic stack/deque

Brute force

For every element, scan left/right until you find the first larger/smaller one.

Waste

Same regions are scanned repeatedly.

Transformation

Maintain unresolved candidates in monotone order.

Conditions required
	•	nearest boundary with monotone comparison
	•	each element can invalidate previous ones

Canonicals
	•	Daily Temperatures
	•	Next Greater Element
	•	Largest Rectangle in Histogram
	•	Sliding Window Maximum

⸻

Transformation 10 — Repeated traversal of ordered search space -> Binary search

Brute force

Try candidate positions or values one by one.

Waste

Sequential probing in a monotone space.

Transformation

Exploit monotonicity and halve the candidate region each step.

Conditions required
	•	monotone yes/no or ordered target relation

Canonicals
	•	Binary Search
	•	First/Last Position
	•	Koko Eating Bananas
	•	Minimize maximum / maximize minimum families

⸻

Transformation 11 — Repeated full sort after each change -> Heap / balanced maintenance / local updates

Brute force

Modify data, then re-sort or rebuild whole order every time.

Waste

Paying global ordering cost repeatedly.

Transformation

Maintain only the necessary ordering incrementally.

Conditions required
	•	updates are local
	•	only part of total order is needed (top/bottom/priority)

Canonicals
	•	streaming kth/top-k
	•	meeting room active interval management
	•	design objects with ordered policies

⸻

Transformation 12 — Repeated full-board validity checks -> Constraint trackers

Brute force

After each placement/move, rescan entire board/row/col/diag.

Waste

Repeated global validation.

Transformation

Maintain row/col/diag or frequency trackers incrementally.

Conditions required
	•	validity decomposes into tracked constraints

Canonicals
	•	N-Queens
	•	Sudoku-like optimizations
	•	board-placement backtracking

⸻

Transformation 13 — Repeated range query under updates -> Segment tree / BIT

Brute force

Each update or query scans the whole range.

Waste

Dynamic range recomputation.

Transformation

Store summarized blocks in a hierarchy.

Conditions required
	•	associative summary over ranges
	•	repeated online updates/queries

Canonicals
	•	Range Sum Query Mutable
	•	RMQ / Fenwick families

⸻

Transformation 14 — Rebuilding structure each operation -> Persistent object state

Brute force

Every API call reconstructs or replays the whole system.

Waste

State is not preserved.

Transformation

Store the right internal representation and mutate only touched parts.

Conditions required
	•	operations repeat
	•	the same internal facts remain useful

Canonicals
	•	LRU Cache
	•	LFU Cache
	•	Read4 buffer problems
	•	iterator design

⸻

Transformation 15 — Testing many numeric candidates -> Math / invariant / bit logic

Brute force

Try each number or simulate arithmetic naively.

Waste

Candidate-by-candidate testing.

Transformation

Find an invariant, formula, cancellation law, or representation trick.

Conditions required
	•	arithmetic structure is stronger than raw simulation
	•	parity/xor/divisibility/bit property exists

Canonicals
	•	Single Number
	•	Counting Bits
	•	Reverse Integer
	•	gcd/lcm problems

