indepth about requirements

Yes — the requirements are the most important part, because they tell you when a pattern is actually valid and what a complete atlas entry must contain.

The cleanest way to think about requirements is that there are four layers:

1. Requirements for the whole atlas

This is what every serious chapter/family in the manual must include.

A pattern chapter is incomplete unless it answers all of these:

A. World requirement

What data world does this pattern naturally live in?
Examples:
	•	sequence
	•	string
	•	linked list
	•	grid
	•	tree
	•	graph
	•	interval line
	•	SQL table
	•	object/API
	•	numeric/bit state

This prevents random pattern matching.

B. Job requirement

What kind of task is this pattern good at?
Examples:
	•	existence
	•	counting
	•	optimization
	•	shortest path
	•	all solutions
	•	dynamic operations
	•	range queries

A pattern without a job profile is too vague.

C. Budget requirement

What constraints justify using it?
Examples:
	•	n <= 20 may allow backtracking
	•	n <= 10^5 usually demands O(n) or O(n log n)
	•	many queries may demand preprocessing or range structures
	•	weighted graph kills plain BFS

This is the “physics” requirement.

D. Brute-force requirement

What naive search does this optimized pattern replace?

Without this, the optimization feels magical instead of motivated.

E. Bottleneck requirement

What exact waste is being removed?
Examples:
	•	repeated rescans
	•	repeated pair checks
	•	repeated subproblems
	•	repeated connectivity tests
	•	repeated best-candidate search
	•	repeated full replay of state

This is the transformation hinge.

F. State requirement

What minimum information must be maintained?
If you cannot define the state precisely, the chapter is not operational.

G. Invariant requirement

What must remain true after each update?
This is the correctness core.

H. Variation requirement

How does the family split?
Examples:
	•	fixed vs variable window
	•	exact vs boundary vs answer-space binary search
	•	single-source vs multi-source BFS
	•	1D/2D/tree/bitmask DP

I. Composite requirement

What helper structures are commonly attached?
Examples:
	•	map
	•	heap
	•	sorting
	•	prefix sums
	•	memoization
	•	queue
	•	constraint trackers

J. Canonical requirement

Which ancestor problem teaches the family cleanly?

K. Proof requirement

How is correctness usually proven?
Examples:
	•	invariant
	•	induction
	•	exchange argument
	•	shortest-path layer argument
	•	amortized lifetime proof

L. Memory requirement

What is the typical footprint?
	•	constant-state
	•	map/set
	•	queue/stack
	•	DP table
	•	recursion depth
	•	object internals
	•	output-sized storage

So a complete atlas entry must cover:
world + job + budget + BF + bottleneck + state + invariant + variations + composites + canonicals + proof + memory

That is the full atlas requirement.

⸻

2. Requirements for using each major pattern

This is the most practical interpretation of “requirements.”

These are the necessary conditions for a pattern to make sense.

⸻

2.1 Direct scan / counting

Requirements
	•	answer can be accumulated in one sweep
	•	each new item can update the summary locally
	•	no future information is required beyond a tiny running state

Strong signs
	•	min/max/count/one-pass aggregate
	•	“just process everything once”

Failure condition

If the problem needs remembering many earlier facts or dynamic boundaries, plain scan is too weak.

⸻

2.2 Prefix sum / prefix state

Requirements
	•	the property can be expressed cumulatively
	•	range information can be derived from prefix differences
	•	repeated range computations are expensive in brute force

Strong signs
	•	subarray sums
	•	balance/parity/remainder
	•	many range queries
	•	cumulative behavior

Failure condition

If the data changes online and often, plain prefix sums may be insufficient; you may need BIT/segment tree.

⸻

2.3 Hashing

Requirements
	•	there exists a useful key
	•	membership / count / lookup is the real bottleneck
	•	order is not the only thing that matters

Strong signs
	•	seen before?
	•	complement exists?
	•	frequency of X?
	•	group by signature
	•	deduplicate

Failure condition

If the main problem is about sorted order, nearest boundary, or global ranking, hashing alone may not solve it.

⸻

2.4 Two pointers

Requirements
	•	pointer movement can safely discard regions
	•	there is monotonic structure
	•	sortedness or boundary geometry matters
	•	movement is meaningful, not arbitrary

Strong signs
	•	sorted array
	•	compare two ends
	•	pair/triple conditions
	•	merge two ordered streams
	•	in-place compaction
	•	fast/slow linked-list logic

Failure condition

If moving a pointer does not logically eliminate possibilities, two pointers is fake pattern matching.

⸻

2.5 Sliding window

Requirements
	•	the region is contiguous
	•	add/remove from window can be updated incrementally
	•	validity can be maintained from local window state
	•	left/right move monotonically, not reset everywhere

Strong signs
	•	substring/subarray
	•	longest/shortest valid contiguous region
	•	at most / at least / exactly k-style conditions

Failure condition

If removing the leftmost element destroys information you cannot restore cheaply, plain sliding window may fail.

⸻

2.6 Binary search

Requirements
	•	an ordered search space exists
	•	there is monotonicity
	•	the answer lies behind a boundary or can be halved repeatedly

Strong signs
	•	sorted input
	•	first/last valid
	•	minimum feasible
	•	maximum feasible
	•	target range / partition / boundary

Failure condition

No monotonicity = no valid binary search.

⸻

2.7 Monotonic stack / deque

Requirements
	•	nearest greater/smaller or boundary relation matters
	•	one-dimensional order exists
	•	elements invalidate earlier candidates in a monotone way

Strong signs
	•	next greater
	•	nearest smaller
	•	histogram areas
	•	daily temperatures
	•	sliding window max/min

Failure condition

If there is no nearest-boundary structure, stack monotonicity is the wrong hammer.

⸻

2.8 Heap / priority queue

Requirements
	•	you need repeated best/worst extraction from a changing active set
	•	one global sort is not enough
	•	dynamic priority matters

Strong signs
	•	top k
	•	kth largest/smallest
	•	repeated min/max under updates
	•	schedule active intervals/jobs
	•	shortest path with priorities

Failure condition

If you only need final sorted order once, sort may be simpler and better.

⸻

2.9 DFS

Requirements
	•	deep exploration is natural
	•	you need connectivity, subtree logic, or full-path search
	•	recursion or explicit stack matches the structure

Strong signs
	•	tree traversal
	•	component exploration
	•	path existence
	•	subtree aggregation
	•	all-path baseline

Failure condition

If the problem is specifically shortest path in an unweighted space, BFS is usually better.

⸻

2.10 BFS

Requirements
	•	all edges/steps have equal cost, or layer semantics matter
	•	shortest number of steps is the goal
	•	“nearest” / “minimum steps” / “spread” language appears

Strong signs
	•	shortest path in unweighted graph/grid
	•	minimum operations
	•	level order
	•	infection/spread/wavefront

Failure condition

Weighted edges break plain BFS.

⸻

2.11 Backtracking

Requirements
	•	solution space is a choice tree
	•	you may need all answers or must try placements/combinations
	•	state can be modified and undone
	•	constraints are small enough or pruning is strong enough

Strong signs
	•	all combinations
	•	all permutations
	•	board placement
	•	exact constraint satisfaction

Failure condition

Large n with weak pruning usually kills backtracking.

⸻

2.12 Dynamic programming

Requirements
	•	overlapping subproblems exist
	•	the future depends only on a compact state
	•	recomputation is the brute-force bottleneck
	•	there is optimal substructure or reusable sub-results

Strong signs
	•	number of ways
	•	min/max under structured choices
	•	repeated recursion
	•	sequence alignment
	•	interval splitting
	•	pick/skip patterns

Failure condition

If a greedy proof exists, DP may be unnecessary overhead.

⸻

2.13 Greedy

Requirements
	•	a local choice can be proven globally safe
	•	there is an exchange argument, dominance rule, or monotone feasibility
	•	sorting often reveals the right local order

Strong signs
	•	interval scheduling
	•	choose smallest/largest safe next piece
	•	lexicographic minimization
	•	local deficit / local coverage reasoning

Failure condition

If you cannot prove the local choice is safe, suspect DP instead.

⸻

2.14 Union-find

Requirements
	•	only connectivity/equivalence matters
	•	the structure changes by merges
	•	repeated component queries are needed

Strong signs
	•	merge accounts
	•	count components
	•	redundant edge
	•	dynamic connectivity

Failure condition

If actual path, distance, or traversal order matters, DSU is not enough.

⸻

2.15 Trie

Requirements
	•	prefix structure is central
	•	many strings share prefixes
	•	repeated prefix lookup/search is expensive

Strong signs
	•	dictionary search
	•	autocomplete
	•	word search with many prefixes
	•	xor maximization with bit trie

Failure condition

If only exact lookup matters, a hash set may be simpler.

⸻

2.16 Range structures

Requirements
	•	many range queries and/or updates
	•	repeated rescans of ranges are the bottleneck
	•	summarized block structure is possible

Strong signs
	•	mutable range sum/min/max
	•	ancestor jumps
	•	repeated RMQ/LCA style queries

Failure condition

If queries are static and simple, prefix sums or preprocessing may be enough.

⸻

2.17 Graph advanced

Requirements
	•	graph semantics matter beyond plain traversal
	•	weighted edges, DAG order, or path costs exist
	•	dependency or relaxation logic is needed

Strong signs
	•	prerequisites
	•	weighted shortest path
	•	topological order
	•	cheapest path / constrained path

Failure condition

Using advanced graph machinery when plain BFS/DFS would solve it is overengineering.

⸻

2.18 SQL / relational

Requirements
	•	row alignment, grouping, or partitioning is the real structure
	•	the problem is about relational semantics, not pointer loops

Strong signs
	•	join
	•	group by
	•	rank
	•	department summary
	•	partition-wise comparison

Failure condition

Treating relational problems as manual nested loops loses the real abstraction.

⸻

2.19 Design / object state

Requirements
	•	operations repeat over persistent state
	•	replaying from scratch is too expensive
	•	internal data representation determines performance

Strong signs
	•	cache design
	•	iterator
	•	buffered reader
	•	API/stateful object

Failure condition

If the problem is just a one-shot batch computation, design-object thinking may be unnecessary.

⸻

2.20 Math / invariant

Requirements
	•	a compact mathematical truth replaces search
	•	parity/xor/divisibility/carry/bit law exists
	•	brute force is over-simulating something that has structure

Strong signs
	•	digit manipulation
	•	xor cancellation
	•	parity
	•	gcd/lcm
	•	direct constructive formula

Failure condition

Using “math” as a guess without an actual invariant is just hand-waving.

