3. Requirements for a canonical archetype

A problem should not be called canonical unless it satisfies these.

A. It isolates one family clearly

It should not be too composite.

B. It teaches the family’s core invariant

The pattern’s “engine law” must be visible.

C. It has a clean brute-force contrast

The optimization should be pedagogically obvious.

D. It mutates into many harder problems

A canonical must have descendants.

E. Its state is compact and teachable

If the state is too weird, it is a poor canonical.

So for example:

Two Sum is canonical because:
	•	brute force is obvious
	•	hash-map optimization is clean
	•	the key idea generalizes to complements / seen-before / map memory

Minimum Window is canonical because:
	•	it teaches the hardest important variable-window invariant
	•	many string/window problems are mutations of it

Coin Change is canonical because:
	•	it teaches state-transition DP and impossible states
	•	many DP problems reduce to the same architecture

That is the canonical requirement standard.

⸻

4. Requirements for a transformation

This is the bridge from brute force to optimization.

A transformation entry is incomplete unless it answers:

A. What brute-force pattern is being replaced?

Example:
	•	all ranges
	•	all pairs
	•	repeated recursion
	•	repeated connectivity scan
	•	repeated replay
	•	repeated best-element scan

B. What exact waste is removed?

Not vague “too slow,” but:
	•	overlap
	•	recheck
	•	restart
	•	rebuild
	•	repeated global search
	•	repeated subproblem

C. What property enables compression?

Example:
	•	monotone window boundaries
	•	prefix decomposability
	•	ordered search space
	•	local-choice safety
	•	state repeatability
	•	connectivity merging
	•	shared prefixes

D. What new state is introduced?

Example:
	•	map
	•	prefix array
	•	queue frontier
	•	DP table
	•	heap
	•	pointer pair
	•	invariant scalar

E. What is the new proof shape?

Example:
	•	one sweep
	•	each pointer moves once
	•	each state solved once
	•	each node visited once
	•	logarithmic halving
	•	push once / pop once

F. What is the memory tradeoff?

Example:
	•	O(1) -> O(n)
	•	exponential time -> polynomial with DP table
	•	full replay -> persistent object state

That is the full requirement for a valid BF→Opt transformation.

