Yes — let’s go much deeper.

What you are really asking is:

What must be true for this entire system to be complete, correct, usable, and internally consistent?

That is a requirements architecture problem.

So instead of treating “requirements” as a small checklist, the correct way is to think in layers.

⸻

1. The deepest meaning of “requirements”

In your project, “requirements” exist at five different levels:

Level 1 — Reality requirements

What must be true in the problem itself for a pattern to apply?

Example:
	•	sliding window requires a contiguous region and incrementally maintainable validity
	•	binary search requires monotonicity
	•	BFS shortest path requires unweighted edges or uniform step cost

These are mathematical / structural requirements.

Level 2 — Solution requirements

What must a correct solution contain?

Example:
	•	state
	•	transition/update rule
	•	invariant
	•	stopping condition
	•	complexity justification
	•	memory justification

These are algorithm-design requirements.

Level 3 — Atlas requirements

What must each chapter/pattern entry in the manual include?

Example:
	•	what it is
	•	when it works
	•	why brute force fails
	•	what canonicals teach it
	•	what variations mutate from it
	•	how to draw it
	•	how to prove it
	•	how it fails

These are documentation requirements.

Level 4 — Teaching requirements

What must exist so a learner can actually understand and transfer the pattern?

Example:
	•	one clean canonical
	•	one strong brute-force contrast
	•	at least one worked transformation
	•	common mistakes
	•	drawing defaults
	•	decision tree placement

These are pedagogical requirements.

Level 5 — System requirements

What must be true so the whole project is internally consistent?

Example:
	•	one term = one meaning
	•	same visual symbol = same function
	•	taxonomy and anatomy must agree
	•	canonicals must map cleanly to families
	•	transformations must preserve causality
	•	no chapter should contradict another

These are architectural requirements.

So the full answer is not one list.
It is a hierarchy of requirement systems.

⸻

2. The master requirement stack

The strongest way to organize everything is this:

A. Ontology requirements

What entities exist in the system?

B. Applicability requirements

When is a pattern allowed?

C. Construction requirements

What must a solution contain?

D. Proof requirements

