3. Ontology requirements

Ontology means: what objects does the system believe exist?

If the ontology is fuzzy, the whole atlas collapses.

Your system must clearly distinguish these as different things:

3.1 Problem world

The shape of input reality:
	•	array / sequence
	•	string / text
	•	linked list
	•	grid / matrix
	•	tree / trie
	•	graph / state network
	•	intervals / geometry
	•	SQL / relational table
	•	object / API / process
	•	number / bit / formula world

Requirement:
Every problem must be assignable to at least one primary world.

3.2 Problem job

What the problem is asking for:
	•	existence
	•	counting
	•	optimization
	•	shortest path
	•	full enumeration
	•	grouping
	•	ordering
	•	dynamic operations
	•	range query/update

Requirement:
Every problem must have one dominant job, even if there are secondary ones.

3.3 Brute-force candidate

What the naive search enumerates:
	•	range
	•	pair
	•	subset
	•	permutation
	•	path
	•	traversal
	•	simulation timeline
	•	row scan
	•	numeric candidate
	•	rebuild/copy state

Requirement:
Every problem must have an explicit brute-force candidate object.

3.4 Bottleneck type

What is repeated wastefully:
	•	rescan
	•	overlap
	•	repeated lookup
	•	repeated subproblem
	•	repeated traversal
	•	repeated best-element search
	•	repeated range query
	•	repeated replay
	•	repeated rebuild/copy
	•	repeated candidate testing

Requirement:
Every optimization must name a bottleneck, not just “it is slow.”

3.5 Engine

What main mechanism removes the waste:
	•	scan
	•	prefix state
	•	hashing
	•	two pointers
	•	window
	•	binary search
	•	stack/deque
	•	heap
	•	DFS
	•	BFS
	•	backtracking
	•	DP
	•	greedy
	•	DSU
	•	trie
	•	range structure
	•	graph advanced
	•	SQL operators
	•	design/object state
	•	math/invariant

Requirement:
Each optimized solution must have one primary engine.

3.6 Variation

What subtype of engine is being used.

Requirement:
Broad pattern names are not enough.
You must go one level lower.

Example:
“DP” is insufficient.
Need:
	•	1D DP
	•	2D DP
	•	interval DP
	•	tree DP
	•	memoized DFS
	•	bitmask DP

3.7 Composite helper

What supporting structure is attached.

Requirement:
Any solution that needs an extra helper must make that explicit.

Example:
	•	sliding window + hash map
	•	binary search + greedy checker
