4. Applicability requirements

This is the most practical layer:
When is a pattern actually valid?

A good atlas must not only say “use X for Y.”
It must say:

X is valid only if these conditions hold.

That is the difference between pattern guessing and real algorithmic judgment.

⸻

4.1 Sliding window applicability requirements

A problem may use sliding window only if:

Structural requirements
	•	the region is contiguous
	•	left/right boundaries are meaningful

Update requirements
	•	adding the next item is cheap
	•	removing the leftmost item is cheap

Validity requirements
	•	the condition can be maintained using local window state
	•	validity can be restored by moving boundaries, not restarting from scratch

Budget requirements
	•	brute force over all ranges is too expensive

Failure requirements

The atlas must explicitly say sliding window is not valid when:
	•	negative numbers break monotonic sum logic in some tasks
	•	the constraint depends on nonlocal history that cannot be updated incrementally
	•	removing leftmost item destroys essential information that cannot be restored cheaply

That is what a real applicability section should look like.

⸻

4.2 Binary search applicability requirements

Binary search is valid only if:

Ordering requirement
	•	there is an ordered search space

Monotonicity requirement
	•	the target condition flips once or obeys a monotone relation

Boundary requirement
	•	surviving interval can be maintained safely

Decision requirement
	•	the midpoint tells you which half is impossible

Failure requirements

Must explicitly warn:
	•	no monotonicity = invalid binary search
	•	“seems ordered” is not enough
	•	boundary variants require different invariants than exact search

⸻

4.3 Greedy applicability requirements

Greedy is valid only if:

Safe-choice requirement
	•	there exists a local decision that never ruins optimality

Exchange/dominance requirement
	•	you can justify that replacing a different choice with the greedy one does not worsen the solution

Structural requirement
	•	global branching can be collapsed by local correctness

Failure requirements

Must explicitly say:
	•	intuition is not proof
	•	if future tradeoffs cannot be safely ignored, suspect DP

⸻

4.4 DP applicability requirements

DP is valid only if:

State requirement
	•	future behavior depends only on compact state

Overlap requirement
	•	same subproblem repeats

Reusability requirement
	•	stored answers can be reused safely

Transition requirement
	•	there is a finite recurrence structure

Failure requirements

Must warn:
	•	huge uncontrolled state = fake DP
	•	if local safe choice exists, greedy may dominate
	•	if no overlap exists, memoization may not help much

⸻

4.5 BFS applicability requirements

BFS shortest-path reasoning is valid only if:

Uniform-cost requirement
	•	each move/edge costs the same
or the variant explicitly supports weighted transitions (e.g. 0-1 BFS)

Layer requirement
	•	expanding by frontier levels preserves path optimality

Visit-control requirement
	•	revisits are controlled correctly

Failure requirements

Must warn:
	•	weighted edges break plain BFS shortest-path correctness

Every major family needs this level of applicability rigor.

⸻

5. Construction requirements

This is the layer of:

What must a complete solution contain?

A solution is not complete just because you know the pattern name.

A complete solution must include these components.

5.1 State

The minimum info needed to continue correctly.

Requirement:
State must be:
	•	sufficient
	•	minimal
	•	non-redundant
	•	update-friendly

5.2 Transition / update rule

How one valid state becomes the next.

Requirement:
Must be explicit, not implied.

Examples:
	•	expand R
	•	shrink L
	•	dp[i] = min(dp[i], dp[i-c]+1)
	•	relax edge
	•	merge interval
	•	pop while monotonicity violated

5.3 Invariant

What remains true after every step.

Requirement:
Must be short and testable.

Bad:
	•	“the structure stays correct”

Good:
	•	“the deque stores indices in decreasing-value order”
	•	“the current window contains at most k distinct chars”
	•	“all nodes in queue belong to the current BFS frontier or next frontier”

5.4 Start state / base case

What is true before iteration/recursion starts?

Requirement:
Must include:
	•	initialization
	•	empty state meaning
	•	smallest solved subproblem

5.5 Stopping rule / answer extraction

How do we know we are done, and where is the answer read from?

Requirement:
This must be visible:
	•	final DP cell
	•	best-so-far box
	•	output list
	•	last pointer/root/node

5.6 Resource statement

What time and memory are used, and why?

Requirement:
Not just big-O labels — must connect to the proof shape.

That is the minimum construction standard for any solution entry.

