16. Final compression

The most rigorous way to say all this is:

Requirements exist at four depths:
	•	applicability: when a pattern is valid
	•	construction: what a solution must contain
	•	pedagogy: what a chapter must teach
	•	architecture: what keeps the whole atlas consistent

And the deepest requirement of all is:

A pattern entry is only complete when it explains:

why brute force wastes work, what property enables compression, what state is kept, what invariant preserves correctness, and what proof bounds runtime and memory.

That is the in-depth requirement architecture.

The strongest next move is to apply this standard to one full chapter — for example Sliding Window — and build the full gold-standard version under this exact template.


