Part I — The deepest split: requirements of truth vs requirements of usefulness

This is the first thing most systems get wrong.

A system can be:
	•	mathematically true but pedagogically bad
	•	pedagogically clear but mathematically sloppy
	•	visually beautiful but taxonomically inconsistent
	•	broad but too vague to solve real problems
	•	deep but impossible to use under time pressure

So the project must satisfy two master requirement families:

A. Truth requirements

These are about whether the system is actually correct.

Examples:
	•	does the pattern really apply under those conditions?
	•	is the invariant stated correctly?
	•	is the complexity argument valid?
	•	is the canonical link honest?
	•	does the brute-force bottleneck actually match the optimization?

B. Usefulness requirements

These are about whether the system can actually be used.

Examples:
	•	can a learner identify the family under time pressure?
	•	can they distinguish it from confusing neighbors?
	•	can they draw it consistently?
	•	can they turn it into code?
	•	can they transfer it to mutations?

That means every chapter, every canonical, every transformation, every diagram, and every term must satisfy both truth and usefulness.

If either side fails, the system is broken.

