Part II — The 10 deep layers of requirements

Now let’s define the full requirement stack properly.

Layer 1 — Ontological requirements

This answers:

What kinds of things exist in the system?

If this layer is weak, the whole atlas becomes fuzzy.

The ontology must distinguish:

1. Problem world

The environment in which the problem lives.

This cannot be vague.
It must be specific enough to constrain patterns.

Examples:
	•	linear sequence
	•	symbolic sequence
	•	linked structure
	•	rooted tree
	•	general graph
	•	grid/board
	•	interval line
	•	relational table
	•	persistent object/process
	•	numeric/bit domain

2. Problem job

What the problem wants from you.

Not “solve it,” but:
	•	detect
	•	count
	•	optimize
	•	construct
	•	enumerate
	•	order
	•	query/update
	•	simulate
	•	decide feasibility

3. Search object

What brute force enumerates.

This is one of the most important ontological categories in your project.

Examples:
	•	range
	•	pair
	•	path
	•	subset
	•	permutation
	•	subtree
	•	state
	•	operation sequence
	•	candidate answer
	•	row match

4. Waste type

What brute force is repeating unnecessarily.

This is critical because your transformation layer depends on it.

Examples:
	•	repeated rescan
	•	repeated lookup
	•	repeated traversal
	•	repeated subproblem
	•	repeated sort/rebuild
	•	repeated best-element search
	•	repeated simulation
	•	repeated range query
	•	repeated path exploration

5. Engine type

What kind of machine compresses that waste.

Examples:
	•	memory compression engine
	•	boundary compression engine
	•	recurrence compression engine
	•	order-exploitation engine
	•	connectivity engine
	•	priority engine
	•	range-summary engine
	•	invariant engine

The atlas can use familiar names like DP, BFS, heap, etc., but ontologically those are really waste-removal machines.

6. State object

What live information exists simultaneously.

7. Invariant object

What law must remain true.

8. Proof object

What kind of argument makes the solution valid.

9. Memory object

What is alive in storage, and how long.

These categories must exist before the atlas can be rigorous.

So the first deep requirement is:

Requirement:

The system must define all major object-types explicitly and non-overlappingly.

Without that, terms blur together.

