Layer 2 — Applicability requirements

This answers:

Under what conditions is a pattern allowed?

This is the single most important practical layer.

A strong system never says:

“Use sliding window for substring problems.”

It says:

“Sliding window is valid when the region is contiguous, the state can be updated incrementally under add/remove, and the validity condition can be restored by monotone boundary motion.”

That is the difference between a pattern atlas and a pattern slogan.

Every family must have these requirement sections:

A. Structural requirement

What structure in the input makes the pattern possible?

Examples:
	•	sortedness
	•	contiguity
	•	graph edges with equal cost
	•	shared prefix structure
	•	merge-only connectivity
	•	recurrence dependency order

B. Information requirement

What information must be maintainable locally?

Examples:
	•	current counts
	•	cumulative prefix state
	•	current best candidate
	•	subtree summaries
	•	active frontier
	•	feasible threshold checker

C. Monotonicity / stability requirement

What must evolve in a disciplined direction?

Examples:
	•	pointers only move forward
	•	search interval shrinks
	•	stack order remains monotone
	•	frontier distance never decreases
	•	component roots only merge
	•	DP fill order only depends on solved states

D. Constraint requirement

What budget makes this pattern relevant?

Examples:
	•	n <= 20 permits backtracking
	•	n <= 10^5 excludes quadratic brute force
	•	many queries force preprocessing
	•	weighted graph forbids plain BFS shortest-path logic

E. Non-applicability requirement

This is equally important.

Every chapter must explicitly say when the pattern is not valid.

This is one of the strongest missing pieces in most tutorials.

Examples:
	•	sliding window fails if the property is not incrementally maintainable
	•	binary search fails without monotonicity
	•	greedy fails without local-choice proof
	•	DSU fails when path details matter
	•	prefix sums alone fail under dynamic updates
	•	hashing alone fails when order/boundary structure is essential

So the second deep requirement is:

Requirement:

Every pattern chapter must include both applicability and non-applicability conditions.

Without non-applicability, the learner overgeneralizes.

⸻

Layer 3 — Construction requirements

This answers:

What must a real solution actually contain?

A serious solution is not just:
	•	a pattern name
	•	a code snippet
	•	a complexity label

It must contain a valid machine.

Every solution entry needs these construction components:

1. Input interpretation

What is the data really?

2. Output interpretation

What exactly must be returned?

3. State

What minimum live information defines progress?

4. Update / transition

How state changes legally.

5. Invariant

What remains true after each change.

6. Initialization

What must be true before the first step.

7. Termination

When the process is complete.

8. Answer extraction

Where the answer is read from.

9. Complexity explanation

Why runtime is bounded.

10. Memory explanation

Why the footprint is bounded.

That means the real minimum requirement for a “solved problem” is:

interpretation + state + update + invariant + initialization + termination + extraction + proof

Anything less is incomplete.

⸻

Layer 4 — Transformation requirements

This is where your project becomes special.

Most people teach:
	•	brute force
	•	then optimized solution

But you are trying to teach:

how brute force transforms into optimized structure

This is much deeper.

A true transformation entry must include:

A. Source brute-force form

What naive search does.

B. Waste diagnosis

What exact repetition hurts.

C. Compression enabler

What hidden structural property allows the optimization.

Examples:
	•	overlapping ranges
	•	reusable prefixes
	•	shared subproblems
	•	monotone feasibility
	•	order after sorting
	•	merge-only connectivity
	•	prefix sharing
	•	local safe choice

D. New state

What optimized machine now stores instead of repeating work.

E. New proof

Why the new machine is valid and bounded.

F. Tradeoff

What is paid in memory, preprocessing, or complexity of implementation.

That is crucial.

Without this, optimization feels like magic.

So the system must require that every major family explain:

what is preserved, what is discarded, and what is newly stored

That is the essence of transformation.

