Layer 5 — Canonical requirements

A canonical archetype is not just a popular problem.

It must be a teaching anchor.

A canonical problem must satisfy:

1. Purity

It isolates one family or one dominant family clearly.

2. Contrast

Its brute-force baseline and optimized solution have a strong pedagogical contrast.

3. Transferability

It generates many mutations.

4. Invariant visibility

The core rule of the family is easy to see in it.

5. Drawability

It supports strong BF/Opt/complexity/memory visuals.

6. Proof teachability

Its correctness proof is representative of the family.

7. Scalability

It is not so weird that it only applies to itself.

That is why:
	•	Two Sum is a canonical
	•	Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters is a canonical
	•	Coin Change is a canonical
	•	Merge Intervals is a canonical
	•	LRU Cache is a canonical

But many hard hybrid problems are not good canonicals, even if they are impressive.

So the deep requirement is:

Requirement:

Canonicals must be chosen for transfer power, not fame.

