Layer 6 — Pedagogical requirements

This answers:

What must exist for a learner to genuinely internalize the pattern?

A chapter can be correct and still be pedagogically weak.

A strong teaching chapter needs:

A. One clean motivating brute-force baseline

The learner must see why optimization is needed.

B. One exact bottleneck diagnosis

They must know what repeated waste is being removed.

C. One clean canonical

The family’s identity must become memorable.

D. One mutation map

The learner must understand the family branches.

E. One confusion map

The learner must know what the family is commonly mistaken for.

Examples:
	•	sliding window vs prefix sum
	•	DFS vs BFS
	•	greedy vs DP
	•	heap vs sort
	•	two pointers vs binary search

F. One failure-mode section

The learner must know how they will likely get it wrong.

G. One drawing recipe

The family must be visualizable.

H. One code-shape skeleton

The learner must see how diagrams become code.

So the atlas must require not only correctness, but transfer-oriented teaching structure.

