Layer 9 — Memory requirements

Most tutorials treat memory as one complexity line.
That is far too shallow.

A full system must require every chapter to specify:

1. Input memory

What is already given.

2. Auxiliary memory

What extra structures are allocated.

3. Temporary memory

What appears briefly and disappears.

4. Persistent memory

What survives across the full run or across API calls.

5. Output-sized memory

What is unavoidable because the answer itself is large.

6. In-place reuse possibility

Whether input storage can be reused.

7. Peak simultaneous occupancy

Especially for queues, stacks, heaps, recursion.

This is necessary because memory is not just:
	•	O(1)
	•	O(n)

It is also about:
	•	lifetime
	•	sharing
	•	ownership
	•	growth law
	•	hidden copying

So the atlas must require explicit memory semantics, not just labels.

