Layer 10 — System architecture requirements

This is the deepest layer.

This answers:

What must be true for the whole manual to function as one coherent machine?

These are the hardest requirements of all.

1. Vocabulary consistency

One term = one meaning.

If “state” means wildly different vague things in different chapters, the system breaks.

2. Taxonomy consistency

The same problem family must not drift between conflicting classifications.

3. Canonical consistency

A canonical’s role must stay stable across the book.

4. Transformation consistency

The same bottleneck should map to the same optimization logic wherever it appears.

5. Symbol consistency

Same symbol = same role.

6. Diagram consistency

The same family should have similar visual defaults everywhere.

7. Proof consistency

Proof labels should be reused consistently:
	•	invariant
	•	exchange
	•	induction
	•	amortized
	•	halving
	•	one-touch

8. Chapter symmetry

Every chapter should answer the same big questions, even if emphasis differs.

Without this, the atlas feels like many good essays rather than one unified system.

