Part III — Requirement failure analysis

Now let’s go even deeper.

A good requirement system must also specify:

What does failure look like?

Because if you cannot diagnose failure, the requirements are incomplete.

⸻

Failure type 1 — Ontological failure

The system does not distinguish key entities clearly.

Symptoms:
	•	“pattern” and “data structure” get mixed
	•	“state” is used vaguely
	•	“canonical” means “famous problem,” not “teaching anchor”
	•	“variation” and “composite” blur together

Result:
The atlas becomes conceptually muddy.

⸻

Failure type 2 — Applicability failure

A pattern is taught as if it works more broadly than it really does.

Symptoms:
	•	“substring => sliding window”
	•	“sorted => binary search”
	•	“optimization => greedy”
	•	“graph => DFS/BFS”
	•	“recursion => DP”

Result:
Learners overapply patterns and fail on edge cases.

⸻

Failure type 3 — Construction failure

A pattern is named, but its state/update/invariant are never fully specified.

Symptoms:
	•	learner recognizes the family but cannot code it
	•	diagrams look right but no machine exists
	•	proofs cannot be articulated

Result:
Recognition without solvability.

⸻

Failure type 4 — Transformation failure

The atlas shows brute force and optimization but not the causal bridge.

Symptoms:
	•	optimization feels magical
	•	learner memorizes tricks instead of deriving them
	•	mutations become hard because the bridge was not learned

Result:
No transfer power.

⸻

Failure type 5 — Pedagogical failure

The system is correct but too hard to learn.

Symptoms:
	•	no canonicals
	•	no mutation maps
	•	no failure modes
	•	no confusion map
	•	no visual defaults

Result:
Knowledge stays fragmented.

⸻

Failure type 6 — Proof failure

The system gives answers but not reasons.

Symptoms:
	•	“works because it works”
	•	“heap is fast”
	•	“greedy is intuitive”
	•	“binary search because sorted”

Result:
No deep trust, no defense in interviews, no adaptation to new variants.

⸻

Failure type 7 — Memory failure

The system ignores storage semantics.

Symptoms:
	•	hidden copying not discussed
	•	recursion stack omitted
	•	output-sized memory mixed into auxiliary memory
	•	in-place reuse not distinguished from rebuild

Result:
Misleading complexity understanding.

