Part VI — Requirement dependencies

This is another deep layer people often miss:

Some requirements depend on other requirements.

For example:

You cannot define the invariant until you define the state.

You cannot define the state until you know the bottleneck.

You cannot know the bottleneck until you define brute force.

You cannot define brute force until you interpret the job and world.

You cannot justify complexity until you know the proof shape.

You cannot choose visuals until you know the state and proof.

That means the system has a dependency chain:

World + Job

→ Brute force
→ Bottleneck
→ Engine
→ State
→ Invariant
→ Proof
→ Complexity/Memory
→ Visuals
→ Teaching/Transfer

This is extremely important.

A lot of weak explanations reverse this and start with:

“Use sliding window.”

That skips the dependency chain.

Your system must require the chain to be preserved.

