Here is the full gold-standard chapter for one family:

Sliding Window

This is the model chapter.
Everything else in the atlas should eventually be written to this same standard.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

A sliding window solves problems about a contiguous region by maintaining one live interval instead of enumerating all intervals from scratch.

Instead of:
	•	start here,
	•	try every end,
	•	recheck the whole region,

the algorithm keeps:
	•	a left boundary,
	•	a right boundary,
	•	a compact summary of what is inside the current window,

and moves the boundaries monotonically.

Deep identity

Sliding window is a boundary-compression engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	many overlapping contiguous candidates

with:
	•	one moving contiguous candidate whose state is updated incrementally.

That is the true identity of the family.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

To place sliding window correctly in the atlas, fill the ontology slots.

World

Usually:
	•	array
	•	string
	•	stream-like linear sequence

This family lives in a linear world.

Job

Usually one of:
	•	longest valid contiguous segment
	•	shortest valid contiguous segment
	•	maximum/minimum score over contiguous region
	•	count of contiguous regions satisfying a condition
	•	detect whether some valid contiguous region exists

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is:
	•	a subarray
	•	a substring
	•	a contiguous segment

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	repeated rescanning of overlapping contiguous segments
	•	repeated recomputation of segment validity
	•	repeated counting of the same characters/elements across neighboring windows

Engine type

Sliding window is a:
	•	boundary engine
	•	contiguous live-state engine
	•	amortized interval-maintenance engine

State object

Usually:
	•	L
	•	R
	•	plus a summary of contents inside [L, R]

Invariant object

A one-line rule describing whether the current window is:
	•	valid,
	•	almost valid,
	•	or in a controlled relation to the target condition.

Proof object

Usually:
	•	monotone boundary movement
	•	each boundary advances at most n times
	•	helper-state updates are constant or bounded per move

Memory object

Usually:
	•	O(1) extra state
or
	•	O(alphabet), O(k), O(distinct), or O(n) helper memory if counts/maps are needed

That is the ontological fingerprint of sliding window.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This section is the single most important one.

A problem belongs to sliding window only if the following requirements hold.

3.1 Contiguity requirement

The target object must be a contiguous region.

Keywords:
	•	subarray
	•	substring
	•	contiguous
	•	window
	•	consecutive segment

If the answer is a subsequence, subset, permutation, or arbitrary path, sliding window is usually not the right base family.

3.2 Incremental update requirement

You must be able to update the window state when:
	•	one element enters on the right
	•	one element leaves on the left

This is essential.

Examples of incrementally maintainable state:
	•	sum
	•	count of items
	•	frequency map
	•	number of distinct characters
	•	maximum frequency among current chars in some relaxed problems
	•	current score if add/remove is local

If removing the leftmost element destroys information that you cannot repair cheaply, plain sliding window is in trouble.

3.3 Monotone boundary requirement

At least one useful strategy must exist where:
	•	R only moves forward
	•	L only moves forward

No chaotic resetting.

This is the amortization source.

3.4 Validity-control requirement

There must be a meaningful concept of:
	•	window valid
or
	•	window invalid but repairable by shrinking
or
	•	fixed-size window whose score can be updated locally

That means the window condition must be controllable from the maintained state.

3.5 Budget requirement

Sliding window becomes attractive when brute force over all subarrays/substrings is too expensive.

Typical signal:
	•	n around 10^4, 10^5, or higher
	•	O(n²) or O(n³) brute force is too slow

3.6 Locality requirement

The property must depend primarily on what is inside the current window, not on arbitrary nonlocal structure outside it.

This is why it works so well for strings and arrays.

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say when the family fails.

4.1 Non-contiguous target

If the problem is about:
	•	subsequence
	•	arbitrary subset
	•	arbitrary path
	•	non-contiguous selection

sliding window is not the base family.

4.2 Non-incremental validity

If removing the left boundary destroys a key property you cannot update cheaply, then standard sliding window fails.

Example pattern:
	•	the condition depends on a complex structure that cannot be reversed when an item leaves.

4.3 Negative-number trap

This is a classic failure.

Some people force sliding window on problems like:
	•	shortest/longest subarray with given sum
when values may be negative.

Why it fails:
	•	expanding right no longer changes the sum monotonically
	•	shrinking left no longer predictably improves validity

In such cases you often need:
	•	prefix sums
	•	hash map on prefix states
	•	monotonic deque on prefix sums
	•	or a different framework entirely

4.4 Exact global optimum with nonlocal interactions

If the value of a region depends on faraway choices or complex structural coupling, window state may be insufficient.

4.5 Need for random access to many past windows

If the problem is not about one live interval but about comparing many intervals globally under more complex rules, prefix-based or DP approaches may dominate.

So the family must explicitly warn:

Sliding window is not “anything with substring.”

It is only valid when contiguity + incremental maintenance + monotone boundary motion all hold.

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand sliding window, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 The canonical brute force

For strings/arrays, brute force is often:
	•	choose a start index i
	•	choose an end index j
	•	inspect the whole segment i..j
	•	test validity / compute score
	•	update answer

That creates:
	•	O(n²) candidate windows
	•	often O(n) validation per window
	•	total O(n³) in bad cases
or O(n²) if validation is optimized but enumeration remains

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because the problem statement usually names a window implicitly:
	•	“substring”
	•	“subarray”
	•	“contiguous”

So the mind naturally says:
“Let me try all of them.”

That is correct but too slow.

5.3 The actual waste

The waste is not just “too many windows.”

It is deeper:
neighboring windows overlap heavily.

For example:
	•	[0..5]
	•	[0..6]
	•	[1..6]
	•	[1..7]

share most of their content.

Brute force keeps re-reading the same middle region.

That overlap is the transformation opportunity.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

Sliding window is only meaningful when the bottleneck is diagnosed precisely.

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Repeated rescanning of overlapping contiguous segments.

6.2 Secondary bottlenecks

Depending on the problem:
	•	repeated recounting of characters
	•	repeated recomputation of distinct-count
	•	repeated recomputation of segment sum
	•	repeated testing of a validity condition

6.3 Hidden structural fact

When the right boundary moves from R to R+1, the new window differs by only one incoming item.
When the left boundary moves from L to L+1, the new window differs by only one outgoing item.

This is the key enabler.

So the diagnosis should always be stated like this:

Brute force wastes time because neighboring windows overlap almost completely, but it recomputes them as if they were unrelated.

That sentence is the heart of the chapter.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> sliding window

This is the causal bridge.

7.1 Source brute-force object

All contiguous windows.

7.2 Waste

Overlapping windows are revalidated from scratch.

7.3 Compression enabler

Neighboring windows differ by only:
	•	one added element
	•	one removed element

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	many independent windows

with:
	•	one live window [L, R]
	•	plus compact window summary

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	O(n²) or O(n³) many windows,

we now argue:
	•	R advances at most n times
	•	L advances at most n times
	•	each update to state is bounded
	•	total is linear or near-linear

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Often:
	•	O(1) extra if only sums/counts needed
	•	O(alphabet) or O(distinct) if counts/map required

That is the full BF→Opt transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

A sliding-window solution is only real when the state is precise.

8.1 Minimum mandatory state

Every window problem needs:
	•	left boundary L
	•	right boundary R

8.2 Common summary state

Depending on the variant:
	•	running sum
	•	count map
	•	set of seen chars
	•	distinct count
	•	max frequency in window
	•	score / cost / deficit
	•	count of target matches

8.3 Answer state

Usually:
	•	best_len
	•	best_range
	•	count_answer
	•	best_score

8.4 Good state test

A good state is:
	•	enough to determine whether the current window is acceptable
	•	enough to update when left or right changes
	•	no larger than necessary

8.5 Bad state

Examples of bad state:
	•	storing every window explicitly
	•	storing entire copied substring
	•	vague state like “current result so far” without definition
	•	storing information that cannot be updated on left-removal

So the state requirement is:

the maintained state must make window validity and answer update possible without rescanning the whole window.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

A sliding-window solution must explicitly state its invariant.

There are several invariant styles.

⸻

9.1 Valid-window invariant

Used for:
	•	longest substring without repeating chars
	•	at most k distinct
	•	many standard variable-size problems

Form:

The current window [L, R] is valid.

Meaning:
	•	after any shrinking step, the window satisfies the constraint again

This is the most common invariant.

⸻

9.2 Tight-window invariant

Used for:
	•	minimum window substring
	•	shortest valid segment

Form:

The current window is valid, and shrinking it would break validity.

This is stronger than just validity.

It is crucial when you want the minimum valid window.

⸻

9.3 Fixed-size invariant

Used for:
	•	max sum subarray of size k
	•	average of every size-k block

Form:

The window size is always exactly k.

Here validity is not about a condition; it is about size.

⸻

9.4 Relaxed-validity invariant

Used in tricky problems like:
	•	Longest Repeating Character Replacement

Form:

The maintained summary is enough to guarantee the answer remains correct even if the state is slightly stale in a controlled way.

This is a more advanced invariant style.

⸻

9.5 Counting-window invariant

Used for:
	•	count all valid windows
	•	count windows with at most k distinct

Form:

After shrinking, the window is the maximal valid suffix ending at R, so it contributes a predictable number of valid subwindows.

This invariant is more combinatorial.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Sliding window is easy to recognize once you see its update grammar.

10.1 Expand

Move R right by one.
Add arr[R] or s[R] into the window state.

10.2 Evaluate

Check whether current state is:
	•	valid
	•	invalid
	•	sufficient
	•	ready to update answer

10.3 Repair

If invalid, move L right until validity is restored.
While shrinking, remove outgoing items from the state.

10.4 Extract answer

Depending on the problem:
	•	update best length
	•	update best score
	•	count new valid windows
	•	record minimum valid window

This gives the family a standard machine rhythm:

expand -> evaluate -> repair -> extract

That rhythm should appear in the chapter.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where most learners get stuck.
They recognize “window” but do not know which subtype.

⸻

11.1 Fixed-size window

Identity

The window size is always exactly k.

Requirements
	•	the problem gives exact length
	•	score can be updated by dropping left and adding right

State
	•	L, R
	•	current window sum/score

Invariant

Window size = k

Canonicals
	•	maximum sum subarray of size k
	•	average of subarrays of size k
	•	fixed-length anagram search variants

Typical proof

Each element enters once and leaves once.

Common confusion

People overcomplicate fixed windows with variable-size repair logic.

⸻

11.2 Variable-size valid window

Identity

The window expands until invalid, then shrinks until valid again.

Requirements
	•	validity is incrementally maintainable
	•	shrinking repairs the violation

State
	•	boundaries
	•	counts/score/constraint summary

Invariant

After repair, window is valid.

Canonicals
	•	longest substring without repeating characters
	•	longest substring with at most k distinct chars
	•	max consecutive ones with at most k flips

Common use

“Longest valid contiguous segment”

⸻

11.3 Minimum valid window

Identity

Expand until valid, then shrink aggressively to become tight.

Requirements
	•	validity can be tested from maintained counts/deficits
	•	shrinking must detect when validity breaks

State
	•	window counts
	•	target counts or deficit counter
	•	current best minimum range

Invariant

At the moment you record an answer, the window is valid and as tight as possible for this R.

Canonical
	•	Minimum Window Substring

Difficulty

This is the hardest standard window archetype.

⸻

11.4 At-most-k window

Identity

Maintain windows satisfying a budget like:
	•	at most k distinct
	•	at most k zeroes
	•	at most k replacements

Requirements
	•	budget violation is easy to detect
	•	shrinking reduces violation

Invariant

Window always satisfies “at most k”.

Canonicals
	•	longest substring with at most k distinct
	•	max consecutive ones III
	•	count subarrays with at most k distinct

⸻

11.5 Exactly-k window via at-most trick

Identity

Some “exactly k” counting problems are solved as:

count(exactly k) = count(at most k) - count(at most k-1)

Requirements
	•	counting is easier under at-most form
	•	target metric is monotone with budget

Canonicals
	•	Subarrays with K Distinct Integers

Why it matters

This is a transformation inside the family itself.

⸻

11.6 Frequency-deficit window

Identity

The state tracks whether the window covers a target multiset.

Requirements
	•	target frequency map exists
	•	current window count map exists
	•	a compact “matched” or “deficit” metric exists

Canonical
	•	Minimum Window Substring

Difficulty

This is the archetype for matching/filling windows.

⸻

11.7 Counting contribution window

Identity

At each right endpoint, once the window is repaired, you can count how many windows ending at R are valid.

Requirements
	•	valid windows form a suffix or prefix class that can be counted in bulk

Canonicals
	•	count subarrays with at most k distinct
	•	count subarrays with score under threshold variants

⸻

12. Composite helpers

Sliding window is often not alone.

12.1 Window + hash map

For:
	•	arbitrary character frequencies
	•	distinct counts
	•	complements inside window
	•	deficit tracking

This is the most common composite.

12.2 Window + fixed count array

For:
	•	lowercase letters
	•	bounded alphabets
	•	digits
	•	small integer domains

This is a memory-optimized hash-map substitute.

12.3 Window + deque

For:
	•	window max/min
	•	monotonic candidate maintenance

This pushes the family toward monotonic deque territory.

12.4 Window + prefix logic

Used in more advanced counting/threshold problems, though often prefix-based methods fully replace plain windows in negative or non-monotone settings.

12.5 Window + binary search

Sometimes the answer is a length, and you binary search a length while checking whether some valid window of that length exists.

That is more advanced and less canonical, but important to note.

⸻

13. Canonical archetype library for sliding window

These are the anchor problems of the family.

⸻

Canonical 1 — Maximum sum subarray of size k

Why canonical

It is the purest fixed-size window.

What it teaches
	•	one item enters
	•	one item leaves
	•	sum updates locally
	•	window size stays constant

Why important

It is the easiest way to understand the family before maps/validity logic are introduced.

⸻

Canonical 2 — Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters

Why canonical

It is the purest variable-size valid-window problem.

What it teaches
	•	contiguity
	•	expand until invalid
	•	shrink until valid
	•	answer = maximum valid length

Core invariant

Window contains unique characters.

Why important

It is the first true “window validity” archetype.

⸻

Canonical 3 — Longest Substring with At Most K Distinct Characters

Why canonical

It teaches budget-based validity.

What it teaches
	•	budget = distinct count
	•	shrinking repairs budget overflow
	•	answer is longest valid window

Why important

It generalizes the previous archetype to a broader family.

⸻

Canonical 4 — Minimum Window Substring

Why canonical

It is the purest and hardest target-coverage window.

What it teaches
	•	target frequency deficits
	•	valid vs tight window
	•	minimum answer extraction

Why important

It is the “boss canonical” of classical sliding window.

⸻

Canonical 5 — Sliding Window Maximum

Why canonical-adjacent

It is not plain window alone; it is window + deque.

What it teaches
	•	windows sometimes need an auxiliary candidate structure
	•	not all windows can be solved with just counts or sums

This is important for composite awareness.

⸻

Canonical 6 — Subarrays with K Distinct Integers

Why canonical-adjacent

It teaches counting and exactly-k via at-most decomposition.

What it teaches
	•	counting contribution logic
	•	family-internal transformation:
exactly-k -> at-most-k difference

⸻

14. Confusion map

A gold-standard chapter must include what sliding window is confused with.

⸻

14.1 Sliding window vs prefix sum

Window

Good when:
	•	contiguous region
	•	dynamic live validity
	•	add/remove local maintenance

Prefix sum

Good when:
	•	cumulative range relation
	•	many static range computations
	•	negative values break monotone window logic

Key diagnostic

Ask:

Can I maintain the current region incrementally by moving boundaries,
or is the property really about differences of cumulative states?

⸻

14.2 Sliding window vs two pointers

Sliding window is a subtype of two-boundary reasoning, but not identical.

Two pointers

Often about:
	•	sorted arrays
	•	pair relationships
	•	monotone comparisons
	•	opposite-end geometry

Sliding window

Specifically about:
	•	one contiguous region
	•	live state of contents inside it

Key diagnostic

Ask:

Are both pointers jointly describing one evolving contiguous region, or are they comparing two positions in a broader ordered structure?

⸻

14.3 Sliding window vs brute-force substring enumeration

The learner often recognizes the same world but misses the transformation.

Key diagnostic:

Am I storing one window state, or am I recomputing every candidate separately?

⸻

14.4 Sliding window vs DP

Some contiguous-region problems tempt DP, especially when there is optimization language.

Key diagnostic:

Is the answer about one live interval that can be maintained locally, or about many overlapping nonlocal states?

⸻

15. Failure modes

A real chapter must say how people break the family.

⸻

Failure 1 — Forgetting contiguity

Trying to use sliding window on subsequences or arbitrary sets.

Failure 2 — Using it with negative numbers blindly

Especially for sum-threshold problems.

Failure 3 — No clear invariant

People say “expand and shrink” without stating what validity means.

Failure 4 — Wrong shrink condition

Shrink too early, too late, or until the wrong property holds.

Failure 5 — Updating answer at the wrong moment

For max window problems, answer may update after repair.
For minimum valid window problems, answer must update while valid before breaking tightness.

Failure 6 — Not removing outgoing contribution correctly

Classic hash-map/count bugs.

Failure 7 — Confusing exactly-k with at-most-k

Especially in counting problems.

Failure 8 — Overusing set instead of count map

When duplicates matter, set may be insufficient.

⸻

16. Correctness proof shapes

Sliding window needs explicit proof language.

⸻

16.1 Invariant proof

The main proof style.

Structure
	1.	Define window state and invariant.
	2.	Show initialization satisfies it.
	3.	Show expanding right updates state correctly.
	4.	Show shrinking left restores/preserves invariant.
	5.	Show answer extraction is correct because it uses windows only when invariant has the right form.

This is the family’s primary proof style.

⸻

16.2 Monotone-boundary proof

Used for complexity.

Structure
	•	R never moves backward
	•	L never moves backward
	•	each boundary advances at most n times
	•	helper updates per move are bounded
	•	total is O(n) or O(n * helper_cost)

This is the family’s primary runtime proof.

⸻

16.3 Tight-window proof

Used for minimum-window problems.

Structure
	•	expand until valid
	•	shrink while still valid
	•	therefore recorded window is tight for that right boundary
	•	minimum over tight valid windows is the answer

⸻

16.4 Counting-contribution proof

Used for counting problems.

Structure
	•	after repair, window represents the maximal valid suffix ending at R
	•	every left endpoint from L onward forms a valid subwindow
or the corresponding counting relation
	•	count contribution is derivable directly

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

This chapter must explicitly teach how the family proves time.

17.1 Single-pass fixed window

Each item:
	•	enters once
	•	leaves once

Total: O(n)

17.2 Variable-size window

Even with nested while, total remains O(n) because:
	•	R increases at most n times
	•	L increases at most n times

Nested syntax does not imply quadratic cost.

17.3 Helper-structure overhead

If each update is O(1)-average map/set/count work:
	•	total remains O(n)

If using a heavier helper:
	•	multiply accordingly

Example:
	•	window + balanced tree might become O(n log n)

This should be stated explicitly.

⸻

18. Memory requirements

A strong chapter must explain memory, not just time.

18.1 O(1) memory cases

Fixed-size sum window.
Simple scalar score windows.

18.2 O(alphabet) memory

Character frequency arrays for bounded alphabets.

18.3 O(distinct) or O(n) memory

Hash map/set for arbitrary characters/elements.

18.4 Peak occupancy

Window memory is not about total updates over time, but about:
	•	how big the helper structure can get simultaneously

Example:
	•	distinct-char map may hold up to all distinct symbols seen in current window

18.5 In-place relation

The family usually does not mutate the input structure deeply.
It relies more on external control state than on in-place rearrangement.

