21. Code-shape skeleton

A gold-standard chapter must also explain the code shape.

Sliding window usually follows one of these skeletons.

⸻

21.1 Fixed-size skeleton
	1.	initialize first window or start empty
	2.	expand right
	3.	once size exceeds k, remove left
	4.	when size is exactly k, evaluate answer

This is the easiest code shape.

⸻

21.2 Variable-size valid-window skeleton
	1.	for each R, add incoming element
	2.	while invalid, move L and remove outgoing elements
	3.	now window valid
	4.	update answer

This is the core classical window skeleton.

⸻

21.3 Minimum-valid-window skeleton
	1.	expand R until valid
	2.	while valid:
	•	update best answer
	•	shrink L
	3.	continue expanding

This is the “tighten while valid” skeleton.

⸻

21.4 Counting skeleton
	1.	expand R
	2.	shrink until validity restored
	3.	count contributions from the repaired window

This is common in at-most-k counting.

