23. Worked transformation recipes

Now make the family concrete.

⸻

Recipe A — Brute force longest unique substring -> variable window

Brute force

Try every substring.
Check whether it has duplicates.

Waste

Same letters are rechecked across overlapping windows.

Compression

Keep one live substring and a frequency/set summary.

New invariant

Current window has no repeated characters.

Update rhythm

Expand right.
If duplicate appears, shrink left until unique again.
Update maximum length.

Canonical

Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters

⸻

Recipe B — Brute force max sum size k -> fixed window

Brute force

Try every length-k subarray and sum it from scratch.

Waste

Adjacent windows differ by one leaving and one entering element.

Compression

Keep current sum.
Subtract outgoing item.
Add incoming item.

New invariant

Window size = k, sum equals sum of current window.

Canonical

Max sum subarray of size k

⸻

Recipe C — Brute force target-coverage substring -> minimum-valid window

Brute force

Enumerate every substring.
Check whether it contains all required chars with required counts.

Waste

Target coverage is recomputed over overlapping substrings.

Compression

Maintain count deficit or matched counter.

New invariant

Window validity is defined by whether all required counts are covered.

Tightening rule

Once valid, shrink left as far as possible while staying valid.

Canonical

Minimum Window Substring

⸻

Recipe D — Brute force count subarrays with exactly k distinct -> at-most trick

Brute force

Enumerate every subarray and count distinct values.

Waste

Distinct counts are repeatedly recomputed.

Compression

Count windows with at most k distinct using a standard variable window, then subtract at-most-(k-1).

New transformation

Exactly-k is reduced to difference of two monotone counting problems.

Canonical

Subarrays with K Distinct Integers

