Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Binary Search

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window chapter.

Binary search is one of the most misunderstood families because people think it means:
	•	“sorted array”
	•	“middle element”
	•	“halve the search space”

That is only the surface.

The deeper truth is:

Binary search is a boundary-finding engine over an ordered or monotone space.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	sequential testing of candidates

with:
	•	repeated elimination of a guaranteed impossible half.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

Binary search solves problems where the candidate space has an order and the truth of the target condition gives you enough information to discard half the remaining space.

This may be:
	•	a sorted array
	•	an index boundary
	•	a rotated structure with ordered halves
	•	an answer range
	•	a feasibility threshold
	•	a partition condition

Deep identity

Binary search is a search-space compression engine.

It is not fundamentally about arrays.
It is fundamentally about:
	•	an ordered domain
	•	a midpoint probe
	•	a monotone or boundary-defining response
	•	safe elimination of one side

That is the real family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Usually one of:
	•	sorted linear sequence
	•	index interval
	•	numeric answer range
	•	monotone predicate space
	•	partition space
	•	jump hierarchy / ordered structure

Job

Usually:
	•	find exact target
	•	find first/last occurrence
	•	find smallest/largest valid value
	•	locate boundary
	•	detect existence in ordered domain
	•	minimize maximum / maximize minimum
	•	find a partition point

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is:
	•	index
	•	value candidate
	•	answer candidate
	•	partition position
	•	threshold

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	sequential probing of an ordered domain
	•	testing candidates one by one
	•	linearly searching for the first/last valid point

Engine type

Binary search is an:
	•	ordered-space engine
	•	halving engine
	•	boundary-finding engine
	•	monotone-predicate engine

State object

Usually:
	•	lo
	•	hi
	•	mid
	•	sometimes best boundary candidate

Invariant object

A statement like:
	•	answer is inside [lo, hi]
	•	left side impossible, right side possible
	•	target, if present, remains in surviving region

Proof object

The proof shape is:
	•	halving / geometric shrinkage
	•	interval invariant preservation
	•	boundary monotonicity

Memory object

Usually:
	•	O(1) extra state
	•	sometimes plus checker memory if answer-space binary search uses helpers

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Binary search is valid only when all needed conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Ordered search-space requirement

There must exist a candidate space with a meaningful order.

This could be:
	•	sorted values
	•	sorted indices
	•	integer answer range
	•	monotone threshold range
	•	partition positions

Without order, binary search has nothing to exploit.

⸻

3.2 Midpoint-information requirement

After probing the midpoint, you must be able to conclude that one side is impossible.

That is the heart of the family.

Examples:
	•	arr[mid] < target -> left half cannot contain target in sorted exact search
	•	feasible(mid) is true -> maybe smaller answers are still possible, so right side or upper region can be discarded depending on objective
	•	left half sorted and target not in it -> discard left half in rotated-array logic

If midpoint gives no safe elimination, binary search is invalid.

⸻

3.3 Monotonicity or boundary requirement

There must be either:

A. Value-order monotonicity

Classic sorted array case.

or

B. Predicate monotonicity

A boolean condition like:
	•	false false false true true true
or
	•	true true true false false false

or

C. Ordered partition correctness

A partition condition where invalidity tells you which side to move toward.

This is the deeper generalization.

⸻

3.4 Interval-invariant requirement

You must be able to maintain a correct invariant over a surviving interval.

Typical forms:
	•	target is in [lo, hi]
	•	first true is in [lo, hi]
	•	smallest feasible value is in [lo, hi]

If you cannot state the interval invariant, your binary search is not yet sound.

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

Binary search is most relevant when:
	•	linear search is too slow
	•	candidate range is large
	•	checker cost is acceptable under log(range) repetition
	•	constraints suggest logarithmic or O(n log range) methods

Typical signal:
	•	huge value range
	•	huge n
	•	need first/last boundary
	•	brute-force candidate testing is obviously linear in a large domain

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where the family fails.

4.1 No monotonicity

If the property flips back and forth unpredictably, binary search is invalid.

This is the single biggest misuse.

4.2 Ordered-looking but not eliminable

Sometimes data has order, but midpoint does not let you safely discard half.

Order alone is insufficient.

4.3 Wrong search domain

People often binary-search the array when they should binary-search the answer, or vice versa.

Binary search must target the actual ordered candidate space.

4.4 Small domain with trivial scan

If the space is tiny, binary search may be unnecessary overhead.

4.5 Broken checker monotonicity

In answer-space search, if feasibility is not monotone, the outer binary search is invalid.

4.6 Hidden overflow / boundary mistakes

In low-level languages or sloppy implementations, midpoint and boundary updates can invalidate correctness.

So the family must explicitly teach:

Binary search is not “sorted => use mid”.

It is “ordered domain + safe half elimination + maintained interval invariant.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand binary search, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Sequentially test candidates:
	•	scan the sorted array linearly
	•	test each candidate answer one by one
	•	try each partition boundary
	•	increment speed/capacity/day threshold one step at a time

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because the candidate space is easy to imagine as:
	•	index 0, 1, 2, …
	•	value 1, 2, 3, …
	•	all possible capacities
	•	all possible days
	•	all possible partition points

So people say:
“Let me just try them in order.”

Correct, but often too slow.

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	treating the remaining candidate interval as if every candidate were equally plausible
	•	not using the information that midpoint testing rules out half the space

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time by probing candidates one by one in an ordered domain where each probe could have ruled out half the remaining space.

That is the exact bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Sequential exploration of an ordered candidate space.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

When the space is ordered and the predicate/value relation is monotone, one midpoint test partitions candidates into:
	•	impossible side
	•	still-possible side

That is the compression enabler.

6.3 Why this matters

Binary search is powerful not because it looks at the middle, but because the middle creates a guaranteed discard region.

That is the true bottleneck diagnosis.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> binary search

7.1 Source brute-force object

Ordered candidates.

7.2 Waste

Sequential candidate checking.

7.3 Compression enabler

Monotone value relation or monotone predicate boundary.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	current sequential probe

with:
	•	interval [lo, hi]
	•	midpoint mid
	•	possible boundary candidate if needed

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	O(n) or O(range)

we now argue:
	•	surviving interval shrinks geometrically
	•	number of probes is logarithmic

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Usually none beyond O(1), unless answer-space checker adds helper state.

That is the full BF→Opt transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Binary search state must be precise.

8.1 Mandatory state
	•	lo
	•	hi
	•	mid

8.2 Optional state
	•	ans for best boundary candidate
	•	checker-local state for answer-space search

8.3 Good state test

The state must be enough to say:
	•	what candidates remain possible
	•	what midpoint is being tested
	•	what boundary is currently best-known if boundary-style answer is used

8.4 Bad state
	•	vague “searching the middle”
	•	not knowing whether interval is inclusive/exclusive
	•	mixing exact-search and boundary-search semantics

So the state requirement is:

The state must define a surviving interval and a rule for how midpoint testing changes that interval.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

Binary search is impossible to reason about without a clean invariant.

There are several standard invariant families.

⸻

9.1 Exact-target invariant

Used for classic exact search.

Form:

If target exists, it is inside [lo, hi].

This is the simplest invariant.

⸻

9.2 Left-boundary invariant

Used for first occurrence / lower bound / first true.

Form:

The first valid position is inside [lo, hi].

Often accompanied by a logical partition:
	•	left side definitely invalid
	•	right side may contain first valid

⸻

9.3 Right-boundary invariant

Used for last occurrence / upper bound / last true.

Form:

The last valid position is inside [lo, hi].

⸻

9.4 Feasibility invariant

Used for answer-space search.

Form:

The optimal answer lies within the candidate value interval [lo, hi], where feasibility is monotone across that range.

Examples:
	•	all values >= X feasible
	•	all values <= X feasible
depending on the problem

⸻

9.5 Partition invariant

Used for median/partition-style searches.

Form:

The correct partition lies within the current search interval, and midpoint tells which direction the partition constraint is violated.

More advanced, but still binary-search family.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Binary search has a small but rigid grammar.

10.1 Probe midpoint

Choose mid.

10.2 Evaluate midpoint

Interpret one of:
	•	exact comparison
	•	predicate truth
	•	boundary condition
	•	partition condition

10.3 Eliminate half

Update lo or hi according to the invariant logic.

10.4 Preserve boundary candidate if needed

For first/last valid style searches, store candidate answer when midpoint qualifies.

This gives the family rhythm:

choose mid -> evaluate -> discard half -> repeat

That is the machine.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where the family really branches.

⸻

11.1 Exact-target binary search

Identity

Find whether/where a specific target exists.

Requirements
	•	sorted data
	•	direct comparison to target tells which half is impossible

Invariant

If target exists, it remains inside the surviving interval.

Canonical
	•	Binary Search
	•	Search Insert Position (adjacent variant)

⸻

11.2 Left-boundary / lower-bound search

Identity

Find the first place where a condition becomes true, or the first occurrence of a target.

Requirements
	•	boundary exists in ordered/predicate space
	•	predicate is monotone

Invariant

First valid position remains in interval.

Canonicals
	•	First Bad Version
	•	First occurrence in sorted array
	•	Lower bound

Why important

This is the most useful “real” binary-search variant.

⸻

11.3 Right-boundary / upper-bound search

Identity

Find last occurrence / last true / last valid.

Requirements

Same as left-boundary but mirrored.

Canonicals
	•	last occurrence in sorted array
	•	upper bound style searches

⸻

11.4 Rotated-array binary search

Identity

Search in a rotated sorted array.

Requirements
	•	array consists of two ordered blocks
	•	midpoint tells which side is sorted
	•	target range membership on sorted side is testable

Invariant

Target, if present, remains in surviving interval.

Canonical
	•	Search in Rotated Sorted Array

Why important

It teaches that binary search can work even when the whole array is not globally sorted, as long as midpoint still gives safe elimination logic.

⸻

11.5 Answer-space binary search

Identity

You are not searching the input itself; you are searching the space of possible answers.

Requirements
	•	candidate answers are ordered
	•	feasibility is monotone
	•	checker can test one candidate

Canonicals
	•	Koko Eating Bananas
	•	Capacity to Ship Packages Within D Days
	•	Minimize maximum / maximize minimum families

Why important

This is the most conceptually important generalization.

⸻

11.6 Partition-based binary search

Identity

You binary search a partition point rather than a raw value.

Requirements
	•	partition correctness condition is order-based
	•	midpoint tells which side violates partition balance

Canonical
	•	Median of Two Sorted Arrays

Why important

This is the advanced family mutation.

⸻

12. Composite helpers

Binary search often needs helpers.

12.1 Binary search + checker

The classic answer-space composite.

Checker may be:
	•	greedy
	•	linear scan
	•	prefix-based validation
	•	DP-ish feasibility in advanced cases

12.2 Binary search + sorted order

Often the sort step creates the ordered domain.

12.3 Binary search + prefix sums

Used when each feasibility check needs quick range info.

12.4 Binary search + rolling hash

Used in some substring/length-search problems.

12.5 Binary lifting / jump tables

Related conceptual family: repeated halving or powers-of-two jumps.

⸻

