14. Confusion map

A gold-standard chapter must include what binary search is confused with.

⸻

14.1 Binary search vs two pointers

Binary search

Good when:
	•	candidate space is ordered
	•	midpoint eliminates half

Two pointers

Good when:
	•	boundary movement itself carries logic
	•	sorted array but relation is pairwise and monotone by pointer movement

Diagnostic

Ask:

Am I probing one midpoint to discard half, or am I moving boundaries incrementally based on pairwise comparisons?

⸻

14.2 Binary search vs divide and conquer

Binary search is a narrow special kind of divide and conquer.

Not every recursive halving algorithm is binary search.

Binary search specifically requires:
	•	ordered candidate space
	•	midpoint test that discards one half without exploring both

⸻

14.3 Binary search vs greedy

Answer-space binary search often uses a greedy checker.

Diagnostic:
	•	if searching a threshold and checking feasibility -> binary search + greedy
	•	if directly constructing the answer with local-choice proof -> greedy proper

⸻

14.4 Binary search vs DP

Some optimization problems look like DP, but if the answer space is monotone and each candidate can be tested, answer-space binary search may be better.

Diagnostic:

Are we solving many subproblems, or just testing candidate thresholds?

⸻

15. Failure modes

A real chapter must say how people break the family.

Failure 1 — No monotonicity

Most common fatal mistake.

Failure 2 — Wrong invariant

People do updates without being able to say what interval still contains the answer.

Failure 3 — Wrong boundary updates

Using lo = mid or hi = mid incorrectly and getting infinite loops or skipping answers.

Failure 4 — Mixing exact search with lower-bound logic

These are not identical code shapes.

Failure 5 — Searching the wrong domain

Binary searching indices when the real domain is answer values.

Failure 6 — Broken checker monotonicity

In answer-space search, the checker must align with the optimization direction.

Failure 7 — Off-by-one at boundaries

Classic issue for first/last occurrence problems.

Failure 8 — Midpoint overflow / low-level implementation issues

Especially in C/C++/Java if midpoint is computed unsafely.

⸻

16. Correctness proof shapes

Binary search has two main proof families.

⸻

16.1 Interval-invariant proof

The default proof.

Structure
	1.	Define what the surviving interval means.
	2.	Show initialization satisfies it.
	3.	Show midpoint evaluation identifies an impossible half.
	4.	Show update preserves the invariant.
	5.	Show termination yields the answer.

This is the core proof grammar.

⸻

16.2 Monotone-boundary proof

Used for first-true / last-true style searches.

Structure
	•	predicate is monotone
	•	midpoint truth tells which side still contains the boundary
	•	interval shrinks while preserving the boundary

⸻

16.3 Answer-space checker proof

Used for Koko-type problems.

Structure
	1.	Define feasibility.
	2.	Prove monotonicity of feasibility over candidate answers.
	3.	Binary search the boundary where feasibility changes.
	4.	Use checker correctness + boundary logic to prove optimal answer found.

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

This chapter must explicitly teach runtime proof.

17.1 Halving proof

Each probe reduces interval size by a constant factor, usually half.

Therefore:
	•	steps = O(log n) or O(log range)

This is the family’s main proof geometry.

17.2 Checker multiplication proof

For answer-space binary search:
	•	number of guesses = O(log range)
	•	each guess costs O(check_cost)
	•	total = O(check_cost * log range)

This should be made explicit.

⸻

18. Memory requirements

Binary search is usually space-light.

18.1 O(1) state

Classic exact and boundary searches use:
	•	lo
	•	hi
	•	mid
	•	maybe ans

18.2 Checker memory

Answer-space search inherits the checker’s memory.

Examples:
	•	O(1) if greedy scan checker
	•	O(n) if helper arrays/maps inside checker

18.3 Recursive vs iterative

Recursive binary search adds call stack depth O(log n).
Iterative version stays O(1).

That distinction should be explicit.

