21. Code-shape skeleton

A gold-standard chapter must explain code shape.

⸻

21.1 Exact-search skeleton
	1.	initialize lo, hi
	2.	while interval nonempty:
	•	compute mid
	•	compare to target
	•	discard left or right half accordingly
	3.	return found or not found result

⸻

21.2 Lower-bound skeleton
	1.	initialize lo, hi
	2.	while interval exists:
	•	probe mid
	•	if condition true, keep left side including mid
	•	else discard left side through mid
	3.	return boundary

⸻

21.3 Answer-space skeleton
	1.	define candidate answer interval
	2.	while interval exists:
	•	probe mid
	•	run feasibility checker
	•	keep feasible or infeasible side depending on objective
	3.	return minimum/maximum valid boundary

⸻

22. Diagnostic decision tree for new problems

Use this mini decision tree.

Q1

Is there an ordered candidate space?
	•	no -> not binary search
	•	yes -> continue

Q2

Can one probe eliminate half safely?
	•	no -> not binary search
	•	yes -> continue

Q3

What is the domain?
	•	sorted positions/values -> direct binary search
	•	candidate answers -> answer-space binary search
	•	partition points -> partition binary search
	•	rotated ordered structure -> structured-half binary search

Q4

Is predicate/value relation monotone?
	•	no -> invalid
	•	yes -> binary search likely valid

