25. Final deep compression of the family

The irreducible statement of binary search is:

Binary search is valid when candidates live in an ordered space and one midpoint test can safely eliminate an entire half while preserving an interval invariant containing the answer.

And the irreducible teaching statement is:

The learner has mastered binary search only when they can name:
	•	the ordered domain,
	•	the monotonicity or boundary law,
	•	the surviving interval invariant,
	•	the subtype,
	•	and the exact reason one half becomes impossible after each probe.

That is the full gold-standard chapter for Binary Search.

The next best family to build to the same standard is Dynamic Programming.




Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Dynamic Programming

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window and Binary Search chapters.

DP is one of the most abused labels in algorithms.
People often say:
	•	“it feels like DP”
	•	“there are overlapping subproblems”
	•	“just memoize it”
	•	“build a table”

That is too shallow.

The deeper truth is:

Dynamic Programming is a state-compression engine over repeated subproblems.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	repeated recursive exploration of the same subproblems

with:
	•	one stored answer per meaningful state.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

Dynamic Programming solves problems where a large problem decomposes into smaller subproblems that repeat, and the future depends only on a compact state.

Instead of:
	•	recomputing the same choices again and again,

it:
	•	names each meaningful subproblem,
	•	solves it once,
	•	stores the result,
	•	reuses it everywhere.

Deep identity

DP is a repeated-subproblem compression engine.

The key is not “table” or “recursion.”
The key is:
	•	compact state,
	•	overlapping subproblems,
	•	reusable transitions,
	•	exact state meaning.

That is the real family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

DP can live in many worlds:
	•	sequence
	•	grid
	•	string pair
	•	interval
	•	tree
	•	subset space
	•	digit/number space
	•	graph-like state machine

So DP is not defined by input shape alone.

Job

Usually one of:
	•	count number of ways
	•	minimize or maximize cost/value
	•	decide reachability/feasibility
	•	compute best score under structured choices
	•	align/transform sequences
	•	optimize over subset/state space

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	recursive choice path
	•	partition split
	•	subset assignment
	•	path of decisions
	•	repeated subtrees
	•	repeated state transitions

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	recomputing the same subproblem/state many times

Engine type

DP is a:
	•	state engine
	•	subproblem cache engine
	•	recurrence engine
	•	dependency-graph compression engine

State object

Examples:
	•	i
	•	(i, j)
	•	(index, remaining)
	•	(row, col)
	•	(mask, last)
	•	(node, parent_choice)
	•	(l, r)

Invariant object

Usually:

Once dp[state] is computed, it equals the exact answer for that state.

Proof object

Usually:
	•	induction on state size/order
	•	DAG of state dependencies
	•	memo correctness by recurrence

Memory object

Usually:
	•	DP table
	•	memo map
	•	rolling rows/columns
	•	recursion stack if memoized DFS
	•	sometimes bitmask table

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

DP is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 State sufficiency requirement

There must exist a compact state such that:

everything relevant about the future depends only on that state

This is the hardest and most important requirement.

Examples:
	•	in House Robber, state i is enough
	•	in Edit Distance, (i, j) is enough
	•	in interval DP, (l, r) is enough
	•	in subset DP, (mask, x) may be enough

If the future depends on too much uncontrolled history, naive DP fails.

⸻

3.2 Overlap requirement

The same state must reappear across multiple brute-force branches.

This is what distinguishes DP from plain divide-and-conquer or plain recursion.

If no overlap exists, memoization may not help much.

⸻

3.3 Transition requirement

There must be a structured rule that computes one state from smaller or earlier states.

This is the recurrence.

Examples:
	•	dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], nums[i] + dp[i-2])
	•	dp[i][j] = ... from dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]
	•	dp[mask] = min over removing/adding one bit

If no finite transition structure exists, DP is not yet well formed.

⸻

3.4 Dependency-order requirement

States must form an acyclic dependency relation.

This can be:
	•	smaller index
	•	smaller amount
	•	smaller interval length
	•	fewer bits in mask
	•	deeper memo recursion over shrinking subproblems

If cycles exist, you need a different framework or a graph shortest-path style view.

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

DP becomes attractive when brute force is exponential or superlinear due to repeated states, but the number of distinct states is manageable.

Typical signals:
	•	brute force recursion is exploding
	•	n too large for exponential search
	•	state dimensions are small enough to store

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where DP fails or is overused.

4.1 No compact state

If you cannot define a small sufficient state, DP is not ready.

4.2 No overlap

If subproblems do not repeat, memoization gives little benefit.

4.3 State space too large

A valid DP idea may still be unusable if:
	•	state count explodes
	•	transitions are too expensive
	•	memory blows up

This is important:
not every correct DP is practical.

4.4 Greedy dominates

If a provably safe local choice exists, DP may be unnecessary.

4.5 Prefix/window/hashing simpler

Some problems tempt DP, but a simpler one-pass or window solution is stronger.

4.6 Badly chosen state

Many “DP problems” fail not because DP is wrong, but because the chosen state is wrong.

So the family must teach:

DP is not “whenever recursion exists.”

It is only valid when repeated subproblems collapse into a manageable exact state space.

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand DP, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Try all choices recursively.

Examples:
	•	take or skip
	•	insert/delete/replace
	•	split at every point
	•	choose next coin
	•	choose next item
	•	recurse on all partitions
	•	recurse on all subsets/paths

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because the recursive choice tree mirrors the statement:
	•	“do this or that”
	•	“cut here or there”
	•	“use this coin or not”
	•	“match these characters or edit them”

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is not just many leaves.

The real waste is:
	•	the same subproblem appears again and again in different branches

Example:
To compute the best answer from index i, many different earlier choice paths may eventually ask:

what is the best answer starting from i?

That repeated question is the DP opportunity.

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time by solving the same subproblem multiple times through different recursive paths.

That is the family’s bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Repeated evaluation of identical subproblems.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

The recursive tree is often much larger than the true state graph.

This is a deep insight.

Brute-force recursion looks like a tree.
But many branches lead to the same state.

DP collapses:
	•	big recursion tree
into
	•	smaller state DAG

This is one of the most important ideas in all of algorithms.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> DP

7.1 Source brute-force object

Recursive branches / repeated subproblems.

7.2 Waste

Same state solved multiple times.

7.3 Compression enabler

Subproblem answer depends only on compact state.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	many recursive paths

with:
	•	one table entry or memo entry per state

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	exponential recursion tree,

we argue:
	•	each state computed once,
	•	each transition evaluated a bounded number of times,
	•	total = states × transitions

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Usually:
	•	time drops drastically
	•	memory increases to store table/memo

That is the full BF→Opt transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

This is the heart of DP.

If the state is wrong, the DP is wrong.

8.1 What state must do

A good DP state must satisfy all of these:

Sufficiency

It contains all information needed to determine the future.

Minimality

It does not contain unnecessary history.

Exact meaning

You can write a sentence:

dp[state] = ...

Transitionability

You can compute it from other states.

Countability

Total number of states is manageable.

⸻

8.2 Common state forms

Single index

dp[i]
For:
	•	prefix/suffix problems
	•	linear pick/skip
	•	simple recurrence chains

Pair of indices

dp[i][j]
For:
	•	two-sequence problems
	•	substring/interval pair logic
	•	alignment

Capacity/value style

dp[i][sum]
For:
	•	knapsack
	•	subset sum
	•	coin-change reachability/count

Interval state

dp[l][r]
For:
	•	interval DP
	•	merging/splitting segments
	•	game intervals

Subset state

dp[mask] or dp[mask][x]
For:
	•	subset optimization
	•	TSP-like transitions
	•	assignment problems

Tree state

dp[node][option]
For:
	•	subtree optimization
	•	parent-child constraints

Grid state

dp[r][c]
For:
	•	path counts / path costs / grid transitions

Digit state

dp[pos][tight][other_flags]
For:
	•	digit DP over number constraints

⸻

8.3 Good-state test

You should be able to answer:
	•	what does the state mean?
	•	what smaller states feed it?
	•	why is no extra history needed?

If you cannot, the state is not ready.

⸻

8.4 Bad-state patterns

Examples:
	•	storing full path history when a smaller summary suffices
	•	vague “current situation”
	•	state too large to enumerate
	•	state missing a needed dependency

This must be taught explicitly.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

DP also has invariants, but they look different from window or binary-search invariants.

9.1 State-meaning invariant

The most important DP invariant is:

once dp[state] is computed, it equals the exact answer for that state.

This is the family’s core law.

⸻

9.2 Dependency-order invariant

In tabulation:

when computing a state, all states it depends on are already correct.

This is crucial.

Without correct fill order, tabulation fails.

⸻

9.3 Memoization invariant

In memoized recursion:

every memoized result matches the true recurrence answer for that state, and no state is recomputed after memoization.

⸻

9.4 Rolling-state invariant

In memory-optimized DP:

the retained rows/columns still contain every dependency needed for future transitions.

This becomes important for optimization.

⸻

10. Update grammar

DP has a different update grammar from window or search.

10.1 Define state meaning

Before any code, write:
dp[state] = ...

10.2 Identify dependencies

What smaller states feed this one?

10.3 Define transition

How do dependencies combine?

Examples:
	•	min
	•	max
	•	sum
	•	count
	•	boolean OR/AND
	•	choose best among options

10.4 Initialize base cases

The smallest states must be filled correctly.

10.5 Fill / recurse

Either:
	•	memoized DFS computes on demand
or
	•	tabulation fills in dependency-safe order

10.6 Extract answer

Where is the final answer?
	•	dp[n]
	•	dp[n][m]
	•	min(dp[last row])
	•	memo[start_state]
	•	max over final states

This is the DP machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where most learners need the taxonomy.

⸻

11.1 1D linear DP

Identity

State is indexed by one dimension.

Requirements
	•	recurrence depends on earlier positions or smaller values

Canonicals
	•	Climbing Stairs
	•	House Robber
	•	Fibonacci-style
	•	simple cost ladder

Proof shape

Linear state chain.

⸻

11.2 2D sequence DP

Identity

State tracks two sequence positions.

Requirements
	•	answer for prefixes/suffixes of two sequences depends on smaller prefix/suffix pairs

Canonicals
	•	Longest Common Subsequence
	•	Edit Distance

Proof shape

2D table with local dependencies.

⸻

11.3 Grid DP

Identity

State is a cell in a grid.

Requirements
	•	movement or dependency comes from local neighboring cells

Canonicals
	•	Unique Paths
	•	Minimum Path Sum

Proof shape

Cell depends on solved neighbors.

⸻

11.4 Knapsack / capacity DP

Identity

State includes capacity/target sum.

Requirements
	•	item choices affect remaining capacity
	•	total capacity/sum is manageable

Canonicals
	•	0/1 Knapsack
	•	Subset Sum
	•	Partition Equal Subset Sum
	•	Coin Change reachability/count/min variants

Proof shape

States over item index and remaining/used capacity.

⸻

11.5 Interval DP

Identity

State is a segment [l, r].

Requirements
	•	answer over interval depends on splitting or shrinking interval

Canonicals
	•	matrix chain style families
	•	game intervals
	•	burst balloons-type structures

Proof shape

Fill by interval length.

⸻

11.6 Tree DP

Identity

State is attached to a node, often with extra local option.

Requirements
	•	subtree answers combine at parent
	•	parent-child dependency is acyclic

Canonicals
	•	House Robber III
	•	tree independent-set style problems
	•	subtree path/score optimizations

Proof shape

Postorder recursion / subtree induction.

⸻

11.7 Bitmask DP

Identity

State tracks chosen subset as bits.

Requirements
	•	n small enough
	•	subset relation is central
	•	transitions add/remove one bit or move among subsets

Canonicals
	•	TSP-like problems
	•	assignment / subset optimization
	•	partition over small sets

Proof shape

states = subsets, transitions over bit flips/choices.

⸻

11.8 Digit DP

Identity

State tracks position in number digits plus restriction flags.

Requirements
	•	problem is over all numbers in a range with digit constraints
	•	tight/started/sum/parity/etc. state is manageable

Canonicals
	•	count numbers with digit properties
	•	digit sum / forbidden digit families

Proof shape

prefix-digit state machine.

⸻

11.9 Memoization vs tabulation

Memoization
	•	natural from brute-force recursion
	•	computes only visited states

Tabulation
	•	more explicit control
	•	avoids recursion depth
	•	makes dependency order visible

A strong chapter must explain both.

⸻

12. Composite helpers

DP often combines with other tools.

12.1 DP + memoized DFS

The most direct BF→Opt bridge.

12.2 DP + bitmask

For subset-state optimization.

12.3 DP + binary search

When a transition can be accelerated by ordered lookup.

12.4 DP + monotonic structure

For optimized transitions in advanced problems.

12.5 DP + prefix sums

To speed interval or range-based transitions.

12.6 DP + graph/topological order

If states form a DAG naturally.

