14. Confusion map

A gold-standard chapter must include what DP is confused with.

⸻

14.1 DP vs greedy

DP

Needed when future tradeoffs matter and local choice is not safely provable.

Greedy

Better when a local choice can be proven safe.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Do I need to remember multiple possible futures, or can one local best move safely represent them all?

⸻

14.2 DP vs backtracking

Backtracking

Explores all choice paths explicitly.

DP

Collapses repeated subproblems into one state.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Do multiple recursive paths ask the same subquestion?

If yes, DP is likely.

⸻

14.3 DP vs sliding window / prefix sum

Some problems that sound like optimization over arrays are easier with window/prefix methods.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is this really a repeated-subproblem problem, or is it a contiguous-region maintenance or cumulative-state problem?

⸻

14.4 DP vs graph shortest path

Some DP recurrences are really state-graph problems.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Are states and transitions better seen as a DAG/graph with path costs?

This matters in advanced formulations.

⸻

15. Failure modes

A real chapter must say how people break the family.

Failure 1 — Wrong state

Most common DP failure.

Failure 2 — State too big

Correct but infeasible.

Failure 3 — State not sufficient

Missing variable makes recurrence invalid.

Failure 4 — Wrong base cases

DP collapses immediately if base cases are wrong.

Failure 5 — Wrong transition

Using recurrence that does not match state meaning.

Failure 6 — Wrong fill order

In tabulation, dependencies not solved yet.

Failure 7 — Double counting

Especially in counting DP.

Failure 8 — Using full table when rolling state would suffice

Memory inefficiency.

Failure 9 — Calling everything with recurrence “DP”

Not every recursive formula with no overlap deserves DP.

⸻

16. Correctness proof shapes

DP needs explicit proof language.

⸻

16.1 State-meaning induction

The default proof.

Structure
	1.	Define exact meaning of each state.
	2.	Prove base states are correct.
	3.	Assume dependencies are correct.
	4.	Show recurrence computes the correct answer for current state.
	5.	Therefore all states are correct.

This is the family’s core proof grammar.

⸻

16.2 Dependency-order proof

For tabulation.

Structure
	•	fill order respects dependencies
	•	every referenced predecessor is already correct
	•	thus current state is correctly computed

⸻

16.3 Memoization proof

For recursive DP.

Structure
	•	recurrence is correct
	•	memo ensures each state solved once
	•	returned memo value is therefore correct for that state

⸻

16.4 Interval-length induction

For interval DP.

Structure
	•	base length 1 or 0 intervals
	•	assume all shorter intervals correct
	•	compute longer intervals from shorter ones

⸻

16.5 Subset-size induction

For bitmask DP.

Structure
	•	assume answers for smaller masks/subsets
	•	build larger masks via one-step extensions

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

This chapter must explicitly teach runtime proof.

17.1 States × transitions

This is the fundamental DP runtime law.

Total time

= number of states
× work per state

This must be taught as the core complexity geometry.

17.2 Memoized DFS proof

Even if recursion tree is huge, memoization collapses it to unique states.

17.3 Space proof

Space is usually:
	•	number of stored states
plus
	•	recursion depth if memoized DFS

17.4 Rolling-state proof

If only a few previous rows/columns/states are needed, full table can be compressed.

This is an important advanced optimization.

⸻

18. Memory requirements

A strong chapter must explain memory properly.

18.1 Memo table / DP table

Usually the main auxiliary memory.

18.2 Recursion stack

For memoized DFS, stack depth matters separately from memo table.

18.3 Rolling optimization

Some DP families allow:
	•	O(n) -> O(1)
	•	O(mn) -> O(n)

by keeping only needed previous states.

18.4 Output-sized memory

Usually not dominant unless returning actual reconstruction path/sequence.

18.5 Reconstruction memory

If you want not just the value but the actual chosen path/solution, parent/choice tracking may add extra memory.

This should be said explicitly.

