25. Final deep compression of the family

The irreducible statement of DP is:

Dynamic Programming is valid when exponentially many recursive paths collapse onto a manageable set of repeated states whose answers can be stored once and reused through a correct recurrence.

And the irreducible teaching statement is:

The learner has mastered DP only when they can name:
	•	the exact state,
	•	why it is sufficient,
	•	where overlap occurs,
	•	what the recurrence is,
	•	what the base cases are,
	•	and why the runtime is states × transitions.

That is the full gold-standard chapter for Dynamic Programming.

The next strongest family to build to the same standard is Greedy or BFS.



Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Greedy

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window, Binary Search, and Dynamic Programming chapters.

Greedy is the family people misuse the most.

They often say:
	•	“take the best option now”
	•	“sort and choose”
	•	“it feels optimal”
	•	“this is probably greedy”

That is not enough.

The deeper truth is:

Greedy is a choice-compression engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	many future branches

with:
	•	one locally chosen branch

only when that local choice can be proven globally safe.

That last part is everything.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

A greedy algorithm solves a problem by making a local decision at each step and never revisiting it.

It does not explore all futures.
It commits.

So greedy only works when the problem has a special structure:
	•	the local choice does not damage global optimality,
or
	•	any optimal solution can be transformed to include the greedy choice.

Deep identity

Greedy is a branch-pruning engine with a proof obligation.

Unlike DP, which preserves many futures, greedy keeps only one future.

So its real identity is:
	•	collapse branching,
	•	keep one path,
	•	justify that all other discarded paths are unnecessary.

That is the real family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Greedy can live in many worlds:
	•	intervals on a line
	•	sorted sequences
	•	resource assignment
	•	graphs with special structure
	•	jump coverage / reachability
	•	process/load balancing
	•	constructive output building

Job

Usually:
	•	minimize or maximize a quantity
	•	choose a maximum-size feasible subset
	•	construct lexicographically best/smallest result
	•	cover/merge/assign with minimal resources
	•	make a sequence of commitments online

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	subset of choices
	•	ordering of choices
	•	branching decision tree
	•	placement sequence
	•	future schedule possibilities

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	exploring many branches that differ only in local early choices

Engine type

Greedy is a:
	•	local-choice engine
	•	branch-collapse engine
	•	dominance-based engine
	•	exchange-argument engine

State object

Usually small:
	•	current chosen endpoint
	•	current resource usage
	•	current farthest reach
	•	current active interval
	•	current best candidate
	•	remaining budget

Invariant object

Usually:

the current partial solution is safe to extend optimally

This is the family’s deepest invariant.

Proof object

Usually:
	•	exchange argument
	•	dominance proof
	•	cut-style argument
	•	feasibility preservation proof

Memory object

Often:
	•	O(1)
or
	•	sort + O(1)
or
	•	heap-assisted O(k)/O(n) if active choices must be maintained

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Greedy is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Safe-choice requirement

There must exist a local choice that can be made now without losing optimality.

This is the heart of the family.

If you cannot justify that, greedy is not ready.

⸻

3.2 Dominance or exchange requirement

There must be a proof that the greedy choice dominates or can replace another choice in an optimal solution.

Typical forms:
	•	earliest finishing interval is always safe
	•	smaller current choice leaves more room later
	•	taking the locally best available resource preserves feasibility
	•	the greedy frontier strictly dominates any weaker frontier

This is what turns intuition into correctness.

⸻

3.3 Irreversibility requirement

Greedy commits.
So it only works when committed choices do not need to be undone later.

If future information can invalidate a local decision, plain greedy is dangerous.

⸻

3.4 Problem-structure requirement

Greedy works best when the problem exposes one of these structures:

A. Ordered dominance

Example:
	•	earliest finishing interval
	•	smallest end time
	•	largest immediate gain with proof

B. Coverage frontier

Example:
	•	jump game
	•	interval covering
	•	farthest reach so far

C. Feasibility threshold

Example:
	•	can continue only if current prefix deficit never goes below some condition
	•	choose minimal resource that keeps feasibility

D. Local canonical form

Example:
	•	lexicographically smallest construction under a safe rule

E. Heap-assisted active choice

Example:
	•	among all currently available options, choose best one

If the problem lacks such structure, greedy may fail.

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

Greedy is attractive when:
	•	brute-force branch search is exponential or combinatorial
	•	a local-choice proof collapses it to sort + sweep or one pass
	•	constraints make DP or search too expensive or unnecessary

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where greedy fails.

4.1 No safe-choice proof

Most common failure.

If you only have intuition and not a proof shape, greedy is not justified.

4.2 Future tradeoffs matter too much

If a local choice can damage unseen future potential in a non-recoverable way, greedy often fails.

4.3 Multiple futures must be preserved

If different future branches remain genuinely relevant, DP is often the right family.

4.4 Counterexample exists

A single small counterexample kills a greedy rule.

This must be emphasized heavily.

4.5 Local objective not aligned with global objective

Choosing the locally biggest/smallest thing is meaningless if it does not correlate with the real goal.

So the chapter must teach:

Greedy is not “pick the best-looking thing now.”

It is “pick a provably safe local thing now.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand greedy, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Try all subsets / all orderings / all schedules / all decision branches.

Examples:
	•	choose intervals in many possible orders
	•	try all start points
	•	try all next jumps
	•	choose different resource assignments
	•	test many candidate constructions

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because many greedy problems are naturally branching:
	•	pick this interval or that interval
	•	jump here or there
	•	assign this meeting room or another
	•	choose this coin / station / course / task

Brute force says:

explore all futures

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	many futures differ only in early local choices
	•	but some local choices dominate others so strongly that most branches are unnecessary

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time exploring many future branches whose early local differences can be collapsed by a provably safe dominance rule.

That is the family bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Combinatorial branching over local decisions.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

Some local decisions dominate alternatives.

Examples:
	•	choosing the interval with earliest finish leaves maximum future room
	•	choosing the farthest reachable frontier dominates weaker reach choices
	•	keeping the best active candidate is enough; weaker active candidates are unnecessary

6.3 Why this matters

Greedy works only when the problem has a compressible decision frontier.

That is the deeper diagnosis:
many branches are not equally meaningful.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> greedy

7.1 Source brute-force object

Branching future choice tree.

7.2 Waste

Exploring many branches whose local differences can be collapsed.

7.3 Compression enabler

A safe local-choice theorem:
	•	exchange
	•	dominance
	•	frontier dominance
	•	feasibility preservation
	•	sorted-order domination

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	many future branches

with:
	•	one current best local commitment
	•	plus enough small state to continue safely

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	exponential branch tree,

we now argue:
	•	one local choice can represent or dominate all other branches at this step
	•	therefore branch factor collapses to 1
	•	often total becomes O(n) or O(n log n)

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Usually:
	•	very small memory
	•	sometimes sort cost
	•	sometimes heap to maintain best active candidate

That is the full BF→Opt transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Greedy state is often small, but it must still be precise.

8.1 What greedy state usually contains

Examples:
	•	current end time
	•	current farthest reachable index
	•	current tank / balance
	•	current room allocation structure
	•	active intervals in heap
	•	current chosen digits/chars
	•	current load / budget / capacity

8.2 Good state test

A good greedy state is enough to:
	•	evaluate the next local choice
	•	preserve feasibility
	•	continue without revisiting past choices

8.3 Bad state patterns
	•	vague “best option so far”
	•	no exact definition of what is being optimized locally
	•	too much hidden future dependence not captured in state

So the state requirement is:

The state must summarize exactly what is needed to make and justify the next local commitment.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

Greedy invariants look different from DP invariants.

⸻

9.1 Feasible-prefix invariant

Form:

The partial solution built so far is feasible.

Examples:
	•	selected intervals do not overlap
	•	chosen assignments do not violate capacity
	•	current path/jump coverage is reachable
	•	current constructed string still satisfies constraints

This is the basic greedy invariant.

⸻

9.2 Dominance invariant

Form:

Among all partial solutions of this size/stage, the greedy one is at least as good as any alternative for future extension.

This is deeper and more important.

Example:
	•	among all ways to choose one non-overlapping interval so far, the one with the earliest finishing time is best for extending later

⸻

9.3 Frontier invariant

Used in reach/cover problems.

Form:

The current greedy frontier dominates all weaker frontiers considered so far.

Examples:
	•	jump game
	•	interval cover
	•	farthest reach

⸻

9.4 Active-choice invariant

Used in heap-assisted greedy.

Form:

Among all currently available options, the selected one is the best safe local choice.

Examples:
	•	choose room/resource/task/job from active pool

⸻

10. Update grammar

Greedy has a distinct machine rhythm.

10.1 Order the candidates

Often the first step is:
	•	sort by end time
	•	sort by start time
	•	sort by value/key
or
	•	scan in natural order if already ordered

10.2 Evaluate local choice

Look at the currently relevant candidate(s).

10.3 Commit

Take or reject one candidate irrevocably, or keep the currently best active one.

10.4 Update feasibility/frontier

Adjust the small greedy state.

10.5 Continue

Never backtrack.

This gives the family rhythm:

order -> evaluate local choice -> commit -> update frontier/feasibility -> continue

That is the greedy machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where the family branches.

⸻

11.1 Sort-then-greedy

Identity

Sort candidates to expose a local dominance rule.

Requirements
	•	sorted order reveals safe local choice

Canonicals
	•	Activity Selection
	•	Merge/Non-overlapping interval variants
	•	some scheduling problems

Why important

This is the most common greedy form.

⸻

11.2 Coverage/frontier greedy

Identity

Track how far the current choices can reach.

Requirements
	•	one frontier dominates weaker ones
	•	local update of farthest reach is meaningful

Canonicals
	•	Jump Game
	•	Jump Game II
	•	interval covering families

⸻

11.3 Resource-allocation greedy

Identity

Assign or schedule based on currently active options.

Requirements
	•	choosing best active option preserves or optimizes future feasibility
	•	often needs a heap

Canonicals
	•	Meeting Rooms II
	•	scheduling/assignment variants

⸻

11.4 Constructive greedy

Identity

Build the answer symbol by symbol / step by step.

Requirements
	•	local choice is lexicographically or structurally safe

Canonicals
	•	remove digits / construct smallest result style problems
	•	string/sequence construction families

⸻

11.5 Greedy with deficit/balance state

Identity

Maintain a local balance and restart/commit based on feasibility.

Canonical
	•	Gas Station

Why important

This teaches that some greedy proofs are about impossibility compression, not just “pick smallest end.”

⸻

11.6 Heap-assisted greedy

Identity

Greedy local choice among a dynamic active set.

Requirements
	•	active candidates change over time
	•	best current candidate needed repeatedly

Canonicals
	•	choose best course/resource/job among available
	•	some interval/resource scheduling problems

