14. Confusion map

A gold-standard chapter must include what greedy is confused with.

⸻

14.1 Greedy vs DP

Greedy

One branch kept, because local choice is provably safe.

DP

Many futures preserved because local choice is not yet provably safe.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Can all alternative futures be safely represented by one local choice?

If no, suspect DP.

⸻

14.2 Greedy vs binary search + checker

Greedy

Directly constructs/decides by local rule.

Binary search + checker

Searches threshold outside, then uses greedy inside as feasibility test.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Am I directly building the answer, or only testing a candidate threshold?

⸻

14.3 Greedy vs heap-only logic

A heap is not itself greedy, but often supports a greedy rule.

Diagnostic:

Is the heap just maintaining the best active candidate for a local commitment?

If yes, this is greedy + heap.

⸻

14.4 Greedy vs monotonic structures

Some constructive local-choice problems may look stack-like.

Diagnostic:

Is the stack/deque enforcing local choice order, or is there a deeper nearest-boundary invariant instead?

⸻

15. Failure modes

A real chapter must say how people break the family.

Failure 1 — No proof

Most common and fatal.
“Feels optimal” is not enough.

Failure 2 — Sorting by the wrong key

In interval problems this kills correctness.

Failure 3 — Local objective mismatch

Picking the locally biggest/smallest thing may not align with global optimum.

Failure 4 — Ignoring counterexamples

A greedy hypothesis must survive adversarial testing.

Failure 5 — Using greedy where branching matters

If future tradeoffs remain important, greedy collapses too aggressively.

Failure 6 — Wrong active-choice data structure

Sometimes the greedy rule is right, but you still need a heap or another helper to implement it correctly.

⸻

16. Correctness proof shapes

Greedy absolutely requires explicit proof language.

⸻

16.1 Exchange argument

The default greedy proof.

Structure
	1.	Let an optimal solution exist.
	2.	Show its first/next choice can be replaced by the greedy choice without worsening optimality.
	3.	Therefore there exists an optimal solution beginning with the greedy choice.
	4.	Repeat inductively.

This is the most classical greedy proof.

⸻

16.2 Dominance proof

Instead of swapping, show the greedy partial solution dominates any alternative partial solution for future extension.

Example

Earliest finishing interval dominates later-finishing alternatives because it leaves at least as much future room.

⸻

16.3 Frontier proof

Used in reach/coverage problems.

Structure

Show the current greedy frontier always reaches at least as far as any competing strategy after the same number of commitments.

This is key for Jump Game style problems.

⸻

16.4 Feasibility-discard proof

Used in Gas Station style reasoning.

Structure

Show that if a prefix fails, none of its internal starting points can succeed under the same deficit logic, so they can all be discarded.

This is one of the best advanced greedy proof styles.

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

Greedy runtime is usually justified by one of these.

17.1 Single sweep

One pass over ordered candidates.

17.2 Sort once then sweep

Total = sort cost + linear processing.

17.3 Heap-assisted ordered maintenance

Total = sort/scan cost + active heap operations.

17.4 Frontier/layer greedy

Still linear because state updates are bounded per element or boundary.

A strong chapter must connect the proof to:
	•	sorted order
	•	one-touch candidates
	•	heap operation count
	•	bounded frontier updates

⸻

