15. Failure modes

A real chapter must say how people break the family.

Failure 1 — Using BFS on weighted shortest-path problems

Most common conceptual failure.

Failure 2 — Marking visited too late

Can cause duplicate processing/explosion.

Failure 3 — No visited control

Classic infinite or redundant exploration issue.

Failure 4 — Losing layer semantics

If you need time/steps and do not track levels properly, answers go wrong.

Failure 5 — Running separate searches from many sources

Instead of multi-source BFS.

Failure 6 — Treating any queue-based process as BFS

Queue alone does not make a solution truly BFS-correct.

