16. Correctness proof shapes

BFS needs explicit proof language.

⸻

16.1 Layer optimality proof

The default BFS proof.

Structure
	1.	Source(s) start at distance 0.
	2.	BFS explores all states at distance d before any at distance d+1.
	3.	Therefore the first time a state is discovered, no shorter path could remain unexplored.
	4.	So first discovery gives shortest distance.

This is the core BFS proof grammar.

⸻

16.2 One-visit proof

For complexity and correctness.

Structure
	•	once a state is visited/discovered, it is not re-enqueued
	•	therefore each state is processed once
	•	each edge/neighbor relation is considered a bounded number of times

⸻

16.3 Multi-source proof

For nearest-source problems.

Structure
	•	all sources are inserted at distance 0 simultaneously
	•	BFS layers then represent minimum distance to the nearest source
	•	whichever source reaches first is optimal because of layer order

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

This chapter must explicitly teach runtime proof.

17.1 One-visit-per-state proof

Each state is enqueued/dequeued once.

17.2 Transition-scan proof

Each edge/neighbor relation is considered a bounded number of times.

Therefore:
	•	graph BFS -> O(V + E)
	•	grid BFS -> O(MN)
	•	implicit-state BFS -> O(number of reachable states × neighbor generation cost)

17.3 Multi-source BFS

Same asymptotic cost as single-source BFS; only initialization changes.

That must be stated explicitly.

⸻

18. Memory requirements

A strong chapter must explain memory.

18.1 Queue footprint

The queue stores the active frontier and possibly part of the next layer.

Peak size matters, not total pushes over time.

18.2 Visited footprint

Visited set/board often dominates auxiliary memory.

18.3 Distance/parent footprint

If path reconstruction or distances are needed, these add memory.

18.4 State-space blowup

Implicit BFS can be memory-heavy because the frontier and visited state space can become large.

This must be emphasized.

