25. Final deep compression of the family

The irreducible statement of BFS is:

BFS is valid when the state space has unit-cost transitions, so expanding a frontier layer by layer processes states in nondecreasing shortest distance and makes first discovery optimal.

And the irreducible teaching statement is:

The learner has mastered BFS only when they can name:
	•	the state space,
	•	the neighbor-generation rule,
	•	the frontier meaning,
	•	the unit-cost assumption,
	•	and the reason first discovery gives shortest distance.

That is the full gold-standard chapter for BFS.

The next strongest family to build to the same standard is DFS.




Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

DFS

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window, Binary Search, Dynamic Programming, Greedy, and BFS chapters.

DFS is often taught too loosely as:
	•	“go deep first”
	•	“use recursion”
	•	“use a stack”
	•	“good for trees and graphs”

That is surface-level.

The deeper truth is:

DFS is a path-expansion engine.

It removes brute-force chaos by replacing:
	•	unstructured exploration

with:
	•	one active path at a time, extended as far as possible before backtracking or returning.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

DFS explores a structure by following one branch/path deeply before switching to alternatives.

In recursive form, it means:
	•	enter a node/state
	•	recursively solve or explore one child/neighbor
	•	continue until a base/leaf/dead-end
	•	return/backtrack
	•	then try the next branch

It is not distance-ordered like BFS.
It is depth-ordered.

Deep identity

DFS is a single-active-path engine.

Its power comes from these facts:
	•	it keeps one path or recursive branch active at a time
	•	it is natural for hierarchical structure
	•	it is ideal when the answer depends on subtree logic, connectivity, path existence, or exhaustive constrained search
	•	it gives a clean mechanism for return-value aggregation and backtracking

That is the real family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

DFS naturally lives in:
	•	tree
	•	graph
	•	grid
	•	recursion tree
	•	implicit search state space
	•	trie/prefix tree
	•	hierarchical decomposition

Job

Usually one of:
	•	explore a connected region
	•	test path existence
	•	compute subtree information
	•	enumerate possibilities
	•	detect cycles/components
	•	traverse structure
	•	recursively aggregate answers

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	path
	•	branch
	•	subtree
	•	recursive choice sequence
	•	region/component expansion

Bottleneck type

DFS itself is often the base exploration engine, but it removes a different kind of waste than BFS:
	•	it avoids repeatedly restarting structured exploration
	•	it leverages hierarchical structure directly
	•	it enables local recursive return values instead of flat repeated scans
	•	in backtracking/memoized forms, it becomes the scaffold for pruning or state reuse

Engine type

DFS is a:
	•	depth-expansion engine
	•	single-active-branch engine
	•	recursive decomposition engine
	•	subtree-aggregation engine

State object

Usually:
	•	current node/cell/state
	•	recursion stack / explicit stack
	•	visited set if graph/grid
	•	current path in backtracking variants
	•	return values from children/substates

Invariant object

Usually one of:
	•	the current recursion stack/path is valid
	•	all descendants/substates of this node are solved before combining upward
	•	visited prevents re-entry into already explored states

Proof object

Usually:
	•	structural induction
	•	recursion correctness
	•	subtree-composition proof
	•	visit-once proof for traversal problems

Memory object

Usually:
	•	recursion stack
	•	visited set/board if needed
	•	current path if backtracking
	•	memo table if memoized DFS

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

DFS is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Path-extension requirement

The problem must admit a natural “continue along one branch” exploration.

Examples:
	•	tree children
	•	graph neighbors
	•	grid neighbors
	•	next recursive subchoice
	•	trie children
	•	next state transitions in a search space

If there is no meaningful branch/path expansion, DFS is not the natural base family.

⸻

3.2 Structural-recursion requirement

DFS is especially strong when the problem decomposes as:

solve children/substates, then combine.

This is the classic subtree/recursive requirement.

Examples:
	•	tree height
	•	subtree sums
	•	postorder aggregations
	•	path existence
	•	component painting

⸻

3.3 Return-value requirement

DFS is ideal when a node/state can return a value summarizing its substructure.

Examples:
	•	max depth below node
	•	whether target exists below node
	•	best score in subtree
	•	number of connected cells in component

⸻

3.4 Exhaustive-depth requirement

DFS is also appropriate when you genuinely need deep exploration or exhaustive search, such as:
	•	all paths
	•	all combinations
	•	search until dead-end then backtrack

This pushes the family toward backtracking.

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

DFS becomes attractive when:
	•	the structure is naturally recursive
	•	O(V+E) or O(MN) exploration is acceptable
	•	BFS layer order is unnecessary
	•	recursion depth is manageable or explicit stack is possible

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where DFS fails or is not ideal.

4.1 Shortest-path-in-unweighted-space objective

If the job is:
	•	minimum steps
	•	shortest path
	•	nearest source

plain DFS is usually the wrong primary family. BFS dominates.

4.2 Deep-recursion risk

If the structure can become very deep:
	•	skew tree
	•	long chain graph
	•	huge recursion depth

recursive DFS may fail in practice due to stack limits, though iterative DFS may still work.

4.3 Need for distance layering

If correctness depends on level order, DFS is not the right tool.

4.4 Repeated subproblem structure without memo

If the real problem is repeated-state optimization, plain DFS may explode and should often become memoized DFS / DP.

4.5 Dynamic best-first priority

If you need current globally best candidate from an active set, heap-based or BFS/Dijkstra-like logic may dominate.

So the chapter must teach:

DFS is not “graph/tree => recurse.”

It is “follow one valid branch deeply when structural recursion, component exploration, or path reasoning is the real shape.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand DFS, you must understand what it replaces or structures.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Without DFS structure, one might:
	•	repeatedly scan adjacency/children from scratch
	•	manually simulate path exploration in a messy way
	•	restart exploration from many places without visit control
	•	reason flatly instead of recursively

For search problems, brute force may also mean:
	•	all path exploration without disciplined stack/path control

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Many tree/graph/grid problems are inherently branchy:
	•	go left or right
	•	move up/down/left/right
	•	choose next neighbor
	•	try next candidate

DFS gives that branching a disciplined shape.

5.3 Actual waste

The waste DFS reduces depends on the context:

In traversal problems

Waste would be repeatedly rediscovering local structure instead of following it once.

In recursive-aggregation problems

Waste would be solving subtree logic non-recursively or repeatedly recomputing child facts manually.

In search problems

Waste would be exploring branch space with no clean path stack or backtrack mechanism.

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

DFS removes unstructured branch exploration by turning the problem into one disciplined active path or subtree computation at a time.

That is the family bottleneck statement.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Unstructured or repeatedly restarted exploration of branching structure.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

The structure already gives a recursive decomposition:
	•	node -> children
	•	cell -> neighbors
	•	state -> next states
	•	choice prefix -> extended choices

DFS exploits this directly.

6.3 Why this matters

DFS is powerful because it matches the shape of branching objects:
	•	trees are recursive
	•	graphs/components are expandable
	•	backtracking spaces are choice trees

That is the real enabler.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> DFS

7.1 Source brute-force object

Branching paths / subtree exploration / recursive choices.

7.2 Waste

Messy, repeated, or structure-ignorant exploration.

7.3 Compression enabler

The problem admits one active branch or subtree at a time, with local recursion/backtracking.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	scattered branch handling

with:
	•	one current node/state
	•	recursion stack / explicit stack
	•	visited/path state as needed

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	ad hoc exploration,

we now argue:
	•	each child/neighbor is explored under a valid recursive contract
	•	each state is visited once when appropriate
	•	return values compose correctly

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Time becomes structured and often linear in structure size, but memory is spent on:
	•	recursion stack
	•	visited/path state
	•	optional memo table in memoized forms

That is the full BF→DFS transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

DFS state must be precise.

8.1 Mandatory state

At minimum:
	•	current node/cell/state

8.2 Common additional state

Depending on subtype:
	•	visited set/board
	•	parent/reference to avoid back edge issues
	•	current path
	•	accumulated value along path
	•	subtree return values
	•	recursion depth or layer count if relevant
	•	memo cache in memoized DFS

8.3 Good state test

A good DFS state is enough to answer:
	•	where am I now?
	•	what next branches are legal?
	•	what local info must I carry?
	•	what value should I return upward, if any?

8.4 Bad state
	•	vague recursive calls with no meaning
	•	no visited logic in cyclic graph
	•	carrying too much history when a smaller summary suffices
	•	missing path state when backtracking constraints need it

So the state requirement is:

DFS state must define the current branch position, the rules for continuing, and any local information needed to return or backtrack correctly.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

DFS invariants differ by subtype.

⸻

9.1 Active-path invariant

For graph/grid/search DFS:

the current recursion stack represents a valid path/branch from the start of the current DFS expansion.

This is the basic path invariant.

⸻

9.2 Visit-control invariant

For traversal/component DFS:

any state marked visited will not be re-entered, so exploration is finite and non-redundant.

This is essential in graphs and grids.

⸻

9.3 Subtree-solved invariant

For tree/subtree DP-style DFS:

when returning from a node, all necessary child information has already been computed correctly.

This is the core recursive-aggregation invariant.

⸻

9.4 Backtracking invariant

For exhaustive choice search:

the current partial construction/path remains valid under all constraints.

This is the bridge toward backtracking.

⸻

10. Update grammar

DFS has a rigid grammar.

10.1 Enter

Move into a node/state.

10.2 Mark / record

If needed:
	•	mark visited
	•	add to path
	•	initialize local accumulators

10.3 Expand

Choose one neighbor/child/next state and recurse or push deeper.

10.4 Return / backtrack

After deeper branch finishes:
	•	combine child info
	•	remove from path if backtracking
	•	continue to next child if needed

This gives the DFS rhythm:

enter -> mark -> recurse deeper -> return/backtrack -> continue siblings

That is the family machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where the family branches.

⸻

11.1 Tree traversal DFS

Identity

Recursively traverse tree structure.

Requirements
	•	children are acyclic descendants
	•	recursive entry order matters

Canonicals
	•	preorder / inorder / postorder
	•	max depth
	•	path sum

Why important

This is the gentlest DFS form.

⸻

11.2 Graph/grid component DFS

Identity

Explore a connected region.

Requirements
	•	neighbors locally generatable
	•	visited control required

Canonicals
	•	Number of Islands
	•	graph connectivity / component counting

Why important

This is the most common DFS form outside trees.

⸻

11.3 DFS with return values

Identity

Children/substates return summaries that are combined upward.

Requirements
	•	problem decomposes into subresults
	•	upward combination rule exists

Canonicals
	•	tree height
	•	subtree sums
	•	balanced-tree checks
	•	tree DP foundations

Why important

This is the core recursive-aggregation form.

⸻

11.4 Path-existence / target-search DFS

Identity

Search deeply until target/dead-end.

Requirements
	•	path existence matters more than shortest path
	•	pruning or early exit may help

Canonicals
	•	path existence in graph/grid/tree
	•	some maze/word-search baselines

⸻

11.5 Backtracking DFS

Identity

DFS over a choice tree with undo.

Requirements
	•	need all or many valid constructions
	•	partial solution constraints matter
	•	undo is required after each recursive branch

Canonicals
	•	Subsets
	•	Permutations
	•	N-Queens
	•	Combination Sum

Why important

This is DFS expanded into exhaustive constrained search.

⸻

11.6 Memoized DFS

Identity

DFS over repeated states with memoization.

Requirements
	•	repeated states
	•	compact memo key
	•	recursive formulation natural

Canonicals
	•	Word Break style memoized recursion
	•	many top-down DP formulations

Why important

This is the bridge from DFS to DP.

