16. Correctness proof shapes

DFS needs explicit proof language.

⸻

16.1 Structural recursion proof

Default for tree DFS.

Structure
	1.	define what the function returns/guarantees for a node
	2.	prove base case
	3.	assume correctness for children
	4.	combine children correctly for current node

This is the core DFS proof grammar.

⸻

16.2 One-visit proof

For graph/grid exploration.

Structure
	•	each state is marked when explored
	•	visited prevents re-entry
	•	therefore every reachable state is processed at most once
	•	region/component is fully covered by recursive expansion

⸻

16.3 Path-validity proof

For path-search and backtracking.

Structure
	•	current recursion path satisfies constraints
	•	recursive extension tries all legal next choices
	•	backtracking restores state after each branch
	•	therefore all valid branches are considered and no invalid state leaks

⸻

16.4 Memoized DFS proof

For DFS + memo.

Structure
	•	recursive definition is correct
	•	memo stores exact result for each state
	•	repeated states reuse stored answers
	•	each state solved once

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

This chapter must explicitly teach runtime proof.

17.1 One-visit-per-state proof

For graph/grid/tree traversal:
	•	each node/cell/state visited once
	•	each neighbor/edge considered bounded times

Therefore:
	•	tree DFS -> O(n)
	•	graph DFS -> O(V+E)
	•	grid DFS -> O(MN)

17.2 Branching-search proof

For backtracking DFS:
	•	time depends on branch factor and depth
	•	DFS is the engine, but complexity may still be exponential

17.3 Memoized DFS proof

For repeated-state DFS:
	•	unique states × transitions

That must be said explicitly, because plain DFS and memoized DFS have very different complexity profiles.

