14. Confusion map

⸻

14.1 Two Pointers vs Sliding Window

Two Pointers

Primary when:
	•	pair relation, compaction, merge, cycle, or symmetric expansion is central

Sliding Window

Primary when:
	•	both boundaries describe one live contiguous region whose internal state matters

Diagnostic

Ask:

Am I maintaining one evolving region with internal contents, or just coordinating two positions for elimination/compaction/merge?

⸻

14.2 Two Pointers vs Binary Search

Two Pointers

Uses monotone boundary movement across many adjacent states.

Binary Search

Uses midpoint probes to discard half the domain.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Am I halving a search space, or moving boundaries stepwise based on local relation?

⸻

14.3 Two Pointers vs Hashing

For pair problems:

Hashing

Good for unsorted direct complement lookup.

Two Pointers

Good when order is present or can be created and exploited.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is order the real tool, or is keyed lookup the real tool?

⸻

14.4 Two Pointers vs Greedy

Some opposite-end pointer problems are really local-choice greedy on a line.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the key proof about safe pointer elimination from order, or about a local dominance rule independent of pointer mechanics?

