15. Failure modes

Failure 1 — No safe move rule

Most common conceptual failure.

Failure 2 — Using opposite-end logic on unsorted data without justification

Fatal unless sorting is part of the plan.

Failure 3 — Confusing window problems with generic two pointers

Leads to missing internal-state maintenance.

Failure 4 — Broken write-pointer invariant

Common in in-place compaction.

Failure 5 — Fast/slow misuse

Advancing wrong amounts or misreading collision/middle semantics.

Failure 6 — Merge invariant bugs

Incorrect output or missed tail cleanup.

Failure 7 — Off-by-one and center handling issues

Common in center-expansion problems.

