16. Correctness proof shapes

⸻

16.1 Elimination proof

Default for opposite-end sorted problems.

Structure
	1.	define current candidate region [L, R]
	2.	show current comparison rules out one side safely
	3.	moving the chosen pointer preserves correctness

This is the classic opposite-end proof grammar.

⸻

16.2 Processed-prefix proof

Default for compaction.

Structure
	•	before write pointer: correct processed output
	•	read pointer examines next input
	•	writing chosen elements preserves prefix correctness

⸻

16.3 Relative-motion proof

Default for fast/slow.

Structure
	•	define relation between slow and fast after each step
	•	prove eventual consequence (meeting/middle/etc.)

⸻

16.4 Merge proof

Default for ordered-stream merging.

Structure
	•	output built so far is correct for already-consumed input
	•	choosing smaller head next preserves sorted merge correctness

⸻

16.5 Symmetry proof

Default for center expansion.

Structure
	•	current inner region is symmetric
	•	if outer chars match, expanded region remains symmetric

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

17.1 Monotone movement proof

Most important.

Each pointer advances at most a bounded number of times:
	•	left ≤ n
	•	right ≤ n
	•	read ≤ n
	•	write ≤ n
	•	each list pointer ≤ length

Therefore total time is linear or near-linear.

17.2 Sort + Two Pointers

If sorting is added:
	•	total = O(n log n) + pointer sweep

17.3 Merge proof

Each stream pointer moves across its sequence once.

This chapter must explicitly teach that nested-looking pointer logic is often still linear due to monotone advancement.

