25. Final deep compression of the family

The irreducible statement of Two Pointers is:

Two Pointers is valid when two coordinated monotone positions can encode safe elimination, compaction, merge progress, relative motion, or symmetric expansion more efficiently than repeated independent checks.

And the irreducible teaching statement is:

The learner has mastered Two Pointers only when they can name:
	•	the two pointer roles,
	•	the processed/eliminated region,
	•	the safe move rule,
	•	the subtype,
	•	and why neither pointer needs chaotic reset.

The next strongest chapter to build is Prefix Sum / Prefix State.



Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Prefix Sum / Prefix State

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window, Binary Search, Dynamic Programming, Greedy, BFS, DFS, Hashing, and Two Pointers chapters.

Prefix Sum is often taught too narrowly as:
	•	“precompute sums”
	•	“range sum = prefix[r] - prefix[l-1]”
	•	“good for subarray sums”

That is only the surface.

The deeper truth is:

Prefix Sum / Prefix State is a cumulative-state compression engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	repeated recomputation of range or prefix-dependent facts

with:
	•	one running cumulative state that makes later answers derivable by difference, comparison, or lookup.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

Prefix methods precompute or maintain cumulative information from the start up to each position.

Instead of:
	•	recomputing sums/counts/balances for many ranges,

they:
	•	accumulate information once,
	•	store or carry it,
	•	derive later answers from prefix relations.

Deep identity

Prefix Sum is not just about “sum.”
It is about prefix state.

That state may be:
	•	numeric sum,
	•	xor,
	•	parity,
	•	modulo remainder,
	•	balance,
	•	count vector,
	•	signed difference,
	•	cumulative score.

So the true family is:

Prefix State = cumulative representation of everything up to a boundary

This is why the family is much broader than plain addition.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Prefix methods naturally live in:
	•	array / sequence
	•	string
	•	grid (2D prefix)
	•	stream-like prefix history
	•	cumulative numeric state space

Job

Usually one of:
	•	answer many range queries
	•	detect/count subarrays with property
	•	compare prefix balances
	•	derive interval property from cumulative states
	•	speed up repeated range recomputation

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	range sum/count/score query
	•	subarray total
	•	cumulative relation over an interval
	•	repeated prefix scan

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	recomputing overlapping prefixes or ranges from scratch

Engine type

Prefix State is a:
	•	cumulative-memory engine
	•	range-difference engine
	•	interval-derivation engine

State object

Usually:
	•	prefix[i]
or a running cumulative state like:
	•	sum
	•	xor
	•	remainder
	•	balance
	•	signed count difference

Invariant object

Usually:

prefix state at position i summarizes exactly the cumulative information up to i

Proof object

Usually:
	•	prefix decomposition
	•	interval = prefix(right) - prefix(left boundary)
	•	equality/difference relation on cumulative states

Memory object

Usually:
	•	O(n) prefix table
or
	•	O(1) running prefix state in streaming scan
or
	•	O(number of distinct prefix states) if combined with hashing

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Prefix State is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Cumulative-decomposability requirement

The target property must be derivable from cumulative information.

Classic example:
	•	sum of [l..r] = prefix[r] - prefix[l-1]

Generalized examples:
	•	equal counts of 0/1 from equal prefix balances
	•	subarray sum k from difference of prefix sums
	•	remainder property from differences of prefix remainders
	•	parity property from prefix parity state

If the interval property cannot be expressed in terms of cumulative states, prefix methods are not primary.

⸻

3.2 Overlap requirement

The brute-force ranges must overlap heavily so recomputation is wasteful.

This is what makes prefix compression valuable.

⸻

3.3 Prefix-state sufficiency requirement

The chosen cumulative state must be enough to recover the needed interval fact.

Examples:
	•	plain sum for range totals
	•	modulo remainder for divisibility
	•	signed balance for equal counts
	•	count vector for some advanced frequency-prefix formulations

If the prefix state is too weak, interval answers cannot be derived.

⸻

3.4 Static-or-streaming requirement

Prefix methods are strongest when:
	•	the input is static and many queries are asked,
or
	•	one sweep over prefixes is enough to answer the problem.

If there are many dynamic point/range updates, plain prefix structures may fail and range structures may be needed.

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

Prefix methods become attractive when:
	•	O(n²) range enumeration or repeated scanning is too expensive
	•	many queries exist
	•	O(n) preprocessing or O(n) scan is acceptable

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where the family fails.

4.1 No cumulative representation

If the property does not reduce to prefix relation, prefix methods are not primary.

4.2 Dynamic updates

If the data changes frequently and queries continue, plain prefix arrays are often insufficient.
Then you may need:
	•	Fenwick tree
	•	segment tree
	•	other range-update/query structures

4.3 Need for live-window validity rather than cumulative difference

If the real problem is maintaining one active contiguous region with add/remove updates, Sliding Window may be primary.

4.4 Nonlocal state not representable by prefix summary

If the needed information is not compressible into a manageable cumulative state, prefix methods are weak.

So the chapter must teach:

Prefix methods are not “anything with subarray.”

They are valid when the interval fact is recoverable from cumulative states.

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand Prefix State, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Typical brute-force forms:
	•	for each range, sum elements from scratch
	•	for each subarray, compute total/count by scanning
	•	for each query, rescan from left to right
	•	recompute cumulative relation repeatedly

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because many problems naturally say:
	•	“sum of this range”
	•	“subarray total”
	•	“how many equal 0s and 1s between here and there”
	•	“is there a subarray with property X”

The naive reaction is:

calculate that interval directly

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	many ranges share the same large prefixes
	•	but brute force recomputes those shared prefixes repeatedly

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time by recomputing overlapping cumulative portions of many ranges as if they were unrelated.

That is the family bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Repeated recomputation of cumulative information.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

Intervals can often be understood as differences between two prefixes.

This is the family’s central theorem.

6.3 Why this matters

Once you have the right prefix state, many interval problems collapse from:
	•	direct interval computation

to:
	•	relation between two cumulative states

That is the real enabler.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> Prefix State

7.1 Source brute-force object

Intervals/ranges repeatedly recomputed from scratch.

7.2 Waste

Repeated scanning of shared prefixes.

7.3 Compression enabler

Cumulative state is compositional:
the state up to one boundary and another boundary determines the interval between them.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	many separate interval computations

with:
	•	one cumulative state per prefix
or
	•	one running prefix state

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	O(length of interval) per query/check,

we now argue:
	•	prefix values are computed once
	•	interval facts are derived in O(1) or bounded lookup time
	•	total becomes O(n), O(n+q), or O(n + number of prefix-state operations)

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Time drops, but memory may increase to:
	•	O(n) prefix array
	•	O(distinct prefix states) with hash support
	•	O(1) if using only a running cumulative value and immediate output

That is the full BF→Prefix-State transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Prefix state must be precise.

8.1 What prefix state means

A good prefix state must summarize everything needed from the start up to the current position.

8.2 Common state forms

Sum prefix

prefix[i] = sum(nums[0..i])

Count prefix

prefix[i] = count of target items up to i

Balance prefix

prefix[i] = (#ones - #zeros) up to i

Remainder prefix

prefix[i] = (sum up to i) mod k

XOR prefix

prefix[i] = xor up to i

2D prefix

Cumulative rectangle sum up to (r, c)

8.3 Good state test

A good prefix state is enough to answer:
	•	what is the interval fact between two boundaries?
	•	what relation between prefix states corresponds to the desired property?

8.4 Bad state
	•	prefix state too weak to recover interval property
	•	prefix state too large/heavy without necessity
	•	forgetting the empty-prefix state

So the state requirement is:

The prefix state must be exactly the cumulative summary whose relation across two boundaries reveals the desired interval fact.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

9.1 Prefix-summary invariant

The fundamental invariant.

Form:

prefix state at index i exactly summarizes the cumulative information from the start through i.

This is the family’s main law.

⸻

9.2 Difference/relationship invariant

For interval queries or subarray detection.

Form:

the desired interval property corresponds to a specific relation between two prefix states.

Examples:
	•	difference = k
	•	equality of balances
	•	equality/mod relation of remainders

This is the key generalized invariant.

⸻

9.3 Empty-prefix invariant

Often essential.

Form:

before processing any element, the prefix state represents the empty prefix correctly.

This is critical in many subarray problems.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Prefix State has a rigid grammar.

10.1 Initialize empty prefix

Set base cumulative state before first item.

10.2 Extend

Consume next item and update cumulative state.

10.3 Store or use

Either:
	•	store cumulative state in prefix array,
or
	•	immediately use the current state in a one-pass scan

10.4 Derive interval relation

Use difference/equality/lookup between prefix states.

This gives the family rhythm:

initialize -> extend prefix state -> derive/use relation -> continue

That is the machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

⸻

11.1 Plain prefix sum array

Identity

Store cumulative sums for direct range queries.

Requirements
	•	interval totals derive by subtraction
	•	data static

Canonicals
	•	Range Sum Query
	•	Product/aggregate cousins where cumulative structure works

Why important

This is the simplest entry point.

⸻

11.2 Running prefix state in one scan

Identity

No full prefix array needed; just carry current cumulative state while solving on the fly.

Requirements
	•	answer can be built during the scan

Canonicals
	•	many subarray-count/detection problems
	•	prefix-hash combinations

Why important

Shows the family is broader than offline arrays.

⸻

11.3 Prefix state + hashing

Identity

Store previous prefix states in a map/set to detect/count relations.

Requirements
	•	the desired interval fact corresponds to relation among prefix states
	•	repeated prefix lookup matters

Canonicals
	•	Subarray Sum Equals K
	•	Continuous Subarray Sum
	•	equal 0/1 count families

Why important

This is the most important mutation of the family.

⸻

11.4 Prefix xor / parity / modulo

Identity

Cumulative state is not plain sum but another compositional summary.

Canonicals
	•	xor interval logic
	•	remainder divisibility subarrays
	•	parity-based subarray problems

Why important

Shows the family is about cumulative state, not only arithmetic addition.

⸻

11.5 2D prefix sums

Identity

Store cumulative rectangle information.

Requirements
	•	rectangle queries decompose by inclusion-exclusion

Canonicals
	•	2D range sum query
	•	submatrix aggregate queries

Why important

This is the dimensional generalization.

⸻

11.6 Difference array / prefix restoration

Identity

Store change events and recover final values by prefix accumulation.

Why important

This is a cousin technique in the same cumulative-state family.

⸻

