Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Monotonic Stack / Deque

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window, Binary Search, Dynamic Programming, Greedy, BFS, DFS, Hashing, Two Pointers, and Prefix State chapters.

Monotonic Stack / Deque is often taught too vaguely as:
	•	“keep a stack in increasing order”
	•	“good for next greater element”
	•	“use deque for sliding maximum”
	•	“pop while smaller”

That is only the surface.

The deeper truth is:

Monotonic Stack / Deque is a candidate-pruning engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	repeated outward scans for nearest better boundaries or active extrema

with:
	•	one ordered container that keeps only candidates that still matter.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

A monotonic structure stores elements in an order such that weaker candidates are removed as soon as a stronger new element makes them irrelevant.

Instead of:
	•	for each position, scanning left/right until you find the next greater/smaller element,
	•	or rescanning the active window to find the max/min,

it:
	•	keeps only unresolved or still-useful candidates,
	•	in a monotone order,
	•	so each new element resolves or prunes older candidates efficiently.

Deep identity

Monotonic Stack / Deque is a dominated-candidate elimination engine.

Its real power is not “stack syntax” or “deque syntax.”
Its power is:
	•	maintain an ordered frontier of candidates,
	•	discard candidates forever once dominated,
	•	use the remaining structure to answer nearest-boundary or active-extremum questions.

That is the family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Monotonic structures naturally live in:
	•	linear array / sequence
	•	histogram / bar chart
	•	sliding window sequence
	•	nearest-boundary problems
	•	some prefix/interval geometry formulations

Job

Usually one of:
	•	next greater/smaller element
	•	previous greater/smaller element
	•	nearest boundary on left/right
	•	largest area/span based on boundaries
	•	sliding-window maximum/minimum
	•	maintain active extrema under monotone motion

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	scan outward from each position
	•	scan active window repeatedly for max/min
	•	search nearest larger/smaller neighbor
	•	recompute width/extent from scratch

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	repeated boundary scans over overlapping regions
	•	repeated rescans of active candidates
	•	rechecking elements that have already been proven irrelevant

Engine type

Monotonic Stack / Deque is a:
	•	nearest-boundary engine
	•	active-extremum engine
	•	amortized pruning engine
	•	candidate-frontier engine

State object

Usually:
	•	stack or deque of indices or values
	•	often unresolved positions
	•	sometimes active window candidates

Invariant object

Usually:

the container is monotone by value (or some derived key), and every element inside is still a live candidate

Proof object

Usually:
	•	push-once / pop-once amortized proof
	•	nearest-boundary correctness from maintained order
	•	active-window candidate correctness for deque variants

Memory object

Usually:
	•	O(n) worst-case stack/deque
	•	O(window size) for sliding-window deque variants

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Monotonic Stack / Deque is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Dominance requirement

There must be a notion that one candidate makes another candidate permanently useless.

Examples:
	•	a later larger element makes smaller earlier elements useless for future “next greater” resolution
	•	a newer larger value dominates smaller values for future sliding-window maxima
	•	a bar boundary discovered by monotone logic determines width so weaker boundary candidates are no longer relevant

Without permanent dominance, monotonic pruning is not justified.

⸻

3.2 One-dimensional order requirement

The structure must have a meaningful traversal order.

This family is fundamentally sequence-oriented.

Examples:
	•	array index order
	•	histogram bar order
	•	sliding-window order

If the problem is not ordered linearly, this family is usually not primary.

⸻

3.3 Nearest-boundary or active-extremum requirement

The problem must care about one of these:

A. Nearest better neighbor
	•	next greater
	•	next smaller
	•	previous greater
	•	previous smaller

B. Boundary span
	•	width until a smaller bar
	•	previous and next smaller boundaries
	•	contribution spans

C. Active max/min in a moving region
	•	window max
	•	window min

If the problem is not about these kinds of candidate-frontier questions, monotonic structures are likely not primary.

⸻

3.4 Monotone update requirement

New elements must interact with the structure in a local monotone way:
	•	pop all now-dominated candidates
	•	then push new candidate

That local pruning behavior is essential.

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

This family becomes attractive when:
	•	O(n²) nearest-boundary scans are too expensive
	•	repeated max/min rescans over windows are too slow
	•	constraints suggest O(n) or O(n log n) should be possible

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where the family fails.

4.1 No permanent domination

If a popped candidate could still become useful later, monotonic pruning is invalid.

4.2 No linear order

If the structure is not sequence-like, stack/deque monotonicity is usually not the main engine.

4.3 Not really nearest-boundary / active-extremum

If the real problem is general optimization, recurrence, or arbitrary set search, monotonic structures may be a helper at most.

4.4 Order statistic / arbitrary rank queries

If you need median, kth, or arbitrary ordered statistics in a moving window, monotonic deque alone is insufficient.

4.5 Confusing with greedy

Just because smaller elements are popped does not mean the problem is greedy in the chapter sense; the core here is nearest-boundary or candidate-frontier maintenance.

So the chapter must teach:

Monotonic Stack / Deque is not “pop while condition.”

It is “maintain only still-relevant candidates under a permanent dominance rule.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand Monotonic Stack / Deque, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Typical brute-force forms:
	•	for each index, scan right until you find a larger element
	•	for each index, scan left/right to find first smaller boundaries
	•	for each window, scan all elements to find max/min
	•	for each bar, expand until blocked to compute width

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because many of these problems literally ask:
	•	next greater element
	•	previous smaller element
	•	max in current window
	•	width until blocked

The naive reaction is:

start from here and search outward

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	many outward scans re-traverse the same elements
	•	active candidates are rescanned even after they are obviously dominated
	•	each element is compared with many future positions unnecessarily

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time by repeatedly scanning across candidates that could have been permanently discarded once a stronger candidate appeared.

That is the family bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Repeated nearest-boundary or active-extremum search.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

Once a new element dominates an older candidate in the relevant way, that older candidate will never be the correct answer for any future position/window context of the same type.

Examples:
	•	smaller bar popped by a smaller boundary
	•	smaller value popped in window-maximum deque by a larger incoming value
	•	unresolved indices popped when their next greater is found

6.3 Why this matters

This means the structure can safely forget dominated elements permanently.

That is the enabler.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> Monotonic Stack / Deque

7.1 Source brute-force object

Outward scans or repeated active-window rescans.

7.2 Waste

Revisiting candidate elements many times.

7.3 Compression enabler

Permanent dominance and ordered arrival.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	many repeated scans

with:
	•	one stack/deque of live candidates in monotone order

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	O(n²) repeated scanning,

we now argue:
	•	each element is pushed once
	•	each element is popped once
	•	total container operations are linear

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Time drops to linear, memory grows to:
	•	O(n) stack/deque
or
	•	O(window size) in window variants

That is the full BF→Monotonic-Structure transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Monotonic structure state must be precise.

8.1 What is stored

Usually:
	•	indices, not just values

Why indices matter:
	•	boundaries and widths often depend on positions
	•	window expiry depends on index range

Values alone may be insufficient.

8.2 Common state forms

Monotonic stack of unresolved indices

For next greater/smaller.

Monotonic stack of boundary candidates

For histogram/area/span problems.

Monotonic deque of active indices

For window max/min.

8.3 Good state test

A good monotonic state is enough to answer:
	•	which candidates are still unresolved or active?
	•	which candidate is nearest relevant boundary or current extremum?
	•	which candidates have become dominated and can be removed?

8.4 Bad state
	•	storing values when indices are needed
	•	wrong monotone direction
	•	keeping elements that are already dominated
	•	popping elements that are not truly dominated

So the state requirement is:

The structure must store exactly the unresolved or still-active candidates in the monotone order required by the problem.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

⸻

9.1 Monotone-order invariant

The fundamental invariant.

Form:

the stack/deque contents are monotone by value (increasing or decreasing, depending on the problem).

Examples:
	•	decreasing deque for window maximum
	•	increasing stack for previous/next smaller
	•	decreasing stack for previous/next greater

This is the family’s main law.

⸻

9.2 Live-candidate invariant

Form:

every element remaining in the structure is still a possible candidate for some future answer.

This is just as important as monotonicity.

⸻

9.3 Unresolved-boundary invariant

For next-greater/smaller problems.

Form:

elements in the stack have not yet found their required next greater/smaller boundary.

⸻

9.4 Active-window invariant

For deque window problems.

Form:

the deque contains only indices inside the current window, and its front is the current optimum candidate.

This is the crucial deque variant invariant.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Monotonic structures have a very specific grammar.

10.1 Expire old candidates if needed

For window problems, remove out-of-window indices from the front.

10.2 Pop dominated candidates

While the new element dominates the tail/top candidate, pop it.

10.3 Push current candidate

Insert the current index/value.

10.4 Resolve answer if needed

Depending on the problem:
	•	the popped element’s answer is now known
	•	the front gives current max/min
	•	previous smaller/greater is top after pops
	•	span/area can now be computed

This gives the family rhythm:

expire -> pop dominated -> push -> resolve/use answer

That is the machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where the family branches.

⸻

11.1 Next Greater / Next Smaller stack

Identity

Find the first later element that is greater/smaller.

Requirements
	•	sequence order
	•	unresolved candidates can wait in stack
	•	current element resolves some earlier candidates

Canonicals
	•	Next Greater Element
	•	Daily Temperatures

Why important

This is the cleanest stack archetype.

⸻

11.2 Previous Greater / Previous Smaller stack

Identity

At each position, use the stack top after popping dominated elements to identify the nearest prior boundary.

Canonicals
	•	previous smaller/greater queries
	•	stock span style families

Why important

This is the mirror archetype.

⸻

11.3 Histogram / area / span stack

Identity

Use previous and next smaller boundaries to compute widths.

Requirements
	•	width/area depends on nearest blocking boundaries

Canonical
	•	Largest Rectangle in Histogram

Why important

This is the most important advanced stack archetype.

⸻

11.4 Sliding-window max/min deque

Identity

Maintain active extrema for a moving window.

Requirements
	•	active window boundaries move monotonically
	•	dominated candidates can be discarded permanently
	•	expired indices can be removed from front

Canonical
	•	Sliding Window Maximum

Why important

This is the main deque archetype.

⸻

11.5 Contribution-span variants

Identity

Each element contributes over the span where it remains the min/max.

Canonicals
	•	sum of subarray minimums/maximums families

Why important

This is a deeper mutation that combines boundary spans with counting.

⸻

12. Composite helpers

Monotonic structures often combine with other tools.

12.1 Monotonic deque + sliding window

The classic composite.

12.2 Stack + prefix/span formulas

For contribution counting or area calculations.

12.3 Stack + index arithmetic

Needed for widths and distances.

12.4 Stack + DP

Sometimes used to optimize transitions in advanced problems.

