14. Confusion map

⸻

14.1 Monotonic Stack/Deque vs Greedy

Monotonic structures

Maintain candidate frontier under permanent domination.

Greedy

Commits to one safe local choice with a proof.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Am I maintaining many live candidates in order, or collapsing the decision tree to one choice?

⸻

14.2 Monotonic Deque vs Sliding Window

Sliding Window

Primary when the real problem is maintaining internal window validity/score.

Monotonic Deque

Primary when the real problem is the active max/min candidate inside the window.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the hard part window validity, or current extremum maintenance?

⸻

14.3 Monotonic Stack vs Two Pointers

Two Pointers

Moves boundaries directly.

Monotonic Stack

Stores unresolved/interior candidates for nearest-boundary reasoning.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Do I need a memory of unresolved candidates, or can I move boundaries directly?

⸻

14.4 Monotonic Stack vs Heap

Heap

Maintains global best among active candidates but not nearest-boundary order.

Monotonic Deque

Maintains active extrema specifically under sequence order and permanent domination.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Do sequence order and candidate expiration/dominance matter? If yes, deque often beats heap.

⸻

15. Failure modes

Failure 1 — Wrong monotone direction

Most common conceptual failure.

Failure 2 — Popping on wrong inequality

Equal values often require careful policy.

Failure 3 — Storing values instead of indices

Fatal for width, distance, and expiry logic.

Failure 4 — Forgetting expiry for deque window problems

Then out-of-window candidates corrupt answers.

Failure 5 — Keeping dominated candidates

Breaks linearity and correctness.

Failure 6 — Treating stack as generic memory instead of candidate frontier

Loses the core invariant.

⸻

16. Correctness proof shapes

⸻

16.1 Candidate-dominance proof

Default proof.

Structure
	1.	define why the new element dominates certain older candidates
	2.	show dominated candidates can never be the correct future answer
	3.	therefore popping them is safe

This is the heart of the family.

⸻

16.2 Unresolved-boundary proof

For next-greater/smaller problems.

Structure
	•	stack stores candidates waiting for a qualifying future element
	•	current element is the first qualifying boundary for all popped entries
	•	therefore their answers are finalized correctly

⸻

16.3 Active-window proof

For deque variants.

Structure
	•	expired indices are removed, so all deque entries are in window
	•	deque monotonicity ensures front is best active candidate
	•	therefore front gives window max/min correctly

⸻

16.4 Width/span proof

For histogram/contribution problems.

Structure
	•	when an element is popped, its nearest smaller/greater boundaries are now known
	•	therefore its maximal valid span is finalized at that moment

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

17.1 Push-once / pop-once amortized proof

The main proof shape.

Each element:
	•	is pushed once
	•	is popped at most once

Therefore total stack/deque operations are O(n).

This is the family’s fundamental runtime geometry.

17.2 Window-expiry proof

For deque variants:
	•	each index enters once
	•	each index leaves once, by expiry or domination
	•	total remains linear

This must be taught explicitly.

⸻

18. Memory requirements

18.1 O(n) worst-case stack/deque

Classic worst-case footprint.

18.2 O(window size) deque

For window variants, active structure size is bounded by current window.

18.3 Index vs value storage

Index storage often increases semantic power without asymptotically changing memory.

