25. Final deep compression of the family

The irreducible statement of Monotonic Stack / Deque is:

Monotonic Stack / Deque is valid when sequence-order candidates can be permanently discarded once dominated, so nearest-boundary or active-extremum queries collapse from repeated scans into one amortized candidate frontier.

And the irreducible teaching statement is:

The learner has mastered Monotonic Stack / Deque only when they can name:
	•	the monotone direction,
	•	what makes a candidate dominated,
	•	what candidates in the structure still represent,
	•	the subtype,
	•	and why each element is pushed and popped at most once.

The next strongest chapter to build is Heap / Priority Queue.



Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Heap / Priority Queue

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window, Binary Search, Dynamic Programming, Greedy, BFS, DFS, Hashing, Two Pointers, Prefix State, and Monotonic Stack / Deque chapters.

Heap / Priority Queue is often taught too vaguely as:
	•	“use a min-heap”
	•	“good for top k”
	•	“extract min/max fast”
	•	“priority queue solves it”

That is only the surface.

The deeper truth is:

Heap / Priority Queue is a dynamic-best-candidate engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	repeated rescans of a changing candidate set

with:
	•	one maintained structure whose top always gives the current best candidate under a priority rule.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

A heap stores a changing set of candidates so that:
	•	insertion is efficient,
	•	removal of the best candidate is efficient,
	•	and the current best candidate is immediately accessible.

Instead of:
	•	scanning the whole active set every time you need the smallest/largest/best element,

it:
	•	maintains that ordering incrementally.

Deep identity

Heap is not just “a tree” or “priority queue syntax.”
It is:
	•	a dynamic ordering machine,
	•	for situations where the candidate set changes over time,
	•	and the only thing you need repeatedly is the current best according to some comparator.

That is the family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Heaps naturally live in:
	•	arrays/sequences with top-k queries
	•	active interval sets
	•	streaming inputs
	•	graph/state search with weighted priorities
	•	merge of many sorted streams
	•	scheduling/resource allocation
	•	design/object-state systems

Job

Usually one of:
	•	repeatedly get min/max
	•	keep top k elements
	•	repeatedly process current best candidate
	•	merge many ordered sources
	•	shortest-path frontier by distance
	•	maintain active tasks/resources by priority

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	current active candidate set
	•	current list of frequencies/items
	•	current graph frontier
	•	current active intervals/jobs
	•	many stream heads

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	rescanning the whole active set to find the best next candidate

Engine type

Heap is a:
	•	priority engine
	•	dynamic-extremum engine
	•	best-first expansion engine
	•	active-candidate maintenance engine

State object

Usually:
	•	heap contents
	•	optional side structures like frequency maps, visited sets, lazy-deletion maps

Invariant object

Usually:

the heap top is the current best candidate among all live candidates under the priority rule

Proof object

Usually:
	•	heap-order invariant
	•	log-height maintenance proof
	•	active-candidate correctness proof
	•	lazy-deletion cleanup proof if used

Memory object

Usually:
	•	O(number of live heap elements)
	•	O(k) for fixed-size top-k variants
	•	O(V) or O(n) in graph/stream cases

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Heap is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Dynamic-best requirement

The problem must repeatedly need the current best candidate:
	•	smallest
	•	largest
	•	highest priority
	•	lowest cost
	•	earliest finish among active items
	•	next merge head
	•	next shortest tentative distance

If the best candidate is only needed once, sorting may be simpler.

⸻

3.2 Changing active-set requirement

The candidate set must change over time.

Examples:
	•	new items arrive
	•	old items are removed
	•	graph neighbors are added to frontier
	•	intervals become active/inactive
	•	stream heads advance
	•	priorities are updated conceptually by reinsertion/lazy strategy

If the set is static, full sorting may dominate.

⸻

3.3 Comparator sufficiency requirement

There must be a clear priority rule.

Examples:
	•	min by value
	•	max by value
	•	min by distance
	•	max by frequency
	•	min by end time
	•	min by current stream head value

If the problem requires arbitrary rank queries or full sorted order, heap may not be enough alone.

⸻

3.4 Local-processing requirement

Once you take the best candidate, either:
	•	that candidate is final,
or
	•	processing it generates or updates future candidates in a controlled way.

This is why heaps fit:
	•	Dijkstra
	•	merge k lists
	•	scheduling active tasks
	•	top-k streaming

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

Heap becomes attractive when:
	•	repeated linear rescans are too slow
	•	O(log n) updates/extractions are acceptable
	•	candidate set is dynamic enough that sort-once is not sufficient

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where the family fails.

4.1 Static one-time ordering

If all elements are known and you need them all sorted once, sort may be cleaner than heap.

4.2 Need for arbitrary order statistics

If you need median, rank selection under deletions, or many arbitrary quantiles, heap alone may be insufficient.

4.3 Sequence-order-sensitive nearest-boundary problems

Monotonic deque/stack may dominate because order and domination matter more than generic priority.

4.4 Direct lookup/grouping problems

Hashing may be the real engine, with heap only as a secondary helper.

4.5 No meaningful active set

If there is no evolving pool of candidates, heap is probably not the right primary family.

So the chapter must teach:

Heap is not “any min/max problem.”

It is “repeated best-element extraction from a changing active set.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand Heap, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Typical brute-force forms:
	•	repeatedly scan all items to find current min/max
	•	recompute top k by sorting or scanning repeatedly
	•	for graph search, search all frontier nodes each step for best tentative distance
	•	for merging k lists, compare all k current heads each time
	•	for active intervals/jobs, rescan all active ones each event

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because many problems sound like:
	•	“what is the smallest one now?”
	•	“what is the next closest?”
	•	“what are the top k?”
	•	“which active thing should I process next?”

The naive reaction is:

scan them all each time

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	the active set changes incrementally,
	•	but brute force keeps re-searching it globally from scratch.

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time by repeatedly rescanning a changing candidate pool for its current best element.

That is the family bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Repeated best-candidate search.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

Only the current best candidate matters at each step; full order is often unnecessary.

This is crucial.

A heap is not a fully sorted structure.
It is a structure that preserves enough order to expose only the top.

6.3 Why this matters

If you only need the next best item repeatedly, heap is exactly the right compression of the active set.

That is the enabler.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> Heap

7.1 Source brute-force object

Changing active candidate set.

7.2 Waste

Repeated global scan for current best.

7.3 Compression enabler

The algorithm only needs one priority-extremum at a time, not full ordering.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	unsorted active set + repeated rescans

with:
	•	priority queue maintaining active candidates by comparator

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	O(n) scan per extraction,

we now argue:
	•	insert/extract use only log-height maintenance
	•	each candidate enters/exits a bounded number of times
	•	total is O(number of operations × log active_size)

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Time drops, memory grows to hold:
	•	active heap elements
	•	optional side maps/visited/lazy-deletion state

That is the full BF→Heap transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Heap state must be precise.

8.1 What is stored

Usually one of:
	•	raw values
	•	(priority, payload) pairs
	•	(distance, node)
	•	(value, stream_id, index)
	•	(frequency, item)
	•	interval endpoints
	•	task/resource descriptors

8.2 Good state test

A good heap state is enough to answer:
	•	what is the current best active candidate?
	•	what additional info is needed once that candidate is popped?

8.3 Bad state
	•	storing only priority when payload is needed later
	•	comparator not matching actual problem objective
	•	failing to model stale entries when priorities change conceptually

So the state requirement is:

Heap state must store each live candidate in the exact priority form needed to choose and process the current best candidate correctly.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

⸻

9.1 Heap-order invariant

The fundamental invariant.

Form:

the root/top of the heap is the best candidate under the comparator among all heap elements.

This is the family’s core structural law.

⸻

9.2 Live-candidate invariant

Form:

every element that still matters is represented in the heap (or else stale items are explicitly handled by a cleanup rule).

This is essential in active-set problems.

⸻

9.3 Active-best invariant

Form:

at each step, processing the heap top is equivalent to processing the globally best active candidate.

This is the operational correctness law.

⸻

9.4 Lazy-deletion invariant

For problems where stale entries can remain in heap.

Form:

if stale entries exist, they are recognized and discarded when popped, so the next valid top still gives the correct active best candidate.

This is common in advanced heap use.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Heap has a rigid grammar.

10.1 Insert

Push new candidate into heap.

10.2 Peek / extract-best

Read or pop the top candidate.

10.3 Generate / update new candidates

Based on popped candidate, add next candidates if needed.

10.4 Cleanup stale candidates if applicable

Discard entries that are no longer valid.

This gives the family rhythm:

push -> peek/pop best -> process -> push new actives -> repeat

That is the machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where the family branches.

⸻

11.1 Min-heap / Max-heap basics

Identity

Use heap directly for repeated smallest/largest extraction.

Canonicals
