14. Confusion map

⸻

14.1 Heap vs Sorting

Heap

Best when:
	•	active set changes
	•	repeated best extraction needed
	•	full order unnecessary

Sorting

Best when:
	•	one global order once is enough

Diagnostic

Ask:

Do I need the whole order once, or the current best many times as the set changes?

⸻

14.2 Heap vs Monotonic Deque

Heap

Maintains generic priority among active candidates.

Monotonic Deque

Maintains active extrema specifically under sequence order and permanent domination.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is this about generic active best, or sequence-order dominance/expiry?

⸻

14.3 Heap vs Greedy

Heap

A data structure for best active candidate.

Greedy

A proof style/family about safe local choice.

Many problems are:
	•	Greedy + Heap

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the heap just supporting the greedy local choice among active candidates?

If yes, heap is helper and greedy may be primary.

⸻

14.4 Heap vs BFS/Dijkstra distinction

BFS

For unit-cost frontier layers.

Heap/Dijkstra

For weighted frontier by tentative distance.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the frontier prioritized only by layer, or by dynamic cost?

