16. Correctness proof shapes

⸻

16.1 Heap-order proof

Default proof.

Structure
	•	heap operations preserve the property that top is best under comparator

This is structural, but not enough alone.

⸻

16.2 Active-best proof

For algorithmic use.

Structure
	•	show heap contains all relevant active candidates
	•	show comparator matches problem objective
	•	therefore top is correct next candidate to process

⸻

16.3 Successor-generation proof

For merge-k-streams.

Structure
	•	heap always contains the smallest current head from each unfinished stream
	•	popping the smallest and inserting its successor preserves that invariant

⸻

16.4 Frontier-finalization proof

For Dijkstra-like usage.

Structure
	•	among all frontier states, smallest tentative distance is popped
	•	under positive-weight assumptions, it becomes final
	•	relaxations preserve future correctness

⸻

16.5 Lazy-deletion proof

For stale entries.

Structure
	•	stale entries may remain
	•	any stale top is discarded
	•	first non-stale top is still the correct active best candidate

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

17.1 Log-height maintenance proof

The main proof shape.

Each push/pop/heapify adjustment touches only a root-to-leaf or leaf-to-root path.

So:
	•	each heap operation is O(log n)

17.2 Operation-count proof

Total time =
	•	number of pushes/pops
×
	•	O(log active_size)

17.3 Fixed-size top-k proof

If heap size is capped at k:
	•	operations are O(log k), not O(log n)

This must be emphasized.

