25. Final deep compression of the family

The irreducible statement of Heap / Priority Queue is:

Heap is valid when a changing active set repeatedly requires only its current best candidate under a fixed comparator, so repeated global rescans collapse into logarithmic incremental maintenance.

And the irreducible teaching statement is:

The learner has mastered Heap only when they can name:
	•	the active candidate set,
	•	the priority rule,
	•	what payload each heap element must carry,
	•	the subtype,
	•	and why the heap top is the correct next live candidate.

The next strongest chapter to build is Backtracking.



Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Backtracking

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window, Binary Search, Dynamic Programming, Greedy, BFS, DFS, Hashing, Two Pointers, Prefix State, Monotonic Stack / Deque, and Heap / Priority Queue chapters.

Backtracking is often taught too vaguely as:
	•	“try all possibilities”
	•	“use recursion”
	•	“undo the choice”
	•	“good for permutations and combinations”

That is only the surface.

The deeper truth is:

Backtracking is a constraint-guided choice-tree engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	blind exhaustive enumeration

with:
	•	disciplined exploration of a choice tree where invalid partial solutions are cut off early and temporary choices are undone precisely.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

Backtracking explores a space of possibilities by:
	•	making one choice,
	•	descending into the smaller remaining problem,
	•	undoing that choice,
	•	trying the next alternative.

Unlike plain brute force, it does not merely enumerate.
It maintains a partial construction and uses constraints to prune impossible branches as early as possible.

Deep identity

Backtracking is a partial-solution search engine.

Its real power comes from:
	•	representing the problem as a choice tree,
	•	keeping one current partial solution,
	•	validating that partial solution incrementally,
	•	abandoning branches as soon as they cannot lead to a full valid answer.

That is the family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Backtracking naturally lives in:
	•	subset/combination space
	•	permutation space
	•	board-placement space
	•	partition/search space
	•	string construction space
	•	path construction space
	•	implicit constraint-satisfaction space

Job

Usually one of:
	•	generate all valid solutions
	•	generate one valid solution
	•	count valid solutions
	•	optimize with pruning over a small search tree
	•	decide feasibility under combinatorial constraints

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	subset
	•	permutation
	•	arrangement
	•	assignment
	•	board placement
	•	partition sequence
	•	construction path

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	exploring huge numbers of complete possibilities even when many prefixes are already invalid

Engine type

Backtracking is a:
	•	choice-tree engine
	•	partial-construction engine
	•	prune-and-undo engine
	•	constraint-search engine

State object

Usually:
	•	current partial solution/path
	•	index/position/depth
	•	used flags / visited flags
	•	constraint trackers (rows, cols, diagonals, counts, sums, remaining budget)
	•	accumulated value if needed

Invariant object

Usually:

the current partial solution is valid under all constraints considered so far

Proof object

Usually:
	•	exhaustive-branch coverage proof
	•	pruning-safety proof
	•	undo-restoration proof

Memory object

Usually:
	•	recursion stack
	•	current path/board/assignment state
	•	auxiliary constraint trackers
	•	output-sized memory if all solutions are stored

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Backtracking is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Choice-tree requirement

The problem must naturally decompose into a sequence of discrete choices.

Examples:
	•	include/exclude this element
	•	choose next unused number
	•	place a queen in a row
	•	choose next partition boundary
	•	choose next character/path step

If there is no branching choice structure, backtracking is not the right family.

⸻

3.2 Partial-solution requirement

It must make sense to talk about a partial construction.

Examples:
	•	current subset
	•	current permutation prefix
	•	queens placed so far
	•	current path in a board
	•	current combination sum path

This is essential.
Backtracking does not reason only about final answers.
It reasons about prefixes of answers.

⸻

3.3 Incremental-validity requirement

You must be able to test whether the current partial solution is still valid or promising.

Examples:
	•	no repeated element
	•	no row/col/diag conflict
	•	sum does not exceed target
	•	word path still matches prefix
	•	partition remains feasible

If validity can only be checked after the full solution is built, backtracking may still work, but pruning power is weak.

⸻

3.4 Undoability requirement

A choice must be reversible.

Typical actions:
	•	append/remove from path
	•	mark/unmark used
	•	place/remove from board
	•	add/subtract from running sum
	•	mark/unmark visited cell

This is core to the family.

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

Backtracking is most appropriate when:
	•	brute-force state space is exponential/factorial but still manageable with pruning
	•	n is small enough
	•	constraints strongly prune
	•	the user wants all solutions or one valid configuration
	•	DP/greedy cannot collapse the branching safely

Typical signal:
	•	n <= 15, n <= 20, small board sizes, small combinatorial universe

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where the family fails.

4.1 Huge search space with weak pruning

If the branching factor is large and constraints do little pruning, backtracking may be infeasible.

4.2 Repeated-state structure with strong overlap

If many branches revisit the same abstract state, DP or memoized DFS may dominate.

4.3 Local safe-choice existence

If a greedy proof exists, backtracking is often overkill.

4.4 Pure counting/optimization with compact recurrence

If the problem is better modeled as DP over states, backtracking may be only the brute-force baseline.

4.5 No meaningful partial validity

If you cannot reject branches early, the method degenerates to raw brute-force enumeration.

So the chapter must teach:

Backtracking is not “anything recursive.”

It is “choice-tree search over partial solutions with incremental validity and exact undo.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand Backtracking, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Typical brute-force forms:
	•	generate all subsets, then test each one
	•	generate all permutations, then validate each
	•	try every board configuration
	•	enumerate all paths blindly
	•	enumerate all partitions and test only at the end

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because the problems often literally ask for:
	•	all combinations,
	•	all permutations,
	•	all placements,
	•	all valid boards,
	•	all paths,
	•	all solutions.

So the naive reaction is:

just generate everything

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	many complete candidates share invalid prefixes
	•	brute force keeps extending those bad prefixes anyway
	•	huge subtrees are explored even after failure is already inevitable

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time by fully exploring many complete candidates whose prefixes were already invalid or hopeless much earlier.

That is the family bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Combinatorial branching over choices.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

A complete invalid solution is often invalid because of an early prefix mistake.

Examples:
	•	two queens already attack each other
	•	path already exceeds target
	•	a cell has already been reused illegally
	•	a duplicate permutation branch is already formed
	•	a word prefix already mismatches

6.3 Why this matters

If invalidity can be detected at partial depth d, the entire subtree below that partial solution can be cut.

That is the enabler.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> Backtracking

7.1 Source brute-force object

Full combinatorial candidate space.

7.2 Waste

Completing branches that were already invalid earlier.

7.3 Compression enabler

Validity/promise can be checked incrementally on a partial solution.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	independent complete-candidate generation

with:
	•	one current partial solution,
	•	one current recursion depth,
	•	constraint trackers,
	•	exact undo after recursive return

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	generating every full candidate blindly,

we now argue:
	•	every valid solution corresponds to a root-to-leaf path
	•	pruning only removes branches that cannot lead to valid answers
	•	undo restores state exactly for sibling exploration

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Time may drop dramatically with pruning, but memory includes:
	•	recursion stack
	•	current path/board
	•	used flags/constraint trackers
	•	potentially huge output storage

That is the full BF→Backtracking transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Backtracking state must be precise.

8.1 Mandatory state

Usually:
	•	current depth/index/position
	•	current partial solution

8.2 Common additional state
	•	used[] array
	•	visited board
	•	running sum / remaining target
	•	row/col/diag attack trackers
	•	multiset counts / frequency map for duplicates
	•	next-start index for combination generation

8.3 Good state test

A good backtracking state is enough to answer:
	•	what choices are available next?
	•	is the current partial solution still legal?
	•	how do I undo after exploring this branch?

8.4 Bad state
	•	no explicit partial solution
	•	no clear depth/position meaning
	•	no incremental constraint trackers even when needed
	•	state too global and not restorable

So the state requirement is:

Backtracking state must define the current partial solution, the branch position, and the reversible constraint information needed to continue or prune.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

⸻

9.1 Partial-validity invariant

The fundamental invariant.

Form:

the current partial solution satisfies all constraints that can already be evaluated.

Examples:
	•	no duplicate chosen element
	•	no conflicting queen placement
	•	no invalid path revisit
	•	current sum within allowed bound
	•	current string/path prefix still matches target condition

This is the family’s main law.

⸻

9.2 Choice-consistency invariant

Form:

used/unused markers or position trackers exactly match the current partial solution.

This is crucial in permutation/board problems.

⸻

9.3 Undo-restoration invariant

Form:

after returning from a recursive branch, all modified state is restored exactly to the parent-state configuration.

This is one of the deepest backtracking invariants.

⸻

9.4 Completion invariant

Form:

whenever depth reaches a terminal state, the current partial solution corresponds to one full candidate.

This matters for correctness of emitted answers.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Backtracking has a rigid grammar.

10.1 Check base case

If the current partial solution is complete:
	•	record it,
	•	count it,
	•	return success/failure,
depending on job.

10.2 Enumerate choices

List all legal next choices from current state.

10.3 Apply choice

Update path/board/trackers.

10.4 Recurse

Explore deeper with that choice fixed.

10.5 Undo choice

Remove choice and restore state.

This gives the family rhythm:

test complete -> choose -> apply -> recurse -> undo -> continue

That is the machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where the family branches.

⸻

