14. Confusion map

⸻

14.1 Backtracking vs DFS

DFS

Broad family for path/subtree exploration.

Backtracking

Specific DFS subtype where:
	•	you maintain a partial solution,
	•	make a reversible choice,
	•	and undo before trying siblings.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Am I just exploring structure, or am I building and undoing a candidate solution?

⸻

14.2 Backtracking vs DP

Backtracking

Explores many branches explicitly.

DP

Collapses repeated states.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Do different branches revisit the same abstract state enough that memoization should replace repeated search?

⸻

14.3 Backtracking vs brute force

Backtracking is not just brute force with recursion.

The difference is:
	•	incremental validity
	•	early pruning
	•	exact undo
	•	structured partial state

Diagnostic

Ask:

Am I rejecting bad branches early, or only testing at the leaves?

⸻

14.4 Backtracking vs Greedy

Greedy

Commits once with proof.

Backtracking

Explores multiple possibilities because no safe single choice is known.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Can one local choice be proven safe, or do I still need branching?

⸻

15. Failure modes

Failure 1 — No undo

Most classic bug.

Failure 2 — Wrong partial-validity test

Prunes too much or too little.

Failure 3 — Duplicate generation

Especially with repeated values.

Failure 4 — Missing used/on-path distinction

Important in permutations and path searches.

Failure 5 — Recording mutable path incorrectly

Appended references mutate later if not copied when saving answers.

Failure 6 — Weak pruning

Algorithm remains too close to brute force.

Failure 7 — State not restored fully

Constraint trackers and path diverge from actual branch state.

⸻

16. Correctness proof shapes

⸻

16.1 Exhaustive-branch coverage proof

Default proof.

Structure
	1.	every legal next choice is considered at each state
	2.	recursion explores all descendant branches from that choice
	3.	therefore all valid full solutions are reachable

This proves completeness.

⸻

16.2 Pruning-safety proof

Critical proof.

Structure
	•	show that when a branch is pruned, no extension of the current partial solution can ever become valid or optimal
	•	therefore pruning does not remove any desired solution

This is the family’s most important advanced proof.

⸻

16.3 Undo-restoration proof

For correctness of sibling exploration.

Structure
	•	applying a choice modifies state consistently
	•	undo restores parent state exactly
	•	therefore each sibling branch starts from the correct base state

⸻

16.4 Duplicate-skipping proof

For unique-solution generation.

Structure
	•	show skip rule removes only symmetric duplicate branches
	•	does not remove any distinct canonical branch

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

Backtracking complexity is subtle.

17.1 Branching-factor × depth proof

The core upper-bound geometry.

Time is often described by:
	•	branching factor b
	•	depth d
	•	upper bound O(b^d), O(n!), etc.

17.2 Pruning-aware complexity discussion

Often there is no tight simple closed form.
A strong chapter must say:
	•	worst case may still be exponential/factorial
	•	practical speed depends heavily on pruning strength

17.3 Output-sized lower bound

If you must return all solutions, total time/output memory is at least proportional to the number of emitted solutions.

This is important and often forgotten.

