25. Final deep compression of the family

The irreducible statement of DSU is:

Union-Find / DSU is valid when the problem’s main structure is merge-only connectivity or equivalence, so repeated traversal-based rediscovery of components collapses into representative maintenance over disjoint sets.

And the irreducible teaching statement is:

The learner has mastered DSU only when they can name:
	•	the component representative meaning,
	•	the find operation’s role,
	•	the union rule,
	•	the subtype,
	•	and why representatives are enough instead of repeated traversals.

The next strongest chapter to build is Trie.







Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Trie

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window, Binary Search, Dynamic Programming, Greedy, BFS, DFS, Hashing, Two Pointers, Prefix State, Monotonic Stack / Deque, Heap / Priority Queue, Backtracking, and Union-Find chapters.

Trie is often taught too vaguely as:
	•	“tree for strings”
	•	“good for prefixes”
	•	“insert/search startsWith”
	•	“like a dictionary”

That is only the surface.

The deeper truth is:

Trie is a shared-prefix compression engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	repeated character-by-character prefix comparison across many strings

with:
	•	one shared branching structure where common prefixes are stored once.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

A trie stores strings or sequences by walking one symbol at a time through shared prefix nodes.

Instead of:
	•	storing many strings independently,
	•	rechecking the same prefixes repeatedly,
	•	scanning full dictionaries for prefix matches,

it:
	•	merges identical prefixes into one path,
	•	branches only when strings diverge,
	•	and lets lookup follow the query prefix directly.

Deep identity

Trie is not just “a tree of letters.”
It is:
	•	a prefix-sharing representation,
	•	a branching index over sequence prefixes,
	•	a way to turn repeated prefix work into one reusable structure.

That is the family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Trie naturally lives in:
	•	strings
	•	words
	•	character sequences
	•	digit sequences
	•	bit sequences
	•	prefix-search state spaces

Job

Usually one of:
	•	exact word lookup
	•	prefix existence/query
	•	retrieve all items with a prefix
	•	support prefix-pruned search
	•	maximize/minimize by bitwise traversal
	•	shared-prefix dictionary processing

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	all dictionary words
	•	all candidate strings
	•	repeated character-by-character prefix comparisons
	•	repeated linear scans for startsWith behavior

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	repeated re-reading of common prefixes across many items or many queries

Engine type

Trie is a:
	•	prefix-index engine
	•	shared-prefix compression engine
	•	prefix-search engine
	•	sequence-branching engine

State object

Usually:
	•	trie root
	•	current node
	•	current character index
	•	child links by symbol
	•	terminal/end-of-word marker
	•	optional count/frequency/word payload

Invariant object

Usually:

every node corresponds to exactly one prefix, and the path from the root to that node spells that prefix

Proof object

Usually:
	•	path-prefix correspondence proof
	•	exact lookup / prefix lookup correctness by traversal
	•	shared-prefix compression proof

Memory object

Usually:
	•	node set proportional to number of distinct prefixes
	•	child maps/arrays per node
	•	optional terminal metadata

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Trie is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Prefix-centrality requirement

The problem must fundamentally care about prefixes or prefix-like branching.

Examples:
	•	startsWith queries
	•	autocomplete
	•	dictionary search by prefix
	•	word-board search with prefix pruning
	•	maximum xor by bit prefix
	•	longest common prefix-style structure

If exact full-key equality alone is all that matters, hashing may be simpler.

⸻

3.2 Shared-prefix reuse requirement

There must be value in not rechecking the same prefix repeatedly.

Examples:
	•	many words share prefixes
	•	many queries share prefix checks
	•	search space can be pruned once a prefix is absent

If prefixes are not reused or queried meaningfully, trie may be overkill.

⸻

3.3 Symbol-by-symbol traversal requirement

The problem must admit stepwise traversal by sequence position.

Examples:
	•	character sequence
	•	digit string
	•	bit string

Trie is strongest when local next-symbol branching is meaningful.

⸻

3.4 Structured child access requirement

At each node, you must be able to interpret next-symbol transitions as child edges.

This can be by:
	•	fixed alphabet array
	•	map/dictionary of children
	•	bitwise 0/1 child

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

Trie becomes attractive when:
	•	repeated prefix scans over many strings are too expensive
	•	the dictionary/query count is high
	•	prefix pruning dramatically cuts search
	•	O(total characters) build and query behavior is acceptable

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where the family fails.

4.1 Exact lookup only, no prefix value

If you only need exact membership, a hash set may be simpler and often better.

4.2 No useful shared-prefix structure

If the sequences do not benefit from shared prefixes, trie may waste memory.

4.3 Ordered/ranked retrieval required

If the problem is about lexicographic ordering with many global ranking operations, trie alone may not be enough.

4.4 Non-sequence domains

If the objects do not naturally decompose into symbols/steps, trie is not primary.

So the chapter must teach:

Trie is not “any string problem.”

It is “sequence problems where shared prefixes are the right indexing structure.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand Trie, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Typical brute-force forms:
	•	for each query, scan all words and compare prefixes
	•	for each startsWith check, compare query prefix against many dictionary items
	•	in word-board search, check many impossible prefixes repeatedly
	•	for bitwise xor, compare against all stored numbers

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because many problems sound like:
	•	“is this word present?”
	•	“is there any word starting with this prefix?”
	•	“which word continues this prefix?”
	•	“what gives best xor?”

The naive move is:

compare against everything

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	the same prefix characters are compared again and again across many candidates.

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time by repeatedly comparing the same leading symbols across many candidate strings or queries.

That is the family bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Repeated prefix comparison across many items.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

Many strings share long prefixes, and a query prefix only needs to be followed once through those shared characters.

6.3 Why this matters

A trie stores each distinct prefix path once, so repeated prefix work collapses into one traversal.

That is the enabler.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> Trie

7.1 Source brute-force object

Dictionary scan / repeated prefix comparison.

7.2 Waste

Re-reading identical prefixes across many words.

7.3 Compression enabler

Common prefixes can be represented by shared nodes.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	many separate strings checked independently

with:
	•	one prefix tree
	•	current node as prefix state

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	O(number of words × prefix length) per prefix search,

we now argue:
	•	build once over total characters
	•	query follows one path of length equal to the query/prefix length
	•	search fails immediately when prefix path missing

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Time drops for prefix-heavy workloads, memory grows to:
	•	nodes for all distinct prefixes
	•	child edges/maps

That is the full BF→Trie transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Trie state must be precise.

8.1 Core persistent state
	•	root node
	•	child links
	•	terminal/end marker

8.2 Query-time state
	•	current node
	•	current position in input sequence

8.3 Optional augmented state
	•	count of words through node
	•	count ending at node
	•	stored word index/value
	•	top suggestions
	•	subtree metadata
	•	frequency scores

8.4 Good state test

A good trie state is enough to answer:
	•	what prefix are we currently at?
	•	what continuations exist from this prefix?
	•	does this path represent a complete word?
	•	what metadata should be returned if query stops here?

8.5 Bad state
	•	nodes without clear prefix meaning
	•	missing terminal markers
	•	no distinction between prefix existence and full-word existence
	•	storing too much redundant payload at every node

So the state requirement is:

Trie state must represent prefix positions explicitly, with each node corresponding to one exact prefix and enough metadata to answer the intended query type.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

⸻

9.1 Prefix-path invariant

The fundamental invariant.

Form:

the path from root to any node spells exactly one prefix, and all strings beneath that node share that prefix.

This is the family’s main law.

⸻

9.2 Terminal-word invariant

Form:

a node is marked terminal iff at least one inserted word ends exactly at that prefix.

This distinguishes exact search from prefix search.

⸻

9.3 Child-transition invariant

Form:

following child edge labeled c extends the current prefix by symbol c.

This is the local traversal invariant.

⸻

9.4 Augmented-metadata invariant

If counts or payloads are stored:

Form:

node metadata correctly summarizes all words passing through or ending at that node.

This matters in advanced tries.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Trie has a rigid grammar.

10.1 Insert

Start at root, follow/create child for each symbol, mark terminal at the end.

10.2 Exact search

Start at root, follow each symbol; success only if full path exists and final node is terminal.

10.3 Prefix search

Start at root, follow each symbol; success if full prefix path exists.

10.4 Enumerate descendants if needed

Once at prefix node, explore subtree for completions.

This gives the family rhythm:

start at root -> consume symbol -> follow/create child -> continue -> check terminal/prefix

That is the machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where the family branches.

⸻

11.1 Basic character trie

Identity

Standard word/prefix dictionary trie.

Requirements
	•	symbol alphabet manageable
	•	exact/prefix queries matter

Canonicals
	•	Implement Trie
	•	startsWith dictionary operations

Why important

This is the base trie form.

⸻

11.2 Trie with counts/frequencies

Identity

Each node stores how many words pass through/end here.

Requirements
	•	query needs counts or multiplicities

Canonicals
	•	prefix-count dictionaries
	•	frequency-augmented autocomplete variants

Why important

Shows trie as more than exact membership.

⸻

11.3 Bitwise trie

Identity

Trie over bits instead of characters.

Requirements
	•	integer bit representation matters
	•	objective depends on bitwise branching, often xor

Canonicals
	•	Maximum XOR of Two Numbers

Why important

This is one of the most important trie mutations.

⸻

11.4 Trie + DFS / backtracking

Identity

Trie provides prefix pruning while DFS searches a board/state space.

Requirements
	•	search path builds a prefix
	•	absent prefix should prune immediately

Canonicals
	•	Word Search II

Why important

This is the most important composite trie archetype.

⸻

11.5 Compressed / optimized trie variants

Identity

Store only needed children or compress chains.

Why important

Advanced implementation/memory optimization form.

⸻

12. Composite helpers

Trie often combines with other tools.

12.1 Trie + DFS / Backtracking

For board search and prefix pruning.

12.2 Trie + Hash maps

For sparse child storage.

12.3 Trie + Bit manipulation

For xor maximization.

12.4 Trie + counts/ranking metadata

For autocomplete/frequency-aware queries.

