14. Confusion map

⸻

14.1 Trie vs Hashing

Trie

Best when:
	•	prefixes matter
	•	startsWith matters
	•	shared-prefix pruning matters

Hashing

Best when:
	•	only exact-key equality matters
	•	no prefix structure needed

Diagnostic

Ask:

Do I care about shared prefixes, or just exact lookup?

⸻

14.2 Trie vs Sorting / lexicographic structures

Trie

Good for prefix navigation.

Sorting

Good for global order, binary search over strings, or one-time ordered output.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the main question prefix branching, or ordered comparison?

⸻

14.3 Trie vs Backtracking

In Word Search II-like problems:

Backtracking

Searches path space.

Trie

Prunes prefix-invalid branches.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the trie the primary engine, or is it a helper attached to DFS/backtracking?

Often primary search engine is DFS/backtracking, with trie as crucial pruning helper.

⸻

14.4 Trie vs Bitmask / DP on strings

If the problem is not about prefix navigation but about combinatorial or recurrence structure, trie may be irrelevant.

⸻

15. Failure modes

Failure 1 — Forgetting terminal marker distinction

Then prefix and full-word queries are confused.

Failure 2 — Wasting memory with dense child arrays when alphabet sparse

Implementation-physics issue.

Failure 3 — Using trie when a hash set is enough

Overengineering.

Failure 4 — Missing pruning opportunity in trie+DFS problems

Then trie adds little value.

Failure 5 — Incorrect payload/count updates

In augmented tries.

Failure 6 — Bit-width mistakes in bitwise trie

For xor problems.

⸻

16. Correctness proof shapes

⸻

16.1 Prefix-path proof

Default proof.

Structure
	•	each insertion creates/follows nodes matching successive symbols
	•	therefore every node corresponds to the exact prefix on its path
	•	query traversal is correct because it mirrors the prefix character sequence

This is the family’s core proof grammar.

⸻

16.2 Terminal correctness proof

For exact word search.

Structure
	•	a word exists iff its full prefix path exists and final node is terminal

⸻

16.3 Prefix-pruning proof

For trie + DFS/backtracking.

Structure
	•	if a current search prefix is absent from trie, no completion under that prefix exists in dictionary
	•	therefore the whole DFS subtree can be pruned safely

This is the major advanced trie proof.

⸻

16.4 Bitwise-best-branch proof

For xor trie.

Structure
	•	at each bit, taking opposite bit if available maximizes xor contribution greedily because higher bits dominate lower bits
	•	trie guarantees only valid stored-number branches are followed

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

17.1 Build by total characters

Insertion across all words:
	•	O(total symbols inserted)

17.2 Query by query length

Exact/prefix query:
	•	O(length of query/prefix)

17.3 Trie + DFS pruning

Total complexity depends on:
	•	board search branching
	•	trie pruning effectiveness
	•	total visited states/paths

A strong chapter should be honest here: the trie reduces search drastically, but exact runtime depends on branching and pruning.

17.4 Bitwise trie proof

Build and query:
	•	O(number of values × bit-width)

⸻

18. Memory requirements

18.1 O(number of distinct prefixes)

Core trie memory cost.

18.2 Child storage representation matters
	•	fixed array children: faster, more memory
	•	hash map children: sparser, less waste, possibly slower constants

18.3 Terminal/metadata storage

Counts/payloads increase per-node memory.

18.4 Bitwise trie footprint

Usually O(number of inserted values × bit-width) worst case, but shared prefixes reduce actual node count.

