16. Correctness proof shapes

⸻

16.1 Frontier-optimality proof

For Dijkstra-like families.

Structure
	•	among all frontier nodes, smallest tentative distance is popped
	•	under nonnegative weights, no unseen route can improve it later
	•	therefore popped distance is final

This is the core weighted-frontier proof.

⸻

16.2 Dependency-readiness proof

For topological sort.

Structure
	•	nodes with zero indegree have all prerequisites satisfied
	•	processing them and removing outgoing edges maintains this property
	•	any valid topological order must begin with some zero-indegree node

⸻

16.3 DAG-induction proof

For DAG DP.

Structure
	•	topological order guarantees predecessors are processed first
	•	transition propagation from predecessors therefore uses final values
	•	induction over topo order proves correctness

⸻

16.4 Restricted-cost deque proof

For 0-1 BFS.

Structure
	•	0-cost edges stay at same distance layer and go to front
	•	1-cost edges go to next layer and go to back
	•	deque order thus preserves nondecreasing distances

⸻

16.5 State-augmentation proof

For extra-state graphs.

Structure
	•	define what each expanded state means
	•	show transitions preserve that meaning
	•	show frontier/order rule applies to expanded states, not just original nodes

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

17.1 Dijkstra complexity proof
	•	each edge may cause relaxation attempts
	•	heap operations dominate
	•	total often O((V+E) log V) with adjacency list + heap

17.2 Topological sort complexity proof
	•	each node enters queue once
	•	each edge processed once
	•	total O(V+E)

17.3 DAG DP complexity proof
	•	process each edge/node once in topological order
	•	total O(V+E)

17.4 0-1 BFS proof
	•	each state processed with deque operations bounded by edge relaxations
	•	near-linear in graph size

17.5 State-augmented graph proof
	•	complexity scales with expanded state count, not original node count alone

This must be emphasized strongly.

