Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Design / Object-State

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window, Binary Search, Dynamic Programming, Greedy, BFS, DFS, Hashing, Two Pointers, Prefix State, Monotonic Stack / Deque, Heap / Priority Queue, Backtracking, Union-Find, Trie, Range Structures, and Graph Advanced chapters.

Design / Object-State is often taught too vaguely as:
	•	“design a class”
	•	“support operations efficiently”
	•	“use hashmap + linked list”
	•	“store state between calls”

That is only the surface.

The deeper truth is:

Design / Object-State is a persistent-state maintenance engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	replaying or rebuilding the whole system on every operation

with:
	•	one carefully maintained internal state representation that stays synchronized across operations.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

Design / Object-State problems ask:
	•	what internal data should the object keep,
	•	how should that data change after each operation,
	•	and how can each operation be supported efficiently without recomputing everything?

Instead of:
	•	reconstructing answers from scratch each time,
	•	rescanning old data,
	•	or replaying operation history,

the object:
	•	preserves state across calls,
	•	updates only touched parts,
	•	and exposes the required API behavior.

Deep identity

This family is not primarily about syntax, classes, or OOP vocabulary.

It is about:
	•	long-lived internal state,
	•	operation contracts,
	•	synchronization between multiple internal representations,
	•	and local updates that preserve global correctness.

That is the family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Design / Object-State naturally lives in:
	•	API / class interfaces
	•	caches
	•	iterators
	•	stream readers
	•	online statistics structures
	•	mutable containers
	•	stateful service-like objects

Job

Usually one of:
	•	support repeated operations
	•	maintain policy over time
	•	expose online queries/updates
	•	preserve internal ordering/recency/frequency
	•	serve buffered or incremental reads
	•	maintain rolling aggregates or special views

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	full history of previous operations
	•	full collection rebuild
	•	repeated scan of all stored items
	•	replay of updates from scratch
	•	recomputation of policy order

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	recomputing current object state from historical data at every operation

Engine type

Design / Object-State is a:
	•	persistent-state engine
	•	operation-maintenance engine
	•	synchronization engine
	•	local-update engine

State object

Usually:
	•	internal containers
	•	helper maps
	•	linked structures
	•	counters/cursors
	•	buffers
	•	policy metadata
	•	sometimes multiple synchronized structures

Invariant object

Usually:

the internal representation always matches the object’s abstract contract after every operation

Proof object

Usually:
	•	representation-invariant proof
	•	operation-preservation proof
	•	synchronization proof across internal structures
	•	amortized/local-touch proof

Memory object

Usually:
	•	persistent internal data structures
	•	auxiliary indices/maps
	•	buffers/cursors
	•	sometimes duplicated structure for speed

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Design / Object-State is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Repeated-operations requirement

The problem must involve multiple operations over time.

Examples:
	•	get/put
	•	next/hasNext
	•	read repeatedly
	•	add/remove/query
	•	update frequency/recency
	•	maintain running summary

If the task is one-shot batch computation, this is not the right primary family.

⸻

3.2 Persistent-state requirement

The answer to a new operation depends on what happened before.

Examples:
	•	cache contents depend on prior inserts/gets
	•	iterator position depends on prior calls
	•	buffered reader depends on unread leftovers
	•	frequency counts depend on previous updates

This persistence is the family’s core.

⸻

3.3 Local-update requirement

A good design solution must avoid global replay.

That means there should exist an internal representation where each operation updates only a small part of the state.

Examples:
	•	moving one node in LRU
	•	updating frequency bucket in LFU
	•	advancing one iterator pointer
	•	consuming from a buffer without rereading whole source

If every operation still needs a full rebuild, the design is poor or incomplete.

⸻

3.4 Representation-sufficiency requirement

The chosen internal state must be enough to answer all operations correctly.

This is analogous to “state sufficiency” in DP, but here the state persists across time instead of across recursive subproblems.

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

This family becomes attractive when:
	•	there are many operations
	•	operations have explicit complexity targets
	•	rebuilding from scratch per call is too slow
	•	the prompt implicitly asks for an online / stateful structure

Typical signal:
	•	“design”
	•	“implement class”
	•	“support operations in O(1)”
	•	“multiple calls”
	•	“read4 multiple times”
	•	“stream”

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where the family fails.

4.1 One-shot computation

If there is only one final answer and no persistent API, design/object-state is not primary.

4.2 No persistent dependence

If each query is independent, a static algorithm/data structure may be enough.

4.3 State chosen without invariants

Many poor designs keep some data, but not the right synchronized representation.

4.4 Overengineering

Sometimes a simple array/map solution is enough; not every repeated-ops problem needs a complex object architecture.

So the chapter must teach:

Design / Object-State is not “any class implementation.”

It is “problems where repeated operations require a durable internal representation that stays correct across time.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand Design / Object-State, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Typical brute-force forms:
	•	on every get, rescan all stored items
	•	on every put, rebuild ordering
	•	on every iterator call, recompute next result from scratch
	•	on every stream read, reread or reconstruct leftover state
	•	on every frequency/recency change, resort or fully recalculate structure

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because many object problems sound like:
	•	“what is the least recently used item now?”
	•	“what is the next unread character now?”
	•	“which item has minimum frequency now?”
	•	“what should this operation return now?”

A naive answer is:

inspect or rebuild the whole current situation

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	the object’s current state changes only locally between operations,
	•	but brute force re-derives it globally every time.

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time by reconstructing the object’s current abstract state from history instead of preserving and updating it directly.

That is the family bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Repeated replay or rebuild across operations.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

Most operations only affect a small local part of the abstract state.

Examples:
	•	one cache item becomes most recent
	•	one key’s frequency changes
	•	one pointer advances
	•	one unread buffer prefix shrinks
	•	one queue/stack front/back changes

6.3 Why this matters

If the representation is right, the object can update just that touched local region.

That is the enabler.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> Design / Object-State

7.1 Source brute-force object

History replay / full-state recomputation.

7.2 Waste

Re-deriving current object state from scratch after every operation.

7.3 Compression enabler

The system’s true state can be stored explicitly and maintained locally.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	operation history as implicit truth

with:
	•	explicit persistent internal representation

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	recomputing from all prior operations,

we now argue:
	•	each operation preserves the representation invariant
	•	only touched parts are updated
	•	the state after each operation is already ready for the next one

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Time drops sharply, memory rises to:
	•	persistent helpers
	•	indices/maps
	•	linked structure nodes
	•	buffers/metadata

That is the full BF→Design/Object-State transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Design state must be extremely precise.

8.1 What state must do

A good persistent state must satisfy all of these:

Sufficiency

It must answer every future operation correctly.

Locality

Each operation should modify only the necessary small part.

Synchronization

If multiple structures exist, they must remain consistent.

Durability

State must survive between calls.

Observability alignment

The internal state must match the abstract API meaning.

⸻

8.2 Common state forms

Hash map + linked list

For:
	•	LRU cache
	•	ordered recency tracking

Hash map + frequency buckets

For:
	•	LFU cache
	•	grouped counts with order inside each bucket

Cursor + buffer

For:
	•	stream readers
	•	Read4-like multi-call problems

Stack/queue pairings

For:
	•	Min Stack
	•	queue via stacks
	•	stack via queues

Iterator state

For:
	•	BST iterator
	•	flattened structure traversal

Running aggregate state

For:
	•	online median
	•	moving averages
	•	counters/statistics

⸻

8.3 Good state test

A good object-state design is enough to answer:
	•	what is the current abstract content/order/policy?
	•	what operation changes it?
	•	how is that change localized?
	•	what must remain synchronized?

8.4 Bad state
	•	no clear source of truth
	•	recomputation still needed each operation
	•	duplicated structures that drift out of sync
	•	state too weak to answer future calls
	•	state too implicit in operation history

So the state requirement is:

The persistent state must explicitly encode the object’s live abstract state, not merely a history from which it could be reconstructed.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

This family lives or dies on invariants.

⸻

9.1 Representation invariant

The fundamental invariant.

Form:

the internal data structures together exactly represent the object’s abstract state after every completed operation.

This is the family’s main law.

⸻

9.2 Synchronization invariant

If multiple structures are used:

Form:

every logical item appears consistently in all linked internal structures in the correct relationship.

Examples:
	•	a cache key in the map points to the right linked-list node
	•	a frequency bucket matches the item’s recorded count
	•	a buffer pointer and unread content agree

This is one of the most important invariants in the family.

⸻

9.3 Policy invariant

For policy-driven objects:

Form:

the internal order/grouping correctly reflects the required policy.

Examples:
	•	LRU order
	•	LFU min-frequency group
	•	iterator next order
	•	min-stack auxiliary structure matches minima policy

⸻

9.4 Cursor/buffer invariant

For reader/iterator systems:

Form:

the cursor or buffer exactly represents the unread/unreturned portion of the source.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Design / Object-State has a characteristic grammar.

10.1 Read current state

Identify current relevant internal item or position.

10.2 Apply operation locally

Touch only affected structures.

10.3 Synchronize helpers

Update all auxiliary indices/links/counters/buffers involved.

10.4 Preserve policy/order

If policy matters, reinsert/move/promote/demote as needed.

10.5 Return result

Return the operation’s output from the now-updated or just-read state.

This gives the family rhythm:

inspect live state -> locally update touched structures -> restore invariant -> return

That is the machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where the family branches.

⸻

11.1 Cache design

Identity

Maintain a bounded store under an eviction policy.

Requirements
	•	repeated get/put
	•	policy order/group must be maintained
	•	eviction must be efficient

Canonicals
	•	LRU Cache
	•	LFU Cache

Why important

This is the central design/object-state archetype.

⸻

11.2 Iterator design

Identity

Expose next elements incrementally without recomputing from scratch.

Requirements
	•	persistent traversal state
	•	future next-element answer encoded in current cursor/stack state

Canonicals
	•	BST Iterator
	•	stream/flattened iterator families

Why important

This teaches cursor-state representation.

⸻

11.3 Buffered stream design

Identity

Read from a lower-level source while preserving leftovers across multiple calls.

Requirements
	•	unread remainder must persist
	•	input source cannot be restarted/replayed cheaply

Canonicals
	•	Read N Characters Given Read4 II

Why important

This is the canonical buffer-state archetype.

⸻

11.4 Online statistics / policy structures

Identity

Maintain running answers under repeated insert/update operations.

Canonicals
	•	moving average
	•	online median
	•	min stack
	•	frequency tracker variants

Why important

This teaches auxiliary-state synchronization.

⸻

11.5 Container emulation / adapter design

Identity

Use one or more internal structures to emulate another API efficiently.

Canonicals
	•	queue using stacks
	•	stack using queues
	•	min stack

Why important

This teaches representation choice under API contracts.

