14. Confusion map

⸻

14.1 Design / Object-State vs ordinary data-structure usage

Ordinary usage

One-shot algorithm uses a structure temporarily.

Design/Object-State

The structure itself is the solution and must remain correct across multiple future calls.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the problem about solving once, or about preserving a live interface over time?

⸻

14.2 Design / Object-State vs Heap/Hashing/etc.

Hash map, heap, linked list, queue may appear, but they are helpers.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the real challenge choosing the internal persistent representation and keeping helpers synchronized?

If yes, primary family is Design/Object-State.

⸻

14.3 Design / Object-State vs DP state

Both involve “state,” but very differently.

DP

State is over subproblems during one solve.

Object-State

State persists across external API calls over time.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the state for future recursive subproblems, or for future user operations?

⸻

14.4 Design / Object-State vs Greedy/Graph/etc.

If an object uses a heap or graph internally, that helper does not necessarily define the family. The primary family is often the persistent API contract.

⸻

15. Failure modes

Failure 1 — No clear representation invariant

Most common conceptual failure.

Failure 2 — Internal structures drift out of sync

Classic map/list/bucket bug.

Failure 3 — Replay still required

Meaning the state was not chosen strongly enough.

Failure 4 — Wrong source of truth

Two different internal views disagree about current object content/order.

Failure 5 — Ignoring repeated-call semantics

Especially in buffered-reader and iterator problems.

Failure 6 — Not updating policy metadata

E.g. forgetting to move key to most-recent, or update min frequency.

Failure 7 — Hidden stale entries

Especially in heap-assisted objects.

