16. Correctness proof shapes

⸻

16.1 Representation-invariant proof

Default proof.

Structure
	1.	define the abstract object state
	2.	define the internal representation invariant
	3.	show initialization satisfies it
	4.	show each operation preserves it
	5.	conclude every returned answer is correct because the representation always matches the abstract contract

This is the family’s core proof grammar.

⸻

16.2 Synchronization proof

For multi-structure objects.

Structure
	•	every logical item is inserted/updated/removed consistently across all helper structures
	•	therefore helpers remain aligned

⸻

16.3 Policy-preservation proof

For caches and ordered objects.

Structure
	•	after each operation, the internal order/grouping still matches the eviction/traversal/statistical policy
	•	therefore future operations see the correct policy state

⸻

16.4 Buffer/cursor proof

For iterators/readers.

Structure
	•	internal cursor/buffer exactly matches what remains unread/unreturned
	•	advancing or consuming updates this state correctly
	•	therefore repeated calls are correct

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

17.1 Local-touch proof

Most important proof shape.

Each operation touches only:
	•	one map entry
	•	one or a few list nodes
	•	one buffer segment
	•	one or two stacks/queues
	•	one heap update

Therefore per-operation cost is bounded.

17.2 Synchronization cost proof

If multiple structures are updated, total work is still the sum of a small constant number of local updates.

17.3 Amortized proof

For some buffered or lazy-cleanup systems, average cost over many operations matters more than worst-case single call.

This must be stated honestly when applicable.

⸻

