25. Final deep compression of the family

The irreducible statement of Design / Object-State is:

Design / Object-State is valid when repeated operations depend on prior history, so the current abstract system state must be stored explicitly and updated locally instead of being reconstructed from scratch each time.

And the irreducible teaching statement is:

The learner has mastered Design / Object-State only when they can name:
	•	the abstract contract,
	•	the persistent internal representation,
	•	the key invariant(s),
	•	the subtype,
	•	and exactly how each operation preserves synchronization without replay.

The next strongest chapter to build is Math / Invariant.

Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Math / Invariant

This chapter is written to the same standard as the Sliding Window, Binary Search, Dynamic Programming, Greedy, BFS, DFS, Hashing, Two Pointers, Prefix State, Monotonic Stack / Deque, Heap / Priority Queue, Backtracking, Union-Find, Trie, Range Structures, Graph Advanced, and Design / Object-State chapters.

Math / Invariant is often taught too vaguely as:
	•	“there is a trick”
	•	“just use xor”
	•	“derive a formula”
	•	“observe a pattern”
	•	“this is math”

That is only the surface.

The deeper truth is:

Math / Invariant is a structure-collapse engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	explicit simulation, enumeration, or repeated state exploration

with:
	•	a smaller conserved quantity, algebraic law, bit property, parity law, modular relation, or closed-form transformation that already determines the answer.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

Math / Invariant problems are solved by identifying a property that remains true, transforms predictably, or determines the answer more directly than step-by-step simulation.

Instead of:
	•	simulating every move,
	•	testing many candidates,
	•	enumerating many combinations,
	•	or replaying arithmetic literally,

they:
	•	expose the hidden conserved or derivable structure,
	•	reason at that structural level,
	•	and compute the answer from it.

Deep identity

This family is not “miscellaneous formulas.”

It is about:
	•	replacing process-level reasoning with law-level reasoning,
	•	finding the right abstract quantity,
	•	proving that quantity is sufficient,
	•	and using it to collapse the problem.

That is the family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Math / Invariant naturally lives in:
	•	integers / arithmetic
	•	bit patterns
	•	parity and xor worlds
	•	modular arithmetic
	•	digit decomposition
	•	geometry / combinatorics
	•	process/game states with conserved quantities
	•	counting worlds with closed forms

Job

Usually one of:
	•	derive exact value
	•	decide feasibility/impossibility
	•	count without enumeration
	•	optimize via formula or monotone relation
	•	compress repeated simulation
	•	prove a process invariant
	•	exploit representation-level structure

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	full simulation timeline
	•	many candidate numbers
	•	many operations/moves
	•	all subsets or counts explicitly
	•	literal arithmetic/string/bit process

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	simulating details that are irrelevant once a stronger structural law is known

Engine type

Math / Invariant is a:
	•	law-extraction engine
	•	conserved-quantity engine
	•	representation-structure engine
	•	algebraic-collapse engine

State object

Usually very small:
	•	parity flag
	•	xor accumulator
	•	carry
	•	remainder
	•	gcd/lcm relation
	•	invariant scalar/vector
	•	digit pointer
	•	combinatorial count formula components

Invariant object

Usually:

some quantity remains unchanged, changes in a fully predictable way, or uniquely characterizes the answer

Proof object

Usually:
	•	invariant proof
	•	algebraic equivalence proof
	•	modular reasoning
	•	parity argument
	•	extremal/impossibility argument
	•	combinatorial counting proof

Memory object

Usually:
	•	O(1)
or
	•	per-digit/per-bit tiny state

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Math / Invariant is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Structural-law requirement

There must exist a hidden law stronger than direct simulation.

Common forms:
	•	parity conservation
	•	xor cancellation
	•	modular remainder relation
	•	gcd/lcm divisibility structure
	•	digit-place decomposition
	•	combinatorial counting identity
	•	symmetry
	•	conserved sum/difference
	•	monotone quantity with impossibility implication

If no such law exists, this family may be only decorative, not primary.

⸻

3.2 Sufficiency requirement

The chosen invariant/formula must actually determine the answer.

This is crucial.

Not every observation is sufficient.
A true math solution needs a quantity that is not just interesting, but decisive.

Examples:
	•	xor of duplicates cancels to single number
	•	equal parity class determines feasibility
	•	gcd condition determines reachability/divisibility
	•	number of set bits or digit contributions determines result
	•	modular equivalence determines sub-condition

⸻

3.3 Compression requirement

The law must collapse the brute-force process meaningfully.

Examples:
	•	O(n²) candidate search -> O(n) xor/parity scan
	•	O(k) repeated operations -> O(1) formula
	•	simulation over huge numbers -> per-digit or logarithmic reasoning
	•	exponential counting -> combinatorial count formula

If the “math insight” does not actually reduce the computational burden, it is not yet the right engine.

⸻

3.4 Proof requirement

A real Math / Invariant solution must be provable.

Intuition like “pattern seems to continue” is not enough.

The problem must support one of:
	•	exact algebraic derivation
	•	invariant preservation proof
	•	modular equivalence proof
	•	counting proof
	•	impossibility proof

⸻

3.5 Budget requirement

This family becomes attractive when:
	•	direct simulation is too slow for large values
	•	n or numeric ranges are huge
	•	brute force has obvious arithmetic redundancy
	•	the process has repeated local actions suggesting conservation/cancellation

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where the family fails.

4.1 Pattern-spotting without proof

Seeing a few examples is not enough.

4.2 Formula without derivation

A guessed closed form is not a valid solution.

4.3 Invariant too weak

Some conserved quantity may be true but insufficient to answer the question.

4.4 Hidden algorithmic core still needed

Sometimes a small formula exists, but the main problem is still graph/DP/search driven.

So the chapter must teach:

Math / Invariant is not “a clever trick.”

It is “a law-level description that replaces lower-level computation and is strong enough to determine the answer.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

To understand Math / Invariant, you must understand what it replaces.

5.1 Canonical brute force

Typical brute-force forms:
	•	simulate process step by step
	•	try all candidates
	•	count by enumeration
	•	perform repeated arithmetic operations literally
	•	compare all numbers/paths/states directly

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because many problems sound procedural:
	•	keep transforming
	•	keep adding/removing
	•	keep moving pieces
	•	keep dividing/multiplying
	•	check all possibilities

The naive reaction is:

just simulate it

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	the low-level process contains repeated structure,
	•	but brute force keeps handling the details instead of the governing law.

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time simulating details that are already determined by a smaller invariant, arithmetic law, or representation-level property.

That is the family bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Over-simulation or over-enumeration.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

Some smaller quantity controls the whole process.

Examples:
	•	duplicates cancel in xor
	•	parity classes decide feasibility
	•	gcd summarizes divisibility reach
	•	digits contribute independently by place
	•	modular residue determines behavior class
	•	geometric or combinatorial symmetry reduces counting

6.3 Why this matters

Once the controlling law is identified, the full process is no longer necessary.

That is the enabler.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> Math / Invariant

7.1 Source brute-force object

Simulation, candidate testing, or enumeration.

7.2 Waste

Repeated low-level work.

7.3 Compression enabler

A decisive invariant, algebraic identity, modular law, or combinatorial formula.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	detailed process state

with:
	•	tiny derived state or formula inputs

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	showing simulation works by exhaustive steps,

we now argue:
	•	the invariant is preserved,
	•	the algebraic equivalence is exact,
	•	or the formula counts exactly what is needed.

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Usually no extra memory; often the method is both faster and lighter.

That is the full BF→Math/Invariant transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Math / Invariant state must be precise.

8.1 Common state forms

Parity state
	•	even/odd
	•	parity count
	•	parity class

XOR state
	•	running xor
	•	bitwise cancellation summary

Modular state
	•	remainder modulo k
	•	residue class

Digit state
	•	current digit
	•	place value
	•	carry

Divisibility state
	•	gcd/lcm
	•	factor counts
	•	prime exponent summary

Conserved scalar
	•	total difference
	•	sum
	•	balance
	•	number of moves parity
	•	invariant score

Counting parameters
	•	n, k, chosen positions
	•	combinatorial coefficients

8.2 Good state test

A good math-state is enough to answer:
	•	what aspect of the process actually matters?
	•	what smaller quantity replaces the whole process?
	•	why do we not need the full simulation anymore?

8.3 Bad state
	•	vague “pattern”
	•	empirical observation without law
	•	too much detail retained
	•	invariant that is true but not useful

So the state requirement is:

The chosen mathematical state must be the smallest decisive quantity that still determines the answer.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

Different subtypes use different invariants.

⸻

9.1 Conservation invariant

Form:

some quantity does not change under the allowed operation(s).

Examples:
	•	parity preserved
	•	xor preserved under pair cancellation style behavior
	•	sum/difference preserved

⸻

9.2 Predictable-transform invariant

Form:

the quantity changes in a fully known way after each operation, so final value is derivable without simulating all details.

Examples:
	•	carry propagation
	•	digit-by-digit change
	•	repeated halving/exponentiation structure

⸻

9.3 Equivalence-class invariant

Form:

states with the same residue/parity/class behave identically for the purpose of the question.

Examples:
	•	modulo classes
	•	parity classes
	•	canonical reduced forms

⸻

9.4 Counting invariant

Form:

each object is counted exactly once by the formula/combinatorial decomposition.

⸻

9.5 Impossibility invariant

Form:

some required property cannot change enough to reach the target, so the answer is impossible.

This is common in game and transformation problems.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Math / Invariant has several grammars depending on subtype.

⸻

10.1 Accumulate-and-collapse grammar
	1.	scan items
	2.	accumulate invariant quantity
	3.	return collapsed result

Example:
	•	xor accumulation
	•	parity count
	•	gcd reduction

⸻

10.2 Per-digit / per-bit grammar
	1.	inspect representation one digit/bit at a time
	2.	update carry/state
	3.	combine place contributions

⸻

10.3 Residue-class grammar
	1.	map values/states into classes mod k
	2.	reason by class relation
	3.	infer answer without full simulation

⸻

10.4 Formula-derivation grammar
	1.	identify decomposition/count law
	2.	compute formula components
	3.	return exact result

This gives the family rhythm:

identify governing law -> compress state to invariant/formula -> derive answer

That is the machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

This is where the family branches.

⸻

11.1 XOR / cancellation math

Identity

Use xor properties to cancel paired duplicates or track bitwise parity.

Requirements
	•	operation or data structure aligns with xor cancellation/bit parity

Canonicals
	•	Single Number
	•	missing/duplicate xor-style families

Why important

This is the cleanest “representation law replaces brute force” archetype.

⸻

11.2 Parity / odd-even reasoning

Identity

Use parity classes or parity conservation.

Requirements
	•	operations preserve or predictably flip parity
	•	parity decides feasibility or count behavior

Canonicals
	•	many transform/impossibility puzzles
	•	count odd/even-driven tasks

Why important

This is a major impossibility/feasibility archetype.

⸻

11.3 Modular arithmetic / residue reasoning

Identity

Use modulo classes to collapse large values/states.

Requirements
	•	the property depends only on residue class or remainder relation

Canonicals
	•	divisibility cycles
	•	modular behavior families
	•	repeated process modulo reduction

Why important

This is one of the broadest math subfamilies.

⸻

11.4 GCD / divisibility structure

Identity

Use gcd/lcm or factor relations to determine reachability/divisibility compatibility.

Requirements
	•	divisibility or repeated additive/multiplicative transformations central

Canonicals
	•	reachability by repeated additions/subtractions
	•	gcd-driven simplification families

Why important

This is a common hidden-law archetype.

⸻

11.5 Digit / place-value decomposition

Identity

Reason per digit or per place rather than by whole-number brute force.

Requirements
	•	decimal/binary representation matters
	•	place contributions are separable or recursively manageable

Canonicals
	•	Reverse Integer
	•	Add Two Numbers (arithmetically)
	•	digit-counting / carry problems
	•	counting digit appearances families

Why important

This is the representation-decomposition archetype.

⸻

11.6 Combinatorial counting / closed form

Identity

Count directly rather than enumerate.

Requirements
	•	objects can be partitioned into countable classes
	•	overcounting/undercounting controlled

Canonicals
	•	handshake/combination-style counts
	•	choose-position/arrangement formulas
	•	contribution counting

Why important

This is the enumeration-collapse archetype.

⸻

11.7 Geometry / symmetry / invariant reasoning

Identity

Use geometric symmetry or conserved geometric quantity.

Requirements
	•	the problem has symmetric equivalence or invariant measure

Why important

Less common in standard interview lists, but still belongs in the family.

⸻

12. Composite helpers

Math / Invariant often combines with other tools.

12.1 Math + scan

For:
	•	xor accumulation
	•	gcd sweep
	•	parity counting

