16. Correctness proof shapes

⸻

16.1 Invariant-preservation proof

Default proof.

Structure
	1.	define invariant quantity
	2.	show each allowed operation preserves it or changes it predictably
	3.	conclude final answer depends only on this quantity

This is the family’s main proof grammar.

⸻

16.2 Algebraic-equivalence proof

For formula derivations.

Structure
	•	transform the brute-force quantity into equivalent algebraic form
	•	simplify exactly
	•	conclude formula correctness

⸻

16.3 Residue/modular proof

For modulo reasoning.

Structure
	•	show behavior depends only on residue class
	•	prove equivalent residues behave identically for the target property

⸻

16.4 Counting proof

For combinatorics.

Structure
	•	partition objects into disjoint classes or count contributions
	•	prove every valid object counted exactly once

⸻

16.5 Impossibility/extremal proof

For feasibility questions.

Structure
	•	show invariant or monotone quantity blocks reaching target
	•	conclude impossible or constrained answer

⸻

