16. Correctness proof shapes

⸻

16.1 Relation-semantics proof

Default proof.

Structure
	1.	define what the base relation means
	2.	define what each transformation does
	3.	show final relation equals the target problem meaning

This is the family’s main proof grammar.

⸻

16.2 Join-correctness proof

Structure
	•	show join condition matches exactly the intended relationship
	•	show resulting row multiplicity is correct

⸻

16.3 Group-aggregate proof

Structure
	•	show each group key collects exactly the intended rows
	•	show aggregate computes desired summary over each group

⸻

16.4 Window-partition proof

Structure
	•	partition isolates correct comparison group
	•	order defines row sequence within that group
	•	analytic function computes the intended per-row quantity

⸻

16.5 Anti-join proof

Structure
	•	LEFT JOIN preserves all candidate rows
	•	null match columns identify missing relationships exactly

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

At the atlas level, SQL complexity is conceptual rather than engine-internal.

17.1 Relational-work proof

The main reasoning is:
	•	avoid manual nested-loop semantics in the logical query design
	•	express matching and grouping at the right grain

17.2 Operator-count intuition

Complexity depends on joins, grouping, sorting for window functions, indexing, and engine implementation.

For atlas purposes, what matters is:
	•	recognizing when a set transformation replaces repeated procedural work.

17.3 Window/sort cost awareness

Partitioned analytic queries often imply ordering within partitions.
That logical sort/rank cost should be conceptually recognized, even if exact engine behavior varies.

