Here is the next full gold-standard chapter:

Direct Scan / Counting

This chapter is written to the same standard as the other family chapters.

Direct Scan / Counting is often dismissed as:
	•	“just loop once”
	•	“just keep a counter”
	•	“easy array problem”
	•	“just track max/min/sum”

That sounds simple, but the deeper truth is:

Direct Scan / Counting is a stream-aggregation engine.

It removes brute-force waste by replacing:
	•	repeated rereading or recomputation over the same sequence

with:
	•	one forward pass that accumulates exactly the sufficient summary.

That is the family identity.

⸻

1. Family identity

Core idea

A direct scan processes input in a single pass, maintaining only the summary needed so far.

Instead of:
	•	rescanning the array multiple times,
	•	recomputing partial facts,
	•	or storing unnecessary history,

it:
	•	reads each item once,
	•	updates a small state,
	•	and produces the answer from that evolving summary.

Deep identity

Direct Scan is not “trivial looping.”
It is:
	•	recognizing that the answer is stream-computable,
	•	identifying the minimum sufficient running state,
	•	and proving that no additional history is needed.

That is the family identity.

⸻

2. Ontology of the family

World

Direct Scan naturally lives in:
	•	arrays
	•	strings
	•	streams
	•	logs/events
	•	flat row-like inputs
	•	one-dimensional sequences

Job

Usually one of:
	•	count
	•	min/max
	•	running total
	•	detect a simple property
	•	track best-so-far
	•	verify monotone/local condition
	•	compute one-pass summary
	•	collect a few simple statistics

Brute-force search object

The brute-force object is usually:
	•	repeated prefix rescans
	•	repeated full-array scans for different metrics
	•	nested checks when one running summary would suffice
	•	storing full history unnecessarily

Bottleneck type

The brute-force waste is:
	•	rereading the same sequence data even though a small running summary is enough

Engine type

Direct Scan is a:
	•	one-pass aggregation engine
	•	running-summary engine
	•	stream-state engine

State object

Usually:
	•	count
	•	sum
	•	min/max
	•	current best
	•	previous item
	•	flag(s)
	•	a few accumulators

Invariant object

Usually:

after processing the first i items, the running state exactly summarizes the needed property of that prefix

Proof object

Usually:
	•	prefix-summary invariant
	•	one-pass sufficiency proof

Memory object

Usually:
	•	O(1)

That is the family fingerprint.

⸻

3. Applicability requirements

This is the most important section.

Direct Scan is valid only when these conditions hold.

⸻

3.1 Stream-sufficiency requirement

There must exist a small running state such that:

everything needed from the processed prefix is captured by that state

Examples:
	•	current count of positives
	•	max seen so far
	•	running sum
	•	previous value for local comparison
	•	number of transitions
	•	current streak length and best streak length

If the future answer depends on rich history not compressible into a tiny state, plain scan is too weak.

⸻

3.2 Local-update requirement

When reading a new item, the running state must update cheaply.

Examples:
	•	count += 1
	•	best = max(best, x)
	•	if x != prev: transitions += 1
	•	streak = streak + 1 or reset

If each new item would require revisiting many earlier items, another family is needed.

⸻

3.3 Single-order requirement

The input is consumed in one natural order, and that order is enough.

Examples:
	•	left to right
	•	event order
	•	token order

If the problem depends on multiple reorderings, rich range queries, or arbitrary future comparisons, scan alone may not suffice.

⸻

3.4 Budget requirement

This family is strongest when:
	•	O(n) is expected
	•	extra memory should be minimal
	•	multiple rescans or nested loops are unnecessary waste

⸻

4. Non-applicability requirements

A real chapter must say where the family fails.

4.1 History too rich

If you need arbitrary prior lookup, grouping, or range relations, hashing/prefix/range structures may dominate.

4.2 Multiple competing subproblems

If many futures matter, DP or graph/state methods may be needed.

4.3 Live contiguous-region maintenance

If the problem is really about one evolving subarray/substring, Sliding Window may be primary.

4.4 Ordered pair/boundary elimination

If safe pointer motion matters, Two Pointers may be primary.

So the chapter must teach:

Direct Scan is not “anything linear.”

It is “problems where one pass with a tiny sufficient summary exactly captures the answer.”

⸻

5. Brute-force baseline

5.1 Canonical brute force

Typical brute-force forms:
	•	scan once to count, again to find max, again to verify condition
	•	recompute prefix stats repeatedly
	•	nested checks where running totals or flags would suffice

5.2 Why brute force feels natural

Because many problems read like:
	•	count all X
	•	find largest Y
	•	verify whether array has property Z
	•	compute streak or trend

The naive move is:

do separate work for each sub-question

5.3 Actual waste

The waste is:
	•	the same input is read repeatedly,
	•	even though each item could have updated the needed summaries when first seen.

So the brute-force waste sentence should be:

Brute force wastes time rereading sequence elements whose contribution could have been absorbed into a small running summary the first time.

That is the family bottleneck.

⸻

6. Bottleneck diagnosis

6.1 Primary bottleneck

Repeated scans or unnecessary retained history.

6.2 Hidden structural fact

Each item contributes to the answer in a locally composable way.

Examples:
	•	each item updates a count
	•	each item may improve max/min
	•	each item extends or breaks a streak
	•	each adjacent comparison updates a local property

6.3 Why this matters

Once contributions are absorbed immediately, no revisit is needed.

That is the enabler.

⸻

7. Transformation layer: brute force -> Direct Scan

7.1 Source brute-force object

Repeated whole-array or prefix rescans.

7.2 Waste

Rereading the same data.

7.3 Compression enabler

A sufficient running summary exists.

7.4 New optimized state

Replace:
	•	raw processed history

with:
	•	a few running accumulators/flags

7.5 New proof shape

Instead of:
	•	many passes,

we now argue:
	•	after each item, state correctly summarizes the processed prefix
	•	final state yields the answer

7.6 New memory tradeoff

Usually:
	•	time drops to O(n)
	•	memory stays O(1)

That is the full BF→Direct-Scan transformation.

⸻

8. State requirements

Direct Scan state must be precise.

8.1 Common state forms
	•	count
	•	sum
	•	min_so_far, max_so_far
	•	best, current
	•	prev
	•	seen_flag
	•	transitions
	•	current_streak, best_streak

8.2 Good state test

A good state is enough to answer:
	•	what do I know about the processed prefix?
	•	what will the next item need to update?
	•	why is no other past detail needed?

8.3 Bad state
	•	storing the entire prefix when only one number was needed
	•	vague “result so far” without semantic meaning
	•	missing one critical variable like previous value or current streak

So the state requirement is:

The scan state must be the minimum exact summary of the processed prefix needed for future updates and the final answer.

⸻

9. Invariant requirements

This is the correctness backbone.

9.1 Prefix-summary invariant

The fundamental invariant.

Form:

after processing index i, the running state exactly summarizes the required property of 0..i.

This is the family’s main law.

9.2 Best-so-far invariant

For optimization scans.

Form:

best is the correct best answer among all processed items/prefixes/substructures considered so far.

9.3 Current-streak/current-segment invariant

For streak problems.

Form:

current describes the exact streak/segment ending at the current position, and best describes the best seen overall.

9.4 Previous-item invariant

For local comparison problems.

Form:

prev is the last processed relevant value, so the next step can compare/update correctly.

⸻

10. Update grammar

Direct Scan has a simple but rigid grammar.

10.1 Read next item

Consume one element/event.

10.2 Update running state

Absorb its contribution immediately.

10.3 Update answer summary if needed

Refresh best, flag, count, etc.

This gives the family rhythm:

read -> update summary -> continue

That is the machine grammar.

⸻

11. Main variations

11.1 Pure counting scan

Identity

Accumulate counts of items/events satisfying a rule.

Canonicals
	•	count negatives/positives
	•	number of transitions
	•	frequency of target in bounded/simple settings

Why important

This is the purest form.

⸻

11.2 Running min/max/sum scan

Identity

Maintain extrema or totals over the whole stream.

Canonicals
	•	maximum element
	•	running sum
	•	stock min price baseline pieces

Why important

This is the pure aggregation form.

⸻

11.3 Best-so-far optimization scan

Identity

Track a running best answer with a local current state.

Canonicals
	•	best streak
	•	max difference with running minimum
	•	simple Kadane-adjacent baselines

Why important

This is the “stream optimization” form.

⸻

11.4 Adjacent/local-condition scan

Identity

Use previous/current relation only.

Canonicals
	•	monotonic check
	•	count adjacent transitions
	•	detect sortedness
	•	compare neighboring timestamps/events

Why important

This is the local-comparison form.

⸻

11.5 Event-log scan

Identity

Consume ordered events and maintain a small running summary.

Canonicals
	•	active count from event deltas
	•	simple timeline consistency checks
	•	interval sweep baselines in simplified form

Why important

This is the sequence-of-events form.

⸻

12. Composite helpers

Direct Scan often combines with other tools.

12.1 Scan + Hashing

When one-pass state needs lookup support.

12.2 Scan + Math/Invariant

When the running state is xor, gcd, parity, etc.

12.3 Scan + Greedy

When the scan maintains a locally optimal current state.

12.4 Scan + Prefix transformation

Sometimes prefix state is really just an enriched scan.

⸻

13. Canonical archetype library for Direct Scan / Counting

Canonical 1 — Find Max / Min in Array

Why canonical

Pure one-pass extremum summary.

What it teaches
	•	no rescans needed
	•	current item updates one scalar summary

⸻

Canonical 2 — Count Occurrences / Simple frequency-by-condition

Why canonical

Pure counting scan.

What it teaches
	•	item contributes locally
	•	answer is cumulative

⸻

Canonical 3 — Best Time to Buy and Sell Stock (baseline view)

Why canonical

Pure running-min + best-profit scan.

What it teaches
	•	processed prefix summarized by min-so-far
	•	current answer updated from local item + running summary

This is one of the most important “simple scan but not trivial” canonicals.

⸻

Canonical 4 — monotonic/sortedness check

Why canonical

Pure previous-item comparison.

What it teaches
	•	only previous value matters
	•	whole-history storage unnecessary

⸻

14. Confusion map

14.1 Direct Scan vs Prefix State

Direct Scan uses a live running summary.
Prefix State stores or reasons explicitly about multiple boundary summaries.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Do I just need the running whole-prefix summary, or relations between many prefixes?

⸻

14.2 Direct Scan vs Sliding Window

Sliding Window tracks one evolving interior region.
Direct Scan tracks only a prefix summary or local stream summary.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Is the hard part one active subarray, or just the processed prefix?

⸻

14.3 Direct Scan vs Greedy

Some one-pass problems are greedy, but only when there is a safe local-choice proof.
Otherwise it may just be a scan with a running statistic.

Diagnostic

Ask:

Am I choosing among alternatives, or merely accumulating the needed summary?

⸻

14.4 Direct Scan vs DP

If the current state represents a genuine recurrence over many substructures, DP may be primary.
If it is just one running prefix summary, Direct Scan is primary.

⸻

15. Failure modes

Failure 1 — Missing one required running variable

Classic bug.

Failure 2 — Recomputing something that should have been maintained

Then the solution is no longer truly one-pass.

Failure 3 — Confusing whole-prefix summary with region-specific summary

Often leads to wrong use of plain scan where window/prefix structures are needed.

Failure 4 — Wrong initialization

Especially for min/max/current/best variables.

Failure 5 — Losing semantic meaning of state

Then updates become ad hoc and bug-prone.

⸻

16. Correctness proof shapes

16.1 Prefix-summary proof

Default proof.

Structure
	1.	define the running state meaning
	2.	show initialization is correct for empty/first prefix
	3.	show each new item updates the state correctly
	4.	conclude final state or best-so-far yields the answer

This is the family’s core proof grammar.

16.2 Best-so-far proof

For optimization scans.

Structure
	•	current state describes candidate ending/current condition
	•	best state tracks optimum over processed prefixes/items
	•	updates preserve both meanings

⸻

17. Complexity proof defaults

17.1 One-touch proof

Each item is read once and updated into state once.

Total:
	•	O(n) time

17.2 Constant-state proof

Only a fixed number of accumulators/flags/pointers are kept.

Total:
	•	O(1) extra memory

This is the family’s standard complexity shape.

⸻

18. Memory requirements

18.1 O(1) running state

Most direct scans use a handful of scalars.

18.2 Small auxiliary counters/flags

Still O(1).

18.3 Composite memory

If scan is paired with hashing or another helper, memory follows that helper.

A strong chapter must emphasize:
Direct Scan wins because it often minimizes both time and memory.

