Here is the next synthesis block:

Confusion / Anti-Pattern Atlas

This is the layer that prevents false pattern matches.

A strong atlas does not only say what a pattern is.
It must also say what it is commonly mistaken for.

That is how you stop shallow trigger-word solving.

⸻

1. Why the confusion atlas matters

Most learners do not fail because they know nothing.

They fail because they pick the adjacent wrong family.

Examples:
	•	seeing “substring” and forcing Sliding Window
	•	seeing “graph” and forcing BFS
	•	seeing “optimization” and forcing DP
	•	seeing “top k” and forcing Heap even when sorting is enough
	•	seeing “state” and calling it DP when it is really Design/Object-State

So the confusion atlas must answer:

For any problem:
	•	what family does it resemble on the surface?
	•	what family is it actually?
	•	what decisive diagnostic separates them?

That is the purpose of this synthesis layer.

⸻

2. The meta-template for every confusion pair

Every confusion entry should use the same structure.

A. Surface similarity

Why they look alike

B. Deep difference

What the real structural distinction is

C. Diagnostic question

The single best question to separate them

D. Failure mode

What goes wrong if you choose the wrong family

E. Mini examples

One example for each side

That is the gold-standard confusion template.

⸻

3. Master confusion atlas

⸻

3.1 Sliding Window vs Prefix State

Surface similarity

Both often involve:
	•	arrays
	•	subarrays
	•	sums
	•	contiguous regions

Deep difference
	•	Sliding Window maintains one live interval by moving boundaries and updating contents incrementally.
	•	Prefix State derives interval facts from the relation between two cumulative boundaries.

Diagnostic question

Is the hard part maintaining one active region, or comparing cumulative states at two boundaries?

Failure mode

If you use Sliding Window when negative numbers break monotonicity, the logic fails.
If you use Prefix State when one live validity constraint matters, the solution becomes awkward or incomplete.

Mini examples
	•	Sliding Window: longest substring with at most k distinct characters
	•	Prefix State: subarray sum equals k with negative numbers allowed

⸻

3.2 Sliding Window vs Two Pointers

Surface similarity

Both use:
	•	left pointer
	•	right pointer
	•	linear sequence
	•	O(n)-style movement

Deep difference
	•	Sliding Window: the two boundaries describe one evolving contiguous region whose contents matter.
	•	Two Pointers: the pointers are coordinated positions for elimination, compaction, merging, center expansion, or relative motion. The interior contents may not matter at all.

Diagnostic question

Do I need to know what is inside the current interval, or only how the two positions relate?

Failure mode

Mistaking a compaction or pair-elimination problem for Sliding Window leads to unnecessary internal state.
Mistaking a true window-validity problem for generic Two Pointers causes missing map/count logic.

Mini examples
	•	Sliding Window: minimum window substring
	•	Two Pointers: Two Sum II

⸻

3.3 Two Pointers vs Binary Search

Surface similarity

Both exploit:
	•	order
	•	monotonicity
	•	shrinking search space

Deep difference
	•	Two Pointers moves boundaries stepwise based on current local relation.
	•	Binary Search probes a midpoint and discards half the candidate space.

Diagnostic question

Am I compressing by adjacent boundary movement, or by midpoint halving?

Failure mode

Using Binary Search where no midpoint elimination exists leads to fake monotonicity.
Using Two Pointers where answer-space monotonicity exists misses logarithmic compression.

Mini examples
	•	Two Pointers: Container With Most Water
	•	Binary Search: Koko Eating Bananas

⸻

3.4 Hashing vs Sorting

Surface similarity

Both often help with:
	•	duplicates
	•	grouping
	•	pair problems
	•	simplifying structure

Deep difference
	•	Hashing gives direct lookup/grouping by key.
	•	Sorting gives global order and adjacency structure.

Diagnostic question

Do I need exact keyed memory, or do I need order?

Failure mode

Using hashing in an order-sensitive problem loses adjacency/rank structure.
Using sorting when direct lookup is the true bottleneck adds unnecessary O(n log n).

Mini examples
	•	Hashing: Two Sum
	•	Sorting: Merge Intervals

⸻

3.5 Hashing vs Trie

Surface similarity

Both support:
	•	dictionary-like storage
	•	string lookup
	•	membership queries

Deep difference
	•	Hashing is for exact-key equality.
	•	Trie is for shared-prefix traversal.

Diagnostic question

Is the question about exact identity, or prefix structure?

Failure mode

Using a trie for exact lookup-only workloads overcomplicates.
Using hashing when prefix pruning is central loses the whole advantage.

Mini examples
	•	Hashing: exact word dictionary membership
	•	Trie: startsWith / Word Search II pruning

⸻

3.6 DFS vs BFS

Surface similarity

Both:
	•	traverse graphs/trees/grids
	•	use visited logic
	•	can test reachability

Deep difference
	•	DFS is depth-ordered and good for structure, recursion, components, subtree logic, path existence, and backtracking.
	•	BFS is layer-ordered and good for shortest steps, nearest source, and wave propagation.

Diagnostic question

Does layer distance matter?

Failure mode

Using DFS for shortest path in an unweighted graph usually breaks optimality.
Using BFS for heavy recursive subtree logic is clumsy and unnatural.

Mini examples
	•	DFS: Number of Islands
	•	BFS: Rotting Oranges

⸻

3.7 DFS vs Backtracking

Surface similarity

Both use recursion and depth-first exploration.

Deep difference
	•	DFS is the broad exploration family.
	•	Backtracking is DFS where the current node is a partial candidate solution and choices must be undone.

Diagnostic question

Am I exploring structure, or building and undoing a candidate?

Failure mode

Calling ordinary DFS “backtracking” dilutes the real need for path/choice undo.
Calling true backtracking “just DFS” hides pruning and duplicate-avoidance logic.

Mini examples
	•	DFS: max depth of tree
	•	Backtracking: N-Queens

⸻

3.8 DFS vs DP

Surface similarity

Both can use recursion and state-like arguments.

Deep difference
	•	DFS explores branches.
	•	DP stores repeated subproblem answers.

Diagnostic question

Do different branches revisit the same abstract state enough that memoization should collapse them?

Failure mode

Using plain DFS where repeated states exist causes exponential blowup.
Using DP when states do not really repeat or are huge creates fake complexity.

Mini examples
	•	DFS: simple tree traversal
	•	DP: memoized Word Break / Edit Distance

⸻

3.9 Backtracking vs DP

Surface similarity

Both handle branching choices and can look recursive.

Deep difference
	•	Backtracking keeps many branches because different partial solutions still matter.
	•	DP collapses branches when only compact state matters.

Diagnostic question

Do I need the actual different partial constructions, or only the best/count/feasible answer for each compact state?

Failure mode

Using backtracking on strong-overlap state spaces becomes exponential.
Using DP when you must enumerate actual solutions loses solution structure.

Mini examples
	•	Backtracking: generate all subsets
	•	DP: count number of ways to reach sum

⸻

3.10 Greedy vs DP

Surface similarity

Both often appear in optimization problems.

Deep difference
	•	Greedy keeps one local choice because it is provably safe.
	•	DP preserves multiple futures because local choice is not yet safe.

Diagnostic question

Can one local choice safely dominate all alternatives right now?

Failure mode

A fake greedy guess fails on counterexamples.
A needless DP wastes effort where an exchange argument exists.

Mini examples
	•	Greedy: Activity Selection
	•	DP: Coin Change minimum coins

⸻

3.11 Greedy vs Heap

Surface similarity

Many solutions use both.

Deep difference
	•	Greedy is the decision logic.
	•	Heap is the data structure that can support that logic.

Diagnostic question

Is the heap merely helping me choose the current best active candidate?

Failure mode

Calling a heap-based scheduling problem “heap” without identifying the greedy policy misses the proof.
Calling it purely greedy without noticing the dynamic active set misses the implementation engine.

Mini examples
	•	Greedy + Heap: Meeting Rooms II
	•	Pure Heap flavor: merge k sorted lists

⸻

3.12 Heap vs Monotonic Deque

Surface similarity

Both can return a current max/min.

Deep difference
	•	Heap maintains best among a generic dynamic active set.
	•	Monotonic Deque maintains best under sequence order plus permanent domination and expiry.

Diagnostic question

Does order and domination in a sliding sequence matter?

Failure mode

Using a heap for sliding max often introduces stale entries and extra log factors.
Using deque when arbitrary active ordering is needed fails.

Mini examples
	•	Heap: process current minimum task among active tasks
	•	Monotonic Deque: Sliding Window Maximum

⸻

3.13 Monotonic Stack vs Greedy

Surface similarity

Both pop weaker candidates.

Deep difference
	•	Greedy commits to one choice path.
	•	Monotonic Stack keeps multiple still-live candidates, deleting only those permanently dominated.

Diagnostic question

Am I preserving a frontier of unresolved candidates, or collapsing the decision tree to one choice?

Failure mode

Treating a monotonic-stack problem as greedy loses the nearest-boundary semantics.
Treating a greedy choice rule as monotonic stack leads to unnecessary container logic.

Mini examples
	•	Monotonic Stack: Daily Temperatures
	•	Greedy: Gas Station

⸻

3.14 Prefix State vs DP

Surface similarity

Both can involve arrays and states.

Deep difference
	•	Prefix State stores cumulative history up to boundaries.
	•	DP stores answers to recursive subproblems/states.

Diagnostic question

Is the answer about relation between cumulative boundaries, or about solving many subproblems?

Failure mode

Calling prefix-sum problems DP causes unnecessary tables.
Calling real DP “prefix” loses branching-state structure.

Mini examples
	•	Prefix State: Subarray Sum Equals K
	•	DP: Longest Common Subsequence

⸻

3.15 DSU vs DFS/BFS

Surface similarity

All can answer connectivity questions.

Deep difference
	•	DSU maintains equivalence classes under merges.
	•	DFS/BFS explicitly explores structure.

Diagnostic question

Do I only need to know who is connected to whom after many unions, or do I need actual traversal/path structure?

Failure mode

Using DFS repeatedly across many merge operations is too slow.
Using DSU when path length/order matters is insufficient.

Mini examples
	•	DSU: Redundant Connection
	•	DFS/BFS: shortest path or actual component exploration once

⸻

3.16 Range Structures vs Prefix State

Surface similarity

Both answer interval queries.

Deep difference
	•	Prefix State handles static cumulative-difference style queries well.
	•	Range Structures handle many updates or more general range combines.

Diagnostic question

Are updates frequent, and can two prefixes solve the query?

Failure mode

Using prefix sums with many updates causes rebuild pain.
Using segment tree when immutable prefix queries suffice is overengineering.

Mini examples
	•	Prefix State: immutable range sums
	•	Segment Tree: mutable range min/sum queries

⸻

3.17 Trie vs Backtracking composite confusion

Surface similarity

Problems like Word Search II use both.

Deep difference
	•	Backtracking/DFS explores paths.
	•	Trie prunes prefixes and indexes dictionary structure.

Diagnostic question

Is the main exploration over board paths, with trie only pruning them?

Failure mode

Calling the problem “trie” alone hides the search tree.
Calling it just backtracking misses the prefix-pruning engine.

Mini examples
	•	Trie primary-ish: startsWith dictionary
	•	Trie + Backtracking composite: Word Search II

⸻

3.18 Design / Object-State vs helper-structure confusion

Surface similarity

Many design problems use hash maps, heaps, linked lists, queues.

Deep difference
	•	Design/Object-State is about preserving a live abstract API state across calls.
	•	The helper structures are only internal mechanics.

Diagnostic question

Is the real challenge persistent representation and invariant maintenance across operations?

Failure mode

Calling LRU “hash map + linked list” misses the object contract and synchronization logic.
Calling BST Iterator “just stack” misses the persistent cursor-state semantics.

Mini examples
	•	Design/Object-State: LRU Cache
	•	Helper-only use elsewhere: ordinary one-shot hash map solution

⸻

3.19 Graph Advanced vs DP

Surface similarity

Both can have states, relaxations, and transitions.

Deep difference
	•	Graph Advanced centers graph structure, frontier order, or dependency order.
	•	DP centers subproblem recurrence over a usually more abstract state DAG/table.

Diagnostic question

Is the main organizing principle a graph processing order or a recurrence over compact subproblems?

Failure mode

Calling Dijkstra “DP” obscures frontier-finalization invariant.
Calling DAG DP “just graph traversal” misses recurrence meaning.

Mini examples
	•	Graph Advanced: Dijkstra
	•	DP on DAG: longest path in DAG via topo order (borderline composite)

⸻

3.20 Math / Invariant vs Greedy / DP / Search

Surface similarity

Sometimes all seem possible.

Deep difference
	•	Math / Invariant collapses the process with a law.
	•	Greedy keeps one safe local decision path.
	•	DP/Search still retain multiple states/branches.

Diagnostic question

Is there a smaller decisive law that makes the whole process unnecessary?

Failure mode

Missing the invariant causes huge overcomputation.
Forcing a fake “math trick” without proof leads to wrong answers.

Mini examples
	•	Math/Invariant: Single Number via xor
	•	Search/DP counterpart: many explicit state-based problems with no collapse law

⸻

4. Anti-pattern atlas

Now the more dangerous layer:

not just “X vs Y,” but “false triggers that cause wrong family selection.”

⸻

4.1 False trigger: “substring/subarray” => Sliding Window

Wrong because

Some subarray problems are actually:
	•	Prefix State
	•	Prefix + Hashing
	•	Monotonic Deque
	•	DP

Safer rule

Only use Sliding Window when:
	•	the interval is contiguous,
	•	and validity/score can be maintained incrementally by add/remove,
	•	and monotone boundary movement works.

⸻

4.2 False trigger: “sorted” => Binary Search

Wrong because

Sorted data might instead want:
	•	Two Pointers
	•	merge logic
	•	Greedy by order
	•	plain scan

Safer rule

Binary Search requires:
	•	ordered domain,
	•	midpoint probe,
	•	safe half elimination.

⸻

4.3 False trigger: “optimization” => DP

Wrong because

Optimization problems may be:
	•	Greedy
	•	Binary Search on answer
	•	Heap
	•	Math / Invariant
	•	Direct Scan

Safer rule

DP requires:
	•	compact state,
	•	overlap,
	•	recurrence.

⸻

4.4 False trigger: “graph” => BFS/DFS

Wrong because

Graph problems may actually be:
	•	DSU
	•	Dijkstra
	•	Topological Sort
	•	DAG DP
	•	state-augmented graph search

Safer rule

Ask first:
	•	unweighted shortest path?
	•	simple traversal?
	•	connectivity only?
	•	weighted?
	•	dependencies?
	•	extra state?

⸻

4.5 False trigger: “top k” => Heap

Wrong because

Sometimes:
	•	sorting once is enough
	•	counting buckets are better
	•	quickselect may dominate

Safer rule

Heap is strongest when:
	•	active set changes
or
	•	only repeated best extraction matters
or
	•	memory capped at k is useful.

⸻

4.6 False trigger: “recursive” => Backtracking

Wrong because

Recursive problems may be:
	•	DFS
	•	DP
	•	divide-and-conquer
	•	tree recursion with return values

Safer rule

Backtracking specifically requires:
	•	partial candidate,
	•	legal next choices,
	•	pruning,
	•	undo.

⸻

4.7 False trigger: “state” => DP

Wrong because

State appears in:
	•	Design/Object-State
	•	Graph Advanced
	•	BFS/DFS
	•	Prefix State
	•	Backtracking

Safer rule

DP state means:
	•	one state summarizes a subproblem,
	•	and repeated branches reuse it.

⸻

4.8 False trigger: “O(1) lookup” => Hashing

Wrong because

Some problems want:
	•	Trie for prefixes
	•	arrays for bounded alphabets
	•	DSU for connectivity reps
	•	object-state synchronization with map as helper

Safer rule

Hashing is primary only when key-based lookup/grouping/counting is the actual engine.

⸻

5. Master diagnostic ladder

When unsure, use this order:

Step 1

What is the shape?
	•	sequence
	•	tree
	•	graph
	•	table
	•	object/API
	•	numbers/bits

Step 2

What is the job?
	•	existence
	•	count
	•	shortest path
	•	grouping
	•	top-k
	•	all solutions
	•	repeated operations
	•	range query
	•	exact formula

Step 3

What is the brute-force object?
	•	pair
	•	range
	•	path
	•	subset
	•	active set
	•	subproblem
	•	row relation
	•	connectivity component

Step 4

What is the waste type?
	•	repeated lookup
	•	repeated range scan
	•	repeated path exploration
	•	repeated best-element search
	•	repeated subproblem
	•	repeated replay across operations
	•	repeated component discovery

Step 5

What is the compression enabler?
	•	order
	•	prefix relation
	•	shared prefix
	•	local dominance
	•	recurrence overlap
	•	layer order
	•	representative equivalence
	•	invariant law
	•	relation key
	•	hierarchical summary

This ladder almost always separates adjacent families.

⸻

6. Central Proof Library

Now the next synthesis block.

A strong atlas needs one centralized proof grammar manual.

⸻

6.1 Why a proof library matters

Most learners know code before they know why the code is correct.

That causes:
	•	shallow memorization
	•	inability to adapt variants
	•	interview weakness
	•	brittle debugging

So each family should map to a small set of proof grammars.

⸻

6.2 Proof grammar catalog

A. Prefix-summary proof

Used for:
	•	Direct Scan
	•	Prefix State
	•	some Hashing scans

Core form:
	1.	define running/prefix state meaning
	2.	prove initialization
	3.	show one new item updates the summary correctly
	4.	conclude final state or relations on states give answer

⸻

B. Loop invariant proof

Used for:
	•	Two Pointers
	•	Sliding Window
	•	Binary Search
	•	many greedy scans
	•	object methods

Core form:
	1.	define invariant before loop iteration
	2.	show step preserves invariant
	3.	show termination + invariant imply correctness

⸻

C. Elimination proof

Used for:
	•	Two Pointers opposite-end
	•	Binary Search
	•	some greedy and graph pruning

Core form:
	1.	identify current candidate region
	2.	show one move discards an impossible part
	3.	prove discarded region cannot contain answer

⸻

D. Exchange argument

Used for:
	•	Greedy

Core form:
	1.	take an optimal solution
	2.	show greedy choice can replace its first conflicting choice
	3.	no loss in optimality
	4.	continue inductively

⸻

E. Dominance proof

Used for:
	•	Greedy
	•	Monotonic structures
	•	some queue/frontier logic

Core form:
	1.	define stronger/weaker candidates
	2.	show weaker candidate can never outperform stronger one later
	3.	discard weaker candidate safely

⸻

F. Layer optimality proof

Used for:
	•	BFS
	•	multi-source BFS

Core form:
	1.	frontier expands by increasing distance
	2.	first discovery occurs at minimum possible layer
	3.	therefore shortest distance is correct

⸻

G. Structural recursion proof

Used for:
	•	DFS on trees
	•	recursion-return problems
	•	divide-like tree decomposition

Core form:
	1.	define function meaning on node/subtree
	2.	base case
	3.	assume child correctness
	4.	combine correctly

⸻

H. Exhaustive-branch + pruning proof

Used for:
	•	Backtracking

Core form:
	1.	every legal branch is explored
	2.	pruned branches cannot contain valid solutions
	3.	undo restores parent state exactly

⸻

I. State-meaning induction

Used for:
	•	DP

Core form:
	1.	define dp[state]
	2.	prove base states
	3.	assume smaller dependency states are correct
	4.	recurrence computes current state correctly

⸻

J. Relaxation / frontier-finalization proof

Used for:
	•	Dijkstra
	•	weighted graph frontier methods

Core form:
	1.	frontier contains tentative best-known states
	2.	minimum frontier state is globally safe under cost assumptions
	3.	relax neighbors
	4.	popped state becomes final

⸻

K. Dependency-readiness proof

Used for:
	•	Topological Sort
	•	DAG processing

Core form:
	1.	zero-indegree means all prerequisites satisfied
	2.	processing preserves correctness of future indegrees
	3.	topological order emerges from repeated readiness

⸻

L. Representative-equivalence proof

Used for:
	•	DSU

Core form:
	1.	parent forest defines components
	2.	find returns canonical root
	3.	union merges components correctly
	4.	same root iff same component

⸻

M. Shared-prefix proof

Used for:
	•	Trie

Core form:
	1.	root-to-node path equals prefix
	2.	child traversal extends prefix correctly
	3.	terminal markers distinguish full words
	4.	prefix absence implies no completion exists

⸻

N. Summary-composition proof

Used for:
	•	Range Structures

Core form:
	1.	each block/node summary is correct
	2.	combine function is correct
	3.	target query decomposes into a bounded set of summaries
	4.	combined result is correct

⸻

O. Representation-invariant proof

Used for:
	•	Design/Object-State

Core form:
	1.	define abstract API state
	2.	define internal representation invariant
	3.	show each operation preserves it
	4.	returned outputs are correct because state stays synchronized

⸻

P. Algebraic / invariant-collapse proof

Used for:
	•	Math / Invariant

Core form:
	1.	define law/invariant
	2.	prove operation preserves or transforms it predictably
	3.	show law is sufficient to determine final answer

⸻

Q. Relational-semantics proof

Used for:
	•	SQL / Relational

Core form:
	1.	define meaning of each intermediate relation
	2.	prove join/group/partition semantics match target meaning
	3.	final relation equals required output

⸻

6.3 Proof selection table

A learner should ask:
	•	Is the core about a running scan? → Prefix-summary / loop invariant
	•	Is a region being discarded? → Elimination proof
	•	Is one local choice kept? → Exchange or dominance
	•	Is order by distance/layer? → Layer optimality
	•	Is recursive structure central? → Structural recursion
	•	Are repeated states central? → State-meaning induction
	•	Is the algorithm about a frontier with best-known values? → Relaxation/finalization
	•	Is the solution a representation with multiple synced internals? → Representation invariant
	•	Is the solution law-based? → Algebraic / invariant-collapse

That table is one of the most important synthesis tools.

⸻

7. Master Transformation Manual

Now the third synthesis block.

This is the manual for:

how brute force turns into optimization.

⸻

7.1 Why this matters

Many learners memorize:
	•	brute force
	•	optimized solution

But they do not learn the causal bridge.

The transformation manual must answer:
	•	what exactly brute force is doing
	•	what exact waste exists
	•	what hidden property removes that waste
	•	what new state is introduced
	•	what proof shape justifies the compressed method
	•	what memory is paid

That is the deepest teaching layer.

⸻

7.2 Universal transformation template

Every BF→Opt entry should have these six fields:

1. Source object

What brute force enumerates or recomputes

2. Waste type

What repeated work happens

3. Compression enabler

What structural fact allows collapse

4. New state

What optimized solution stores instead

5. New proof

Why the new state is correct and sufficient

6. Memory tradeoff

What extra memory is paid, if any

This six-part template should exist for every major family.

⸻

7.3 Transformation library

A. Pair scan -> Hashing
	•	Source: all prior elements
	•	Waste: repeated search for complement/duplicate
	•	Enabler: stable key
	•	New state: map/set
	•	Proof: seen-so-far invariant
	•	Memory: O(distinct keys)

⸻

B. Pair scan on sorted data -> Two Pointers
	•	Source: all pairs
	•	Waste: repeated impossible pair checks
	•	Enabler: sorted order
	•	New state: left/right pointers
	•	Proof: elimination invariant
	•	Memory: O(1)

⸻

C. Exhaustive contiguous ranges -> Sliding Window
	•	Source: all subarrays/substrings
	•	Waste: overlapping rescans
	•	Enabler: add/remove incremental maintenance
	•	New state: live interval + summary
	•	Proof: valid-window invariant + monotone boundaries
	•	Memory: O(1) to O(distinct)

⸻

D. Repeated range totals -> Prefix State
	•	Source: range scans
	•	Waste: repeated overlapping prefixes
	•	Enabler: interval = relation of two prefixes
	•	New state: cumulative prefix summaries
	•	Proof: prefix-state relation
	•	Memory: O(n) or O(distinct prefix states)

⸻

E. Recursive branch tree -> DP
	•	Source: recursive choice tree
	•	Waste: same subproblem repeated
	•	Enabler: compact repeated state
	•	New state: dp table / memo
	•	Proof: state-meaning induction
	•	Memory: O(number of states)

⸻

F. Branch tree with invalid prefixes -> Backtracking
	•	Source: full candidate enumeration
	•	Waste: invalid full completions
	•	Enabler: partial-solution validity
	•	New state: current path + trackers
	•	Proof: prune-safe exhaustive search
	•	Memory: recursion + current path

⸻

G. Ordered sequential testing -> Binary Search
	•	Source: linear candidate scan
	•	Waste: testing candidates one by one
	•	Enabler: monotone order/boundary
	•	New state: [lo, hi]
	•	Proof: surviving interval invariant
	•	Memory: O(1)

⸻

H. All-path shortest search in unit-cost world -> BFS
	•	Source: arbitrary path exploration
	•	Waste: longer paths before shorter ones
	•	Enabler: equal edge cost
	•	New state: frontier queue + visited
	•	Proof: layer optimality
	•	Memory: O(states)

⸻

I. Weighted frontier rescans -> Heap / Dijkstra
	•	Source: repeated scan for smallest tentative frontier cost
	•	Waste: repeated min search
	•	Enabler: priority frontier
	•	New state: min-heap + distance
	•	Proof: frontier-finalization
	•	Memory: O(frontier + graph state)

⸻

J. Repeated nearest-boundary scans -> Monotonic Stack/Deque
	•	Source: outward scans or repeated window rescans
	•	Waste: dominated candidates revisited
	•	Enabler: permanent domination
	•	New state: monotone container of live candidates
	•	Proof: push-once/pop-once + candidate dominance
	•	Memory: O(n) or O(window)

⸻

K. Repeated connectivity rediscovery -> DSU
	•	Source: DFS/BFS per merge/query
	•	Waste: component rediscovery
	•	Enabler: merge-only connectivity
	•	New state: representatives
	•	Proof: representative equivalence
	•	Memory: O(n)

⸻

L. Repeated prefix comparisons -> Trie
	•	Source: scan many words per query
	•	Waste: repeated shared-prefix comparisons
	•	Enabler: common prefixes stored once
	•	New state: prefix tree
	•	Proof: root-to-node prefix semantics
	•	Memory: O(distinct prefixes)

⸻

M. Repeated interval scans with updates -> Range Structures
	•	Source: interval rescans / full rebuilds
	•	Waste: repeated overlap recomputation
	•	Enabler: composable block summaries
	•	New state: BIT / segtree / sparse table / jump table
	•	Proof: summary composition + range decomposition
	•	Memory: O(n) to O(n log n)

⸻

N. Repeated best-element search in changing set -> Heap
	•	Source: active set rescans
	•	Waste: repeated global best search
	•	Enabler: only top element needed repeatedly
	•	New state: priority queue
	•	Proof: active-best invariant
	•	Memory: O(active set)

⸻

O. Operation-history replay -> Design/Object-State
	•	Source: full replay/rebuild each call
	•	Waste: re-deriving current live state
	•	Enabler: explicit persistent representation
	•	New state: synchronized internal structures
	•	Proof: representation invariant
	•	Memory: persistent internal state

⸻

P. Process simulation -> Math / Invariant
	•	Source: step-by-step process
	•	Waste: low-level details
	•	Enabler: decisive conserved/predictable law
	•	New state: tiny law-level summary
	•	Proof: invariant/algebraic derivation
	•	Memory: O(1)

⸻

Q. Manual row-loop reasoning -> SQL / Relational
	•	Source: nested row loops
	•	Waste: procedural matching/grouping
	•	Enabler: relational keys and set operators
	•	New state: intermediate relations
	•	Proof: relational-semantics correctness
	•	Memory: intermediate result relations conceptually

⸻

7.4 Transformation failure catalog

A good transformation manual must also show failed transformations.

Example 1

“Subarray” -> Sliding Window
Fails when negative numbers break monotonicity.

Example 2

“Optimization” -> Greedy
Fails when no exchange/dominance proof exists.

Example 3

“Recursion” -> DP
Fails when states do not overlap.

Example 4

“Graph” -> BFS
Fails when weighted edges matter.

Example 5

“Prefix sum” -> enough
Fails when dynamic updates require hierarchical summaries.

Example 6

“Top K” -> Heap
Fails when one sort is sufficient and active set never changes.

This failure catalog is essential because real learning requires seeing why a tempting transformation breaks.

