The family chapters are deep dives.
The taxonomy table is the bird’s-eye map.

Its job is to let you classify a new problem fast by asking the same structural questions for every family.

⸻

1. Why the taxonomy table matters

A learner usually asks:
	•	what pattern is this?
	•	why this one and not the nearby one?
	•	what is the brute-force version?
	•	what property unlocks the optimization?
	•	what proof do I need?
	•	what picture should I draw?

The taxonomy table answers all of that in one place.

It is the bridge between:
	•	the deep family chapters
and
	•	real-time problem diagnosis.

⸻

2. The master columns

Every family should be classified under the same columns.

Core columns
	•	Family
	•	World / Shape
	•	Typical Job
	•	Brute-force Object
	•	Waste Type
	•	Compression Enabler
	•	Optimized State
	•	Primary Proof Grammar
	•	Default Visual Bucket
	•	Canonical Archetypes
	•	Common Impostors / Confusions

That is the minimum gold-standard schema.

