4. The higher-order buckets

The table above is family-by-family.
Now the deeper synthesis:

4.1 By brute-force object

This is often the fastest classifier.

If brute force is:
	•	all pairs -> Hashing, Two Pointers, Sorting
	•	all ranges -> Sliding Window, Prefix State, Range Structures
	•	all paths -> DFS, BFS, Graph Advanced
	•	all subsets/permutations -> Backtracking, DP
	•	repeated active-set rescans -> Heap, Monotonic Deque
	•	repeated same subproblem -> DP
	•	repeated connectivity recomputation -> DSU
	•	repeated prefix comparisons -> Trie
	•	replay across API calls -> Design/Object-State
	•	simulation of arithmetic/process -> Math / Invariant

That one classifier is extremely powerful.

⸻

4.2 By waste type

If the waste is:
	•	repeated lookup -> Hashing
	•	repeated shared prefixes -> Trie
	•	repeated overlapping ranges -> Sliding Window / Prefix / Range Structures
	•	repeated full scans for current best -> Heap
	•	repeated nearest-boundary scans -> Monotonic Stack / Deque
	•	repeated same recursion states -> DP
	•	repeated graph/path exploration without order -> BFS / Graph Advanced
	•	repeated connectivity discovery -> DSU
	•	repeated replay across operations -> Design/Object-State
	•	repeated low-level simulation -> Math / Invariant

This bucket is often even better than trigger words.

⸻

4.3 By compression enabler

This is the deepest classifier.

Compression enabler:
	•	stable key -> Hashing
	•	shared prefix -> Trie
	•	monotone pointer movement -> Two Pointers
	•	live interval maintenance -> Sliding Window
	•	cumulative boundary relation -> Prefix State
	•	dominance in ordered candidates -> Monotonic Stack / Deque or Greedy
	•	priority of current best active candidate -> Heap
	•	safe half elimination -> Binary Search
	•	overlapping subproblems -> DP
	•	partial-solution validity + undo -> Backtracking
	•	layer order -> BFS
	•	recursive structure -> DFS
	•	merge-only equivalence -> DSU
	•	dependency or weighted frontier order -> Graph Advanced
	•	hierarchical summaries -> Range Structures
	•	persistent synchronized representation -> Design/Object-State
	•	law/invariant/formula -> Math / Invariant
	•	relational keys and set operators -> SQL / Relational

If you can name the enabler, you can usually name the family.

