8. The “first 5 questions” classifier

When opening a new problem, ask these five in order:

1. What is the world?
	•	sequence
	•	tree
	•	graph
	•	table
	•	API/object
	•	numbers/bits

2. What is the job?
	•	lookup
	•	range
	•	shortest path
	•	all solutions
	•	top-k
	•	grouping
	•	repeated operations
	•	formula/collapse

3. What does brute force enumerate or recompute?
	•	pair
	•	range
	•	path
	•	subset
	•	active set
	•	subproblem
	•	relation
	•	connectivity
	•	operation history

4. What exact waste occurs?
	•	repeated search
	•	repeated rescans
	•	repeated same state
	•	repeated best-element search
	•	repeated path exploration
	•	repeated replay
	•	repeated component rediscovery
	•	repeated low-level simulation

5. What structural fact kills that waste?
	•	key
	•	order
	•	prefix relation
	•	dominance
	•	overlap
	•	layer
	•	representative
	•	shared prefix
	•	hierarchy
	•	invariant law
	•	relation key
	•	persistent state

Those five questions essentially are the atlas.

⸻

9. The real use of the taxonomy table

This is not just a summary artifact.

It has four direct uses:

A. Pattern recognition

Classify new problems quickly.

B. Error correction

When stuck, compare your chosen family against its nearby impostors.

C. Teaching order

Use it to sequence chapters from simpler to harder.

D. Visual consistency

Each family maps to a fixed visual language and proof grammar.

That makes the system stable.

