9. Mastery gates

Each stage needs explicit exit criteria.

⸻

9.1 Stage 1 exit gate

You are ready to leave Perception when you can:
	•	classify common sequence/tree/graph problems without coding
	•	separate Hashing vs Two Pointers vs Sliding Window vs Prefix State
	•	separate DFS vs BFS
	•	state the brute-force object for a problem

⸻

9.2 Stage 2 exit gate

You are ready to leave Compression when you can:
	•	explain BF→Opt for major medium problems
	•	separate Greedy vs DP
	•	separate Heap vs Monotonic Deque
	•	separate Backtracking vs DFS
	•	state the compression enabler cleanly

⸻

9.3 Stage 3 exit gate

You are ready to leave Correctness when you can:
	•	define DP state precisely
	•	explain Dijkstra/Topo correctness order
	•	explain segment tree node meaning
	•	state design/object representation invariants
	•	prove a math/invariant answer instead of just guessing it

⸻

9.4 Stage 4 exit gate

You are ready to call yourself advanced when you can:
	•	identify primary vs helper family in composite problems
	•	explain why tempting impostors fail
	•	generalize a known family to a nearby unseen problem
	•	reverse engineer optimization from brute force for new problems

⸻

10. The anti-roadmap: what not to do

This is just as important.

⸻

10.1 Do not learn only by tags

That creates trigger-word dependence.

10.2 Do not learn DP before state language

That creates table memorization with no meaning.

10.3 Do not learn Greedy from accepted code only

That creates intuition without proof.

10.4 Do not treat Backtracking and DFS as the same

That prevents correct pruning and undo thinking.

10.5 Do not jump into advanced graph/range structures before frontier/order/summary thinking is stable

That creates mechanical coding without understanding.

10.6 Do not use “hard problems” as your main curriculum

They are too composite early on.

