Use a small staged subset, not all 58.

Schulhoff et al. organize the 58 text prompting techniques into 6 major categories: In-Context Learning (ICL), Zero-Shot, Thought Generation, Decomposition, Ensembling, and Self-Criticism. They also benchmark only a subset of techniques rather than claiming one universally best method, so the right choice depends on task and cost/latency constraints.  ￼

My practical default stack

1) Start with Zero-Shot

Use this first for:
	•	straightforward extraction
	•	classification
	•	formatting
	•	rewriting
	•	summarization

Good base pattern:
	•	role/context
	•	task
	•	constraints
	•	output format

Why: cheapest, fastest, easiest to debug. The paper treats zero-shot as the natural baseline.  ￼

2) Add Few-Shot / ICL when consistency matters

Use when:
	•	labels are subtle
	•	style must match examples
	•	edge cases matter
	•	structured outputs drift

Best for:
	•	classification with tricky boundaries
	•	transformation tasks
	•	domain-specific tone or schema

3) Add Thought Generation only for reasoning-heavy tasks

Use when:
	•	math/logic is nontrivial
	•	multi-step planning is needed
	•	the model misses intermediate reasoning

Best candidates:
	•	Chain-of-Thought
	•	Zero-shot CoT
	•	Self-Consistency over reasoning traces

But do not default to this for simple tasks; it adds cost and latency. The survey treats thought-generation as its own major category, not a universal default.  ￼

4) Use Decomposition for long or compound tasks

Use when the task is naturally split into stages:
	•	retrieve facts -> analyze -> answer
	•	classify -> extract evidence -> produce label
	•	plan -> execute -> verify

Best for:
	•	long documents
	•	workflows
	•	multi-constraint generation
	•	coding/debugging pipelines

Examples:
	•	least-to-most
	•	plan-and-solve
	•	subproblem prompting

5) Use Self-Criticism when correctness matters more than speed

Use when:
	•	hallucinations are costly
	•	you need verification
	•	answers should be revised against criteria

Best for:
	•	safety-sensitive outputs
	•	factual analysis
	•	policy/legal/business drafts
	•	code review

Pattern:
	•	answer
	•	critique
	•	revise

6) Use Ensembling only when quality is worth extra cost

Use when:
	•	one-shot reliability is too low
	•	variance between runs is high
	•	you can afford multiple generations

Best for:
	•	hard reasoning
	•	ambiguous classification
	•	high-stakes ranking/judgment

Typical forms:
	•	self-consistency
	•	multiple prompt variants
	•	vote/select best

