LeetCode Q1 — Two Sum

1. Problem Identity

Problem ID: 1
Title: Two Sum
Difficulty: Easy
World Shape: Array
Primary Family: Hashing
Helper Family: Direct Scan / Counting
Canonical Archetype: Complement lookup with seen-so-far map

⸻

2. Problem Contract

Question

Given an array of integers nums and an integer target, return the indices of the two numbers such that they add up to target.

You may assume:
	•	exactly one valid answer exists
	•	you may not use the same element twice

Input Shape
	•	nums: array of integers
	•	target: integer

Output Shape
	•	array of 2 indices

Important Hidden Contract

This is not:
	•	“return the values”
	•	“return any pair after sorting”
	•	“return whether a pair exists”

It is specifically:
	•	return original indices

That is why a sorted two-pointer method is not the cleanest primary solution.

⸻

3. Anatomy of the Question

Data Shape
	•	1D array
	•	no ordering guarantee
	•	one pass is possible
	•	exact complement relation exists

Job

Find a pair of indices.

Brute-Force Object

All pairs (i, j) where i < j

Waste Type

Repeatedly checking pair sums independently, even though each number only needs one complement

Compression Enabler

For a number x, the only thing we care about is whether target - x has already appeared.

That is the entire key insight.

⸻

4. Core Pattern Diagnosis

Why this is Hashing

Because each current element asks one question:

“Have I already seen the complement I need?”

That is a classic seen-so-far lookup pattern.

Why this is not primarily Two Pointers

Two Pointers usually needs:
	•	sorted order
	•	safe monotone pointer movement

Here:
	•	the array is unsorted
	•	original indices matter
	•	direct lookup is simpler than sorting and preserving indices

Why this is not Sliding Window

There is no live contiguous region whose contents matter.
We are not maintaining a window.
We are checking complement existence in prior elements.

Why Direct Scan is helper, not primary

Yes, we scan once left to right.
But the scan alone is not enough.
The real engine is the hash map.

So:
	•	Primary Pattern: Hashing
	•	Helper Pattern: Direct Scan

⸻

5. Brute Force Method

Brute Force Idea

Check every possible pair:
	•	pick first index i
	•	pick second index j > i
	•	test whether nums[i] + nums[j] == target

Brute Force Pseudologic

for i in [0..n-1]:
  for j in [i+1..n-1]:
    if nums[i] + nums[j] == target:
      return [i, j]

Why it works

Because it literally tests all valid pairs.

Why it is weak

Because it treats every pair as independent.

But for each nums[i], there is only one thing we really want:
	•	target - nums[i]

So instead of checking all future/past elements manually, we can remember earlier values.

⸻

6. BF Complexity Visual

Time

O(n^2)

Why:
	•	outer loop chooses first index
	•	inner loop checks many later indices
	•	total pair checks are quadratic

Space

O(1) extra space

Why:
	•	only loop counters and temporary sum

Visual Interpretation

Draw the array as a row of boxes.

Then:
	•	from index 0, draw arrows to 1,2,3,…,n-1
	•	from index 1, draw arrows to 2,3,4,…,n-1
	•	from index 2, draw arrows to 3,4,5,…,n-1

This creates a triangular comparison web.

That triangle is the brute-force complexity picture.

