9. Optimized Pattern

Optimized Pattern

Hashing

Exact Technique

Seen-so-far complement lookup

Core Law

When you are at nums[i], the only useful earlier fact is:

whether target - nums[i] already appeared before

If yes:
	•	done immediately

If no:
	•	store current value for future elements

That is the optimization.

⸻

10. Invariant / Core Law

This is the most important teaching line.

Invariant

After processing indices 0..i-1, the hash map contains all earlier values and their indices.

So at step i, if target - nums[i] exists in the map, then we have found the answer.

Why this invariant is powerful

It means:
	•	the processed prefix is summarized perfectly by the map
	•	we do not need to rescan old elements
	•	all earlier complement information is compressed into one structure

⸻

11. Optimized Algorithm

Logic

For each index i:
	1.	compute need = target - nums[i]
	2.	check if need exists in the map
	3.	if yes, return [map[need], i]
	4.	otherwise store nums[i] -> i

C++ Code

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        unordered_map<int, int> seen;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            int need = target - nums[i];

            if (seen.count(need)) {
                return {seen[need], i};
            }

            seen[nums[i]] = i;
        }

        return {};
    }
};


⸻

12. Why “check before insert” matters

This is a subtle but important teaching point.

Suppose:
	•	nums[i] = 3
	•	target = 6

If you insert first, then check:
	•	you might accidentally pair the element with itself

Correct order:
	1.	check whether complement already exists
	2.	only then insert current value

This preserves the rule:
	•	cannot use same element twice

