18. Why BF is weak

Short explanation

BF checks many pairs even though every number only needs one specific complement.

Deep explanation

When looking at nums[i], BF asks:
	•	try nums[i] with every possible future element

But the optimized view asks:
	•	I only need target - nums[i]

So BF treats pair search as:
	•	many possibilities

OPT compresses it into:
	•	one key lookup

That is the real transformation.

⸻

19. Why OPT works

Short explanation

The hash map remembers every earlier value, so the current element can instantly check whether its required complement already exists.

Deep explanation

The map is a compressed representation of the processed prefix.
It stores exactly the information future elements need:
	•	past value
	•	where it appeared

So each new step becomes:
	•	one question
	•	one answer
	•	one insert if unanswered

That is why time collapses from quadratic to linear.

⸻

20. Common Wrong Approach

Wrong instinct

“Sort the array and use two pointers.”

Why that is risky here

Sorting changes positions.
The problem needs original indices.

You can solve it with sorting if you store index-value pairs first, but:
	•	that is more complicated
	•	adds sorting cost
	•	is not the cleanest primary method

Better view

This is a direct complement-lookup problem.

