About all the different phases in solving a coding question 


Here’s the full phase model.

A coding question is not just “read problem -> write code.”
A strong solve goes through layers, and each layer has a different job.

Master phases of solving a coding question

1. Problem intake

This is the first contact phase.

Your job here is not solving.
Your job is to understand the contract.

You identify:
	•	what the input is
	•	what the output is
	•	what exactly must be returned
	•	what is forbidden
	•	what assumptions are guaranteed
	•	whether there is exactly one answer, multiple answers, or maybe none

This phase ends when you can restate the problem in plain words.

Good output of this phase

“I am given an unsorted array and a target. I need to return original indices of two numbers whose sum is the target. I cannot use the same element twice.”

⸻

2. Surface translation

Now strip away fluff.

Many coding questions contain story text:
	•	robber
	•	bananas
	•	islands
	•	meetings
	•	courses
	•	ladders
	•	oranges

You translate the story into pure structure.

Examples:
	•	robber houses -> array of values with adjacency restriction
	•	islands -> grid connected-component problem
	•	courses -> directed dependency graph
	•	meeting rooms -> interval overlap / active resource count

This phase ends when the question is no longer a story and becomes a structural object.

Good output of this phase

“This is really an array optimization problem.”
or
“This is really a directed graph prerequisite problem.”

⸻

3. Input anatomy

Now inspect the shape of the data.

This is where many good solves begin.

Ask:
	•	is it an array?
	•	string?
	•	linked list?
	•	tree?
	•	graph?
	•	grid?
	•	interval list?
	•	stream?
	•	object/API design?
	•	numbers/bits/math?

This phase matters because data shape kills many wrong patterns immediately.

Examples:
	•	tree -> DFS/BFS, recursion, traversal
	•	sorted array -> binary search / two pointers candidates
	•	grid -> DFS/BFS or DP depending on semantics
	•	API class -> design/object-state
	•	table -> SQL/relational

This phase ends when you know the world shape.

⸻

4. Output anatomy

Now inspect what the answer itself looks like.

Ask:
	•	exact value?
	•	boolean?
	•	count?
	•	indices?
	•	path?
	•	ordering?
	•	all solutions?
	•	top k?
	•	shortest path?
	•	grouped result?
	•	mutable API behavior?

This is important because different outputs imply different families.

Examples:
	•	“all possible” -> backtracking is suspicious
	•	“top k” -> heap becomes suspicious
	•	“shortest path” -> BFS or weighted-graph family becomes suspicious
	•	“minimum steps” -> graph/layer thinking
	•	“return all combinations” -> not greedy, not simple DP only

This phase ends when the output type strongly narrows the family.

⸻

5. Constraint reading

This is one of the most underused phases.

Read constraints carefully:
	•	n <= 20
	•	n <= 10^5
	•	values up to 10^9
	•	duplicates allowed?
	•	negative numbers allowed?
	•	graph weighted?
	•	exactly one answer?
	•	mutable operations count high?

Constraints tell you:
	•	allowed complexity
	•	whether brute force is viable
	•	whether window logic can work
	•	whether sorting is okay
	•	whether DP state is too big
	•	whether memory-heavy methods are acceptable

This phase ends when you know the time-space budget.

Example
	•	n <= 20 often allows exponential/backtracking
	•	n <= 10^5 usually means O(n) or O(n log n)
	•	negative numbers often break naive sliding-window sum logic
	•	many updates + many queries suggests range structures

⸻

6. Clarification / contract locking

Before solving, lock subtle details.

Examples:
	•	do I return indices or values?
	•	can answer be in any order?
	•	do duplicates matter?
	•	are we guaranteed one solution?
	•	is empty input possible?
	•	do we allow revisiting nodes/cells?
	•	is graph directed?

In interviews, this is the phase where you ask clarifying questions.
In self-study, this is where you clarify silently.

This phase ends when the rules are stable.

⸻

7. Brute-force construction

Now build the naive version first.

This is one of the most important phases in all problem solving.

Ask:
	•	what would the most straightforward way do?
	•	what object would it enumerate?
	•	pairs?
	•	ranges?
	•	paths?
	•	subsets?
	•	states?
	•	active set?
	•	operation history?

This gives you:
	•	a correctness anchor
	•	a baseline
	•	the future optimization target

This phase ends when you can say:
“Brute force would do X.”

Example

Two Sum brute force:
	•	enumerate all pairs

Subarray Sum brute force:
	•	enumerate all ranges

N-Queens brute force:
	•	enumerate all placements

Dijkstra-type brute force:
	•	compare many weighted paths

⸻

8. Waste diagnosis

This is where real optimization begins.

After brute force, ask:
	•	what repeated work is happening?
	•	repeated lookup?
	•	repeated range scan?
	•	repeated subproblem?
	•	repeated path exploration?
	•	repeated best-candidate search?
	•	repeated connectivity rediscovery?
	•	repeated prefix comparison?
	•	repeated replay across operations?
	•	repeated simulation?

This phase is the bridge from brute force to pattern.

This phase ends when you can say:
“Brute force is wasteful because of ___.”

⸻

9. Compression insight

Now ask the key question:

What hidden structure kills that waste?

This is the most important phase in the whole solve.

Possible answers:
	•	a stable key -> hashing
	•	sorted order -> two pointers or binary search
	•	live interval add/remove -> sliding window
	•	relation between prefixes -> prefix state
	•	overlap of states -> DP
	•	partial validity + undo -> backtracking
	•	layer order -> BFS
	•	representative equivalence -> DSU
	•	shared prefixes -> trie
	•	active best candidate -> heap
	•	candidate dominance -> monotonic deque/stack
	•	persistent internal representation -> design/object-state
	•	governing law/invariant -> math

This phase ends when you know the compression enabler.

⸻

10. Pattern selection

Only now do you choose the family.

This should happen after:
	•	data shape
	•	output type
	•	constraints
	•	brute force
	•	waste type
	•	compression enabler

Not before.

This phase is:
	•	choosing the primary family
	•	identifying helper family if composite
	•	rejecting nearby impostors

Examples:
	•	primary: hashing, helper: direct scan
	•	primary: graph advanced, helper: heap
	•	primary: backtracking, helper: trie
	•	primary: monotonic deque, helper: sliding window
	•	primary: design/object-state, helpers: hashmap + linked list

This phase ends when you can justify:
“Why this family and not the nearby wrong one?”

⸻

11. State definition

Now define what the algorithm stores.

This is where many solutions become clear or collapse.

Ask:
	•	what does my state mean?
	•	what variables are live?
	•	what is the running invariant?
	•	what does each helper structure represent?
	•	what does dp[x] mean?
	•	what does the map contain?
	•	what does the heap hold?
	•	what does the deque still represent?
	•	what does each object field mean?

This phase is absolutely critical.

This phase ends when you can state your variables semantically, not just syntactically.

Good examples
	•	seen[value] = earliest/last seen index
	•	dist[node] = best known distance so far
	•	dp[i] = best answer for prefix ending at i
	•	windowCounts[c] = occurrences of c in current window
	•	parent[x] = representative parent in DSU

⸻

12. Invariant definition

Now define what must remain true.

This is the correctness backbone.

Examples:
	•	current window is valid
	•	binary search answer remains in [lo, hi]
	•	map stores all prior values
	•	deque remains decreasing and only stores live candidates
	•	popped Dijkstra node has final shortest distance
	•	current backtracking path is valid so far
	•	object internals match abstract API state

This phase ends when you can say:
“After every step, this remains true.”

⸻

13. Transition / update logic

Now define how the algorithm moves.

Ask:
	•	what happens when I read the next item?
	•	what pointer moves?
	•	what gets inserted?
	•	what gets removed?
	•	what state gets updated?
	•	what recurrence applies?
	•	what edge gets relaxed?
	•	what child gets explored?
	•	what choice gets undone?

This is the motion phase.

This phase ends when your loop/recursion update rule is fully clear.

⸻

14. Edge-case modeling

Now attack the weird cases.

Ask:
	•	empty input?
	•	size 1?
	•	all duplicates?
	•	all negative?
	•	overflow?
	•	no valid answer?
	•	repeated zero?
	•	sorted but descending?
	•	disconnected graph?
	•	cycle?
	•	one-node tree?
	•	same element misuse?

This phase is where fragile solutions become robust.

This phase ends when your algorithm survives the obvious traps.

⸻

15. Complexity modeling

Only after the method is defined should you compute complexity.

Ask:
	•	how many times is each item touched?
	•	are there nested loops or monotone pointers?
	•	are states repeated?
	•	how big can the helper structure get?
	•	what is the cost of heap/map operations?
	•	is preprocessing one-time or repeated?

This phase ends when you can justify time and space, not just guess them.

⸻

16. Proof phase

Now explain why it is correct.

Choose the right proof grammar:
	•	prefix-summary
	•	loop invariant
	•	elimination
	•	exchange argument
	•	dominance
	•	recursion induction
	•	DP state induction
	•	frontier finalization
	•	representative equivalence
	•	representation invariant
	•	algebraic/invariant collapse

This phase ends when you can explain correctness in 3–6 clean sentences.

⸻

17. Coding phase

Only now do you actually write code.

Good coding should follow the already-chosen structure:
	•	variables reflect state meaning
	•	loops reflect transitions
	•	helpers reflect invariants
	•	names reflect semantics

This phase is execution, not discovery.

⸻

18. Dry run phase

Run the code on a small example manually.

Check:
	•	variable changes
	•	pointer motion
	•	inserts/removals
	•	edge handling
	•	termination conditions
	•	return value

This phase catches:
	•	off-by-one errors
	•	wrong update order
	•	missing insert/remove
	•	bad initialization
	•	self-use bugs
	•	stale state bugs

⸻

19. Debug / repair phase

If dry run or tests fail:
	•	don’t randomly patch
	•	go back to:
	•	state meaning
	•	invariant
	•	update rule
	•	edge case
	•	wrong family selection

The deepest debugging question is:

Which phase above was actually wrong?

Many bugs are not “coding bugs.”
They are:
	•	wrong pattern
	•	wrong state
	•	wrong invariant
	•	wrong boundary semantics

⸻

20. Communication phase

In interviews especially, you must explain the solve.

A clean communication order is:
	1.	restate problem
	2.	identify brute force
	3.	identify waste
	4.	state optimized family
	5.	define state and invariant
	6.	explain transitions
	7.	explain complexity
	8.	dry run briefly

That is the best speaking order.

⸻

The compressed master model

If you want the full solve lifecycle in one line:

Contract -> Shape -> Output -> Constraints -> Brute Force -> Waste -> Compression Enabler -> Pattern -> State -> Invariant -> Transition -> Edge Cases -> Complexity -> Proof -> Code -> Dry Run -> Debug

That is the full operating system.

⸻

The four super-phases

If we compress even more, all coding-question solving becomes four mega-phases:

A. Understand
	•	intake
	•	translation
	•	shape
	•	output
	•	constraints

B. Model
	•	brute force
	•	waste
	•	compression enabler
	•	family selection
	•	state
	•	invariant

C. Build
	•	transitions
	•	code
	•	edge handling

D. Validate
	•	complexity
	•	proof
	•	dry run
	•	debug
	•	communicate

⸻

What most people skip

The most skipped phases are:
	•	brute-force object
	•	waste diagnosis
	•	compression enabler
	•	explicit invariant
	•	proof grammar
	•	dry run

That is exactly why many people memorize patterns but cannot transfer them.

⸻

Best practical checklist for any question

Before coding, answer these:
	1.	What is the input world?
	2.	What exactly is the output?
	3.	What would brute force enumerate?
	4.	What repeated waste does brute force have?
	5.	What structural fact removes that waste?
	6.	What family does that imply?
	7.	What does my state mean?
	8.	What invariant stays true?
	9.	How do updates preserve it?
	10.	What edge cases can break it?

If you can answer those 10, you usually can solve the question.

⸻

Deepest truth

A coding question is not fundamentally a code-writing task.

It is a modeling-and-compression task.

Code comes near the end.

If you want, I can turn this into a visual phase framework for your app, where each LeetCode question gets tagged by:
	•	intake phase
	•	brute-force phase
	•	compression phase
	•	invariant phase
	•	code phase
	•	dry-run phase

Talk about every details about problem intake in all the 3872 leetcode question 


You can’t do 3872 questions one by one at intake time.

The right way is to build a universal intake system that works across all 3872.

That is what top solvers actually do.

What “problem intake” really is

Problem intake is the phase before pattern selection.

Its job is to answer:
	•	What is the problem really asking?
	•	What is the shape of the data?
	•	What is the shape of the answer?
	•	What is guaranteed?
	•	What is not guaranteed?
