Intake Layer 3: Guarantee recognition

Across all 3872, the most important intake mistakes happen because solvers ignore guarantees.

You must always extract these.

1. Exactly one solution?

This changes everything.

Example:
	•	Two Sum with exactly one solution
	•	no need to handle ambiguity
	•	can return immediately

2. At least one solution?

Different from exactly one.

3. May be no solution?

Then you need failure handling.

4. Duplicates allowed?

This changes:
	•	hashing
	•	two pointers
	•	sorting
	•	backtracking duplicate skip rules
	•	subsets/permutations handling

5. Negative numbers allowed?

This is a huge intake fork.

Negative numbers can break:
	•	naive sliding window sum logic
	•	greedy assumptions
	•	some monotonic accumulations

6. Input already sorted?

This strongly changes:
	•	binary search candidacy
	•	two pointers candidacy
	•	merge logic

7. Weighted or unweighted?

Huge graph intake fork.
	•	unweighted shortest path -> BFS
	•	weighted shortest path -> Dijkstra/graph advanced

8. Tree guaranteed BST?

If yes:
	•	inorder sortedness matters
	•	binary-search-style tree logic may apply

9. In-place required?

If yes:
	•	extra memory approaches may become invalid or secondary

10. Multiple operations?

If yes:
	•	design/object-state may be primary

