Intake Layer 4: Constraint reading

This is one of the most universal intake tools across all 3872.

The constraints tell you what complexity world the problem belongs to.

If n is tiny

Examples:
	•	n <= 15
	•	n <= 20

Then:
	•	exponential may be okay
	•	backtracking becomes plausible
	•	subset/state compression may be plausible

If n is medium

Examples:
	•	n <= 10^3
	•	n <= 10^4

Then:
	•	O(n²) may or may not be okay
	•	DP may be okay
	•	nested loops might survive

If n is large

Examples:
	•	n <= 10^5
	•	n <= 2 * 10^5

Then:
	•	O(n²) is dead
	•	O(n), O(n log n) likely expected
	•	hashing, heap, greedy, scan, monotonic structures, binary search, graph linear-ish methods become dominant

If value range is huge

Examples:
	•	10^9
	•	2^31 - 1

Then:
	•	simulation may be impossible
	•	binary search on answer or math may appear
	•	overflow handling matters

If there are many queries and updates

Then:
	•	prefix only may fail
	•	range structures become suspicious

If recursion depth could be huge

Then:
	•	iterative versions may matter
	•	stack overflow risk matters in implementation

So every intake for every LeetCode question should explicitly ask:
	•	What time budget is allowed?
	•	What space budget is allowed?
	•	Is brute force even remotely legal?

