Surface Translation — Universal Guide for Any LeetCode Question

1. What surface translation really is

Surface translation means:

remove theme, preserve mechanics

A LeetCode problem usually presents itself in one of two forms:

A. Story-wrapped form

Examples:
	•	robber
	•	banana eating
	•	islands
	•	oranges
	•	ladders
	•	flights
	•	workers
	•	courses
	•	meetings

B. technical-looking form

Examples:
	•	reverse linked list
	•	kth ancestor
	•	top k frequent elements
	•	segment tree query
	•	LRU cache

Even the technical-looking ones still need surface translation, because you still have to convert wording into structure.

So surface translation is not only for “story problems.”

It is for every problem.

⸻

2. The goal of surface translation

At the end of this phase, the problem should no longer feel like:
	•	a story
	•	a toy world
	•	a real-life situation
	•	a domain-specific scenario

It should feel like:
	•	an array problem
	•	a graph problem
	•	a path problem
	•	an interval problem
	•	a state machine problem
	•	a DP recurrence
	•	a lookup problem
	•	a constraint satisfaction problem

That is the success criterion.

⸻

3. The master rule

For any problem, translate these 4 things:

1. Objects -> data structures

What are the nouns really?

2. Actions -> allowed operations

What are the verbs really?

3. Rules -> constraints/invariants

What restrictions matter?

4. Goal -> computational target

What exactly must be optimized / counted / decided / returned?

That is the whole phase in one sentence.

⸻

4. Universal surface translation template

For any LeetCode question, rewrite it using this template:

Step A — Remove the nouns

Replace story-specific nouns with structural nouns.

Examples:
	•	houses -> array positions
	•	islands -> connected 1-cells
	•	courses -> graph nodes
	•	meetings -> intervals
	•	flights -> weighted edges
	•	oranges -> grid states
	•	accounts -> equivalence classes
	•	words -> strings / prefixes / paths
	•	rooms -> resources / slots
	•	ladders -> BFS frontier states

⸻

Step B — Remove the verbs

Replace story-specific actions with structural actions.

Examples:
	•	rob -> choose
	•	eat bananas -> test processing rate
	•	rot oranges -> spread state to adjacent cells
	•	take course -> process node after prerequisites
	•	attend meeting -> allocate interval to resource
	•	climb ladder -> move between graph states
	•	merge accounts -> union equivalence classes
	•	search word -> follow path under adjacency rules

⸻

Step C — Identify the real restriction

Ask:
what story rule is actually a structural restriction?

Examples:
	•	cannot rob adjacent houses -> cannot choose adjacent indices
	•	must finish in h hours -> feasibility threshold
	•	oranges infect neighbors each minute -> BFS layer propagation
	•	course requires prerequisite -> directed edge dependency
	•	meetings overlap -> interval conflict
	•	word cells cannot be reused -> path visited constraint
	•	same number cannot be used twice -> distinct index restriction

⸻

Step D — Identify the true goal

Ask:
what are we really trying to compute?

Examples:
	•	maximum stolen money -> max non-adjacent sum
	•	minimum eating speed -> minimum feasible rate
	•	number of islands -> connected component count
	•	minimum meeting rooms -> maximum active overlap / min resources
	•	can finish all courses -> detect whether directed graph is acyclic
	•	shortest ladder length -> shortest path in unweighted graph
	•	top k frequent -> return k highest-frequency items

⸻

5. The translation ladder

For any question, move down these layers:

Layer 1 — Story sentence

“You are a robber robbing houses on a street.”

Layer 2 — Reduced story

“You choose houses, but adjacent houses conflict.”

Layer 3 — Structural sentence

“This is an array where I want the maximum sum under a non-adjacency constraint.”

Layer 4 — Algorithmic sentence

“This is a DP optimization over prefix states.”

That is the full translation ladder.

Every LeetCode question should be translated down this ladder.

