Q1. Two Sum

1. Problem intake

Given an unsorted array and a target, return the indices of two numbers whose sum is target.

2. Surface translation

This is not really “find a pair.”
This is:

an array complement-lookup problem with original-index preservation.

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: array + target
	•	output: 2 indices
	•	restriction: cannot use same element twice

4. Constraint reading

Usually large enough that O(n^2) is acceptable only as baseline.

5. Brute force

Check every pair (i, j).

6. Waste diagnosis

Repeated pair checks.
For each value, we only care about one complement, not all other numbers.

7. Compression insight

Replace “search all previous/future values” with:

direct lookup of target - nums[i]

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Hashing
	•	Helper: Direct Scan

9. State definition

seen[value] = index

10. Invariant

Before processing index i, the map contains all earlier values and their indices.

11. Transition logic

For each nums[i]:
	•	compute need = target - nums[i]
	•	if need in map -> return pair
	•	else insert current value

12. Edge cases
	•	duplicates like [3,3]
	•	zero target
	•	negatives
	•	check-before-insert to avoid using same index twice

13. Complexity
	•	BF: O(n^2), O(1)
	•	OPT: O(n) average, O(n)

14. Proof idea

Seen-so-far invariant:
if complement exists in processed prefix, current index plus stored index is valid.

⸻

Q2. Add Two Numbers

1. Problem intake

Two linked lists represent reversed digits of two nonnegative integers. Return their sum as a linked list.

2. Surface translation

This is not really “big integer math.”
This is:

digit-by-digit linked-list simulation of grade-school addition

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: two linked lists
	•	output: new linked list
	•	each node = one digit
	•	digits in reverse order

4. Constraint reading

Linear solution expected.

5. Brute force

Convert lists into whole integers, add them, then rebuild list.

6. Waste diagnosis

Whole-number conversion is unnecessary and can overflow.
The true process is local digit addition with carry.

7. Compression insight

You only need:
	•	current digits
	•	carry
	•	output tail

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Direct Simulation / Linked List Traversal
	•	Helper: Math / carry handling

9. State definition
	•	p1, p2
	•	carry
	•	dummy head
	•	output tail

10. Invariant

After each step, output list correctly stores the sum of processed digits, and carry stores overflow into next digit.

11. Transition logic

At each step:
	•	sum = digit1 + digit2 + carry
	•	output sum % 10
	•	carry = sum / 10
	•	advance pointers

12. Edge cases
	•	unequal lengths
	•	final carry
	•	one list empty at tail earlier
	•	zero lists

13. Complexity
	•	O(max(m,n)) time
	•	O(max(m,n)) output space

14. Proof idea

Grade-school addition invariant:
processed suffix is correct, carry is exactly what remains to propagate.

⸻

Q3. Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters

1. Problem intake

Return the length of the longest substring with all unique characters.

2. Surface translation

This is:

a live contiguous window validity problem.

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: string
	•	output: max length
	•	condition: no repeated chars in current substring

4. Constraint reading

Linear or near-linear expected.

5. Brute force

Enumerate all substrings and test uniqueness.

6. Waste diagnosis

Huge overlap between adjacent substrings.
Rescanning uniqueness repeatedly is wasteful.

7. Compression insight

Maintain one active window and repair it when duplicate appears.

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Sliding Window
	•	Helper: Hashing

9. State definition
	•	left, right
	•	char counts or last seen index
	•	best

10. Invariant

Current window [left..right] is always valid: all chars unique.

11. Transition logic

Expand right.
If duplicate appears, move left until valid again.
Update best length.

12. Edge cases
	•	empty string
	•	all same chars
	•	all unique
	•	repeated character far apart

13. Complexity
	•	BF: O(n^3) or O(n^2) with set check
	•	OPT: O(n) with moving pointers

14. Proof idea

Window-validity invariant:
each character enters and leaves window at most once.

⸻

Q4. Median of Two Sorted Arrays

1. Problem intake

Find median of two sorted arrays in O(log(m+n)).

2. Surface translation

This is not “merge arrays then pick middle.”
This is:

a binary-search partition problem over two sorted arrays.

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: two sorted arrays
	•	output: median value
	•	order matters globally

4. Constraint reading

The required complexity tells you brute force merge is not the intended final solution.

5. Brute force

Merge arrays, then read middle.

6. Waste diagnosis

Full merge computes far more order information than needed.

7. Compression insight

Median depends only on finding a valid partition:
	•	left side has correct size
	•	all left values <= all right values

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Binary Search
	•	Helper: Partition reasoning on sorted arrays

9. State definition

Binary search on partition index in smaller array.

10. Invariant

Search interval contains a partition candidate that can produce the correct median split.

11. Transition logic

Pick partition i in array A, deduce j in array B.
Check boundary values:
	•	if A-left too big -> move left
	•	if B-left too big -> move right
	•	else valid partition found

12. Edge cases
	•	one array empty
	•	even total length
	•	odd total length
	•	partitions at boundaries

13. Complexity
	•	BF merge: O(m+n)
	•	OPT: O(log min(m,n))

14. Proof idea

Elimination via partition monotonicity:
invalid boundary comparisons tell which side cannot contain the correct partition.

⸻

Q5. Longest Palindromic Substring

1. Problem intake

Find the longest substring that is a palindrome.

2. Surface translation

This is:

a center-expansion symmetry problem

or, in advanced form, a palindrome-DP / Manacher problem.

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: string
	•	output: substring
	•	palindrome requires mirror equality

4. Constraint reading

Typical accepted solution is O(n^2) expand-around-center.

5. Brute force

Enumerate all substrings, test palindrome.

6. Waste diagnosis

Repeated palindrome checking recomputes mirror comparisons.

7. Compression insight

Every palindrome has a center:
	•	one char center (odd)
	•	gap center (even)

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Expand Around Center
	•	Helper: Direct Scan over centers

9. State definition

For each center:
	•	expand L, R
	•	keep best start/length

10. Invariant

During expansion, substring s[L..R] remains palindrome while characters match.

11. Transition logic

For each center:
	•	expand outward while equal
	•	measure length
	•	update best

12. Edge cases
	•	even-length palindromes
	•	one char string
	•	all same chars
	•	no length >1 palindrome

13. Complexity
	•	BF: O(n^3)
	•	center expansion: O(n^2), O(1)

14. Proof idea

Any palindrome can be recovered from its center by maximal symmetric expansion.

⸻

Q6. Zigzag Conversion

1. Problem intake

Rearrange a string in zigzag rows, then read row by row.

2. Surface translation

This is:

a row-assignment simulation problem.

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: string, row count
	•	output: transformed string
	•	character order redistributed by row path

4. Constraint reading

Linear simulation expected.

5. Brute force

Actually draw a 2D zigzag matrix.

6. Waste diagnosis

A full matrix stores many empty cells.
Only row membership matters.

7. Compression insight

Track:
	•	current row
	•	direction (down/up)
	•	append characters directly to row strings

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Direct Simulation
	•	Helper: State Machine / direction toggle

9. State definition
	•	rows[]
	•	currentRow
	•	goingDown

10. Invariant

After processing prefix of string, each char has been appended to exactly the correct zigzag row.

11. Transition logic

Append current char to row.
Flip direction at top or bottom.
Move row pointer accordingly.

12. Edge cases
	•	numRows = 1
	•	numRows >= len(s)
	•	short strings

13. Complexity
	•	O(n) time
	•	O(n) output space

14. Proof idea

State machine correctness:
row pointer and direction exactly reproduce zigzag traversal.

