Q7. Reverse Integer

1. Problem intake

Reverse digits of a signed 32-bit integer. Return 0 on overflow.

2. Surface translation

This is:

a digit-decomposition and reconstruction problem with overflow guards.

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: integer
	•	output: reversed integer or 0
	•	sign matters
	•	overflow matters

4. Constraint reading

32-bit boundary is central.

5. Brute force

Convert to string, reverse, parse back, check range.

6. Waste diagnosis

String conversion is extra machinery.
Digits already can be processed numerically.

7. Compression insight

Repeatedly:
	•	pop last digit
	•	push into result

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Math / Invariant
	•	Helper: Direct simulation per digit

9. State definition
	•	x
	•	digit
	•	rev

10. Invariant

After each step, rev equals reverse of digits already popped from original number.

11. Transition logic
	•	digit = x % 10
	•	x /= 10
	•	check overflow before rev = rev*10 + digit

12. Edge cases
	•	negative numbers
	•	trailing zeroes
	•	overflow like 1534236469
	•	0

13. Complexity
	•	O(number of digits)
	•	O(1)

14. Proof idea

Digit invariant + overflow guard:
each step preserves correct partial reverse unless next multiplication/addition would leave 32-bit range.

