Q8. String to Integer (atoi)

1. Problem intake

Parse a string into a 32-bit signed integer following specific lexical rules.

2. Surface translation

This is:

a deterministic parsing state machine problem.

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: string
	•	output: integer
	•	must:
	•	skip leading spaces
	•	accept optional sign
	•	read contiguous digits
	•	stop at first invalid char
	•	clamp overflow

4. Constraint reading

Linear scan expected.

5. Brute force

Trim, slice, regex, parse, clamp in several passes.

6. Waste diagnosis

Multiple passes and temporary strings are unnecessary.
The parse is fundamentally sequential.

7. Compression insight

A one-pass parser can track:
	•	started or not
	•	sign
	•	current result

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Direct Scan / State Machine
	•	Helper: Math / overflow handling

9. State definition
	•	i
	•	sign
	•	result
	•	parsing phase

10. Invariant

At each step, result equals the numeric value of the valid digit prefix parsed so far, before sign application or with sign tracked separately.

11. Transition logic
	•	skip spaces
	•	parse optional sign
	•	consume digits
	•	stop on invalid
	•	clamp on overflow

12. Edge cases
	•	"   -42"
	•	"4193 with words"
	•	"words and 987"
	•	"+-12"
	•	overflow
	•	no digits

13. Complexity
	•	O(n) time
	•	O(1) space

14. Proof idea

Parsing-state invariant:
the machine consumes exactly the maximal valid numeric prefix under the problem contract.

