Q9. Palindrome Number

1. Problem intake

Return whether an integer reads the same forward and backward.

2. Surface translation

This is:

a digit symmetry problem.

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: integer
	•	output: boolean
	•	negative numbers are not palindromes

4. Constraint reading

Avoid full-string conversion if solving numerically.

5. Brute force

Convert to string and compare with reverse.

6. Waste diagnosis

String conversion hides the real digit structure.

7. Compression insight

Reverse only half the number.

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Math / digit decomposition
	•	Helper: Direct numeric simulation

9. State definition
	•	x
	•	reversedHalf

10. Invariant

After each step, reversedHalf contains reverse of digits removed from the right side of x.

11. Transition logic

While x > reversedHalf:
	•	move one digit from x into reversedHalf
Then compare:
	•	even digits: x == reversedHalf
	•	odd digits: x == reversedHalf / 10

12. Edge cases
	•	negatives -> false
	•	numbers ending with 0 but not 0 itself -> false
	•	single digit -> true

13. Complexity
	•	O(digits)
	•	O(1)

14. Proof idea

Half-reversal symmetry:
once half the digits are reversed, full reversal is unnecessary.

