Q10. Regular Expression Matching

1. Problem intake

Implement regex matching with . and *, where the entire string must match.

2. Surface translation

This is not “normal regex library use.”
This is:

a state recurrence / DP matching problem.

3. Input/output anatomy
	•	input: string s, pattern p
	•	output: boolean
	•	pattern rules:
	•	. matches any one char
	•	* means zero or more of previous element
	•	full match required, not partial

4. Constraint reading

Naive recursion can blow up due to repeated states.

5. Brute force

Recursive branching:
	•	if *, try zero use, one use, many uses
	•	otherwise match next char directly

6. Waste diagnosis

Same (i, j) matching state gets recomputed many times.

7. Compression insight

Matching suffix/prefix states repeat:
match(i, j) is a reusable subproblem.

8. Pattern selection
	•	Primary: Dynamic Programming
	•	Helper: Recursion / memoized DFS view

9. State definition

dp[i][j] or memo(i,j) =
whether s[i:] matches p[j:]

10. Invariant

Each DP state exactly answers the matching truth for one suffix pair.

11. Transition logic

If next pattern char is *:
	•	skip x*
	•	or consume one matching char and stay on same pattern
Else:
	•	chars must match and both advance

12. Edge cases
	•	empty string + empty pattern
	•	empty string + a*
	•	.*
	•	repeated stars
	•	full-string requirement

13. Complexity
