1. What surface translation actually does

Every LeetCode prompt contains four layers:
	1.	Theme words
robber, ladder, rooms, oranges, sticks, courses, flights
	2.	Hidden objects
array, graph nodes, intervals, grid cells, states, edges
	3.	Hidden actions
choose, merge, propagate, traverse, allocate, parse, union
	4.	Hidden goal
maximize, minimize, count, decide, return ordering, return path

Surface translation removes layer 1 and exposes 2–4.

⸻

2. The universal 5-step translation pipeline

Use this for any question.

Step 1 — Replace story nouns with structural nouns

Examples:
	•	houses -> array positions
	•	islands -> connected land cells
	•	courses -> graph nodes
	•	meetings -> intervals
	•	rooms -> resources
	•	oranges -> grid states
	•	boxes -> state containers / resources
	•	flights -> weighted edges
	•	users/posts/orders -> relational rows
	•	cache/history/browser -> persistent object state

Step 2 — Replace story verbs with computational verbs

Examples:
	•	rob -> choose
	•	infect / rot -> propagate
	•	attend -> allocate
	•	take course -> process after prerequisites
	•	fly -> traverse weighted edge
	•	merge accounts -> union equivalent identities
	•	decode -> parse
	•	build -> construct structure under rules
	•	push dominoes -> simulate state transitions

Step 3 — Extract the real restriction

Examples:
	•	cannot rob adjacent houses -> cannot choose adjacent indices
	•	must finish in h hours -> feasibility threshold
	•	cannot reuse board cell -> visited-path restriction
	•	exactly one answer -> early-return safe
	•	weighted edges -> BFS no longer enough
	•	sorted input -> midpoint/boundary logic becomes possible
	•	original indices required -> sorting may complicate result recovery

Step 4 — Extract the true output target

Examples:
	•	max stolen money -> maximize constrained sum
	•	minimum rooms -> minimum resources under interval overlap
	•	can finish all courses -> detect whether dependency graph is acyclic
	•	shortest ladder -> shortest path in an implicit graph
	•	top k frequent -> highest-frequency ranking
	•	return all valid parentheses -> enumerate valid constructions
	•	implement class -> preserve correct behavior across repeated operations

Step 5 — Rewrite as one structural sentence

Use this formula:

This is a [shape] problem about [mechanic] under [restriction], where the goal is to [target].

Examples:
	•	“This is an array problem about pair lookup under distinct-index restriction, where the goal is to return original indices.”
	•	“This is a grid problem about connected components under 4-direction adjacency, where the goal is to count regions.”
	•	“This is a graph problem about dependency order under directed prerequisite constraints, where the goal is to determine feasibility.”

That sentence is the output of surface translation.

