More good techniques to do surface translation 



Yes. Here are better techniques for doing surface translation well.

Not just the basic:
	•	surface words
	•	structural nouns
	•	structural verbs

but stronger methods that make the translation sharper and more reusable.

1. Noun collapse

Replace story nouns with algorithm nouns.

Examples:
	•	houses -> array cells
	•	courses -> graph nodes
	•	meetings -> intervals
	•	oranges -> grid states
	•	browser history -> persistent object state

Use when:
	•	the problem is wrapped in theme language

Goal:
	•	remove domain flavor fast

⸻

2. Verb collapse

Replace story actions with computational actions.

Examples:
	•	rob -> choose
	•	rot -> propagate
	•	attend -> allocate
	•	merge -> union
	•	read -> consume stream
	•	build -> construct under constraints

Use when:
	•	the story verbs are hiding the actual operation

Goal:
	•	expose what the algorithm repeatedly does

⸻

3. Constraint extraction

Translate soft wording into hard rules.

Examples:
	•	cannot rob adjacent houses -> no adjacent index selection
	•	cannot reuse the same cell -> path-local visited restriction
	•	finish in h hours -> feasibility threshold
	•	exactly one answer -> early return safe
	•	full string must match -> no partial-match acceptance

Use when:
	•	the prompt sounds casual but rules are strict

Goal:
	•	reveal the legal solution space

⸻

4. Target sharpening

Rewrite vague task language into exact computational form.

Examples:
	•	find the best time -> maximize profit difference
	•	can finish all courses -> decide DAG feasibility / cycle absence
	•	minimum rooms -> minimum simultaneous resource count
	•	convert string to integer -> parse maximal valid numeric prefix

Use when:
	•	the output sounds natural-language vague

Goal:
	•	identify the exact objective type:
	•	decide
	•	count
	•	optimize
	•	return indices
	•	enumerate
	•	maintain API behavior

⸻

5. Brute-force object extraction

Ask:

What would brute force enumerate?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum -> all pairs
	•	longest substring -> all substrings
	•	N-Queens -> all placements
	•	shortest path -> many candidate paths
	•	LRU -> replay operation history or rescan order

Use when:
	•	the structure is still unclear

Goal:
	•	reveal the search object

This is one of the strongest translation techniques.

⸻

6. Waste identification

Ask:

What repeated work is hidden in the obvious approach?

Examples:
	•	repeated pair checking
	•	repeated range rescans
	•	repeated path exploration
	•	repeated same subproblem
	•	repeated best-candidate rescans
	•	repeated prefix comparison

Use when:
	•	you have brute force but not the true structure yet

Goal:
	•	expose what later optimization must compress

⸻

7. Shape-first translation

Ignore the story and classify only the shape first.

Ask:
	•	array?
	•	string?
	•	linked list?
	•	tree?
	•	graph?
	•	grid?
	•	interval set?
	•	design/API?
	•	numeric/bit/math?
	•	SQL/table?

Examples:
	•	robber -> array
	•	islands -> grid
	•	course schedule -> directed graph
	•	meeting rooms -> intervals
	•	LRU cache -> object-state

Use when:
	•	the statement has lots of fluff

Goal:
	•	kill wrong pattern families early

⸻

8. Output-first translation

Classify by answer shape before algorithm.

Ask:
	•	boolean?
	•	count?
	•	max/min?
	•	indices?
	•	path?
	•	ordering?
	•	all solutions?
	•	modified structure?
	•	repeated operations?

Examples:
	•	“return all combinations” -> enumeration flavor
	•	“minimum steps” -> shortest-path flavor
	•	“indices” -> original position preservation matters
	•	“implement class” -> design/object-state

Use when:
	•	the shape is broad and many families are still plausible

Goal:
	•	narrow the structural family by output contract

⸻

9. Story stripping sentence

Force a one-sentence rewrite:

“This is really a [shape] problem about [mechanic] under [restriction], where the goal is to [target].”

Examples:
	•	Two Sum -> array pair-matching under sum constraint returning original indices
	•	Course Schedule -> directed dependency graph under prerequisite edges deciding feasibility
	•	Rotting Oranges -> grid wave propagation under 4-neighbor spread minimizing time
	•	Word Search -> grid path search under no-reuse constraint deciding existence

Use when:
	•	you want a final clean translation artifact

Goal:
	•	compress the whole intake into one useful sentence

This is one of the best techniques overall.

⸻

10. Negative framing

Explicitly say what the problem is not.

Examples:
	•	Two Sum is not primarily a sorting problem
	•	House Robber is not about real robbery
	•	atoi is not generic library conversion
	•	Course Schedule is not about education; it is dependency order
	•	Rotting Oranges is not about fruit; it is multi-source BFS

Use when:
	•	the problem has strong misleading surface cues

Goal:
	•	prevent impostor patterns

This is underrated and very powerful.

⸻

11. Replacement table technique

Make a 2-column table:

Surface phrase	Structural translation
two numbers	pair of distinct elements
add up	satisfy sum equality
target	fixed constraint
return indices	preserve original positions

Use when:
	•	you want a repeatable worksheet format

Goal:
	•	make translation explicit and teachable

This is probably the cleanest method for your visual guide.

⸻

12. State lens

Ask:

What hidden state must exist if I simulate this honestly?

Examples:
	•	atoi -> parser phase, sign, accumulator
	•	zigzag -> row pointer, direction
	•	add two numbers -> carry, two node pointers
	•	browser history -> current page, back stack, forward stack
	•	regular expression matching -> suffix match state (i, j)

Use when:
	•	the problem looks like a process or simulation

Goal:
	•	reveal whether it is a state-machine / DP / object-state problem

⸻

13. Operation legality lens

Ask:

What actions are allowed, forbidden, or reversible?

Examples:
	•	cannot reuse cell
	•	may skip prerequisite-free node only after indegree zero
	•	may use * as zero or more repetitions
	•	may pop from stack only under monotonic violation
	•	may choose or skip house, but not adjacent house

Use when:
	•	the problem is about search, traversal, or parsing

Goal:
	•	expose the move system and valid transition graph

⸻

14. Boundary lens

Ask:

Where do boundaries matter?

Examples:
	•	substring -> contiguous boundaries
	•	median partition -> left/right boundary values
	•	binary search -> low/high interval
	•	palindrome -> left/right mirrored expansion
	•	intervals -> start/end boundaries
	•	sliding window -> moving left/right edges

Use when:
	•	the problem is about ranges, partitions, or symmetry

Goal:
	•	expose whether the problem is really about boundary management

⸻

15. Equivalence lens

Ask:

Which objects are actually treated as the same?

Examples:
	•	Accounts Merge -> same connected identity via shared email
	•	DSU problems -> same representative/component
	•	group anagrams -> same canonical signature
	•	modulo classes -> same remainder behavior
	•	prefix sums with equal relation -> same cumulative state class

Use when:
	•	grouping, merging, clustering, or union is hidden in story form

Goal:
	•	expose union/find, hashing, or grouping structure

⸻

16. Time-evolution lens

Ask:

Is this a one-shot question or a process over time?

Examples:
	•	Rotting Oranges -> discrete time layers
	•	stock problems -> sequence over time
	•	design problems -> repeated operations over time
	•	shortest path -> frontier expansion over steps/cost
	•	dynamic updates -> query/update regime

Use when:
	•	the problem mentions minutes, days, turns, operations, rounds, or repeated calls

Goal:
	•	expose BFS, simulation, greedy scheduling, or object-state structure

⸻

17. Resource lens

Ask:

What resource is scarce or being allocated?

Examples:
	•	meeting rooms -> room count
	•	CPU tasks -> cooldown/resource schedule
	•	cache -> capacity
	•	flights with k stops -> stop budget
	•	knapsack-style -> weight/capacity budget

Use when:
	•	the story involves rooms, capacity, budget, limit, or k operations

Goal:
	•	expose interval/heap/greedy/DP resource models

⸻

18. Symmetry lens

Ask:

Is the problem really about mirrored equality or balanced structure?

Examples:
	•	palindrome -> mirrored boundaries
	•	balanced parentheses -> open/close consistency
	•	tree symmetry -> mirrored subtree comparison
	•	reverse integer / palindrome number -> digit symmetry

Use when:
	•	the story mentions reflection, same forward/backward, balance, or pairing

Goal:
	•	expose center-expansion, stack, or recursive symmetry logic

⸻

19. Canonical archetype mapping

Ask:

What known pure prototype is this secretly closest to?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum -> complement lookup canonical
	•	House Robber -> non-adjacent choice DP canonical
	•	Course Schedule -> topological sort canonical
	•	Rotting Oranges -> multi-source BFS canonical
	•	Word Search -> DFS/backtracking with visited canonical

Use when:
	•	you already have a pattern atlas

Goal:
	•	translate new problems into known anchors quickly

⸻

20. Minimal structural sentence

After all of the above, force the shortest useful sentence possible.

Examples:
	•	Two Sum -> unsorted array complement-pair lookup with original-index output
	•	Add Two Numbers -> linked-list digit addition with carry
	•	Longest Substring Without Repeating -> max valid distinct-character window
	•	Median of Two Sorted Arrays -> valid median partition of two ordered arrays
	•	atoi -> one-pass lexical numeric prefix parser with clamping

Use when:
	•	you want the final distilled statement

Goal:
	•	produce the cleanest mental handle for the problem

