⸻

Brute-force object
	•	all unordered pairs of distinct indices (i, j) with i < j

This is the naive search space.

⸻

Waste type
	•	repeated partner search for each element
	•	repeated pair-sum testing across many irrelevant pairs
	•	full pair enumeration even though each value only needs one specific complement

The waste is not “doing addition.”
The waste is searching too many candidate partners.

⸻

Fast operation needed
	•	given current value x, quickly determine whether target - x already exists
	•	equivalently:
	•	complement existence lookup
	•	partner lookup under sum constraint

This is the one operation the optimized solution must make cheap.

⸻

Required key
	•	element value

Why:
The question we need to ask is:
	•	“Have I seen the value target - nums[i] before?”

So the lookup key is not:
	•	index
	•	pair
	•	prefix sum
	•	sorted rank

It is:
	•	value

⸻

Required payload
	•	original index of the seen value

Why:
The output contract is:
	•	return indices

So storing only existence is not enough.
You must also recover:
	•	where the complement occurred

Thus payload = index

⸻

Minimal past summary
	•	map from previously seen value -> its index

This is the smallest useful summary of the processed prefix.

The future does not need:
	•	all previous pairs
	•	all previous sums
	•	the full prefix order
	•	a sorted history

It only needs:
	•	whether a needed complement exists
	•	and where

So the processed prefix compresses into:
	•	value -> index

⸻

Current-vs-history asymmetry
	•	current element -> query source
	•	processed prefix -> lookup memory

Brute force treats the two elements symmetrically:
	•	test (i, j) pairs

Optimized structure is asymmetric:
	•	current value asks a question
	•	past values answer it through stored memory

This asymmetry is the real optimized viewpoint:
	•	not “find any pair”
	•	but
	•	“for the current value, has the required partner already appeared?”

⸻

Identity / order preservation
	•	original index identity must be preserved
	•	input order is not itself the target, but source positions are part of the answer
	•	reordering is structurally unnatural as a primary move

This matters because:
	•	the problem does not ask only for values
	•	it asks for original indices

That weakens sorting as the primary structural model.

⸻

Anti-pattern to reject
	•	sorting + two pointers as the primary formulation

Why reject it as the main structural model:
	•	input is unsorted
	•	original indices matter
	•	sorting destroys direct position identity
	•	extra bookkeeping would be needed to recover original indices
	•	complement lookup is more native than global reordering

This does not mean sorting is impossible.
It means it is not the cleanest structural reading.

⸻

Optimized data structure
	•	hash map
	•	more specifically:
	•	value -> original index

Why this structure:
	•	required fast operation = complement lookup
	•	required key = value
	•	required payload = index
	•	processed prefix summary = associative lookup table

So the most natural optimized structure is:
	•	hash map

⸻

Optimized pattern
	•	one-pass seen-so-far complement lookup
	•	also describable as:
	•	hashing over processed prefix
	•	current-value complement query

Pattern logic:
	1.	scan left to right
	2.	for current value x, compute need = target - x
	3.	ask if need is in seen map
	4.	if yes, return stored index and current index
	5.	otherwise store current value and index

