1. How a for loop actually runs

For a loop like this:

for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); ++i) {
  // body
}

the execution order is always:

For-loop execution stack
	1.	Initialization
	•	int i = 0
	•	runs once only
	2.	Condition check
	•	i < nums.size()
	•	if false, loop stops
	•	if true, enter body
	3.	Body execution
	•	all code inside {} runs top to bottom
	4.	Increment
	•	++i
	•	runs after body finishes
	5.	Condition check again
	•	then repeat body
	•	then increment
	•	then condition again

So the real loop stack is:

init -> condition -> body -> increment -> condition -> body -> increment -> ...

Not:

init -> body -> increment

The condition runs before every iteration.

That matters a lot in dry runs.

⸻

2. Nested for loop methodology

For brute force Two Sum:

for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); ++i) {
  for (int j = i + 1; j < nums.size(); ++j) {
    ...
  }
}

the stack is:

Outer loop
	•	initialize i
	•	check outer condition
	•	enter outer body

Inner loop
	•	initialize j
	•	check inner condition
	•	execute inner body
	•	increment j
	•	check inner condition again
	•	repeat until inner loop ends

Then outer resumes
	•	outer body ends
	•	increment i
	•	check outer condition again
	•	start new inner loop

So nested loop stack is:

outer init
outer condition
  inner init
  inner condition
  inner body
  inner increment
  inner condition
  ...
outer increment
outer condition
...

This is exactly what your visualizer should show.

