Innovative techniques to make the dry run better

A. Phase labeling

Every step belongs to one phase:
	•	setup
	•	loop control
	•	value extraction
	•	relation computation
	•	decision
	•	memory mutation
	•	return

This makes long traces readable.

B. Hit/Miss semantics

For lookup problems like Q1, always tag lookup steps as:
	•	miss
	•	hit

This is more useful than generic “if false / true”.

C. Before/After delta

For mutable structures, show only the change:
	•	before: {2:0}
	•	after: {2:0, 7:1}

Not just the final whole container every time.

D. Skipped-step reporting

When return happens, explicitly say:
	•	line 14 skipped
	•	line 6(c) skipped
	•	next loop condition skipped

This is one of the most important execution clarifiers.

E. Invariant echo

At important points, restate the invariant in one short line.
That prevents the dry run from becoming only mechanical.

F. Dual stack

For each example:
	•	Brute-force dry run summary
	•	Optimized dry run stack

This makes the optimization visible.

