Optimized Pattern

Hashing

Optimal Technique

One-pass seen-so-far complement lookup

Optimized Data Structure

Hash map: value -> original index

Optimized Code (Google-style)

class Solution {
 public:
  std::vector<int> TwoSum(const std::vector<int>& nums, int target) {
    std::unordered_map<int, int> seen_index_by_value;

    for (int i = 0; i < static_cast<int>(nums.size()); ++i) {
      const int current_value = nums[i];
      const int needed_value = target - current_value;

      if (seen_index_by_value.contains(needed_value)) {
        return {seen_index_by_value[needed_value], i};
      }

      seen_index_by_value[current_value] = i;
    }

    return {};
  }
};

Invariant / Core Law

Before processing index i, the map contains all earlier values and their original indices.

Why OPT Works

Each current value needs exactly one complement:

needed_value = target - current_value

So pair search becomes direct lookup.

Common Wrong Approach

Sorting + two pointers is possible, but it is not the cleanest primary model because original indices are part of the output.

Mem Vis (OPT)
	•	hash map seen_index_by_value
	•	current scalar variables:
	•	i
	•	current_value
	•	needed_value

