Techniques to show code sync path and memory delta and how many memory deltas in different optimised patterns


Use two separate systems:
	1.	Code Sync Path
	2.	Memory Delta Model

They should be independent, then joined.

1. Techniques to show Code Sync Path

A. Line-to-microstep decomposition

Break each executable line into ordered substeps.

Example:
	•	6(a) loop init
	•	6(b) loop condition
	•	6(c) loop increment

And for expressions:
	•	8(a) read left operand
	•	8(b) read right operand
	•	8(c) compute
	•	8(d) assign

Best for:
	•	loops
	•	expressions
	•	returns
	•	container mutations

⸻

B. Control-flow phase tags

Every code-sync step should carry a phase:
	•	setup
	•	loop-init
	•	loop-condition
	•	body
	•	branch-check
	•	branch-taken
	•	branch-skipped
	•	mutation
	•	increment
	•	return
	•	exit

This makes long traces readable.

⸻

C. Path arrows

Show the path explicitly:
	•	4 -> 6(a) -> 6(b) -> 7 -> 8 -> 10 -> 14 -> 6(c) -> 6(b) ...

For branches:
	•	hit path
	•	miss path

For loops:
	•	loop-back arrow after increment

This is the cleanest “execution lane” view.

⸻

D. Branch outcome labeling

Instead of only showing line 10, show:
	•	10(hit)
	•	10(miss)

This is much better than plain true/false for lookup-heavy patterns.

⸻

E. Exit-path annotation

When a return happens, explicitly show:
	•	return path entered
	•	loop increment skipped
	•	next condition skipped
	•	function terminated

This is critical for code-sync correctness.

⸻

F. Sync compression levels

Use 3 levels.

Level 1: Full micro-sync

Every microstep shown.

Best for:
	•	first canonical example
	•	tricky control flow
	•	teaching mode

Level 2: Grouped line-sync

Example:
	•	7->8->10(miss)->14

Best for:
	•	medium traces

Level 3: Path summary

Example:
	•	scan -> miss -> store
	•	scan -> hit -> return

Best for:
	•	many test cases

