2. Techniques to show Memory Delta

Memory delta means:

what changed in memory at this step, not the whole state repeated every time

A. Delta-only display

Show:
	•	added
	•	updated
	•	removed
	•	unchanged

Example:
	•	+ seen[2] = 0
	•	~ dist[5]: INF -> 7
	•	- deque front index 3 expired

This is the best default.

⸻

B. Container-specific delta language

Different structures need different verbs.

Hash map / set
	•	insert
	•	overwrite
	•	erase
	•	lookup hit/miss

Stack
	•	push
	•	pop
	•	top unchanged

Queue / deque
	•	enqueue
	•	dequeue
	•	push front/back
	•	pop front/back
	•	expire stale index

Heap
	•	push
	•	pop min/max
	•	lazy stale pop
	•	heap top changed

DP table
	•	fill cell
	•	improve cell
	•	carry forward unchanged

Graph state
	•	mark visited
	•	relax distance
	•	parent update
	•	indegree decrement

DSU
	•	parent update
	•	rank/size update
	•	path compression rewrite

Linked list / pointers
	•	next reassigned
	•	prev reassigned
	•	node attached
	•	node detached

⸻

C. Memory snapshot + delta pair

Show both:
	•	compact delta
	•	optional current snapshot

Example:
	•	Delta: + seen[7] = 1
	•	Snapshot: {2:0, 7:1}

This is ideal for teaching.

⸻

D. No-delta steps

Explicitly mark:
	•	memory unchanged

This matters because many code steps are read-only.

Example:
	•	complement lookup hit
	•	comparison only
	•	loop condition check

⸻

E. Semantic delta

Not just raw mutation, but meaning.

Example for Two Sum:
	•	raw: + seen[2] = 0
	•	semantic: “processed prefix now knows value 2 occurs at index 0”

This is powerful for learning mode.

