Memory delta behaviour across different patterns


Memory delta behavior is the pattern of what changes in memory per step, how often it changes, and what kind of mutation dominates.

That is one of the best ways to distinguish algorithm families.

Core idea

A pattern is not only defined by:
	•	time complexity
	•	data structure
	•	control flow

It is also defined by:
	•	memory mutation rhythm

Some patterns mostly:
	•	overwrite a few scalars

Others:
	•	grow and shrink a live structure

Others:
	•	push/pop in bursts

Others:
	•	write a table monotonically

Others:
	•	mutate, then undo

That is memory delta behavior.

⸻

Master dimensions of memory delta behavior

For any pattern, ask:

1. Delta frequency

How often does memory change?
	•	rare
	•	once per iteration
	•	multiple times per iteration
	•	bursty

2. Delta magnitude

How much changes at once?
	•	one scalar
	•	one container entry
	•	many entries
	•	full row/column/table region

3. Delta direction

Does memory mostly:
	•	grow
	•	shrink
	•	overwrite
	•	oscillate
	•	grow then undo

4. Delta reversibility

Are mutations:
	•	permanent
	•	temporary
	•	later undone
	•	lazily invalidated

5. Delta locality

Where do changes happen?
	•	one scalar slot
	•	front/back of container
	•	arbitrary keyed slot
	•	structured table cell
	•	graph node metadata
	•	pointer links

These five dimensions are the deep model.

⸻

1. Scalar scan / direct accumulation patterns

Examples:
	•	running sum
	•	max/min scan
	•	Kadane-like simple forms
	•	reverse integer
	•	palindrome number

Memory delta behavior
	•	very low mutation count
	•	mostly scalar overwrites
	•	almost no structural growth
	•	deltas are local and permanent

Typical delta rhythm

Per step:
	•	read input
	•	compute next scalar state
	•	overwrite 1–3 variables

Typical deltas
	•	sum: 10 -> 14
	•	best: 14 -> 14
	•	rev: 12 -> 123

Signature
	•	few deltas
	•	small deltas
	•	overwrite-only
	•	no container churn

Mental image

A few boxes changing values repeatedly.

⸻

2. Hashing patterns

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
	•	frequency counting
	•	Group Anagrams
	•	prefix-sum counting
	•	longest substring variants

Memory delta behavior
	•	low to medium mutation count
	•	mostly keyed insert/update operations
	•	changes are sparse and associative
	•	memory tends to grow, sometimes overwrite

Typical delta rhythm

Per step:
	•	maybe a lookup
	•	maybe an insert
	•	maybe a count increment/decrement

Typical deltas
	•	+ seen[2] = 0
	•	count['a']: 1 -> 2
	•	prefix_count[5]: 3 -> 4
	•	overwrite last_seen['c']: 2 -> 7

Signature
	•	map/set mutations
	•	keyed sparse changes
	•	lookup-heavy, mutate-light
	•	mostly permanent growth or overwrite

Mental image

A side table where a few entries appear or update each iteration.

⸻

3. Sliding window patterns

Examples:
	•	longest unique substring
	•	minimum window substring
	•	at most K distinct
	•	fixed-size window aggregates

Memory delta behavior
	•	medium mutation count
	•	state changes often happen on both sides of the window
	•	memory oscillates as window expands and shrinks
	•	several mutations can happen in one logical iteration

Typical delta rhythm

Per iteration:
	•	right edge expands
	•	frequency map increases
	•	validity changes
	•	maybe left edge shrinks repeatedly
	•	frequency map decreases repeatedly

Typical deltas
	•	right: 4 -> 5
	•	freq['c']: 0 -> 1
	•	left: 2 -> 3
	•	freq['a']: 2 -> 1
	•	distinct_count: 4 -> 3

Signature
	•	oscillating memory
	•	paired grow/shrink behavior
	•	multiple deltas per iteration
	•	validity-driven mutation bursts

Mental image

A live interval with counts expanding and contracting.

⸻

4. Two pointers

Examples:
	•	sorted Two Sum
	•	move zeroes
	•	container with most water
	•	linked-list fast/slow pointer
	•	merge-style scans

Memory delta behavior
	•	low mutation count
	•	mostly pointer/index movement
	•	sometimes swap or write
	•	little auxiliary memory

Typical delta rhythm

Per step:
	•	move left or right pointer
	•	maybe compare
	•	maybe swap/write

Typical deltas
	•	left: 3 -> 4
	•	right: 9 -> 8
	•	slow: node5 -> node6
	•	swap nums[2], nums[7]

Signature
	•	pointer-motion dominated
	•	minimal auxiliary mutation
	•	structural movement more than storage growth

Mental image

Pointers move; memory barely grows.

