How to represent them cleanly

1. Use a 3-layer representation for every mutation

Each step should show:
	•	Symbol
	•	Raw mutation
	•	Semantic meaning

Example:

+ seen[2] = 0
meaning: processed prefix now knows value 2 occurred at index 0

Another:

d~ dist[5]: INF -> 8
meaning: found a shorter path to node 5

2. Use pattern-specific preferred symbols

Hashing

Use:
	•	+, ~, -, ✓, ✗

Example:

✓ lookup 2
+ seen[7] = 1

Sliding window

Use:
	•	+1, -1, ←, →, -

Example:

→ right 4 -> 5
+ freq['c'] 0 -> 1
← left 2 -> 3
- freq['a'] 1 -> 0
erase freq['a']

Monotonic deque/stack

Use:
	•	≻-, ⌛-, →+, ↑+, ↑-

Example:

≻- pop index 5
≻- pop index 4
→+ push-back index 6

Heap

Use:
	•	△+, △-, ⌛△-

Example:

△+ push (8,5)
⌛△- stale-pop (10,3)
△- pop (8,5)

Backtracking

Use:
	•	+choice, -choice, used✓, used✗, +place, -place

Example:

+choice add 3
used✓ 3
...
-choice remove 3
used✗ 3

Graph advanced

Use:
	•	d~, p=, F+, F-, in-

Example:

d~ dist[7]: INF -> 4
p= parent[7] = 2
F+ enqueue 7

Design / object-state

Use grouped deltas:
	•	detach, attach, ⇡, evict, sync

Example:

sync
- detach node 7
+ attach node 7 at front
⇡ promote key 7

Delta count model

Add a delta count tag to each step:

Delta Count	Meaning	Typical Patterns
0	read-only	lookups, comparisons, loop conditions
1	single mutation	simple hash insert, scalar overwrite
2	paired mutation	pointer move + count update, pop + push
3–4	compound mutation	deque prune + push, BFS visit + enqueue + dist
5+	burst mutation	backtracking multi-undo, design sync ops, heavy monotonic pruning

Representation:

Δcount = 3

Reversibility tags

Use:
	•	Permanent
	•	Reversible
	•	Read-only

Example:

+choice add 3
reversibility: Reversible

+ seen[2] = 0
reversibility: Permanent

✓ lookup 2
reversibility: Read-only

