Can we implement chairman llm with gemini copilot github chatgpt here


Yes, but only in a specific way.

You can implement a “chairman LLM” architecture that sits above multiple systems, but not as a native multi-model runtime inside this chat itself. The workable pattern is:

ChatGPT/GPT as the front end
	•	A custom GPT can call external REST APIs through Actions. OpenAI documents GPT Actions for connecting ChatGPT to external systems you define, and GPTs can use external APIs/apps with the warning that relevant parts of user input may be sent to those third parties. Also, a GPT can use either apps or actions, not both at once.  ￼

Your own chairman/orchestrator service in the middle
	•	This is where you route requests, compare outputs, arbitrate disagreements, apply confidence rules, store memory, and choose which provider to call. ChatGPT would call your API, not directly “run Gemini + Copilot + ChatGPT together” inside the same native chat runtime. That orchestration layer is your implementation choice; it is not a built-in ChatGPT feature. The reason this is the right pattern is that OpenAI’s supported extension point here is external API calling via Actions.  ￼

Gemini as one backend
	•	Gemini is straightforward to plug in because Google exposes the Gemini API over REST/SDKs and uses API keys from Google AI Studio.  ￼

GitHub/Copilot as context/tooling, not usually as a general model backend
	•	GitHub documents MCP support for Copilot and provides the GitHub MCP Server so AI tools can interact with repositories, issues, PRs, and related GitHub context. That makes GitHub/Copilot strong for repo-aware tooling and context sharing. But from the docs I found, GitHub is documented here as an MCP/context system and GitHub server, not as a general “call Copilot like a model API backend” replacement for Gemini/OpenAI.  ￼

So the practical answer is:

What you can do

Build this:

User -> ChatGPT custom GPT -> your chairman API -> {Gemini API, OpenAI API, GitHub tooling/MCP, your own rules}

This works well for:
	•	model routing
	•	majority vote / arbitration
	•	“Gemini for long-context doc pass, OpenAI for coding synthesis”
	•	GitHub repo retrieval and code context
	•	fallback and guardrail logic

What you cannot do cleanly “here”

You cannot make this exact ChatGPT conversation natively become a first-class runtime that directly hosts Gemini + Copilot + ChatGPT as equal built-in internal engines. In ChatGPT, the supported way is to connect external APIs or apps, so the multi-model layer has to live outside and be called from here.  ￼

Best role for each component
	•	ChatGPT: front-end conversation, explanation, synthesis, action calling.  ￼
	•	Gemini: external multimodal/long-context/document backend via API.  ￼
	•	GitHub/Copilot side: repo context and tool access through MCP/GitHub MCP server.  ￼

Recommended chairman logic

Your orchestrator should do:
	•	classify task type
	•	choose primary engine
	•	optionally send to a second engine for validation
	•	normalize outputs to one schema
	•	compare confidence / agreement
	•	return one final answer plus provenance

A simple routing policy could be:
	•	codebase/repo task -> GitHub context tools first
	•	long PDF/doc digestion -> Gemini first
	•	final coding explanation / clean synthesis -> OpenAI last

Safest implementation path
	1.	Build a small orchestrator API.
	2.	Add providers:
	•	OpenAI API
	•	Gemini API
	•	GitHub context via MCP/server integration
	3.	Expose one REST endpoint like /chairman/respond.
	4.	Connect that endpoint to a custom GPT Action.
	5.	Keep provider logs, confidence scores, and fallback rules in your backend.  ￼

One important privacy note

When a GPT uses external APIs/apps, relevant parts of user input may be sent to those third-party services. So if your chairman sends prompts to Gemini or GitHub-connected systems, you need to treat that as cross-provider data sharing by design.  ￼

