In depth about representation of every pattern or bucket

Below is the deep representation guide for every major pattern / bucket in your system.

This is not about solving only.
This is about how to represent each pattern so that:
	•	the structure becomes visible
	•	the memory behavior becomes visible
	•	the control flow becomes visible
	•	the “reason the algorithm works” becomes visible
	•	the visualizer / slide system knows what to draw

⸻

0. Master idea

Every pattern should be represented through the same layered lens.

For any problem bucket, show these layers:

A. Surface Layer

What the problem says in story form.

B. Structural Layer

What the problem really is.

C. Search Layer

What is being searched / maintained / transformed.

D. Control-Flow Layer

How execution moves.

E. Memory Layer

What memory exists.

F. Delta Layer

How memory changes.

G. Invariant Layer

What remains true.

H. Decision Layer

What branch or choice is being made.

I. Exit Layer

What ends the process.

⸻

1. Universal bucket template

Use this for every pattern.

Problem Identity Bucket
	•	problem title
	•	surface form
	•	minimal structural sentence
	•	final structural sentence

Pattern Identity Bucket
	•	primary pattern
	•	secondary pattern if any
	•	optimized data structure
	•	fast operation
	•	anti-pattern

Search Object Bucket
	•	what the algorithm is trying to find
	•	what unit is processed each step
	•	what relationship matters

Memory Bucket
	•	primary memory structure
	•	auxiliary memory structures
	•	scalar state
	•	frontier state
	•	persistent vs temporary memory

Memory Delta Bucket
	•	delta rhythm
	•	delta count
	•	delta direction
	•	delta reversibility
	•	delta locality
	•	dominant delta types

Control-Flow Bucket
	•	loop shape
	•	recursion shape
	•	branch shape
	•	early-exit behavior
	•	retry / revisit behavior

Invariant Bucket
	•	local invariant
	•	global invariant
	•	why current state is sufficient

Visualization Bucket
	•	what to draw
	•	what to highlight
	•	what should animate
	•	what should stay stable
	•	what should be faded / considered old

Dry Run Bucket
	•	canonical example
	•	tricky example
	•	compressed batch examples

⸻

2. Direct scan / scalar accumulation pattern

Examples:
	•	running sum
	•	max/min scan
	•	Kadane-style simple scan
	•	reverse integer
	•	palindrome number

Structural identity

This is a single forward scan where the answer can be maintained using only a few scalars.

What to represent

Primary visual object
	•	array or digit stream
	•	current index pointer
	•	scalar boxes

Scalar boxes

Usually:
	•	current
	•	best
	•	sum
	•	answer
	•	maybe carry, sign, rev

Delta behavior
	•	overwrite
	•	increment / decrement
	•	reset

Control flow
	•	one loop
	•	no nested structure usually
	•	branch decides whether to keep / reset / improve

Best representation

Draw
	•	horizontal array strip
	•	one active pointer
	•	2–4 scalar state boxes on side

Highlight
	•	current element
	•	current scalar updates

Animate
	•	scalar overwrite
	•	best improvement
	•	reset event

Invariant style

“After processing index i, these scalars summarize everything needed about prefix [0..i].”

Common mistake representation

Show:
	•	“no need to store full history”
	•	“history is compressed into scalars”

⸻

3. Hashing pattern

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
	•	frequency counting
	•	longest substring without repeating
	•	prefix sum count
	•	grouping / membership problems

Structural identity

This is a state caching pattern where prior information is stored in keyed form for fast lookup.

What to represent

Primary visual object
	•	current element / pointer
	•	hash map / set / frequency table

Map meaning

Must explicitly show:
	•	key
	•	payload
	•	why that payload is enough

Examples:
	•	value -> index
	•	char -> last position
	•	prefix sum -> count
	•	group key -> list

Delta behavior
	•	insert
	•	update
	•	increment count
	•	decrement count
	•	erase
	•	lookup hit / miss

Control flow
	•	scan current item
	•	derive query key
	•	query map
	•	on miss -> store
	•	on hit -> act / return / update

Best representation

Draw
	•	main sequence on left
	•	hash map panel on right

Highlight
	•	current item
	•	queried key
	•	hit/miss outcome
	•	inserted/updated row

Animate
	•	new row insertion
	•	row update
	•	hit glow

Invariant style

“The map summarizes all relevant information from the processed prefix.”

Important sub-representations

Seen-so-far hashing

Example: Two Sum
Show:
	•	prefix vs current
	•	complement query
	•	return on hit

Frequency hashing

Show:
	•	count rising/falling
	•	zero-count erasure if relevant

Last-seen hashing

Show:
	•	overwrite instead of insert
	•	why only latest index matters

Grouping hashing

Show:
	•	key normalization process
	•	bucket/list attached to each key

⸻

4. Sliding window pattern

Examples:
	•	longest unique substring
	•	minimum window substring
	•	at most K distinct
	•	fixed-size window sums

Structural identity

This is an active interval maintenance pattern.

What to represent

Primary visual object
	•	sequence
	•	left pointer
	•	right pointer
	•	active shaded window

Memory
	•	frequency map
	•	distinct count
	•	validity flag
	•	current best window

Delta behavior
	•	right expansion
	•	left shrink
	•	count increment/decrement
	•	validity entering/exiting

Control flow

Usually:
	•	expand right
	•	update state
	•	while invalid or while valid:
	•	shrink left
	•	update state
	•	maybe update answer

Best representation

Draw
	•	sequence strip
	•	left/right markers
	•	active window shade
	•	side map

Highlight
	•	entering element
	•	leaving element
	•	validity status

Animate
	•	window growth
	•	window shrink
	•	frequency deltas
	•	answer interval update

Invariant style

“The state structure matches exactly the current window [left, right].”

Representation variants

Fixed-size window

Show:
	•	one element enters
	•	one element exits each step

Variable-size valid-window

Show:
	•	expansion phase
	•	shrink-until-valid phase

Variable-size optimize-over-valid windows

