In depth about analysing the algorithm 

Algorithm analysis means:

take a solution idea and prove what it is doing, why it works, what it costs, where it fails, and how to represent its behavior clearly.

For your system, algorithm analysis should not be only:
	•	time complexity
	•	space complexity

It should be a full structural dissection.

⸻

1. Full meaning of algorithm analysis

When you analyze an algorithm deeply, you answer all of these:
	1.	What is the algorithm trying to do?
	2.	What exact object is it processing?
	3.	What state does it maintain?
	4.	How does state change step by step?
	5.	Why is that state sufficient?
	6.	What invariant makes the method correct?
	7.	Why does it terminate?
	8.	What is the cost in time and memory?
	9.	What structural waste does it remove compared to brute force?
	10.	What class of problems does this algorithm belong to?

That is true algorithm analysis.

⸻

2. Main layers of algorithm analysis

Use these layers every time.

A. Problem-object analysis

What is the true shape of the problem?

You ask:
	•	is it array / string / grid / graph / tree / linked list / stream?
	•	is the goal search / count / optimize / validate / transform / enumerate?
	•	is the relation local or global?
	•	does order matter?
	•	does identity matter?
	•	does contiguity matter?

This layer tells you what kind of algorithm is even possible.

⸻

B. Brute-force analysis

Before the optimal method, analyze the raw search space.

You ask:
	•	what would the naive search enumerate?
	•	what is the search object?
	•	what gets repeated?
	•	what is the structural waste?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum brute force checks all pairs
	•	Islands brute force may re-scan connected land repeatedly
	•	LCS brute force explores many overlapping subsequences
	•	shortest path brute force explores too many routes

This layer is critical because optimization is always removal of waste.

⸻

C. State analysis

Every good algorithm compresses the problem into state.

You ask:
	•	what information does the algorithm remember?
	•	why this state, not something bigger or smaller?
	•	what does one unit of state mean?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum: seen[value] = index
	•	Kadane: current_best_ending_here
	•	BFS: queue + visited
	•	DP: dp[i], dp[i][j], memo state
	•	backtracking: current path + used markers
	•	sliding window: [left, right] + freq map

This is one of the deepest parts of algorithm analysis.

⸻

D. Transition analysis

After defining state, you analyze how state evolves.

You ask:
	•	how does one step move to the next?
	•	what is read?
	•	what is written?
	•	what causes each branch?

This is where:
	•	loops
	•	recursion
	•	branch conditions
	•	updates
	•	insertions
	•	pops
	•	relaxations

are studied.

This is the dynamic layer.

⸻

E. Invariant analysis

This is the core correctness layer.

An invariant is something that remains true throughout execution.

You ask:
	•	what must always be true before and after each step?
	•	what does the current state guarantee?
	•	why does the next transition preserve correctness?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum: map contains exactly processed prefix values
	•	sliding window: freq map matches current window exactly
	•	monotonic stack: stack is monotone and unresolved
	•	BFS: dequeued nodes already have minimum distance
	•	Dijkstra: popped min node is finalized
	•	DP: dependencies of current state are already solved
	•	backtracking: path exactly matches current decisions

If you miss the invariant, you do not really understand the algorithm.

⸻

F. Correctness analysis

This is the proof layer.

You ask:
	•	why does the algorithm always return a correct answer?
	•	why can it never miss the answer?
	•	why is each discarded possibility safely discardable?
	•	why is each greedy/local step safe?
	•	why is the recurrence sufficient?
	•	why does the stored memory summarize enough information?

Correctness analysis usually comes from:
	•	invariant proof
	•	induction
	•	exchange argument
	•	contradiction
	•	monotonicity
	•	exhaustive coverage of search branches

⸻

G. Termination analysis

You must explain why the algorithm stops.

You ask:
	•	what strictly progresses?
	•	which variable shrinks/grows toward a boundary?
	•	what prevents infinite loops?
	•	what prevents repeated revisits?

Examples:
	•	for-loop index reaches n
	•	BFS queue empties
	•	recursion reaches base case
	•	binary search interval shrinks
	•	backtracking exhausts choices
	•	DSU processes finite unions/finds

This is often ignored, but it matters.

⸻

H. Complexity analysis

Only after structure and correctness.

You ask:
	•	how many times does each operation happen?
	•	what is the cost of each operation?
	•	which structure dominates runtime?
	•	what memory grows with input size?

This must be derived, not guessed.

⸻

3. The full algorithm analysis pipeline

This is the best universal methodology.

Step 1 — Identify the computational target

What exact output is required?

Not vague:
	•	“solve the problem”

Precise:
	•	find one pair
	•	find minimum path
	•	count valid substrings
	•	maximize score
	•	return all combinations

⸻

Step 2 — Identify the search object

What would brute force search through?

Examples:
	•	all pairs
	•	all subarrays
	•	all substrings
	•	all paths
	•	all subsets
	•	all partitions
	•	all alignments
	•	all graph traversals

This step defines brute-force size.

⸻

Step 3 — Identify the waste

What repeats unnecessarily?

Examples:
	•	repeated partner scanning
	•	repeated prefix recomputation
	•	repeated subtree solving
	•	repeated range max/min computation
	•	repeated route exploration
	•	repeated membership tests

Optimization begins here.

⸻

Step 4 — Identify the fast operation needed

What operation would remove that waste?

Examples:
	•	O(1) lookup
	•	prefix reuse
	•	monotonic candidate filtering
	•	queue frontier expansion
	•	memo reuse
	•	state transition table
	•	greedy boundary move

This predicts the pattern.

⸻

Step 5 — Identify the state

What minimal information must persist across steps?

Examples:
	•	map of seen values
	•	running best
	•	active window counts
	•	unresolved monotonic candidates
	•	frontier queue
	•	dp table
	•	parent representative

This is the compression layer.

⸻

Step 6 — Identify the invariant

What does that state guarantee at all times?

This is the truth layer.

⸻

Step 7 — Analyze transitions

How does one step preserve the invariant?

This is the execution logic.

⸻

Step 8 — Prove correctness

Why must a correct answer eventually emerge?

This is the proof layer.

⸻

Step 9 — Analyze complexity

Count transitions and storage.

⸻

Step 10 — Compare against alternatives

Why this algorithm instead of the others?

This gives pattern maturity.

⸻

4. Different dimensions of algorithm analysis

A deep algorithm analysis has multiple dimensions.

1. Structural analysis

What shape of problem is this?

2. Behavioral analysis

How does execution move?

3. Memory analysis

What is stored and why?

4. Delta analysis

How does memory change?

5. Invariant analysis

What remains true?

6. Proof analysis

Why is it correct?

7. Performance analysis

How expensive is it?

8. Failure analysis

Where do wrong approaches break?

9. Pattern analysis

Which family does it belong to?

10. Transfer analysis

What other problems share this structure?

That is full analysis.

⸻

5. What to ask while analyzing an algorithm

These are the best questions.

Goal questions
	•	What exactly is being returned?
	•	Is it one answer, best answer, or all answers?

Structure questions
	•	Is this local, global, contiguous, ordered, rooted, graph-connected?

Search questions
	•	What would brute force enumerate?
	•	How large is that space?

Waste questions
	•	What repeated work exists?

State questions
	•	What memory is necessary?
	•	What memory is sufficient?
	•	What memory is unnecessary?

Transition questions
	•	What happens first?
	•	What gets read?
	•	What gets updated?
	•	Why that order?

Invariant questions
	•	What is always true here?
	•	Why can I trust this state?

Correctness questions
	•	Why can’t the algorithm miss the answer?
	•	Why is discarding this case safe?

Complexity questions
	•	How many times can this line run?
	•	Can one iteration cause multiple pops/pushes?
	•	Is this amortized or worst-case?

Edge-case questions
	•	What happens on empty/minimal/maximal input?
	•	Duplicates?
	•	Zero?
	•	Negative?
	•	Overflow?
	•	disconnected components?
	•	repeated states?

⸻

6. Deep analysis by algorithm family

Now the important part.

⸻

A. Direct scan algorithm analysis

Examples:
	•	max element
	•	running sum
	•	Kadane-like basic scan

What to analyze
	•	what scalar state is maintained?
	•	what summary does each scalar represent?
	•	why is full history unnecessary?
	•	when is reset needed?
	•	when is best updated?

Core insight

The whole processed prefix is compressed into a few scalars.

Typical invariant

After index i, scalar state fully summarizes the best result over the processed prefix.

Typical proof

Induction on processed prefix.

⸻

B. Hashing algorithm analysis

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
	•	longest substring
	•	prefix count problems

What to analyze
	•	what is the key?
	•	what is the payload?
	•	why is the payload enough?
	•	what information from the past matters?
	•	why can past information be summarized by a map/set?

Core insight

The processed prefix can be represented by associative memory.

Typical invariant

The hash structure stores exactly the relevant summary of all previous elements.

Typical proof

When current element is processed, if the needed relation exists in the past, it must already be in the map.

⸻

C. Sliding window algorithm analysis

Examples:
	•	longest unique substring
	•	min window substring

What to analyze
	•	what makes a window valid or invalid?
	•	what state must match the current window exactly?
	•	when does left move?
	•	when does right move?
	•	why does shrinking not lose needed answers?

Core insight

You maintain an active interval instead of recomputing all substrings/subarrays.

Typical invariant

All maintained counts/statistics correspond exactly to [left, right].

Typical proof

Right expansion explores possibilities; left contraction removes only what is safe under validity logic.

⸻

D. Two pointers algorithm analysis

Examples:
	•	sorted two sum
	•	container with most water
	•	remove duplicates

What to analyze
	•	why is moving left/right safe?
	•	what monotonic property allows discarding half or one side?
	•	what region is already processed / impossible?

Core insight

Pointer movement discards impossible cases without enumeration.

Typical invariant

Everything outside the active pointer region is either resolved or impossible.

Typical proof

Monotonic order or inequality reasoning.

⸻

E. Monotonic stack/deque analysis

Examples:
	•	daily temperatures
	•	next greater element
	•	sliding window max

What to analyze
	•	why are popped elements safe to remove forever?
	•	what order does the stack/deque maintain?
	•	what makes a candidate dominated?
	•	what makes a candidate expired?

Core insight

The structure keeps only unresolved, still-useful candidates.

Typical invariant

Stack/deque remains monotonic and contains only relevant unresolved indices.

Typical proof

If a candidate is dominated now, it can never beat the current one later.

⸻

F. Heap analysis

Examples:
	•	top k
	•	Dijkstra
	•	merge k sorted lists

What to analyze
	•	what priority is used?
	•	why does top represent the next best state?
	•	when are stale entries possible?
	•	what does pushing a state mean semantically?

Core insight

Candidate states are ordered by usefulness, not by arrival time.

Typical invariant

Heap top is always the highest-priority candidate among not-yet-consumed states.

Typical proof

Priority rule + push/pop semantics.

⸻

G. BFS analysis

Examples:
	•	shortest unweighted path
	•	rotting oranges

What to analyze
	•	what is a node/state?
	•	what is a frontier?
	•	when is a node first discovered?
	•	why is first discovery optimal?
	•	how are layers represented?

Core insight

Queue order corresponds to distance layers.

Typical invariant

All nodes previously popped have finalized minimum BFS distance.

Typical proof

Level-order expansion.

⸻

H. DFS / Backtracking analysis

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	word search

What to analyze
	•	what is the branching factor?
	•	what partial state is maintained?
	•	what must be undone?
	•	what is the base case?
	•	what pruning is valid?

Core insight

Search tree exploration with reversible state.

Typical invariant

The mutable path/board/used markers match the current recursion path exactly.

Typical proof

Exhaustive search over valid branches plus correct undo.

⸻

I. DP analysis

Examples:
	•	house robber
	•	coin change
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance

What to analyze
	•	what is the state?
	•	why is the state complete?
	•	what are dependencies?
	•	what fill order guarantees dependencies already solved?
	•	is recurrence exhaustive and non-overlapping?
	•	where is overlapping subproblem reuse?

Core insight

Problem decomposes into subproblems with reusable solved states.

Typical invariant

When computing a state, all required smaller states are already correct.

Typical proof

Induction on state order / recurrence correctness.

⸻

J. Graph relaxation analysis

Examples:
	•	Dijkstra
	•	Bellman-Ford
	•	DAG shortest path

What to analyze
	•	what does relaxation mean?
	•	when is a node finalized?
	•	when can a better path still arrive?
	•	why is current improvement valid?

Core insight

Distances/metadata improve until optimal structure emerges.

Typical invariant

Current metadata is best known so far under processed frontier rules.

Typical proof

Depends on algorithm:
	•	Dijkstra: min frontier finalization
	•	Bellman-Ford: path length bound by edges
	•	DAG DP: topological dependency order

⸻

K. DSU analysis

Examples:
	•	provinces
	•	redundant connection
	•	merge problems

What to analyze
	•	what equivalence classes exist?
	•	what does parent/root mean?
	•	why is union safe?
	•	how does path compression preserve correctness?

Core insight

Connectivity is summarized by representatives instead of explicit graph traversal every time.

Typical invariant

Same component => same representative root.

Typical proof

Union preserves partition correctness.

⸻

7. Analysis of correctness

This deserves its own section.

There are a few major proof styles.

Induction proof

Common in:
	•	scans
	•	DP
	•	prefix methods

Form:
	•	base case correct
	•	assume previous states correct
	•	show next state correct

Exchange argument

Common in:
	•	greedy algorithms

Form:
	•	show any optimal solution can be transformed to use greedy choice without becoming worse

Contradiction

Common in:
	•	graph / greedy / ordering proofs

Form:
	•	assume a better alternative exists
	•	derive contradiction

Exhaustive branch proof

Common in:
	•	backtracking / recursion

Form:
	•	every valid branch explored
	•	invalid branches pruned safely
	•	no valid branch omitted

Monotonicity proof

Common in:
	•	binary search
	•	two pointers
	•	monotone deque/stack

Form:
	•	once a case becomes impossible/dominated, it stays impossible/dominated

⸻

8. Analysis of complexity in depth

Do not just state complexity. Derive it.

Bad analysis

“This is O(n).”

Good analysis
	•	loop runs n times
	•	each lookup is O(1) average
	•	each element inserted once
	•	therefore total O(n)

Great analysis
	•	identify exact event counts
	•	identify amortization
	•	identify worst-case vs average-case
	•	identify hidden structure cost

Example: monotonic stack

Bad:
	•	O(n)

Good:
	•	each element is pushed once and popped at most once
	•	total push count = n
	•	total pop count ≤ n
	•	so total O(n), even though inner while exists

That is real analysis.

⸻

9. Analysis of failure modes

A deep algorithm analysis should also include:

What wrong method looks tempting?

Examples:
	•	sorting Two Sum without preserving indices
	•	DFS for shortest unweighted path instead of BFS
	•	greedy where recurrence is needed
	•	local window logic without exact frequency state
	•	using set instead of count map when multiplicity matters

Why it fails structurally?

Not just “it’s wrong.”

Explain:
	•	destroys identity
	•	loses multiplicity
	•	breaks optimality
	•	misses overlapping states
	•	can revisit stale states
	•	fails on duplicates
	•	invalid discard rule

This is one of the best ways to learn patterns.

⸻

10. Analysis of memory

Algorithm analysis must include memory semantics, not just space complexity.

You ask:
	•	what memory is primary?
	•	what memory is auxiliary?
	•	what memory is persistent?
	•	what memory is temporary?
	•	what memory is reversible?
	•	what does each memory slot mean?

Examples:
	•	map key/payload meaning
	•	stack as unresolved candidate frontier
	•	queue as current BFS frontier
	•	DP cell as solved subproblem
	•	recursion stack as current path
	•	linked list pointers as structure definition

⸻

11. Analysis of deltas

This is your advanced system.

For each pattern, analyze:
	•	delta rhythm
	•	delta count
	•	delta direction
	•	delta reversibility
	•	delta locality
	•	delta type

Example:
Two Sum
	•	rhythm: one lookup + one optional insert per iteration
	•	count: low
	•	direction: grow / overwrite
	•	reversibility: permanent
	•	locality: keyed slot
	•	dominant delta types: lookup-hit, lookup-miss, insert

This tells you how the algorithm behaves internally.

⸻

12. Analysis of control flow

Algorithm analysis should also show execution behavior.

You ask:
	•	is flow linear?
	•	nested?
	•	recursive?
	•	frontier-driven?
	•	branch-heavy?
	•	early exit?
	•	prune-heavy?
	•	backtracking with undo?

This matters because different algorithms feel different when executed.

Examples:
	•	scan: linear flow
	•	sliding window: linear + oscillating inner shrink
	•	monotonic stack: linear with burst pops
	•	BFS: queue frontier loop
	•	backtracking: tree-shaped flow
	•	DP: table fill order
	•	binary search: interval halving flow

⸻

13. Best final framework for algorithm analysis

Use this exact checklist.

Algorithm Analysis Framework

1. Problem target

What exact output is required?

2. Structural form

What kind of object/problem is this really?

3. Brute-force search object

What would the naive method enumerate?

4. Waste

What gets repeated or recomputed?

5. Fast operation

What operation removes the waste?

6. State

What memory/state is maintained?

7. State meaning

What does each part of state represent?

8. Transition

How does state evolve step by step?

9. Invariant

What remains true at all times?

10. Correctness

Why must this algorithm work?

11. Termination

Why must it stop?

12. Complexity

Why is time/space what it is?

13. Failure modes

What tempting wrong methods fail, and why?

14. Pattern family

What general algorithm family does it belong to?

15. Transferability

What other problems share the same structure?

