Indepth about designing of algorithm 



Designing an algorithm is earlier than analyzing it.

Analysis asks:
	•	what does this algorithm do?
	•	why does it work?
	•	how expensive is it?

Design asks:
	•	how do I invent the algorithm in the first place?
	•	how do I choose the right structure before coding?
	•	how do I move from problem statement to method?

So algorithm design is the discipline of turning a raw problem into a correct, efficient process.

⸻

1. What algorithm design really is

Algorithm design is the process of deciding:
	•	what information matters
	•	what can be ignored
	•	what state must be maintained
	•	what operations must be fast
	•	what structure the execution should follow
	•	what proof idea will justify it

A designed algorithm is not just code.

It is a package of:
	•	problem model
	•	state model
	•	transition model
	•	correctness model
	•	cost model

⸻

2. The real stages of algorithm design

A strong design process has these stages.

A. Problem modeling

Convert the surface statement into a structural object.

Ask:
	•	what is the input object really?
	•	what is the output really?
	•	what relation defines success?
	•	what constraints change the approach?

Examples:
	•	“houses” -> array with adjacency restriction
	•	“courses” -> dependency graph
	•	“islands” -> connected components in grid
	•	“two numbers sum to target” -> complement search over indexed sequence

This is the foundation.
Bad modeling produces bad algorithms.

⸻

B. Search-space modeling

Ask what the naive algorithm would do.

Examples:
	•	all pairs
	•	all subarrays
	•	all substrings
	•	all paths
	•	all subsets
	•	all partitions
	•	all assignments

This matters because optimization is always about controlling search.

⸻

C. Waste discovery

This is one of the deepest design steps.

Ask:
	•	what gets repeated?
	•	what is recomputed?
	•	what is scanned again and again?
	•	what choices are explored redundantly?
	•	what information from the past is being forgotten?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum brute force forgets prior values
	•	DP brute force re-solves same subproblems
	•	window brute force re-counts same range
	•	graph brute force revisits states
	•	monotonic problems keep useless candidates

The optimal algorithm is often:

the brute-force method minus repeated waste.

⸻

D. Fast-operation design

Once waste is found, ask:

What operation would remove that waste?

Examples:
	•	repeated membership test -> hash lookup
	•	repeated prefix total -> prefix sum
	•	repeated range max candidate -> monotonic deque
	•	repeated shortest-frontier choice -> heap
	•	repeated state solving -> memo/DP
	•	repeated connectivity query -> DSU

This step often predicts the data structure.

⸻

E. State design

This is the heart of algorithm design.

Ask:
	•	what must be remembered?
	•	what is the smallest sufficient memory?
	•	what summary of the past is enough?
	•	what summary of the current region is enough?
	•	what partial answer state is enough?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum: seen values with indices
	•	sliding window: left/right + freq map
	•	BFS: queue + visited
	•	DP: subproblem table
	•	backtracking: current path + constraints
	•	Dijkstra: heap + distance map

A badly designed state is:
	•	too weak -> cannot solve correctly
	•	too large -> slow / messy / redundant

A great state is:
	•	minimal
	•	sufficient
	•	composable
	•	easy to update

⸻

F. Transition design

After state comes motion.

Ask:
	•	how does one valid state become the next?
	•	what event triggers change?
	•	in what order do updates happen?
	•	what branch conditions matter?
	•	what must happen before what?

Examples:
	•	in Two Sum: compute complement before inserting current value
	•	in sliding window: expand then shrink as needed
	•	in BFS: pop then discover neighbors then enqueue
	•	in backtracking: choose -> recurse -> unchoose
	•	in DP: fill state only after dependencies are available

Good transition design is what makes execution clean.

⸻

G. Invariant design

This is the correctness backbone.

When designing an algorithm, you should actively ask:

What truth should remain true after every step?

Examples:
	•	map contains processed prefix
	•	window state exactly matches current interval
	•	monotonic stack remains monotone and unresolved
	•	deque front is best window candidate
	•	queue contains current frontier
	•	dp state means “best answer for this subproblem”
	•	current recursion path matches chosen decisions

A good invariant:
	•	is precise
	•	is easy to check mentally
	•	explains why state is trustworthy

Design without invariant is fragile.

⸻

H. Termination design

Ask:
	•	what strictly progresses?
	•	what shrinks?
	•	what becomes resolved?
	•	what finite resource is consumed?

Examples:
	•	index increases
	•	interval shrinks
	•	queue empties
	•	recursion reaches base case
	•	candidates are popped and never re-added in same form

This prevents hidden infinite behavior.

⸻

I. Proof-shape design

Before coding, ask what kind of proof will justify the method.

Possible proof types:
	•	induction
	•	contradiction
	•	exchange argument
	•	monotonicity
	•	exhaustive search with pruning
	•	shortest-frontier argument

Design is stronger when the proof idea is visible early.

⸻

3. The 5 major design questions

These are the most important questions in algorithm design.

1. What is the true object?

Array? graph? state space? interval? frontier? search tree?

2. What is the brute-force search object?

Pairs? windows? paths? assignments? subproblems?

3. What is the repeated waste?

Repeated lookup? repeated counting? repeated solving? repeated candidate storage?

4. What is the smallest sufficient state?

What exact memory summarizes what matters?

5. What invariant makes that state trustworthy?

Why can the algorithm rely on it?

If you can answer these 5 well, the design is usually close.

⸻

4. Core principles of algorithm design

Principle 1 — Compress information

A good algorithm does not keep raw history if a summary is enough.

Examples:
	•	prefix sum instead of raw prefix scan
	•	frequency map instead of rescanning substring
	•	DP state instead of recomputing subtree
	•	heap frontier instead of global re-search
	•	DSU representative instead of full connectivity traversal every time

⸻

Principle 2 — Preserve only what matters

Store only information that affects future decisions.

Examples:
	•	next greater element keeps unresolved monotonic frontier
	•	sliding window keeps only active window counts
	•	LRU keeps recency order plus key lookup
	•	binary search keeps only boundaries, not discarded half

⸻

Principle 3 — Choose the right granularity

Design depends on the unit of processing.

Possible units:
	•	element
	•	pair
	•	boundary
	•	node
	•	edge
	•	subproblem state
	•	recursion level
	•	window
	•	candidate frontier entry

Many bad algorithms happen because the wrong unit is processed.

⸻

Principle 4 — Let constraints guide structure

Constraints are design signals.

Examples:
	•	n <= 20 may allow exhaustive search
	•	n <= 10^5 usually forbids quadratic
	•	graph edges sparse -> adjacency list
	•	exact one answer -> early return
	•	sorted input -> binary search / two pointers
	•	duplicates -> need counts not set
	•	original indices matter -> avoid destructive sorting or preserve metadata

Constraints are not afterthoughts.
They are design hints.

⸻

Principle 5 — Design for proof, not just execution

An algorithm should be easy to justify.

A design is stronger if you can naturally say:
	•	why it never misses a valid case
	•	why discarded cases are impossible or dominated
	•	why each update preserves correctness
	•	why termination is guaranteed

⸻

5. Main design strategies

These are the big algorithm-design families.

A. Brute force then optimize

Start with exhaustive search, then remove waste.

Good for:
	•	pair / subarray / substring / path problems
	•	hashing
	•	prefix sums
	•	monotonic structures
	•	DP

⸻

B. Divide and conquer

Split problem into smaller independent or combinable parts.

Good for:
	•	merge sort
	•	quicksort
	•	closest pair
	•	segment-tree-like reasoning
	•	recursive structure problems

Design questions:
	•	how to split?
	•	how to combine?
	•	what is the recurrence?

⸻

C. Greedy design

Make the locally best choice and prove it stays globally safe.

Good for:
	•	interval scheduling
	•	jump game style
	•	Huffman / MST style logic

Design questions:
	•	what is the greedy choice?
	•	why is it safe?
	•	what exchange argument exists?

⸻

D. Dynamic programming design

Define subproblems and reuse them.

Good for:
	•	overlapping subproblems
	•	sequence alignment
	•	optimization over prefixes / states

Design questions:
	•	what is the state?
	•	what is the transition?
	•	what is the base case?
	•	in what order do states fill?

⸻

E. Graph traversal design

Represent problem as nodes and transitions.

Good for:
	•	dependencies
	•	reachability
	•	shortest path
	•	states as graph nodes

Design questions:
	•	what is a node?
	•	what is an edge?
	•	do we need BFS, DFS, Dijkstra, topological order?

⸻

F. Search-tree design

Explore choices recursively.

Good for:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	assignment
	•	constraint search

Design questions:
	•	what choice is made at each level?
	•	what is the base case?
	•	what pruning is valid?
	•	what state must be undone?

⸻

G. State-space compression design

Represent many possibilities compactly.

Good for:
	•	bitmask DP
	•	memoization
	•	compressed history states
	•	automata-like problems

Design questions:
	•	what dimensions matter?
	•	what can be encoded compactly?
	•	what transitions exist between compressed states?

⸻

6. Designing the data structure inside the algorithm

Algorithm design and data-structure design are linked.

Ask:
	•	what operation must be fast?
	•	what structure gives that operation cheaply?
	•	what cost does that structure impose elsewhere?

Examples:
	•	membership / complement lookup -> hash map
	•	min/max frontier -> heap
	•	FIFO frontier -> queue
	•	monotone candidate pruning -> stack/deque
	•	connectivity representative -> DSU
	•	prefix aggregation -> array / Fenwick / segment tree
	•	recency order + lookup -> linked list + hash map

A data structure is chosen because it supports a needed operation pattern.

⸻

7. Designing for execution order

Order matters.

Many algorithms fail if the same state is updated in the wrong sequence.

Examples:
	•	Two Sum must lookup before insert to allow [3,3]
	•	sliding window may need to update right count before validity test
	•	backtracking must unmark on return
	•	DP fill order must respect dependencies
	•	Dijkstra must compare tentative distances before pushing or finalizing

So design must include:
	•	what happens first
	•	what happens second
	•	which updates are logically before branch checks
	•	what must happen after return is impossible

This is execution-order design.

⸻

8. Designing for edge cases

A good algorithm is designed with edge cases, not patched later.

Ask:
	•	empty input?
	•	one element?
	•	minimum valid size?
	•	duplicates?
	•	negative numbers?
	•	zeros?
	•	overflow?
	•	disconnected states?
	•	repeated values?
	•	all equal?
	•	strictly increasing/decreasing?
	•	answer at beginning?
	•	answer at end?
	•	no answer? if allowed?

Edge cases often reveal missing invariant or weak state design.

⸻

9. Designing for complexity

You should design with cost in mind from the start.

Ask:
	•	what is the event count?
	•	can an inner loop still be amortized O(n)?
	•	what grows with input size?
	•	is this worst-case or average-case?
	•	what is the memory bottleneck?

Examples:
	•	monotonic stack has while-loop, but each item pops once
	•	hash map gives average O(1), not worst-case guarantee
	•	BFS on adjacency list is O(V+E)
	•	DP table may be too large if state dimension is poor

Complexity is not added at the end.
It should influence the design itself.

⸻

10. Designing from brute force to optimal

This is the most reusable workflow.

Step 1

Write the brute-force search object.

Step 2

Name the repeated waste.

Step 3

Ask what summary would avoid repeating it.

Step 4

Choose the data structure that supports the needed fast operation.

Step 5

Design the invariant around that summary.

Step 6

Design the transitions that preserve the invariant.

Step 7

Prove correctness.

Step 8

Derive complexity.

This is how many optimal algorithms are invented.

⸻

11. Designing by pattern signals

Certain signals suggest certain designs.

Signal: “find relation with something seen before”

Likely design:
