12. Designing invariants in depth

One of the most advanced skills is designing the invariant itself.

A strong invariant should say:
	•	what the current state means
	•	what region of input it summarizes
	•	what is already finalized
	•	what is still unresolved

Examples:

Two Sum

Before processing index i, the map contains all earlier values and their indices.

Sliding window

The frequency map exactly matches the current window [left, right].

BFS

When a node is dequeued, its recorded distance is minimum.

Monotonic stack

The stack stores unresolved indices in monotonic order.

DP

dp[i] is the best/correct answer for the subproblem ending at or defined by i.

Backtracking

The current path and markers exactly represent the decisions taken on the active recursion branch.

If you can design the invariant, much of the algorithm becomes obvious.

