16. Common failures in algorithm design

1. Designing from code first

Bad approach:
	•	start writing loops without structural model

2. Ignoring brute force

Then you do not know what waste you are removing

3. Overstoring state

Memory becomes messy and hard to reason about

4. Understoring state

Algorithm becomes incorrect

5. No invariant

Then correctness is accidental

6. Wrong unit of processing

Example:
	•	trying to process values when indices matter
	•	trying to process nodes when edges define transition

7. No edge-case design

Algorithm breaks on duplicates, zeros, or boundaries

8. Choosing data structure before operation needs

You must first know what operation must be fast

