11. Example: using the taxonomy on major families

Example A — Two Sum
	•	Objective: Search
	•	Object: Sequence
	•	Search space: All pairs
	•	Identity: Yes, indices matter
	•	Order: Original index identity matters
	•	Contiguity: No
	•	Waste: Repeated partner scan
	•	Fast operation: O(1) membership/complement lookup
	•	State: seen value -> index
	•	Control: Hash-assisted scan
	•	Proof: processed-prefix invariant
	•	Anti-pattern: destructive sort without index preservation

Final formulation

This is really a sequence relation problem about indexed complement lookup under identity preservation, where the goal is to find one valid pair by caching prior values.

⸻

Example B — Number of Islands
	•	Objective: Counting
	•	Object: Grid
	•	Search space: All connected land regions
	•	Identity: Cell identity matters
	•	Order: No
	•	Contiguity: Connectedness matters
	•	Adjacency: 4-neighbor grid adjacency
	•	Waste: Re-discovering same connected land
	•	Fast operation: mark visited once
	•	State: visited/component state
	•	Control: DFS/BFS traversal
	•	Proof: each component explored exactly once

Final formulation

This is really a connected-component counting problem on a grid graph, where the goal is to count how many disjoint land regions exist under grid adjacency.

⸻

Example C — House Robber
	•	Objective: Optimization
	•	Object: Sequence
	•	Search space: all valid non-adjacent selections
	•	Identity: position matters
	•	Order: yes
	•	Contiguity: no, but adjacency restriction matters
	•	Waste: repeated solving of same prefix decisions
	•	Fast operation: reuse best answer for prefix states
	•	State: dp over prefix
	•	Control: dynamic programming
	•	Proof: induction on prefix

Final formulation

This is really a prefix-optimization DP problem over a linear sequence with adjacency exclusion, where the goal is to maximize total value.

