Define what “neighbor” means.

Possible adjacency:
	•	adjacent indices
	•	left/right window boundary
	•	parent-child
	•	graph edge
	•	grid directions
	•	same component representative
	•	next greater unresolved candidate
	•	one-edit transformation neighbor
	•	parser token successor

This is the deep relation layer.

⸻

1.8 Brute-force search-space formulation

Now define what the naive method would enumerate.

Possible brute-force spaces:
	•	all pairs
	•	all triples
	•	all subarrays
	•	all substrings
	•	all subsequences
	•	all subsets
	•	all assignments
	•	all paths
	•	all partitions
	•	all states
	•	all subproblems
	•	all operation sequences over an object

This is critical because optimization begins here.

⸻

1.9 Waste formulation

Ask:

What is repeated in brute force?

Main waste types:
	•	repeated partner lookup
	•	repeated range counting
	•	repeated subproblem solving
	•	repeated candidate comparison
	•	repeated path exploration
	•	repeated connectivity testing
	•	repeated invalid branch exploration
	•	repeated structural mutation from scratch

This is the bridge to design.

⸻

1.10 Fast-operation formulation

Ask:

What fast operation would remove that waste?

Examples:
	•	repeated membership -> hash lookup
	•	repeated prefix total -> prefix sum
	•	repeated best-candidate search -> heap/deque/stack
	•	repeated reachability -> visited/union-find/BFS
	•	repeated subproblem solving -> memo/DP
	•	repeated range aggregate -> segment tree/Fenwick
	•	repeated invalid choice exploration -> pruning / greedy discard

This predicts the design direction.

⸻

1.11 Minimal sufficient state formulation

This is the deepest formulation step.

Ask:

What is the smallest sufficient information that must be remembered so the future can be solved correctly?

State families:
	•	scalar state
	•	prefix summary
	•	window state
	•	frontier state
	•	component state
	•	path state
	•	subproblem state
	•	structural mutation state
	•	constraint state
	•	synchronized object state

If the state is too weak, the algorithm is wrong.
If it is too large, the algorithm is bloated.

⸻

1.12 Final structural sentence

Every question should end formulation with one canonical sentence:

This is really a [problem class] problem about [relation/mechanic] under [restriction], where the goal is to [objective].

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
This is really a sequence relation problem about indexed complement lookup under identity preservation, where the goal is to find one valid pair.
	•	Number of Islands
This is really a connected-component counting problem on a grid graph under 4-direction adjacency, where the goal is to count disjoint land regions.
	•	House Robber
This is really a prefix-optimization problem over a linear sequence under adjacency exclusion, where the goal is to maximize total value.

That is complete formulation.

⸻

Phase 2 — Designing the algorithm

Once the problem is formulated, design begins.

Design means:
	•	choosing the state
	•	choosing the operations
	•	choosing the control pattern
	•	choosing the data structure
	•	choosing the invariant

⸻

2.1 Design from brute force

Good design begins from the naive search object.

Ask:
	•	what would brute force enumerate?
	•	what part of that search is repeated?
	•	what can be cached, compressed, discarded, or ordered?

This gives the first optimization direction.

⸻

2.2 Choose the design family

Most LeetCode algorithms come from these design families:

Direct scan

Use a few scalars

Hash-assisted scan

Use associative memory

Sliding window

Maintain active interval

Two pointers

Move boundaries based on monotonic logic

Monotonic stack/deque

Keep only unresolved undominated candidates

Heap frontier

Always process highest-priority candidate

BFS

Layered expansion

DFS

Depth-first exploration

Backtracking

Choose / recurse / undo

Dynamic programming

Solve reusable subproblem states

Greedy

Take local safe choice

Binary search

Exploit monotonicity

Graph relaxation

Improve metadata over edges/frontier

Union-Find

Merge component representatives

Trie

Store/traverse prefix states

Structural rewiring

Modify links or in-place partitions

Multi-structure synchronization

Design/API problems

Every question should be mapped to one primary design family and maybe one secondary support family.

⸻

2.3 Design the state

The central question:

What must be stored so future work becomes cheap and correct?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum -> seen[value] = index
	•	longest substring -> left/right + freq or last seen
	•	BFS -> queue + visited
	•	DP -> dp state table
	•	backtracking -> current path + used markers
	•	Dijkstra -> heap + distances
	•	LRU -> map + doubly linked list

Design quality depends on state quality.

⸻

2.4 Design the data structure

Choose the structure that supports the needed fast operation.

Examples:
	•	O(1) membership -> hash map / set
	•	minimum frontier -> heap
	•	FIFO wavefront -> queue
	•	dominance filtering -> monotonic deque/stack
	•	component merge -> DSU
	•	prefix tree -> trie
	•	in-place pointer motion -> linked-list pointers / array indices
	•	synchronized recency + lookup -> list + hash map

A data structure is not chosen because it is famous.
It is chosen because it supports the exact required operations.

⸻

2.5 Design the transition order

Execution order matters.

Ask:
	•	what must happen first?
	•	what must be checked before insertion?
	•	what must be undone after recursion?
	•	what dependencies must already exist before filling this state?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum must query before insert for [3,3]
	•	backtracking must unmark when unwinding
	•	DP fill order must respect dependencies
	•	BFS must mark at discovery time if using standard shortest-path visitation logic
	•	Dijkstra must relax before pushing updated states or with known stale-state handling

This is the execution-engine design.

⸻

2.6 Design the invariant

This is the correctness backbone.

Ask:

What truth remains true after every step?

Examples:
	•	map contains processed prefix summary
	•	window state exactly matches [left, right]
	•	stack is monotone and unresolved
	•	queue is the current BFS frontier
	•	dp[i] is the correct best answer for that subproblem
	•	current path matches recursion choices
	•	heap top is best-priority candidate among active frontier states
	•	linked structure remains well-formed after rewiring

A strong invariant turns design into something provable.

⸻

2.7 Design termination

Ask:
	•	what strictly progresses?
	•	what shrinks?
	•	what gets finalized?
	•	what finite search branches are exhausted?

Examples:
	•	index moves right
	•	search interval shrinks
	•	queue empties
	•	recursion reaches base case
	•	unresolved candidates pop and do not return in the same form

⸻

2.8 Design edge-case behavior

Good design includes edge cases early.

Check:
	•	empty
	•	minimum size
	•	duplicates
	•	negatives
	•	zeros
	•	equal values
	•	all increasing/decreasing
	•	answer at start
	•	answer at end
	•	disconnected graph
	•	cycles
	•	overflow risk
	•	one-node / one-row / one-column
	•	repeated keys / collisions of meaning

⸻

2.9 Design proof shape

Before coding, ask what proof family fits.

Possible proof styles:
	•	induction on prefix/state
	•	contradiction
	•	exchange argument
	•	exhaustive search coverage
	•	monotonicity
	•	frontier-optimality
	•	structural invariant preservation

This matters because a design that has no natural proof is usually weak.

⸻

Phase 3 — Analyzing the algorithm

After design comes analysis.

Analysis asks:
	•	what exactly is happening?
	•	why does it work?
	•	what does it cost?
	•	what memory/control behavior does it have?
	•	what are the failure modes?

⸻

3.1 Structural analysis

State:
	•	true object
	•	true relation
	•	objective type
	•	search space

This ties back to formulation.

⸻

3.2 State analysis

Explain:
	•	what each state field means
	•	why it is sufficient
	•	why it is not too much
	•	how it summarizes past/current/future-relevant information

⸻

3.3 Transition analysis

Explain step-by-step:
	•	what gets read
	•	what gets written
	•	what branch is taken
	•	what order is used
	•	how invariant is preserved

This is where micro-step code sync comes from.

⸻

3.4 Invariant analysis

For every major family, articulate the invariant clearly.

Examples:
	•	hashing: map summarizes relevant processed prefix
	•	sliding window: freq map matches exact active window
	•	monotonic stack: unresolved candidates stay monotone
	•	BFS: dequeued nodes have finalized layer distance
	•	DP: dependencies already solved
	•	backtracking: state matches current branch exactly
	•	LRU: map/list stay synchronized

⸻

3.5 Correctness analysis

Explain:
	•	why valid answers are never missed
	•	why discarded candidates are safe to discard
	•	why local updates remain globally valid
	•	why the first/last/best/earliest discovered thing is correct

Use the right proof style:
	•	induction
	•	exchange
	•	contradiction
	•	exhaustive branch proof
	•	monotonicity
	•	structural preservation

⸻

3.6 Termination analysis

Prove:
	•	loop ends
	•	recursion bottoms out
	•	queue empties
	•	search interval shrinks
	•	branch tree is finite

⸻

3.7 Complexity analysis

Derive, do not guess.

Explain:
	•	event count
	•	operation cost
	•	amortization if relevant
	•	dominant memory structures

Examples:
	•	monotonic stack: each element pushed once, popped at most once
	•	BFS: O(V+E)
	•	Dijkstra: depends on heap and edges
	•	DP: table size times transition cost
	•	hashing: average-case lookup/update

⸻

3.8 Memory analysis

Do more than O-space.

Explain:
	•	primary memory structure
	•	auxiliary structures
	•	persistent vs temporary memory
	•	reversible vs permanent state
	•	what each memory slot semantically represents

⸻

3.9 Delta analysis

For your framework, every algorithm should have delta analysis:
	•	delta rhythm
	•	delta count
	•	delta direction
	•	delta reversibility
	•	delta locality
	•	dominant delta types

Examples:
	•	hash scan -> lookup miss/hit + insert/update
	•	sliding window -> expand/shrink + freq deltas
	•	monotonic deque -> dominated pops + expiry + push
	•	BFS -> enqueue/dequeue + mark visited
	•	backtracking -> choose/unchoose + place/remove
	•	DP -> fill/improve cells
	•	design object -> sync-update / evict / promote / detach / attach

⸻

3.10 Failure-mode analysis

State what tempting wrong method fails, and why.

Examples:
	•	sorting Two Sum destroys identity unless metadata preserved
	•	DFS is not shortest-path proof for unweighted shortest path
	•	set instead of count map loses multiplicity
	•	greedy where recurrence is required breaks global optimality
	•	forgetting undo breaks backtracking
	•	wrong DP fill order breaks dependency correctness

This is essential for pattern discrimination.

⸻

Phase 4 — Extending the problem

Extension is the most advanced phase.

This is where one problem becomes a family.

⸻

4.1 Constraint extension

Change limits:
	•	larger n
	•	stricter memory
	•	streaming input
	•	distributed input
	•	online queries
	•	dynamic updates

This changes the design.

⸻

4.2 Output extension

Change what must be returned:
	•	one answer -> all answers
	•	best value -> actual path/solution reconstruction
	•	boolean -> count
	•	count -> enumerate

This often changes algorithm family.

⸻

4.3 Structure extension

Change the object:
	•	array -> circular array
	•	string -> stream
	•	grid -> weighted grid
	•	tree -> graph
	•	static -> dynamic updates
	•	exact value -> range of values

⸻

4.4 Adversarial extension

Make edge cases central:
	•	duplicates everywhere
	•	negatives mixed with positives
	•	overflow-risk values
	•	cycles
	•	disconnected components
	•	repeated identical intervals
	•	all equal characters

⸻

4.5 Interview extension

FAANG-style mutations:
	•	infinite stream
	•	multiple queries
	•	immutable input
	•	return lexicographically smallest answer
	•	memory cap
	•	can’t sort
	•	must support updates
	•	weighted version
	•	k-generalization

⸻

4.6 Pattern extension

Ask how the current problem maps to nearby families.

Examples:
	•	Two Sum -> k-Sum -> hash+sort hybrids
	•	Islands -> components -> dynamic connectivity
	•	House Robber -> tree robber -> graph-like DP
	•	substring without repeats -> window with constraints -> min window variants
	•	LRU -> LFU -> generalized cache design

This builds transfer skill.

⸻

