Computational tractability for all 3872 leetcode question 

Computational tractability for all 3872 LeetCode questions should be studied as a master classification system, not as 3872 disconnected complexity notes.

The right question is not:
	•	“what is the time complexity of each?”

The deeper question is:
	•	what makes a problem tractable at LeetCode scale?
	•	what search spaces explode?
	•	what structure saves them?
	•	what constraints force pseudo-polynomial, exponential, or near-linear solutions?

So below is the full tractability framework.

⸻

1. What computational tractability means here

For LeetCode-style problems, computational tractability means:

whether a problem can be solved within contest/interview constraints using a feasible amount of time and memory.

That depends on 4 things:

A. Input size

How large can the input be?

B. Search-space size

How many raw candidates exist?

C. Structural compressibility

Can the search be reduced using state, ordering, recurrence, or invariants?

D. Required output size

Does the problem ask for one answer, count, optimum, or all answers?

A problem can be mathematically simple but computationally intractable if the search space is huge.
A problem can be combinatorial but still tractable if it has:
	•	pruning
	•	DP reuse
	•	monotonicity
	•	graph frontier structure
	•	small parameter size

⸻

2. The master tractability equation

For all LeetCode questions, tractability is governed by:

Raw Search Space

What naive enumeration would do.

Compression Mechanism

What structure lets you avoid full enumeration.

Effective State Count

How many distinct meaningful states remain after compression.

Transition Cost

How expensive it is to move between states.

So the effective complexity is usually:

tractable if
	•	state count is manageable
	•	transition cost is manageable
	•	output size is manageable

⸻

3. The main tractability classes

For the full LeetCode universe, questions fall into these tractability classes.

⸻

Class T1 — Constant / logarithmic / near-constant tractable

Typical complexity:
	•	O(1)
	•	O(log n)

Examples:
	•	direct math
	•	bit hacks
	•	binary search lookup
	•	simple design operations

Characteristics
	•	no combinatorial explosion
	•	tiny state
	•	strong structural monotonicity or formula

Common sources
	•	arithmetic identities
	•	direct pointer manipulation
	•	exact data-structure ops
	•	balanced search logic

LeetCode role

These are highly tractable.

⸻

Class T2 — Linear tractable

Typical complexity:
	•	O(n)
	•	O(V+E)

Examples:
	•	single pass
	•	hashing
	•	BFS/DFS
	•	monotonic stack/deque
	•	two pointers
	•	topological traversal

Characteristics
	•	each input unit processed constant number of times
	•	no repeated global rescans
	•	memory usually O(n) or O(V)

This is the core “Beat LeetCode” zone

A large portion of practical interview problems are tractable because they compress naive enumeration into linear or near-linear processing.

⸻

Class T3 — N log N tractable

Typical complexity:
	•	O(n log n)
	•	O((V+E) log V)

Examples:
	•	sorting
	•	heap-based frontier
	•	Dijkstra
	•	merge-based logic
	•	interval scheduling after sort

Characteristics
	•	one expensive ordering or priority step
	•	still strongly feasible for common constraints

This is usually fully tractable for n ~ 10^5.

⸻

Class T4 — Quadratic tractable only for medium constraints

Typical complexity:
	•	O(n²)

Examples:
	•	DP on pairs
	•	all-pairs scans for n <= 2000
	•	matrix DP
	•	string alignment problems

Characteristics
	•	tractable only when n is modest
	•	common in DP where n <= 1000 or 2000

This class is conditionally tractable.

⸻

Class T5 — Cubic or higher polynomial, only tractable for small n

Typical complexity:
	•	O(n³)
	•	O(n^4)

Examples:
	•	interval DP
	•	Floyd-Warshall
	•	some parsing DP
	•	naive multi-index transitions

Characteristics
	•	feasible only for small constraints
	•	often optimized with pruning or better formulation

This class is tractable only under strict bounds.

⸻

Class T6 — Pseudo-polynomial tractable

Typical complexity:
	•	O(n * sum)
	•	O(n * target)
	•	O(capacity * items)

Examples:
	•	subset sum DP
	•	knapsack
	•	partition by target sum
	•	coin change style target DP

Characteristics

Complexity depends on numeric value magnitude, not just input length.

So:
	•	polynomial in target/capacity
	•	not polynomial in bit-length of the numeric values

Practical meaning

Often tractable on LeetCode because:
	•	target is bounded tightly
	•	values are small enough

This is a very important class.

⸻

Class T7 — Exponential but tractable under small n

Typical complexity:
	•	O(2^n)
	•	O(n!)
	•	O(3^n)

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	brute-force backtracking
	•	bitmask DP
	•	branch and bound
	•	meet-in-the-middle variants

Characteristics

In general these are intractable for large n, but LeetCode often makes them tractable by using:
	•	n <= 15
	•	n <= 20
	•	n <= 25
	•	aggressive pruning
	•	memoization
	•	bitmask compression

This is “parameter-bounded tractability.”

⸻

Class T8 — Output-sensitive tractable

Complexity depends on output size.

Examples:
	•	generate all subsets
	•	all permutations
	•	all valid parentheses
	•	all combinations

Characteristics

Even optimal algorithms may be exponential because output itself is exponential.

This is still tractable if:
	•	output size is small enough
	•	the problem explicitly expects exponential output

This is not a failure of the algorithm; it is a property of the required output.

⸻

4. The true cause of intractability

For LeetCode problems, intractability usually comes from one of these sources:

I1. Combinatorial candidate explosion

Examples:
	•	all subsets
	•	all permutations
	•	all paths
	•	all partitions
	•	all assignments

I2. Overlapping subproblem explosion

Examples:
	•	naive recursion for Fibonacci/coin change/LCS
	•	same state solved repeatedly

I3. Dense relational explosion

Examples:
	•	all pairs
	•	all intervals
	•	all substring checks
	•	all graph path comparisons

I4. Numeric parameter explosion

Examples:
	•	target sum huge
	•	knapsack capacity huge
	•	DP over large values

I5. State-space explosion

Examples:
	•	puzzle states
	•	bitmask states
	•	graph over configurations
	•	search with many dimensions

I6. Output explosion

Examples:
	•	enumerate all valid objects
	•	return all combinations/permutations/partitions

⸻

5. The major tractability-saving mechanisms

All tractable LeetCode solutions use one or more of these mechanisms.

⸻

M1. State compression

Replace raw history with small sufficient state.

Examples:
	•	map of seen values
	•	prefix sum
	•	current best scalar
	•	DP state
	•	current window count

This is one of the biggest tractability levers.

⸻

M2. Reuse of overlapping work

Memoization / DP.

This turns:
	•	exponential repeated recursion
into
	•	polynomial state solving

Examples:
	•	coin change
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance
	•	word break
	•	interval DP

⸻

M3. Monotonicity

Use ordering to discard impossible or dominated regions.

Examples:
	•	binary search
	•	two pointers
	•	monotonic deque
	•	monotonic stack

This transforms huge search into boundary motion.

⸻

M4. Frontier restriction

Explore only active useful candidates.

Examples:
	•	BFS queue
	•	Dijkstra heap
	•	A-like or best-first styles
	•	monotone frontier candidates

This prevents global rescanning.

⸻

M5. Dominance pruning

Delete candidates that can never help again.

Examples:
	•	monotonic stack/deque
	•	branch-and-bound pruning
	•	DP state minimization
	•	skyline-like filters

⸻

M6. Structural decomposition

Split the problem into smaller independent or semi-independent pieces.

Examples:
	•	divide and conquer
	•	tree recursion
	•	graph components
	•	interval splits

⸻

M7. Small-parameter tractability

Even exponential methods become feasible if the hard dimension is tiny.

Examples:
	•	bitmask DP for n <= 15..20
	•	backtracking on short strings
	•	state compression over few features
	•	meet-in-the-middle on n ~ 40

This is huge across LeetCode.

⸻

M8. Output sensitivity acceptance

For enumeration problems, exponential time is acceptable if the output is exponential.

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	combination sum outputs

⸻

6. Tractability by major problem family

Now the practical part.

⸻

A. Sequence / array relation problems

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
	•	max subarray
	•	remove duplicates
	•	stock
	•	jump game

Raw brute force

Often:
	•	all pairs
	•	all subarrays
	•	all decisions over positions

Why tractable

Because arrays often permit:
	•	prefix summaries
	•	pointer order
	•	monotonicity
	•	local-to-global recurrence
	•	hash compression

Typical tractable complexity
	•	O(n)
	•	O(n log n)
	•	O(n²) only for medium constraints

Main saving mechanisms
	•	hashing
	•	sliding window
	•	two pointers
	•	greedy scan
	•	DP

⸻

B. String problems

Examples:
	•	anagrams
	•	substrings
	•	pattern matching
	•	parsing
	•	edit distance

Raw brute force
	•	all substrings
	•	all subsequences
	•	all partitions
	•	all parser branches

Why tractable

Strings often have:
	•	contiguous structure
	•	finite alphabet
	•	prefix/state-machine structure
	•	strong DP recurrence

Typical tractable complexity
	•	O(n)
	•	O(n²)
	•	O(nm)

Hard edge

Subsequence and regex-like matching can quickly become DP-heavy.

⸻

C. Interval problems

Examples:
	•	merge intervals
	•	meeting rooms
	•	non-overlapping intervals

Raw brute force
	•	compare many pairs / subset selections

Why tractable

Intervals have ordered endpoints, which gives:
	•	sortability
	•	sweep-line behavior
	•	greedy order structure

Typical tractable complexity
	•	O(n log n)
	•	O(n)

Intervals are one of the most structurally tractable families.

⸻

D. Grid / graph traversal problems

Examples:
	•	islands
	•	rotting oranges
	•	shortest path
	•	course schedule

Raw brute force
	•	all traversals / all paths / repeated component rediscovery

Why tractable

Graphs and grids become tractable when:
	•	visited state prevents revisits
	•	BFS/DFS explores each node/edge a bounded number of times
	•	topological ordering resolves dependencies
	•	frontier structures restrict search

Typical tractable complexity
	•	O(V+E)
	•	O((V+E) log V) for weighted shortest path

Hard edge

All-path enumeration is usually not tractable unless graph is tiny or DAG-constrained.

⸻

E. Dynamic programming problems

Examples:
	•	robber
	•	coin change
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance
	•	unique paths

Raw brute force
	•	exponential branch search
	•	repeated state solving

Why tractable

Subproblem overlap lets us compress exponential recursion into polynomial state count.

Typical tractability depends on:
	•	number of states
	•	transition cost per state

Typical classes
	•	O(n)
	•	O(n²)
	•	O(nm)
	•	pseudo-polynomial O(n * target)

Hard edge

Bad state design causes explosion.

⸻

F. Backtracking / combinatorial search problems

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	N-Queens
	•	combination sum
	•	word search

Raw brute force
	•	exponential / factorial

Why sometimes tractable

Because LeetCode usually limits:
	•	n
	•	board size
	•	target depth
	•	branching
and allows:
	•	pruning
	•	memoization
	•	symmetry cuts

Typical tractable regime
	•	small n
	•	strong pruning
	•	output-sensitive tasks

These are rarely polynomial in general, but often interview-tractable.

⸻

G. Heap / priority problems

Examples:
	•	top K
	•	kth largest
	•	merge k sorted lists
	•	Dijkstra

Why tractable

Heap maintains only the frontier/best candidates rather than all candidates.

Typical tractable complexity
	•	O(n log k)
	•	O((V+E) log V)
	•	O(n log n)

⸻

H. Design problems

Examples:
	•	LRU
	•	LFU
	•	Min Stack

Why tractable

They are not large search problems. They are invariant-maintenance problems.

Main tractability factor

Can each API operation maintain synchronized structures in O(1) or O(log n)?

Typical complexity target
	•	O(1)
	•	amortized O(1)
	•	O(log n)

⸻

7. The parameterized tractability view

For all 3872, the best deep lens is:

many hard-looking problems are tractable because the hard parameter is small.

Common small parameters:
	•	subset size n <= 15..20
	•	target sum small
	•	alphabet small
	•	tree depth small
	•	state dimensions bounded
	•	number of transactions k small
	•	number of colors/letters/features small

This is why LeetCode contains many problems that are:
	•	theoretically exponential in general
	•	but practically tractable under the given bounds

This is fixed-parameter style thinking, even if the problem is not phrased that way.

⸻

8. Pseudo-polynomial tractability in the LeetCode universe

This deserves special attention.

A lot of LeetCode DP is not polynomial in the strict theoretical sense.

Examples:
	•	knapsack
	•	subset sum
	•	target sum
	•	coin change by amount

Complexity may be:
	•	O(n * target)

This is tractable only because:
	•	target is small enough
	•	values are bounded

So for all 3872, you should mark a separate tractability bucket:

PT — Pseudo-polynomial tractable

Polynomial in numeric magnitude, not in encoded input length.

This is a huge family.

⸻

9. Output-size tractability

Some LeetCode questions ask for all solutions.

Then the lower bound is output size itself.

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	combinations
	•	restore IP addresses
	•	palindrome partitions

These are tractable only in the sense that:
	•	you cannot beat the size of the output
	•	exponential runtime may still be optimal

So classify these as:

OT — Output-sensitive tractable

Runtime is acceptable because output is inherently large.

⸻

