All about order of growth and time in all leetcode question 


To cover all LeetCode questions, “order of growth and time” should be treated as a universal framework, not as 3872 isolated Big-O labels.

Because the real task is:
	•	understand how runtime grows
	•	understand why it grows
	•	understand what structural event is being counted
	•	understand which patterns produce which growth laws
	•	understand when a growth rate is acceptable under LeetCode constraints

So below is the full system.

⸻

1. What “order of growth” really means

Order of growth describes:

how the runtime or memory increases as input size increases.

It ignores:
	•	tiny constants
	•	machine speed
	•	syntax differences
	•	language overhead details

and focuses on:
	•	dominant growth behavior

Examples:
	•	O(1)
	•	O(log n)
	•	O(n)
	•	O(n log n)
	•	O(n²)
	•	O(2^n)

This is not just notation.
It is a statement about how expensive the algorithm becomes as scale increases.

⸻

2. What time complexity really measures

Time complexity is not “how many seconds”.

It is:

how many primitive computational events happen as a function of input size.

Those events may be:
	•	comparisons
	•	pointer moves
	•	hash lookups
	•	inserts
	•	pops
	•	recursive calls
	•	DP state fills
	•	edge traversals
	•	heap operations

So for all LeetCode questions, runtime analysis should always ask:

What is the counted event?

Not just “it is O(n).”

But:
	•	one loop iteration
	•	one stack push/pop
	•	one edge relaxation
	•	one state transition
	•	one subproblem fill
	•	one branch expansion

That is the deepest view.

⸻

3. The master equation of runtime

For almost every LeetCode problem:

Time complexity =

number of meaningful states/events
×
cost per state/event

This is the universal formula.

Examples:

Direct scan
	•	events = n elements
	•	cost per event = O(1)
	•	total = O(n)

Binary search
	•	events = number of interval halvings
	•	cost per event = O(1)
	•	total = O(log n)

DP
	•	events = number of subproblem states
	•	cost per event = transition cost
	•	total = O(states × transition_cost)

BFS
	•	events = vertices + edges processed
	•	cost per event = O(1)
	•	total = O(V + E)

Dijkstra
	•	events = relaxations and heap operations
	•	cost per event = O(log V)
	•	total = O((V + E) log V)

This is the universal lens for all questions.

⸻

4. Order of growth classes across all LeetCode

These are the major runtime growth classes.

⸻

G1. Constant growth — O(1)

Runtime does not scale with input size.

Examples:
	•	return a constant
	•	direct formula
	•	fixed number of operations
	•	stack top retrieval
	•	hashmap lookup average
	•	pointer swap
	•	min stack getMin if maintained properly

Meaning

Even if n doubles, runtime stays roughly same.

In LeetCode

Usually appears as:
	•	single operation in design questions
	•	helper step inside larger algorithm
	•	direct math questions

⸻

G2. Logarithmic growth — O(log n)

Runtime grows by repeated halving or balanced tree behavior.

Examples:
	•	binary search
	•	balanced BST operations
	•	heap height traversal
	•	divide problem size by constant factor each step

Meaning

Very slow growth. Extremely scalable.

Typical source

Monotonicity or balanced structure.

⸻

G3. Linear growth — O(n)

Process each unit a constant number of times.

Examples:
	•	single array scan
	•	hash-assisted scan
	•	two pointers
	•	BFS/DFS traversal with visited
	•	monotonic stack/deque amortized
	•	topological traversal

Meaning

Most desirable practical growth class.

Core property

Each element/node/state is touched a bounded number of times.

⸻

G4. Linearithmic growth — O(n log n)

Usually:
	•	sorting
	•	heap-based repeated updates
	•	balanced tree maintenance

Examples:
	•	merge intervals after sort
	•	Dijkstra
	•	top-K with heap
	•	sorting + two pointers

Meaning

Still very tractable for large n.

⸻

G5. Quadratic growth — O(n²)

Often from:
	•	all pairs
	•	2D DP
	•	nested loops over same dimension
	•	matrix-style transitions

Examples:
	•	all-pairs scan
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance
	•	palindrome DP
	•	some interval comparisons

Meaning

Only tractable for moderate n.

⸻

G6. Cubic growth — O(n³)

Often from:
	•	interval DP
	•	Floyd-Warshall
	•	triple nested loops
	•	split-point transitions over 2D states

Meaning

Only tractable for small/medium constraints.

⸻

G7. Polynomial of higher degree — O(n^k)

Comes from:
	•	k nested loops
	•	k-dimensional state interactions
	•	tuple enumeration

Meaning

Quickly becomes impractical unless n is tiny.

⸻

G8. Pseudo-polynomial growth

Examples:
	•	O(n × target)
	•	O(n × sum)
	•	O(capacity × items)

Typical in:
	•	subset sum
	•	knapsack
	•	coin change
	•	target-sum DP

Meaning

Polynomial in numeric magnitude, not in input bit-length.

This is extremely important across LeetCode.

⸻

G9. Exponential growth — O(2^n), O(3^n), …

Comes from:
	•	subsets
	•	branching recursion
	•	bitmask DP
	•	partitioning
	•	choose/not-choose trees

Meaning

Usually only tractable for small n or with pruning/reuse.

⸻

G10. Factorial growth — O(n!)

Comes from:
	•	permutations
	•	full assignment ordering
	•	brute-force arrangement search

Meaning

Only tractable for very tiny n.

⸻

G11. Output-sensitive growth

Runtime must at least match output size.

Examples:
	•	all subsets
	•	all permutations
	•	all combinations
	•	all partitions

Meaning

Exponential runtime can still be optimal because output itself is exponential.

⸻

5. What determines time growth in LeetCode problems

There are a few universal drivers.

⸻

D1. Search-space size

What brute force would enumerate:
	•	pairs
	•	subarrays
	•	paths
	•	subsets
	•	assignments
	•	states
	•	subproblems

This is the most basic driver.

⸻

D2. Redundancy

How much repeated work exists?

Examples:
	•	recomputing the same range sum
	•	resolving the same subproblem many times
	•	revisiting the same node/state
	•	rescanning the same candidates

Good algorithms reduce redundancy.

⸻

D3. State-space size

How many distinct states remain after compression?

Examples:
	•	dp[i] gives n states
	•	dp[i][j] gives n² states
	•	memo(mask, i) gives n·2^n states
	•	graph node count gives V states
	•	visited grid gives r·c states

⸻

D4. Transition cost

How expensive is one step from one state?

Examples:
	•	O(1) scalar update
	•	O(log n) heap update
	•	O(alphabet) scan
	•	O(split points) transition in interval DP

⸻

D5. Structural ordering

Does ordering let us discard huge regions?

Examples:
	•	binary search
	•	two pointers
	•	greedy sorted intervals
	•	monotonic deque

This often changes O(n²) to O(n) or O(n log n).

⸻

D6. Output size

If you must output all valid objects, time cannot be smaller than output size.

⸻

6. Universal way to derive time for any question

Use this method every time.

Step 1 — Identify the processing unit

What is one main event?

Possible units:
	•	element
	•	pair
	•	window shift
	•	node
	•	edge
	•	subproblem state
	•	recursion branch
	•	heap pop
	•	queue push/pop
	•	map operation

⸻

Step 2 — Count how many such events happen

Examples:
	•	one per element -> n
	•	one per pair -> n²
	•	one per edge -> E
	•	one per DP state -> number of states
	•	one per subset -> 2^n

⸻

Step 3 — Find cost per event

Examples:
	•	O(1) update
	•	O(log n) heap push/pop
	•	O(k) transition scan
	•	O(length) trie traversal

⸻

Step 4 — Multiply

Total time = event count × per-event cost

⸻

Step 5 — Reduce by amortization if needed

Example:
monotonic stack has inner while loop, but each item pops once
so total pops ≤ n

This changes apparent nested looping into linear time.

⸻

7. Order of growth by major algorithm family

Now the practical full mapping.

⸻

A. Direct scan family

Examples:
	•	max/min element
	•	running sum
	•	Kadane
	•	move zeros
	•	simple validators

Growth law

Usually O(n)

Why

Each input element is processed once.

Event count

n iterations

Event cost

O(1)

Order of growth

Linear

Common mistake

Thinking extra if-statements change asymptotic growth.
They usually do not.

⸻

B. Hash-assisted scan family

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
	•	frequency counting
	•	longest substring variants
	•	prefix sum count map

Growth law

Usually O(n) average

Why

Each element causes constant expected-time map operations.

Event count

n iterations

Event cost

average O(1) lookup/update

Order of growth

Linear average

Caveat

Hash tables give average O(1), not always strict worst-case O(1)

⸻

C. Sliding window family

Examples:
	•	longest unique substring
	•	minimum window substring
	•	fixed-size window problems

Growth law

Usually O(n)

Why

Left and right pointers each move at most n times.

Event count

At most 2n boundary moves plus auxiliary updates

Event cost

Usually O(1), sometimes O(log σ) depending on structure

Order of growth

Linear or near-linear

Important point

Even if there is a nested while loop, total pointer movement is bounded.

⸻

D. Two-pointers family

Examples:
	•	sorted Two Sum
	•	container with most water
	•	remove duplicates
	•	merge-like scans

Growth law

Usually O(n), sometimes O(n log n) if sorting first

Why

Pointers move monotonically and never retreat.

Event count

At most n pointer advances per pointer

Event cost

O(1)

Order of growth

Linear after ordering

⸻

E. Monotonic stack/deque family

Examples:
	•	daily temperatures
	•	next greater element
	•	sliding window maximum

Growth law

Usually O(n) amortized

Why

Each element is pushed once and popped at most once.

Event count

≤ n pushes + ≤ n pops

Event cost

O(1)

Order of growth

Linear amortized

Common mistake

Misreading the inner while as O(n²)

⸻

F. Heap / priority queue family

Examples:
	•	top K frequent
	•	kth largest
	•	Dijkstra
	•	merge k sorted lists

Growth law

Usually O(n log k), O(n log n), or O((V+E) log V)

Why

Each important event triggers heap push/pop

Event count

depends on number of insertions/extractions/relaxations

Event cost

O(log heap_size)

Order of growth

Linearithmic or graph-priority scale

⸻

G. BFS family

Examples:
	•	islands (if BFS)
	•	shortest path in unweighted graph
	•	rotting oranges
	•	word ladder

Growth law

Usually O(V+E) or O(rc) on grids

Why

Each node is visited once, each edge examined a bounded number of times

Event count

vertices + edges

Event cost

O(1)

Order of growth

Linear in graph size

⸻

H. DFS family

Examples:
	•	components
	•	tree traversal
	•	graph traversal
	•	recursive structural checks

Growth law

Usually O(V+E) or O(n) on trees

Why

Each node/edge processed a bounded number of times

Event count

vertices + edges or nodes only

Event cost

O(1)

Order of growth

Linear in structure size

⸻

I. Backtracking family

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	N-Queens
	•	combination sum

Growth law

Exponential or factorial

Why

Algorithm explores a search tree

Event count

number of nodes in recursion tree

Event cost

depends on copying/path operations/checking constraints

Order of growth
	•	subsets -> O(2^n)
	•	permutations -> O(n!)
	•	often multiplied by output-building cost

Tractability note

Only feasible for small n or strong pruning.

⸻

J. Dynamic programming family

Examples:
	•	House Robber
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance
	•	coin change
	•	unique paths

Growth law

states × transition cost

This is the master formula.

Examples
	•	dp[i] with O(1) transition -> O(n)
	•	dp[i][j] with O(1) transition -> O(n²)
	•	dp[i][j] with O(n) split -> O(n³)
	•	dp[mask][i] -> O(n·2^n)
	•	dp[n][target] -> O(n·target)

Key lesson

DP runtime is driven by:
	•	number of states
	•	cost to fill one state

⸻

K. Binary search family

Examples:
	•	search sorted array
	•	search rotated array
	•	binary search on answer

Growth law

O(log n) if direct position search
O(log A × check_cost) if answer-space search

Why

Search interval shrinks by constant factor each step

Event count

number of halvings

Event cost

O(1) or cost of feasibility check

Order of growth

logarithmic or logarithmic times check

⸻

L. Greedy family

Examples:
	•	merge intervals
	•	activity selection
	•	jump-game style
	•	scheduling

Growth law

Often O(n) or O(n log n)

Why

Usually scan after sort or one pass with local updates

Event count

n after preprocessing

Event cost

O(1)

Order of growth

depends on sorting need

⸻

M. Graph shortest path / relaxation family

Examples:
	•	Dijkstra
	•	Bellman-Ford
	•	Floyd-Warshall

Dijkstra

O((V+E) log V)

Bellman-Ford

O(VE)

Floyd-Warshall

O(V³)

Why

Driven by:
	•	number of relaxations
	•	frontier ordering mechanism
	•	all-pairs closure in dense formulation

This family shows how different formulations of “shortest path” produce very different growth laws.

⸻

N. Union-Find family

Examples:
	•	number of provinces
	•	redundant connection
	•	account merge

Growth law

Nearly O(1) per operation, more precisely inverse Ackermann

Overall

Often O(n α(n)) or O((V+E) α(n))

Practical meaning

Almost linear

⸻

O. Trie family

Examples:
	•	Implement Trie
	•	prefix search
	•	word dictionary
	•	Word Search II support structure

Growth law

Usually proportional to total characters processed

Insert/search

O(length of word/prefix)

Batch complexity

O(total characters)

⸻

P. Design/API family

Examples:
	•	LRU
	•	LFU
	•	Min Stack
	•	Browser History

Growth law

Per operation target matters:
	•	O(1)
	•	amortized O(1)
	•	O(log n)

Why

These are operation-sequence problems, not one-shot batch problems

Analysis style

Focus on:
	•	each API call
	•	average/worst-case per call
	•	synchronization overhead

⸻

8. Pseudo-polynomial time in LeetCode

This is one of the most misunderstood parts.

Examples:
	•	coin change
	•	subset sum
	•	target sum
	•	knapsack

If runtime is O(n × target), that is not polynomial in strict encoded input size.
It is pseudo-polynomial.

Why?
Because target may be large relative to bit-length.

Still, on LeetCode it is often acceptable because:
	•	target is bounded
	•	numbers are small enough

So across all questions, you need a separate bucket:

Pseudo-polynomial growth

Depends on numeric magnitude, not just number of input elements.

⸻

9. Output-sensitive time

Some questions require all answers.

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	palindrome partitions
	•	combinations

Then runtime must at least be proportional to output size.

Example

All subsets:
	•	number of outputs = 2^n
	•	any full generator must take at least O(2^n)

So exponential runtime may still be optimal.

This is critical when discussing “all LeetCode questions”.

⸻

10. Amortized time

Many LeetCode problems are best understood using amortized analysis.

Examples:
	•	monotonic stack
	•	sliding window
	•	deque
	•	some design questions
	•	union-find path compression

Amortized means:

one step may be expensive, but across the full run, average cost per operation stays small.

Example

Stack pops inside while loop:
	•	looks nested
	•	but each element pops once
	•	so total work stays O(n)

This is extremely important across the full problem set.

⸻

11. Best way to think about time in all LeetCode questions

For every problem, ask:

1. What would brute force count?

pairs? windows? paths? subsets? states?

2. What is the real event in the optimized algorithm?

lookup? push/pop? relax? fill state?

3. How many times can that event happen?

once per element? once per edge? once per state?

4. What is the cost of one event?

O(1)? O(log n)? O(k)?

5. Is amortization involved?

Can repeated inner-loop work still total linear?

6. Is output size itself large?

If yes, runtime lower bound rises.

That is the universal runtime framework.

⸻

