All about implementation 




Implementation is the phase where the designed algorithm becomes an exact executable procedure.

For your system, implementation is not just “write code.”

It means:
	•	translate structure into code
	•	preserve invariant in code
	•	preserve execution order
	•	preserve edge-case correctness
	•	preserve complexity target
	•	preserve memory behavior
	•	preserve readability and debuggability

So if:
	•	formulation = what the problem really is
	•	design = what algorithm should solve it
	•	analysis = why it works and what it costs

then:
	•	implementation = how to realize that algorithm correctly in code

⸻

1. What implementation really means

Implementation is the mapping from:
	•	problem model
	•	algorithm state
	•	transitions
	•	invariants
	•	proof idea

into:
	•	variables
	•	loops
	•	recursion
	•	data structures
	•	function boundaries
	•	update order
	•	return behavior

A correct algorithm can still fail in implementation because of:
	•	wrong variable meaning
	•	wrong update order
	•	missing edge handling
	•	off-by-one
	•	stale state
	•	incorrect mutation
	•	broken invariant

So implementation is the discipline of preserving the algorithm in code form.

⸻

2. The 7 layers of implementation

Every LeetCode implementation should be built through these layers.

Layer 1 — State implementation

Turn abstract state into concrete variables and structures.

Examples:
	•	seen[value] = index -> unordered_map<int, int> seen
	•	current window -> left, right, freq
	•	BFS frontier -> queue<int>
	•	DP state -> vector<int> dp
	•	recursion path -> vector<int> path, vector<bool> used
	•	DSU -> parent, rank, size

Question:
	•	what exact code structure represents each conceptual state?

⸻

Layer 2 — Transition implementation

Turn transitions into exact update steps.

Examples:
	•	compute complement
	•	check map
	•	insert current value
	•	expand window
	•	shrink window
	•	pop dominated stack elements
	•	fill dp cell
	•	recurse then undo

Question:
	•	what exact line order preserves algorithm semantics?

⸻

Layer 3 — Boundary implementation

Turn abstract ranges into exact indices and limits.

Examples:
	•	for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)
	•	while (left <= right)
	•	if (row < 0 || row >= rows) return
	•	base case for recursion
	•	queue emptiness condition

Question:
	•	where exactly does processing start and stop?

⸻

Layer 4 — Mutation implementation

Turn memory changes into safe code.

Examples:
	•	map insert/update
	•	stack push/pop
	•	linked-list rewiring
	•	backtracking choose/unchoose
	•	DP overwrite vs improve
	•	union-find parent rewrite

Question:
	•	what gets changed?
	•	in what order?
	•	what must be preserved first?

⸻

Layer 5 — Control-flow implementation

Turn algorithm shape into code shape.

Examples:
	•	straight scan
	•	nested loops
	•	while frontier not empty
	•	recursion tree
	•	memoized DFS
	•	iterative simulation

Question:
	•	what construct matches the algorithm best?

⸻

Layer 6 — Error-resistance implementation

Protect correctness from common bugs.

Examples:
	•	no out-of-bounds
	•	no same-index reuse
	•	avoid stale heap entries
	•	avoid double visiting
	•	avoid forgetting undo
	•	avoid overflow
	•	avoid invalid pointer dereference

⸻

Layer 7 — Clarity implementation

Write code that preserves reasoning.

This means:
	•	precise names
	•	obvious state meaning
	•	small helper functions when useful
	•	comments only where they add meaning
	•	avoid tangled mutation order

⸻

3. The master implementation pipeline

Use this exact implementation pipeline for any problem.

Step 1 — Write the state map

Before writing code, write:
	•	abstract state
	•	concrete code representation

Example:
	•	“processed prefix cache” -> unordered_map<int, int> seen
	•	“current best ending here” -> int current_best
	•	“window counts” -> unordered_map<char, int> freq
	•	“visited nodes” -> vector<bool> visited

This is the bridge from design to code.

⸻

Step 2 — Write the transition list

Before writing loops, write the transitions in order.

Example for Two Sum:
	1.	read current value
	2.	compute needed complement
	3.	check whether complement exists
	4.	if yes, return answer
	5.	otherwise store current value

Implementation becomes easy if transition order is explicit first.

⸻

Step 3 — Choose the code skeleton

Pick the structural code form.

Possible skeletons:
	•	single scan
	•	nested scan
	•	sliding window
	•	while frontier
	•	recursion
	•	memoized recursion
	•	iterative DP fill
	•	sort + scan
	•	API class design

Choose the simplest skeleton that matches the algorithm.

⸻

Step 4 — Lock invariants into code

Ask:
	•	what code line establishes the invariant?
	•	what code lines preserve it?
	•	what line would break it if moved?

Example:
In Two Sum, if insertion happens before lookup, duplicate handling changes.
So the invariant must control implementation order.

⸻

Step 5 — Implement edge cases intentionally

Do not patch later.

Ask:
	•	empty?
	•	one element?
	•	duplicates?
	•	zeros?
	•	negatives?
	•	overflow?
	•	disconnected graph?
	•	repeated chars?
	•	minimal valid input?
	•	all equal?

⸻

Step 6 — Verify micro-order

This is crucial.

Many wrong implementations are not logically wrong, but ordered wrongly.

Examples:
	•	query before insert
	•	shrink after expand
	•	mark visited before enqueue vs after dequeue depending on style
	•	save next pointer before rewiring linked list
	•	pop stale heap top before using it
	•	undo after recursive call

Implementation is often won or lost here.

⸻

Step 7 — Dry run the code shape

Before finalizing, trace:
	•	one standard case
	•	one tricky case
	•	one edge case

That catches most implementation bugs.

⸻

4. Implementation dimensions

Implementation has multiple dimensions.

A. Representational implementation

How ideas become variables and structures.

B. Operational implementation

How transitions become code steps.

C. Boundary implementation

How ranges/base cases are encoded.

D. Mutation implementation

How memory is changed safely.

E. Flow implementation

How control shape is encoded.

F. Safety implementation

How bugs are prevented.

G. Readability implementation

How code stays understandable.

A strong implementation respects all of them.

⸻

5. State implementation in depth

This is the first real coding step.

For every algorithm, ask:

What abstract state exists?

Examples:
	•	prefix cache
	•	current best
	•	active window
	•	frontier
	•	visited
	•	dp table
	•	path state
	•	parent links

What concrete code type matches it?

Examples:
	•	int
	•	long long
	•	vector<int>
	•	unordered_map<int, int>
	•	unordered_set<char>
	•	queue<pair<int, int>>
	•	priority_queue<...>
	•	vector<vector<int>>

What does each field mean?

This must be explicit.

Example:
	•	left = start of active window
	•	seen[x] = latest index of value x
	•	dp[i] = best answer for prefix ending at i
	•	parent[x] = representative tree parent of x

If field meaning is fuzzy, implementation becomes bug-prone.

⸻

6. Transition implementation in depth

Every algorithm is transitions.

Implementation quality depends on how precisely they are encoded.

Example transition types
	•	read current item
	•	derive query key
	•	branch on hit/miss
	•	update scalar
	•	push frontier
	•	pop stale state
	•	relax edge
	•	fill dp cell
	•	choose candidate
	•	undo candidate

For each transition, ask:
	•	what is read first?
	•	what is computed next?
	•	what is written last?
	•	what branch exits early?

This is the basis of micro-step execution.

⸻

7. Boundary implementation in depth

A huge number of bugs are boundary bugs.

You must implement:

Loop boundaries
	•	< n vs <= n-1
	•	left < right vs left <= right

Range starts
	•	j = i + 1
	•	right = n - 1
	•	dp[0] initialization

Base cases
	•	empty node
	•	index beyond end
	•	target exhausted
	•	recursion depth complete

Grid bounds
	•	0 <= r < rows
	•	0 <= c < cols

Graph / tree null checks
	•	if (!node) return ...

Boundary implementation is not secondary. It is core.

⸻

8. Mutation implementation in depth

Some patterns are mostly about mutation correctness.

Common mutation types
	•	assign
	•	overwrite
	•	increment
	•	decrement
	•	insert
	•	erase
	•	push
	•	pop
	•	enqueue
	•	dequeue
	•	relax
	•	attach
	•	detach
	•	rewire
	•	choose
	•	unchoose
	•	mark
	•	unmark

When implementing mutation, ask:

What must be preserved before mutation?

Examples:
	•	linked list next
	•	old frequency count
	•	parent representative
	•	stack top relationship

Is mutation permanent or reversible?
	•	map insert in Two Sum -> permanent
	•	path append in backtracking -> reversible
	•	BFS visited -> permanent
	•	window frequency -> reversible by shrink
	•	pointer rewiring -> structural permanent

Does one mutation require synchronized mutations?

Example:
LRU:
	•	map
	•	doubly linked list
	•	maybe size counter

All must stay consistent.

⸻

9. Control-flow implementation in depth

Choose the right code form.

Single pass

For:
	•	scans
	•	hashing
	•	prefix

Nested loops

For:
	•	brute force pairs
	•	matrix fill
	•	2D DP

While with frontier

For:
	•	BFS
	•	heap-based search
	•	deque maintenance

Recursion

For:
	•	trees
	•	DFS
	•	divide and conquer
	•	backtracking

Memoized recursion

For:
	•	top-down DP
	•	state search with overlap

Iterative DP

For:
	•	explicit state tables
	•	prefix/subsequence recurrences

Sort + scan

For:
	•	interval / greedy / ordering problems

Implementation should mirror the natural algorithm shape.

⸻

10. Implementation by major algorithm family

Now the important part.

⸻

A. Direct scan implementation

Examples:
	•	max subarray
	•	running sum
	•	max/min
	•	simple greedy scan

Main implementation objects
	•	array/string
	•	index
	•	scalar state

Main coding tasks
	•	initialize scalars correctly
	•	update in correct order
	•	compare current vs best
	•	handle first element carefully

Common bugs
