State meaning must be crystal clear.

⸻

C. Sliding window implementation

Examples:
	•	unique substring
	•	min window
	•	at-most-k distinct

Main implementation objects
	•	left, right
	•	frequency structure
	•	validity tracker
	•	answer range

Main coding tasks
	•	expand right
	•	update state
	•	shrink while needed
	•	update answer at the right moment

Common bugs
	•	shrink condition wrong
	•	update answer before state is valid
	•	frequency decrement order wrong
	•	forgetting to remove/decrement when left moves

Implementation style

Very order-sensitive.

⸻

D. Two-pointers implementation

Examples:
	•	sorted Two Sum
	•	merge scans
	•	partitioning
	•	remove duplicates

Main implementation objects
	•	left/right or slow/fast pointers

Main coding tasks
	•	correct pointer initialization
	•	safe movement rule
	•	avoid infinite loop
	•	preserve write pointer meaning

Common bugs
	•	wrong pointer movement
	•	stale value use after overwrite
	•	duplicate skipping mistakes
	•	pointer cross condition bugs

⸻

E. Monotonic stack/deque implementation

Examples:
	•	next greater
	•	daily temperatures
	•	sliding max

Main implementation objects
	•	stack/deque of indices usually

Main coding tasks
	•	decide whether to store values or indices
	•	implement pop condition correctly
	•	write answer on pop if needed
	•	expire stale elements for deque

Common bugs
	•	wrong inequality (< vs <=)
	•	storing values when indices are needed
	•	forgetting expiry
	•	output write mismatch

Implementation style

Conditions matter more than code size.

⸻

F. Heap implementation

Examples:
	•	top K
	•	kth largest
	•	Dijkstra
	•	merge K lists

Main implementation objects
	•	min-heap / max-heap
	•	comparator
	•	maybe stale-state handling

Main coding tasks
	•	correct priority definition
	•	correct push/pop rules
	•	handle stale entries if needed
	•	bound heap size for top-K

Common bugs
	•	wrong comparator direction
	•	using stale popped states as current truth
	•	forgetting visited/finalized logic where needed

⸻

G. BFS implementation

Examples:
	•	islands
	•	shortest unweighted path
	•	rotting oranges

Main implementation objects
	•	queue
	•	visited
	•	direction list
	•	distance/time/level state

Main coding tasks
	•	initialize starting frontier
	•	mark visited at correct time
	•	process neighbors safely
	•	level-order handling if needed

Common bugs
	•	double enqueue
	•	visited marking too late
	•	boundary check errors
	•	level counting off-by-one

⸻

H. DFS implementation

Examples:
	•	components
	•	tree recursion
	•	graph traversal

Main implementation objects
	•	recursion or explicit stack
	•	visited
	•	node return values if needed

Main coding tasks
	•	base case
	•	visited marking
	•	recurse on neighbors/children
	•	combine child results

Common bugs
	•	forgetting visited
	•	stack overflow on deep recursion
	•	wrong base case
	•	incorrect return aggregation

⸻

I. Backtracking implementation

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	N-Queens
	•	combination sum

Main implementation objects
	•	current path
	•	used/constraint state
	•	recursive depth/index

Main coding tasks
	•	choose
	•	recurse
	•	undo
	•	skip duplicates if needed
	•	collect full solution at base case

Common bugs
	•	forgetting undo
	•	copying too much or too little
	•	duplicate generation
	•	incorrect pruning

Implementation rule

Always make choose and unchoose visually symmetric in code.

⸻

J. DP implementation

Examples:
	•	robber
	•	coin change
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance

Main implementation objects
	•	DP state array/table
	•	base cases
	•	transition loops

Main coding tasks
	•	define state meaning in code comments or mentally
	•	initialize base cases correctly
	•	fill in dependency-respecting order
	•	choose min/max/count/boolean update correctly

Common bugs
	•	wrong base initialization
	•	wrong transition order
	•	mixing “unreachable” with 0
	•	dimension off-by-one
	•	memory optimization breaking dependency order

Implementation rule

If state meaning is not one clear sentence, code will likely be wrong.

⸻

K. Binary search implementation

Examples:
	•	search sorted
	•	answer search

Main implementation objects
	•	left, right, mid
	•	predicate or direct compare

Main coding tasks
	•	choose closed vs half-open interval style
	•	compute mid safely
	•	move correct boundary
	•	know whether searching exact value, first true, last false, lower_bound, upper_bound

Common bugs
	•	infinite loop
	•	boundary update wrong
	•	wrong return value after loop
	•	off-by-one

Implementation rule

Decide interval convention before coding.

⸻

L. Graph relaxation implementation

Examples:
	•	Dijkstra
	•	Bellman-Ford
	•	DAG shortest path

Main implementation objects
	•	adjacency list
	•	distance array
	•	heap or iteration frontier
	•	maybe parent array

Main coding tasks
	•	initialize distances
	•	relax correctly
	•	push improved states
	•	skip stale states if using heap
	•	prevent negative-cycle assumptions from leaking into wrong algorithm

Common bugs
	•	stale heap states
	•	overflow in distance addition
	•	wrong infinity initialization
	•	forgetting directedness

⸻

M. Union-Find implementation

Examples:
	•	provinces
	•	redundant connection
	•	account merge

Main implementation objects
	•	parent
	•	rank or size

Main coding tasks
	•	find with path compression
	•	union by rank/size
	•	only merge roots

Common bugs
	•	unioning non-roots
	•	forgetting path compression return assignment
	•	wrong size/rank update

⸻

N. Trie implementation

Examples:
	•	Implement Trie
	•	dictionary prefix matching

Main implementation objects
	•	trie node
	•	child map/array
	•	terminal flag

Main coding tasks
	•	create nodes lazily
	•	advance per character
	•	mark word end
	•	handle search vs prefix search correctly

Common bugs
	•	not distinguishing prefix from full word
	•	wrong child indexing
	•	forgetting terminal marker

⸻

O. Linked-list implementation

Examples:
	•	reverse list
	•	merge lists
	•	remove nth
	•	reorder list

Main implementation objects
	•	node pointers
	•	temp pointers
	•	dummy nodes often useful

Main coding tasks
	•	preserve next pointer before rewiring
	•	use dummy head when simplifying edge cases
	•	split/reverse/merge safely

Common bugs
	•	lost pointer
	•	cycle creation
	•	null dereference
	•	skipping head edge cases

Implementation rule

When rewiring, preserve reachability before mutation.

⸻

P. Design/API implementation

Examples:
	•	LRU
	•	LFU
	•	Min Stack

Main implementation objects
	•	class state
	•	synchronized structures
	•	helper operations

Main coding tasks
	•	define API invariant
	•	implement each operation as state-preserving mutation
	•	ensure all structures stay synchronized

Common bugs
	•	one structure updates, other doesn’t
	•	size counter mismatch
	•	stale pointer/map entry
	•	eviction rules not fully synchronized

Implementation rule

Each API call should be seen as a mini-transaction on internal state.

⸻

11. Implementation and variable naming

Implementation quality depends heavily on naming.

Bad names:
	•	a, b, temp1, x2

Good names:
	•	left
	•	right
	•	need
	•	current_sum
	•	seen_index_by_value
	•	visited
	•	current_path
	•	best_ending_here
	•	remaining_target

Names should preserve the state meaning from design.

⸻

12. Implementation and helper functions

Use helpers when they preserve logic.

Good helpers:
	•	IsValid(r, c)
	•	RelaxEdge(...)
	•	Backtrack(...)
	•	FindRoot(...)
	•	MergeIntervals(...)
	•	UpdateWindow(...)

Bad helpers:
	•	helpers that hide crucial invariant logic unnecessarily

Rule:
Use helpers to clarify structure, not to bury meaning.

⸻

13. Implementation and edge cases

Every implementation should explicitly think through:
	•	empty input
	•	one item
	•	two items
	•	duplicates
	•	repeated chars
	•	all equal
	•	negatives
	•	zero
	•	overflow
	•	null root
	•	single-node tree/list
	•	disconnected graph
	•	unreachable target
	•	answer at first step
	•	answer at last step

Implementation is not complete until edge behavior is deliberate.

⸻

14. Implementation and micro-step execution

For your system, implementation should also be describable in micro-steps.

Example:
Line:
if (seen.count(need)) return {seen[need], i};

Micro-steps:
	•	read need
	•	query map for need
	•	evaluate branch condition
	•	if hit, read stored index
	•	construct return vector
	•	exit function

This is very useful for:
	•	debugging
	•	dry run visualization
	•	explaining execution order

⸻

15. Implementation and testing

After implementation, test in layers.

Layer 1 — Standard case

Does the core happy path work?

Layer 2 — Edge case

Duplicates, zeros, minimal size, null, boundaries

Layer 3 — Tricky case

Where wrong update order would fail

Layer 4 — Stress-like logic case

Late hit, many repeated states, deep window, dense duplicates

Layer 5 — Adversarial case

Specifically designed to break naive implementation mistakes

Implementation is only trustworthy after this.

⸻

16. The master implementation template

Use this for any LeetCode question.

1. Abstract state

What conceptual memory exists?

2. Concrete state

What exact variables/structures implement it?

3. Transition order

What exact steps happen in what order?

4. Code skeleton

Scan / recursion / BFS / DP / heap / design object

5. Boundary rules

Indices, base cases, loop limits

6. Mutation rules

What gets updated and in what sequence?

7. Invariant preservation

What must stay true after each step?

8. Edge-case handling

What special inputs must be supported?

9. Bug-risk check

Off-by-one, stale state, duplicate handling, overflow, undo, null

10. Dry run

Standard + tricky + edge case

That is the universal implementation framework.

⸻

17. Ultra-compressed version

Implementation means:
	•	encode state correctly
	•	encode transitions in the right order
	•	encode boundaries safely
	•	mutate memory without breaking invariants
	•	preserve edge-case correctness
	•	preserve the intended complexity
	•	make the code reflect the algorithm clearly

⸻

18. Final sentence

Deep implementation is:

the art of translating a correct algorithmic idea into exact code without losing its invariant, complexity, or correctness at the boundaries.

The strongest next step is a pattern-by-pattern implementation guide:
hashing, sliding window, two pointers, monotonic stack, BFS, DFS/backtracking, DP, heap, graph, DSU, trie, linked list, and design questions.


All about caching in all leetcode question 


Caching across all LeetCode questions is one of the deepest universal ideas.

Because many problems become fast only when the algorithm stops recomputing information and starts remembering the right summary.

So “caching” is not just:
	•	hash map
	•	memoization
	•	LRU

It is much broader.

Caching means:

storing previously computed, observed, or maintained information so future work becomes cheaper.

That idea appears across almost the entire LeetCode universe.

⸻

1. What caching really means

A cache is any stored information that helps avoid repeated work.

That repeated work may be:
	•	repeated lookup
	•	repeated counting
	•	repeated subproblem solving
	•	repeated traversal
	•	repeated candidate comparison
	•	repeated structure reconstruction
	•	repeated path exploration
	•	repeated aggregate computation

So in LeetCode, caching is a general optimization principle, not one narrow pattern.

⸻

2. The universal definition of caching

For all LeetCode problems, caching can be defined as:

storing a reusable summary of the past, present, or solved substructure so the future can be processed without recomputing from scratch.

This summary may represent:
	•	past elements
	•	current active interval
	•	solved subproblems
	•	frontier candidates
	•	connectivity state
	•	prefix information
	•	parser state
	•	object/API state
	•	computed metadata like distance, indegree, min/max, etc.

⸻

3. Why caching exists

Caching exists because brute force wastes time by forgetting.

A brute-force algorithm often does this:
	•	sees something useful
	•	does not store it
	•	later needs it again
	•	recomputes it from scratch

Caching fixes that.

So the deep view is:

brute force

recompute

optimized solution

reuse

That reuse is caching.

⸻

4. The master caching equation

Caching is useful when:

recomputation cost > storage cost

If remembering something costs little but saves a lot of future work, cache it.

So every caching decision is really a tradeoff between:
	•	time saved
	•	space spent
	•	update complexity
	•	consistency burden

This is why caching is deeply linked to:
	•	time-space tradeoff
	•	state design
	•	invariant design

⸻

5. The main kinds of caching in LeetCode

There are many caching families.

⸻

C1. Lookup cache

Store previously seen items for fast membership or retrieval.

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
	•	contains duplicate
	•	longest substring without repeating
	•	anagram grouping
	•	prefix frequency maps

Typical structures:
	•	hash map
	•	hash set

What is cached:
	•	value existence
	•	value frequency
	•	last seen index
	•	complement partner info
	•	grouped bucket

Purpose:
	•	avoid repeated search through prior elements

⸻

C2. Prefix cache

Store cumulative information about everything seen so far.

Examples:
	•	prefix sums
	•	subarray sum equals k
	•	running balance/parity
	•	cumulative min/max variants

Typical structures:
	•	scalar running sum
	•	prefix array
	•	prefix hash map

What is cached:
	•	cumulative total
	•	cumulative count
	•	cumulative parity
	•	cumulative difference

Purpose:
	•	avoid recomputing aggregate over a prefix/range

⸻

C3. Window cache

Store exact information about the active interval.

Examples:
	•	longest unique substring
	•	minimum window substring
	•	at most K distinct
	•	sliding window frequency problems

Typical structures:
	•	frequency map
	•	counts
	•	distinct-value counter
	•	deficit/surplus stats

What is cached:
	•	exact summary of current window

Purpose:
	•	avoid rescanning the whole window after each move

Important:
This is still caching even though the cache changes dynamically.

⸻

C4. Memoization cache

Store solved subproblems.

Examples:
	•	Fibonacci-type DP
	•	coin change
	•	word break
	•	edit distance
	•	DFS with repeated state
	•	grid path DP
	•	bitmask DP

Typical structures:
	•	map from state -> answer
	•	DP table
	•	recursion memo

What is cached:
	•	result of a subproblem state

Purpose:
	•	avoid solving the same state repeatedly

This is one of the most important caching families.

⸻

C5. DP table cache

This is memoization made systematic/iterative.

Examples:
	•	House Robber
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance
	•	knapsack
	•	interval DP
	•	tree DP tables

Typical structures:
	•	1D array
	•	2D matrix
	•	3D table
	•	compressed rolling array

What is cached:
	•	fully solved subproblem states

Purpose:
	•	structured reuse instead of top-down cache lookup

Memoization and DP are both caching, just in different implementation styles.

⸻

C6. Frontier cache

Store currently relevant candidates, not all history.

Examples:
	•	BFS queue
	•	Dijkstra heap
	•	monotonic stack
	•	monotonic deque
	•	top-K heap

Typical structures:
	•	queue
	•	stack
	•	deque
	•	priority queue

What is cached:
	•	unresolved candidates
	•	active frontier
	•	best current next states
	•	undominated candidates

Purpose:
	•	avoid repeated global rescanning

This is a powerful and under-recognized caching family.

⸻

C7. Candidate dominance cache

Store only candidates that are still useful.

Examples:
	•	daily temperatures
	•	next greater element
	•	sliding window maximum
	•	convex-hull-like DP optimizations conceptually

Typical structures:
	•	monotonic stack
	•	monotonic deque

What is cached:
	•	filtered unresolved candidates only

Purpose:
	•	avoid keeping dominated candidates that can never help later

This is caching with pruning.

⸻

C8. Connectivity cache

Store connectivity/visited/component state.

Examples:
	•	number of islands
	•	graph traversal
	•	provinces
	•	redundant connection
	•	account merge

Typical structures:
	•	visited array/set
	•	DSU parent array
	•	component labels

What is cached:
	•	whether state/node/cell was already explored
	•	representative root of component
	•	component membership info

Purpose:
	•	avoid repeated rediscovery or repeated connectivity traversal

⸻

C9. Structural metadata cache

Store helpful properties of a structure to avoid recomputation.

Examples:
	•	subtree heights
	•	node balances
	•	parent pointers
	•	distances
	•	indegrees
	•	subtree sums
	•	low-link / timestamps

Typical structures:
	•	arrays
	•	node fields
	•	maps keyed by node/state

What is cached:
	•	metadata about nodes/substructures

Purpose:
	•	avoid recomputing expensive structural facts repeatedly

⸻

C10. Object-state cache

Used in design questions.

Examples:
	•	LRU Cache
	•	LFU Cache
	•	Min Stack
	•	Browser History
	•	Twitter feed style design

Typical structures:
	•	map + list
	•	freq buckets
	•	stacks with extra fields
	•	queues/lists/heaps synchronized

What is cached:
	•	recent values
	•	frequency
	•	min/max so far
	•	internal object state summaries

Purpose:
	•	make API operations fast without rebuilding global state

This is explicit, deliberate system-style caching.

⸻

C11. Parsing/state-machine cache

Store parser progress or interpretation state.

Examples:
	•	decode ways
	•	regex DP
	•	parser validation
	•	calculator/token parsing

Typical structures:
	•	parser mode variables
	•	DP tables for prefixes
	•	stacks for nested states

What is cached:
	•	interpretation state of consumed prefix
	•	partial parse results

Purpose:
	•	avoid reinterpreting the same prefix/state repeatedly

⸻

C12. Output-construction cache

Store partial answers to assemble final output efficiently.

Examples:
	•	parent pointers in shortest path
	•	backtracking path vectors
	•	reconstruction arrays in DP
	•	memoized choice reconstruction

What is cached:
	•	how to reconstruct answer
	•	current partial output
	•	predecessor choice

Purpose:
	•	avoid recomputing solution reconstruction after solving optimization/counting problem

⸻

6. Caching is broader than hash maps

Many people incorrectly equate caching with hash maps.

But caching includes all of these:
	•	prefix sum array
	•	DP table
	•	memo dictionary
	•	visited set
	•	deque of window candidates
	•	heap frontier
	•	parent array
	•	subtree metadata
	•	rolling DP state
	•	stack with min-so-far
	•	path compression in DSU
	•	current window frequencies

So the correct statement is:

a cache is any stored reusable state that prevents future recomputation.

⸻

7. What exactly gets cached

Across all LeetCode questions, caches typically store one of these:

1. Existence

Have I seen this before?

2. Location

Where did I see it before?

3. Frequency

How many times have I seen it?

4. Aggregate

What is the cumulative sum/count/min/max so far?

5. Best-known answer

What is the best answer for this state so far?

6. Connectivity

Has this region/node/component already been explored?

7. Frontier relevance

Which candidate is still unresolved/useful?

8. Structure metadata

What property of this subtree/node/graph state is already known?

9. Partial solution

What path, partition, or assignment have I built so far?

10. Reconstruction data

How do I recover the final answer later?

These are the universal cached information types.

⸻

8. The deep relationship between caching and state

Caching is really the concrete side of state design.

When you ask:
	•	what should the algorithm remember?

you are really asking:
	•	what should be cached?

So the smallest sufficient state is the best cache.

If the cache is too small:
	•	repeated work remains
	•	algorithm may be incorrect

If the cache is too large:
	•	memory grows
	•	update logic gets messy
	•	implementation risk rises

So the best cache is:
	•	minimal
	•	sufficient
	•	updateable
	•	proof-friendly

⸻

9. Caching by major pattern family

Now the practical mapping.

⸻

A. Direct scan problems

Examples:
	•	max element
	•	running sum
	•	Kadane
	•	stock single pass

What is cached?

Usually a few scalars:
	•	current sum
	•	best sum
	•	best prefix
	•	min so far
	•	max so far

Why it works

The entire processed prefix is compressed into scalar summaries.

Deep point

Even one scalar variable can be a cache.

⸻

B. Hashing problems

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
	•	contains duplicate
	•	longest substring without repeats
	•	group anagrams
	•	subarray sum equals k

What is cached?
	•	seen values
	•	last seen position
	•	frequency
	•	grouped lists
	•	prefix counts

Why it works

Past search is replaced by O(1) average retrieval.

Cache meaning examples
	•	seen[value] = index
	•	freq[char] = count
	•	prefix_count[sum] = number of occurrences

⸻

C. Sliding window problems

Examples:
	•	minimum window substring
	•	longest unique substring
	•	permutation in string

What is cached?

The exact active-window state:
	•	frequencies
	•	deficit counts
	•	distinct counts
	•	number of satisfied requirements

Why it works

Without the cache, you would repeatedly rescan the window.

Deep point

The cache here is not static past memory; it is dynamic maintained present memory.

⸻

D. Two pointers problems

Examples:
	•	sorted Two Sum
	•	merge scans
	•	container with most water

What is cached?

Mostly positional information:
	•	left pointer
	•	right pointer
	•	write pointer
	•	sometimes sorted order itself acts like implicit cached structure

Deep point

Ordering can behave like an implicit cache because it lets pointer movement encode past logic.

⸻

E. Monotonic stack/deque problems

Examples:
	•	daily temperatures
	•	next greater element
	•	sliding window max

What is cached?

Only unresolved useful candidates.

Why it works

It avoids keeping candidates that are already dominated.

Deep point

This is selective cache retention:
	•	keep only future-relevant states
	•	discard permanently useless ones

⸻

F. BFS / DFS / graph problems

Examples:
	•	islands
	•	course schedule
	•	shortest path
	•	clone graph

What is cached?
	•	visited
	•	frontier
	•	distance
	•	indegree
	•	parent
	•	component representative

Why it works

Without visited or frontier metadata, states get rediscovered and recomputed.

Deep point

Graph algorithms are heavily cache-driven.

⸻

G. DP / memoization problems

Examples:
	•	House Robber
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance
	•	coin change
	•	word break

What is cached?

Solved subproblems.

Why it works

Naive recursion revisits the same state exponentially many times.

Deep point

DP is one of the purest forms of caching.

⸻

H. Backtracking problems

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	N-Queens
	•	word search

What is cached?
	•	current path
	•	used markers
	•	board state
	•	sometimes memoized failed states too

Deep point

Backtracking uses two kinds of cache:
	1.	current reversible state
	2.	optional memo/pruning cache for repeated dead states

So even search-tree algorithms may use caching in layered ways.

⸻

I. Design problems

Examples:
	•	LRU
	•	LFU
	•	Min Stack

What is cached?

Exactly the information needed for future fast API responses:
	•	recency order
	•	frequency
	•	min-so-far
	•	next/prev links
	•	key-node mapping

Deep point

These are explicit “cache design” questions, but the same principles apply everywhere else too.

⸻

10. The main cache operations

Across all questions, caches support a small set of core operations.

1. Lookup

Is info already known?

2. Insert

Store newly useful info.

3. Update

Change existing cached summary.

4. Improve

Replace old answer with better one.

5. Evict / discard

Remove stale or dominated info.

6. Mark

Record that a state/node/choice is active or processed.

7. Unmark

Undo reversible cached state in backtracking.

8. Compress

Rewrite state into a more efficient summary.

Examples:
	•	path compression in DSU
	•	rolling DP arrays
	•	compressed prefix summary

⸻

11. Cache lifetime types

Different caches live for different durations.

Permanent cache

Once written, stays useful until end.
Examples:
	•	seen values in Two Sum
	•	DP table entries
	•	visited in BFS

Dynamic cache

Continuously updated as active region changes.
Examples:
	•	sliding window frequencies
	•	heap frontier
	•	deque candidates

Reversible cache

Written and later undone.
Examples:
	•	backtracking used markers
	•	current path
	•	board placements

Expiring cache

Information is removed when no longer relevant.
Examples:
	•	deque front leaving window
	•	stale heap states conceptually
	•	LRU eviction

This is a very useful classification.

⸻

12. Cache correctness questions

Whenever you design or inspect a cache, ask:

A. What exactly does this cache entry mean?

Example:
	•	seen[x] = latest index of x
	•	not “some index,” but latest index

B. Is that meaning enough?

Does it preserve everything future logic needs?

C. Is it too much?

Could a smaller summary work?

D. When is it written?

Before or after a check?

E. When is it updated?

Does overwrite change semantics?

F. When is it invalid?

Can it go stale?

G. When must it be removed or undone?

Deque expiry, backtracking unchoose, LRU eviction, etc.

These questions cover almost all cache bugs.

⸻

13. Common caching mistakes across LeetCode

1. Caching the wrong thing

Example:
storing value when index is needed

2. Caching too much

Huge memory, messy logic, stale fields

3. Caching too little

Future logic lacks needed info

4. Wrong write order

Example:
in Two Sum, insert before lookup can change duplicate behavior

5. Wrong overwrite policy

Example:
latest index vs earliest index confusion

6. Not invalidating stale cache

Example:
window/deque/heap stale candidates

7. Forgetting undo

Example:
backtracking used-state not reverted

8. Confusing local and global cache meaning

Example:
window frequency ≠ full string frequency

9. Misusing cache API

Example:
using map[key] when find() is safer semantically

