14. Caching and time-space tradeoff

Caching almost always trades:
	•	more space
for
	•	less time

Examples:

Two Sum
	•	no cache: O(n²), O(1)
	•	hash cache: O(n), O(n)

Prefix sum
	•	no cache: repeated range scan
	•	prefix cache: O(1) range query, O(n) preprocessing

DP
	•	no cache: exponential recursion
	•	cache states: polynomial runtime, more memory

LRU
	•	no maintained state: expensive recomputation
	•	synchronized cache state: O(1) operations, more structure

So caching is one of the main sources of algorithmic time-space tradeoffs.

⸻

15. Caching and implementation

To implement caching well, you must specify:

1. Key

What identifies cached information?

2. Payload

What is stored for that key?

3. Lifetime

How long does it stay valid?

4. Update rule

Insert / overwrite / improve / count increment?

5. Query rule

Exact lookup? prefix match? stale check?

6. Invariant

What must always be true about the cache?

Examples:

Two Sum
	•	key = value
	•	payload = index
	•	lifetime = permanent
	•	update = overwrite or insert
	•	query = exact complement lookup
	•	invariant = cache summarizes processed prefix

Sliding window
	•	key = char/value
	•	payload = count
	•	lifetime = active window only
	•	update = increment/decrement
	•	query = validity condition
	•	invariant = cache equals exact current window content

DP
	•	key = subproblem state
	•	payload = answer
	•	lifetime = permanent after solve
	•	update = fill or improve
	•	query = memo reuse
	•	invariant = cached state answer is correct

⸻

