All about all type of approach in all leetcode question like top down,etc


Here is the full master map of approach types in LeetCode, including things like top-down, bottom-up, brute force, greedy, recursive, iterative, offline, online, amortized, meet-in-the-middle, and more.

This is the right way to think about “all types of approach”:

An approach type is a style of solving.
It tells you:
	•	how the algorithm thinks
	•	how it explores the problem
	•	how it stores information
	•	how it moves through the state space
	•	how it avoids repeated work

⸻

1. The highest-level classification

All LeetCode approaches can be organized into these master groups:

A. Search approaches

Explore candidate answers directly.

B. State-reuse approaches

Solve by caching reusable information.

C. Ordering approaches

Exploit sortedness, monotonicity, or event order.

D. Traversal approaches

Move through a structure or state graph.

E. Structural transformation approaches

Modify or rebuild structure directly.

F. Constraint-driven approaches

Explore choices under restrictions.

G. Mathematical/compression approaches

Use formula, algebra, combinatorics, encoding, or bit tricks.

H. Systems/design approaches

Maintain object state across operations.

But since you asked specifically for things like top-down, below is the more useful implementation/problem-solving style taxonomy.

⸻

2. Brute-force approach

This is the root approach.

Meaning

Try all candidates directly.

Examples
	•	all pairs
	•	all subarrays
	•	all paths
	•	all subsets
	•	all assignments

Role
	•	baseline
	•	correctness reference
	•	reveals repeated waste
	•	shows what must be optimized

Strength
	•	simplest to invent
	•	easiest to reason about initially

Weakness
	•	often too slow

Typical complexity
	•	O(n²), O(n³), O(2^n), O(n!), etc.

⸻

3. Recursive approach

Meaning

Solve the problem by defining it in terms of smaller versions of itself.

Common forms
	•	tree recursion
	•	DFS recursion
	•	recursive decomposition
	•	recursive enumeration
	•	recursive DP

Examples
	•	tree traversals
	•	subsets/permutations
	•	merge sort
	•	DFS on graph/tree
	•	memoized recursion

Strength
	•	natural for self-similar structure
	•	elegant for trees and search spaces

Weakness
	•	stack depth issues
	•	can repeat huge work if not memoized

⸻

4. Iterative approach

Meaning

Use loops and explicit state instead of recursive calls.

Common forms
	•	for-loop scan
	•	while-loop frontier
	•	iterative DP
	•	stack simulation

Examples
	•	single pass array scan
	•	BFS queue loop
	•	iterative inorder traversal
	•	bottom-up DP

Strength
	•	explicit control
	•	often lower overhead
	•	avoids recursion depth limits

Weakness
	•	can become mechanically complex for naturally recursive problems

⸻

5. Top-down approach

This is one of the most important.

Meaning

Start from the full problem and recursively break it into smaller subproblems.

Core idea

Ask:
	•	“what smaller things do I need to solve this?”

Then solve those first, usually recursively.

Common forms

Top-down without memoization

Pure recursion

Top-down with memoization

Recursive DP

Examples
	•	coin change memoization
	•	word break memoization
	•	DFS + memo
	•	edit distance top-down

Strength
	•	mirrors problem definition
	•	often easier to derive
	•	computes only states actually needed

Weakness
	•	recursion overhead
	•	may still be complex if state design is unclear
	•	without memoization it may explode exponentially

When to use
	•	recurrence is natural
	•	state space is sparse
	•	easier to think recursively

⸻

6. Bottom-up approach

The counterpart to top-down.

Meaning

Start from the smallest subproblems and build upward until the full answer is reached.

Core idea

Ask:
	•	“in what order can I solve smaller states so larger states become easy?”

Common forms
	•	iterative DP
	•	table fill
	•	prefix build
	•	topo-order processing

Examples
	•	House Robber DP
	•	LCS table
	•	edit distance matrix
	•	Fibonacci iterative

Strength
	•	no recursion stack
	•	predictable runtime
	•	often easier to optimize memory

Weakness
	•	fill order can be tricky
	•	may compute states that are never actually needed

When to use
	•	state dependencies are clear
	•	full table is manageable
	•	memory optimization matters

⸻

7. Memoized approach

Meaning

Cache results of recursive/top-down subproblems.

Core idea

If the same state is asked again, return cached answer.

Examples
	•	coin change
	•	word break
	•	grid paths with obstacles
	•	DFS on DAG/state graph with overlap

Strength
	•	turns repeated recursion into reusable computation
	•	often simpler than bottom-up to derive

Weakness
	•	must design good memo key
	•	recursion overhead remains
	•	hidden stack depth issues

⸻

8. Tabulation approach

Meaning

Explicitly fill a DP table iteratively.

Core idea

Store every subproblem answer in a table/array and compute in dependency order.

Examples
	•	knapsack
	•	edit distance
	•	LCS
	•	palindrome DP
	•	interval DP

Strength
	•	systematic
	•	good visibility into state space
	•	easier to prove fill order correctness

Weakness
	•	may use more memory
	•	fill order must be exact

⸻

9. Greedy approach

Meaning

Make the locally best choice and trust it leads to a global optimum.

Core idea

Do not explore all futures. Commit early.

Examples
	•	interval scheduling
	•	activity selection
	•	jump game reachability
	•	merge intervals style
	•	some string/array constructions

Strength
	•	often very fast
	•	elegant and compact

Weakness
	•	only works with a valid greedy-choice property
	•	easy to misuse

Proof style
	•	exchange argument
	•	contradiction
	•	monotonicity

⸻

10. Divide-and-conquer approach

Meaning

Split the problem into smaller independent parts, solve them, then combine.

Examples
	•	merge sort
	•	quicksort
	•	maximum subarray divide-and-conquer version
	•	tree divide/combine
	•	closest pair style reasoning

Strength
	•	structurally clean
	•	powerful when subproblems are independent enough

Weakness
	•	combine step may be expensive
	•	not all problems decompose naturally

⸻

11. Dynamic programming approach

Meaning

Solve overlapping subproblems and reuse their answers.

Core formula

states × transitions

Common styles
	•	top-down memoization
	•	bottom-up tabulation
	•	rolling DP
	•	state compression DP
	•	interval DP
	•	tree DP
	•	bitmask DP

Examples
	•	House Robber
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance
	•	knapsack
	•	coin change
	•	unique paths

Strength
	•	turns exponential recomputation into polynomial state solving

Weakness
	•	state design can be hard
