All about memoized 

Memoization is one of the most important ideas in all of LeetCode.

It is not just a DP trick.
It is a way of thinking:

if the same computational state can appear more than once, solve it once, store the answer, and reuse it.

That is memoization.

⸻

1. What memoization really is

Memoization is:
	•	top-down caching of subproblem results
	•	usually implemented with recursion
	•	used when the same state would otherwise be recomputed many times

So if brute-force recursion does this:
	•	solve state A
	•	branch to B and C
	•	later from another path reach B again
	•	solve B again from scratch

memoization changes it to:
	•	solve B once
	•	store answer for B
	•	every later request for B returns cached answer instantly

That is the whole idea.

⸻

2. The core formula of memoization

Memoized runtime is usually:

number of distinct states × cost to compute one state

Not:
	•	number of recursive calls in the raw tree

Because many raw recursive calls collapse into the same cached state.

This is the central power of memoization.

⸻

3. Memoization vs recursion

These are not the same.

Plain recursion
	•	defines a problem in terms of smaller subproblems
	•	may repeat work badly

Memoized recursion
	•	same recursive structure
	•	but stores solved states

So:
	•	recursion = decomposition style
	•	memoization = reuse mechanism

Memoization is recursion plus caching.

⸻

4. Memoization vs dynamic programming

Memoization is one form of dynamic programming.

Memoization
	•	top-down
	•	recursive
	•	compute only needed states
	•	cache results on demand

Tabulation
	•	bottom-up
	•	iterative
	•	fill table systematically
	•	often computes all states

So:

memoization is top-down DP

and

tabulation is bottom-up DP

⸻

5. When memoization is needed

Memoization is needed when three things are present:

A. Recursive subproblem structure

The problem can be written in terms of smaller states.

B. Overlapping subproblems

The same state can be reached multiple times.

C. Optimal or definite reusable answer per state

Once a state is solved, the answer is stable and can be reused.

If there is no overlap, memoization gives little value.

If state is not well-defined, memoization becomes incorrect.

⸻

6. What exactly gets memoized

Memoization stores:

the answer for a state

So the first deep question is:

What is the state?

This is the hardest part.

Possible state examples:
	•	i
	•	(i, j)
	•	(index, remaining_target)
	•	(row, col)
	•	(node, mask)
	•	(position, previous_choice)
	•	(left, right)
	•	(day, holding_stock, transactions_left)

Memoization is only as good as the state design.

⸻

7. The anatomy of a memoized solution

Every memoized solution has 5 parts.

1. State definition

What uniquely identifies a subproblem?

2. Recursive meaning

What does Solve(state) return?

3. Base case

When is the answer immediately known?

4. Transition

How is the answer built from smaller states?

5. Cache lookup/store

If state already solved, return it. Otherwise compute and save.

That is the full structure.

⸻

8. Canonical memoized template

In abstract form:

ReturnType Solve(State state) {
  if (base_case) {
    return base_answer;
  }

  if (memo contains state) {
    return memo[state];
  }

  ReturnType answer = combine(Solve(smaller_states...));

  memo[state] = answer;
  return answer;
}

That is memoization in one pattern.

⸻

9. Why memoization works

Memoization works because:
	•	recursion defines the logical recurrence
	•	cache prevents repeated evaluation of identical states

Without memoization:
	•	recursive tree may explode exponentially

With memoization:
	•	identical branches collapse into one solved state

So memoization transforms:
	•	tree of calls
into
	•	graph of unique states

This is a very deep idea.

Raw recursion explores a tree.
Memoization realizes many nodes in that tree are actually the same state.

⸻

10. Tree vs DAG view

This is one of the best ways to understand memoization.

Without memoization

You have a recursion tree.

Same state may appear many times in different branches.

With memoization

That tree becomes a DAG of distinct states.

Repeated states are merged.

That is why runtime drops so much.

⸻

11. Memoization and overlapping subproblems

Overlapping subproblems are the heart of memoization.

Example:

f(5)
├─ f(4)
│  ├─ f(3)
│  └─ f(2)
└─ f(3)
   ├─ f(2)
   └─ f(1)

Here f(3) and f(2) repeat.

Memoization stores them once.

So instead of recomputing:
	•	f(3) twice
	•	f(2) multiple times

you compute each once.

This is the main saving.

⸻

12. Common memoization families in LeetCode

Memoization appears in many problem families.

⸻

A. 1D index state

Examples:
	•	climbing stairs
	•	House Robber
	•	decode ways
	•	word break-like prefix problems

State:
	•	i

Meaning:
	•	answer starting at or up to position i

⸻

B. 2D position state

Examples:
	•	grid paths
	•	edit distance
	•	LCS
	•	interval recursion

State:
	•	(i, j) or (left, right)

Meaning:
	•	answer for subproblem over those boundaries/positions

⸻

C. Index + remaining resource

Examples:
	•	coin change
	•	target sum
	•	knapsack-like recursion
	•	partition problems

State:
	•	(index, remaining_target)
	•	(index, remaining_capacity)

Meaning:
	•	best/count answer using suffix starting from index with remaining budget

⸻

D. Tree node state

Examples:
	•	tree DP
	•	path sum variants
	•	robbing a tree
	•	subtree optimization

State:
	•	node
	•	or (node, extra_flag)

Meaning:
	•	answer for subtree rooted at node under given condition

⸻

E. Graph/state-space memoization

Examples:
	•	DFS on DAG
	•	longest path in DAG
	•	state graph problems
	•	game states

State:
	•	node or full configuration

Meaning:
	•	answer from that state onward

⸻

F. Bitmask memoization

Examples:
	•	traveling salesman style
	•	assignment problems
	•	subsets with state
	•	small-n combinatorial DP

State:
	•	(mask, i) or (mask, other_state)

Meaning:
	•	answer for chosen set mask with current endpoint/position/etc.

⸻

G. Interval memoization

Examples:
	•	burst balloons
	•	matrix chain style
	•	palindrome partitioning variants
	•	interval DP recursion

State:
	•	(left, right)

Meaning:
	•	answer restricted to interval

⸻

13. The deepest question in memoization: state design

This is the core skill.

You must ask:

What information is sufficient to uniquely determine the answer from here onward?

Not:
	•	what full history happened before

But:
	•	what minimal summary of the past matters now

That minimal summary is the memo key.

Examples:

Good state

(i, remaining_target)

Bad oversized state

(i, remaining_target, full_previous_path_vector)

If the extra data does not affect future answers, it should not be in state.

⸻

14. Good memo state properties

A good memo state is:

1. Sufficient

It contains everything needed for future decisions.

2. Minimal

It avoids irrelevant history.

3. Stable

Same state always means same subproblem.

4. Hashable/indexable

It can be stored/retrieved efficiently.

5. Small enough

The state space remains tractable.

⸻

15. Base cases in memoization

Memoized recursion always needs base cases.

Base cases are:
	•	smallest subproblems
	•	impossible states
	•	exact success states
	•	exhausted input states

Examples:
	•	i == n
	•	remaining == 0
	•	left > right
	•	node == nullptr
	•	row out of bounds
	•	mask == full_mask

Bad base cases are one of the main memo bugs.

⸻

16. Transitions in memoization

Transitions define how a state depends on smaller states.

Examples:

Choice recurrence
	•	take / skip
	•	split here / not here
	•	choose one of many next moves

Min/max recurrence
	•	answer = min(...)
	•	answer = max(...)

Counting recurrence
	•	answer = sum(...)

Boolean recurrence
	•	answer = any(...)
	•	answer = all(...)

Memoization is agnostic to whether the answer is:
	•	bool
	•	int
	•	long long
	•	vector
	•	string
	•	custom structure

What matters is recurrence correctness.

⸻

17. Time complexity of memoization

Memoization usually changes runtime from:
	•	exponential recursion tree

to:
	•	number of unique states × transition cost

Examples:

Fibonacci
	•	raw recursion: O(2^n)
	•	memoized: O(n)

Edit distance
	•	states: n * m
	•	transition cost: O(1)
	•	total: O(nm)

Coin change top-down
	•	states: n * target
	•	transition cost depends on formulation
	•	total often O(n * target)

This is the universal formula.

⸻

18. Space complexity of memoization

Memoization uses space for:

1. The cache

Store result for each distinct state

2. The recursion stack

Active call chain depth

So total space is often:
	•	cache size
	•	plus recursion depth

Example:
	•	2D memo table O(nm)
	•	recursion depth O(n+m) or O(n)

⸻

19. Memoization vs tabulation in practice

When to prefer memoization:

Prefer memoization when:
	•	recurrence is easy to write recursively
	•	only some states are reachable
	•	state graph is sparse
	•	top-down thinking is natural
	•	implementation is clearer recursively

Prefer tabulation when:
	•	full state space is dense anyway
	•	dependency order is easy
	•	recursion depth is risky
	•	memory optimization is easier iteratively
	•	constant factors matter

This is a very common tradeoff in LeetCode.

⸻

20. Common memoization data structures

⸻

A. Array / vector memo

Use when state dimensions are small integer ranges.

Examples:
	•	vector<int> memo(n, -1)
	•	vector<vector<int>> memo(n, vector<int>(m, -1))

Strength:
	•	fast
	•	simple

Weakness:
	•	needs bounded indexable state

⸻

B. Hash map memo

Use when state is sparse or not naturally indexable.

Examples:
	•	unordered_map<string, int>
	•	unordered_map<long long, int>
	•	custom hashed tuple state

Strength:
	•	flexible
	•	good for sparse state spaces

Weakness:
	•	slower constant factors
	•	key design matters a lot

⸻

C. Map with tuple-like key

Use for composite states:
	•	(i, remaining)
	•	(node_id, mask)
	•	(left, right)

This may be represented by:
	•	nested maps
	•	encoded integer key
	•	pair/tuple hash

⸻

21. Sentinel values in memoization

A very important implementation detail.

You often need to distinguish:
	•	state not computed yet
	•	state computed and answer is 0
	•	state impossible
	•	state valid with positive answer

So do not casually use 0 as “not computed” if 0 can be a valid answer.

Common strategies:
	•	use separate visited/computed array
	•	use sentinel like -1 only if invalid as real answer
	•	use optional-like logic conceptually
	•	use maps and “key exists” check

This is a major source of bugs.

⸻

22. Common memoization bugs

⸻

1. Wrong state

The answer depends on something not included in key.

This makes cache reuse invalid.

⸻

2. Oversized state

Including irrelevant history makes state space explode.

⸻

3. Wrong base case

The recursion returns wrong value at boundary.

⸻

4. Cache check too late

You compute before checking memo.

⸻

5. Wrong sentinel

Using 0 or -1 ambiguously.

⸻

6. Mutating shared state badly

Especially when recursion uses references or global structures.

⸻

7. Memoizing non-stable states

If “same key” can mean different realities because hidden state changed, memoization breaks.

⸻

8. Forgetting recursion stack cost

Memoized solution may still stack overflow for deep recursion.

⸻

23. Memoization and hidden state

This is subtle and important.

Memoization only works if the state key fully determines the future answer.

If the recursion also depends on hidden mutable global state not encoded in the key, memoization may become wrong.

Example of dangerous pattern:
	•	using global visited/path state that changes
	•	memo key only includes index

If future answer depends on visited configuration too, key must include it.

This is why memoization in graph/backtracking/state-space search must be designed carefully.

⸻

24. Memoization for optimization vs counting vs boolean

Memoization works across answer types.

⸻

Optimization memoization

Store best value:
	•	min cost
	•	max gain
	•	shortest length

Examples:
	•	House Robber
	•	minimum path sum
	•	burst balloons

⸻

Counting memoization

Store number of ways

Examples:
	•	decode ways
	•	target sum count
	•	count paths

⸻

Boolean memoization

Store true/false feasibility

Examples:
	•	can partition
	•	word break
	•	can reach target

⸻

Structural memoization

Store a structure or partial solution

Less common but possible:
	•	string answer
	•	vector result
	•	reconstructed path info

⸻

25. Memoization in trees

Trees often use memoization in two ways.

A. Natural recursion without repeated overlap

Many tree problems do not need memoization because each subtree is visited once.

B. Tree DP / conditional subtree states

When each node has multiple conditions, memoization/state DP matters.

Example:
	•	solve(node, can_take)
	•	solve(node, color)
	•	solve(node, parent_taken)

So tree memoization often appears when subtree answer depends on a mode/flag.

⸻

26. Memoization in graphs

Graph memoization is trickier.

It works best when:
	•	graph is DAG-like
	•	or state graph has no infinite recursion loops under the chosen recurrence
	•	or cycle handling is explicit

Examples:
	•	longest path in DAG
	•	DFS with memo on acyclic dependency graph
	•	game states with well-defined memo states

If cycles exist and recursion does not handle them properly, memoization alone is not enough.

⸻

27. Memoization and pruning

Memoization and pruning are different.

Memoization

Avoid recomputing same state.

Pruning

Avoid exploring obviously useless branches.

A good search may use both:
	•	prune impossible branches
	•	memoize repeated valid states

This is powerful in:
	•	word break
	•	game states
	•	subset/partition variants
	•	DFS on state graphs

⸻

28. Memoization and top-down design style

Memoization is especially useful when the natural way to think is:
	•	“What is the answer from here?”
	•	“If I am at position i, what is the best I can do?”
	•	“If remaining target is x, how many ways?”
	•	“If current state is s, can I finish?”

This “from here onward” thinking is classic top-down memoization.

⸻

29. Memoization and implementation style in C++

Because you asked about LeetCode generally, here is the implementation mindset.

Common forms:

1D

std::vector<int> memo(n, -1);

2D

std::vector<std::vector<int>> memo(n, std::vector<int>(m, -1));

Sparse / hash-based

std::unordered_map<long long, int> memo;

Recursion function
	•	either helper function inside class
	•	or lambda with self-reference
	•	or private member method

Important:
	•	define clear return meaning
	•	define clear state meaning
	•	separate computed/not-computed cleanly

⸻

30. Memoization and proof

Memoization does not change the mathematical recurrence.

It only changes efficiency.

So correctness proof usually has two parts:

A. Recurrence correctness

Why does Solve(state) return the right answer?

B. Cache correctness

Why is reusing cached result safe?

The second part is usually:
	•	because identical state means identical future subproblem

That is the key proof idea.

⸻

31. When memoization is not the best choice

Memoization is powerful, but not always best.

Avoid or reconsider when:
	•	recurrence is awkward
	•	state space is dense and easy bottom-up
	•	recursion depth too large
	•	need very tight constants
	•	same problem fits greedy, hashing, or graph traversal better
	•	state depends on large hidden mutable context

Examples:
	•	Two Sum is not a memoization problem
	•	BFS shortest path is not naturally memoization-first
	•	simple scan problems do not need memoization

⸻

32. Memoization patterns across LeetCode

You can classify memoized problems by state shape.

Prefix state

solve(i)

Suffix state

solve(i) from i to end

Pair boundary state

solve(l, r)

Position pair state

solve(i, j)

Position + budget

solve(i, rem)

Position + mode

solve(i, can_buy) or solve(i, k, holding)

Node + mode

solve(node, taken)

Mask state

solve(mask) or solve(mask, last)

These are the major memoized state templates.

⸻

33. Memoization as “cache over recursion frontier”

A good deep mental model:

Recursion asks many “questions.”

Memoization says:
	•	if the exact same question was asked before,
	•	do not re-solve it,
	•	just reuse the answer.

So memoization is a question-answer cache.

This mental model helps a lot.

⸻

34. Universal memoization template for any problem

Use this checklist.

1. What is the recursive question?

What does Solve(state) mean?

2. What is the minimal state?

What uniquely determines that question?

3. What are the base cases?

When is the answer immediate?

4. What smaller questions does it depend on?

That is the transition.

5. Can the same state appear multiple times?

If yes, memoization helps.

6. How will the state be stored?

Array / matrix / hash map

7. What sentinel or computed-marker is safe?

Avoid ambiguity.

8. What is the total number of distinct states?

That determines runtime.

That is the memoization design framework.

⸻

35. Ultra-compressed version

Memoization is:
	•	top-down DP
	•	recursion + cache
	•	solve state once
	•	reuse thereafter

It is used when:
	•	subproblems overlap
	•	state is well-defined
	•	answer per state is stable

Core formula:
	•	time = number of unique states × transition cost

Biggest challenge:
	•	designing the right state

Biggest bug source:
	•	wrong or incomplete state key

⸻

36. Final sentence

The deepest way to understand memoization is:

memoization turns a recursive explosion of repeated questions into a finite set of unique solved states.

