Iterative compute opt for all 3872 leetcode question 


“Iterative compute optimization” across all 3872 LeetCode questions means:

how to turn a solution into a loop-driven, state-efficient, execution-efficient form that computes only what is necessary, in the right order, with minimal overhead.

This is bigger than “convert recursion to iteration.”

It includes:
	•	replacing recursion with loops when beneficial
	•	reducing repeated computation
	•	shrinking state
	•	improving update order
	•	exploiting monotone progress
	•	doing in-place updates
	•	using rolling state instead of full tables
	•	making each iteration do exactly the useful work

So below is the master framework.

⸻

1. What iterative compute optimization really is

An algorithm has:
	•	a set of states
	•	a rule for moving between states
	•	a way to stop

Iterative compute optimization asks:
	•	can the state transition be driven by loops instead of call stack?
	•	can we compute states in a better order?
	•	can we avoid recomputing already known values?
	•	can we reduce memory read/write volume?
	•	can we compress states?
	•	can we update fewer things per step?
	•	can we eliminate dead or dominated work?

So the core idea is:

make computation proceed through explicit, efficient state progression.

⸻

2. The 5 main goals of iterative optimization

G1. Remove recursion overhead

Avoid:
	•	call stack cost
	•	repeated function setup
	•	deep recursion limits

G2. Reduce recomputation

Avoid:
	•	repeated subproblem solving
	•	repeated scans
	•	repeated aggregation
	•	repeated candidate checks

G3. Reduce state size

Replace:
	•	full tables
with:
	•	rolling rows
	•	scalars
	•	compressed frontier
	•	in-place storage

G4. Improve traversal order

Compute states in an order that:
	•	respects dependencies
	•	reduces cache misses conceptually
	•	reduces unnecessary work
	•	enables early pruning/skipping

G5. Reduce per-iteration work

Make each loop step:
	•	O(1) if possible
	•	monotone
	•	incremental
	•	frontier-limited

⸻

3. The universal iterative-compute model

Every LeetCode problem can be seen like this:

State space

What possible states matter?

Dependency rule

What previous states are needed?

Iteration order

In what order can those states be computed safely?

Update rule

How is each new state computed?

Compression opportunity

Can some old states be discarded?

That is the iterative viewpoint.

⸻

4. Main iterative optimization families across all 3872 questions

These are the big categories.

A. Scan optimization

Single-pass or few-pass loop computation

B. Incremental maintenance optimization

Maintain result/state while moving boundaries

C. Table-fill optimization

Compute DP states iteratively in dependency order

D. Frontier-driven optimization

Process only active states/candidates

E. Ordered-elimination optimization

Discard impossible/dominated states while iterating

F. Structural-update optimization

Update structure in-place rather than rebuild

G. State-compression optimization

Keep only needed partial results

⸻

5. Scan optimization

This is the simplest and most common iterative compute form.

Meaning

Process each unit once or a constant number of times.

Common in
	•	arrays
	•	strings
	•	simple greedy
	•	hash-assisted scans
	•	prefix/suffix methods

Typical optimization moves
	•	use running scalar summaries
	•	avoid nested rescans
	•	fold prefix knowledge into loop state
	•	write result while scanning

Examples
	•	max/min scan
	•	Kadane
	•	Two Sum hash scan
	•	stock buy-sell
	•	product except self

Master rule

If the whole processed prefix can be summarized compactly, scanning is the best iterative form.

⸻

6. Incremental-maintenance optimization

This is the core of sliding windows and related problems.

Meaning

Instead of recomputing a region, update its summary when the region changes.

Common in
	•	sliding window
	•	prefix variants
	•	active-interval problems
	•	fixed-size windows

Typical optimization moves
	•	one element enters, one leaves
	•	update count/sum/frequency incrementally
	•	maintain validity score instead of rechecking entire region

Examples
	•	longest substring without repeat
	•	min window substring
	•	fixed window sum/max
	•	at most K distinct

Master rule

If the current answer depends on a changing contiguous region, maintain that region incrementally.

⸻

7. Table-fill optimization

This is the iterative form of DP.

Meaning

Replace recursive recomputation with explicit state table updates.

Common in
	•	House Robber
	•	coin change
	•	edit distance
	•	LCS
	•	knapsack
	•	interval DP

Typical optimization moves
	•	choose a legal fill order
	•	compute each state once
	•	use precomputed dependencies
	•	optionally compress dimensions

Example forms
	•	1D DP
	•	2D DP
	•	interval DP
	•	bitmask DP
	•	tree DP iterative variants sometimes

Master rule

If the same subproblem can appear many times, compute each state once in a dependency-respecting order.

⸻

8. Frontier-driven iterative optimization

This is very important.

Meaning

Do not iterate over all states blindly. Process only currently relevant states.

Common in
	•	BFS
	•	Dijkstra
	•	topological processing
	•	heaps
	•	monotonic structures
	•	some sparse DP/state-graph problems

Typical optimization moves
	•	queue only reachable frontier
	•	heap only candidate-optimal frontier
	•	stack/deque only unresolved useful states
	•	skip stale states

Examples
	•	BFS shortest path
	•	Dijkstra
	•	top K
	•	daily temperatures
	•	sliding window maximum

Master rule

If only a small subset of states is active/useful at a time, iterate over the frontier, not the whole universe.

⸻

9. Ordered-elimination optimization

Meaning

As iteration proceeds, eliminate states that can never matter again.

Common in
	•	two pointers
	•	binary search
	•	monotonic stack
	•	monotonic deque
	•	greedy interval methods

Typical optimization moves
	•	move one pointer and permanently discard a region
	•	pop dominated candidates
	•	shrink search interval
	•	delete expired frontier states

Examples
	•	sorted Two Sum
	•	container with most water
	•	next greater element
	•	binary search on answer
	•	window max deque

Master rule

If a monotone or dominance relation exists, iteration can safely throw work away.

⸻

10. Structural-update optimization

Meaning

Iteratively modify the existing structure instead of creating new ones.

Common in
	•	linked lists
	•	arrays
	•	matrices
	•	design questions
	•	in-place transforms

Typical optimization moves
	•	rewire pointers
	•	swap in-place
	•	partition in-place
	•	reverse iteratively
	•	maintain object invariants per update

Examples
	•	reverse linked list
	•	merge two sorted lists
	•	rotate array
	•	move zeroes
	•	LRU internals

Master rule

If the target structure can be reached by local safe mutations, iterative rewiring often beats reconstruction.

⸻

11. State-compression optimization

This is one of the most important iterative ideas.

Meaning

Store only the states still needed for future computation.

Common in
	•	1D/2D DP
	•	rolling arrays
	•	prefix/suffix methods
	•	scalarized recurrences
	•	compressed frontier representations

Typical optimization moves
	•	full DP table -> previous row only
	•	previous row -> two scalars
	•	full prefix arrays -> running sum
	•	full history -> monotone candidate frontier

Examples
	•	Fibonacci / House Robber scalar DP
	•	edit distance rolling rows
	•	unique paths rolling row
	•	Kadane using two scalars

Master rule

If state dependencies are local in time/order, discard older solved states.

⸻

12. Converting top-down to iterative compute

This is likely close to what you mean by “iterative compute opt.”

Generic conversion path

Step 1

Define the recursive state:
solve(state)

Step 2

Identify dependencies:
which smaller states are needed?

Step 3

Find a legal evaluation order:
small -> large, short -> long, left -> right, topo order, subset order, etc.

Step 4

Replace recursive call with table/loop lookup

Step 5

Compress memory if only nearby states matter

This is the standard top-down -> bottom-up optimization path.

⸻

13. Iterative optimization by major family

Now the full practical map.

⸻

A. Arrays / strings

Raw style
	•	nested loops
	•	recursive splitting
	•	repeated scans

Iterative optimized styles
	•	one-pass scan
	•	hash-assisted scan
	•	sliding window
	•	prefix/suffix arrays
	•	two pointers
	•	monotonic deque/stack

Common optimization moves
	•	maintain running state
	•	avoid rescanning prefixes/windows
	•	convert pair search to complement lookup
	•	compress repeated comparisons into monotone frontier

Usual target complexity
	•	O(n)
	•	O(n log n)
	•	O(n²) only when structurally necessary

⸻

B. DP problems

Raw style
	•	exponential recursion

Iterative optimized styles
	•	bottom-up table
	•	rolling DP
	•	state-compressed DP
	•	topo-order DP on DAG/grid

Common optimization moves
	•	compute each state once
	•	shrink dimensions
	•	reduce transition cost
	•	precompute prefix minima/maxima if transitions are expensive

Usual target complexity
	•	O(states × transitions)
	•	then optimize transitions if possible

⸻

C. Graph / grid problems

Raw style
	•	repeated DFS from scratch
	•	uncontrolled recursion
	•	all-path search

Iterative optimized styles
	•	BFS queue
	•	iterative DFS stack
	•	topological queue
	•	Dijkstra heap
	•	DSU merges

Common optimization moves
	•	visited marking
	•	frontier restriction
	•	distance caching
	•	only process discovered nodes
	•	use queue/heap instead of repeated global search

Usual target complexity
	•	O(V+E)
	•	O((V+E) log V)

⸻

D. Backtracking / combinatorial problems

Raw style
	•	full search tree

Iterative optimized styles

Usually still recursive, but compute can be optimized by:
	•	pruning
	•	bitmask compression
	•	iterative subset generation for some families
	•	DP over subsets
	•	meet-in-the-middle
	•	stack simulation if needed

Common optimization moves
	•	prune invalid branches early
	•	cache repeated dead states
	•	represent sets compactly
	•	split large search in half

Usual target complexity
	•	still exponential, but bounded by small n or better pruning

⸻

E. Design / data-structure problems

Raw style
	•	rebuild or rescan on each operation

Iterative optimized styles
	•	maintain synchronized state incrementally per API call

Common optimization moves
	•	update local state only
	•	avoid global recomputation
	•	maintain recency/frequency/min in parallel structures
	•	keep helper pointers and maps

Usual target complexity
	•	O(1)
	•	amortized O(1)
	•	O(log n)

⸻

14. Iterative compute optimization patterns you should always look for

These are the universal “upgrade moves.”

Upgrade 1 — Recompute -> maintain

Instead of recalculating a property, update it incrementally.

Upgrade 2 — Recursive tree -> state DAG

Memoize or tabulate repeated subproblems.

Upgrade 3 — Full set -> active frontier

Use queue/heap/deque/stack to process only useful states.

Upgrade 4 — Full history -> compressed summary

Use prefix sums, running minima, counts, or scalars.

Upgrade 5 — Full table -> rolling state

Keep only the last needed rows/columns/scalars.

Upgrade 6 — Unordered search -> ordered elimination

Sort, binary search, two-pointer, monotonic prune.

Upgrade 7 — Rebuild structure -> mutate in place

Update links/cells directly.

These 7 cover most iterative compute improvements.

⸻

15. Iteration order is the heart of optimization

A lot of iterative optimization is really about choosing the right order.

Common iteration orders:

Left to right

prefix DP, scans, hashing

Right to left

suffix DP, next-greater variants, reverse accumulations

Short interval to long interval

interval DP

Small mask to large mask

bitmask DP

Topological order

DAG DP, dependency problems

BFS layers

minimum steps / propagation

Heap priority order

best-first / weighted shortest path

Window boundary order

sliding window

Sorted event order

intervals / sweep line / greedy

Wrong order can make iterative compute impossible or incorrect.

⸻

16. Memory-write optimization

Iterative compute is not only about fewer states. It is also about fewer writes.

Good iterative optimization asks:
	•	do I need to write every table cell?
	•	can I keep only best-so-far?
	•	can I overwrite input?
	•	can I delay writes?
	•	can I aggregate several updates?

Examples:
	•	rolling DP rows
	•	scalar DP
	•	in-place partitioning
	•	mark visited directly in grid instead of extra array
	•	use answer accumulator instead of full prefix table when only current value matters

⸻

17. Dependency-distance optimization

This is a deep DP idea.

Ask:

how far back do I need to look?

If only nearby states matter:
	•	use rolling state
	•	use queue/deque optimization
	•	use scalars

Examples:
	•	Fibonacci -> 2 scalars
	•	House Robber -> 2 scalars
	•	fixed-window -> O(1) update
	•	some DP with limited dependency radius -> rolling array

This is one of the strongest iterative optimizations.

⸻

18. Transition-cost optimization

Even after choosing DP/iteration, transitions may still be too expensive.

Then optimize:
	•	naive transition over all previous states -> prefix min/max
	•	naive range scan -> monotonic deque
	•	repeated best candidate -> heap
	•	repeated subset combine -> bitset/bitmask tricks conceptually
	•	repeated overlap count -> sorting/events

So iterative compute optimization has two stages:

Stage 1

Compute each state once

Stage 2

Make each state cheaper to compute

This is very important.

⸻

19. Common iterative compute mistakes

1. Converting recursion to loops without understanding dependency order

Then the loop computes states before prerequisites are ready.

2. Keeping full memory when rolling state is enough

Wastes space and hurts clarity.

3. Recomputing per-iteration aggregates

Kills the intended optimization.

4. Wrong update order

Especially in:
	•	sliding window
	•	DP overwrite
	•	linked-list rewiring
	•	BFS visited logic
	•	stale heap skip logic

5. Ignoring amortization

Mistakenly assuming inner while means quadratic.

6. Not skipping stale states

Common in heap/frontier problems.

7. Over-updating

Updating whole rows/regions when only small local changes are needed.

⸻

