Different protocols in all leetcode question 


If by “protocols” you mean the standard operating procedures / repeatable workflows used to solve LeetCode problems, then yes — there are a finite number of major protocols that cover most questions. “Thinking patterns” and common algorithm families are exactly how many LeetCode study guides organize problem solving.  ￼

Below is the master protocol map.

1. What a protocol is

A protocol is a repeatable sequence of decisions you follow when a problem has a certain structure.

It is not just:
	•	a data structure
	•	an algorithm name
	•	a code template

It is:
	•	how you recognize the problem
	•	how you set up state
	•	how you move through the state space
	•	how you stop
	•	how you verify correctness

So “two pointers” is not only a technique.
It is a protocol:
	•	detect ordered structure
	•	initialize two boundaries
	•	compare current state
	•	move one pointer by a monotone rule
	•	terminate when boundaries cross

That is a protocol.

⸻

2. The universal meta-protocol for any LeetCode question

Before any specific bucket, use this on every question.

Protocol 0 — Universal intake
	1.	Read the objective: decision, search, optimize, count, enumerate, transform.
	2.	Read constraints and infer allowable time complexity. A common interview heuristic is that larger n pushes you toward O(n) or O(n log n), while smaller n may permit O(n²) or exponential methods.  ￼
	3.	Translate story words into structure.
	4.	Identify the brute-force search space.
	5.	Identify repeated waste.
	6.	Choose the protocol that removes that waste.
	7.	Define state and invariant.
	8.	Implement and dry run edge cases.

That is the master protocol above all others.

⸻

3. The major LeetCode protocols

Protocol 1 — Direct scan

Use when the answer can be maintained by processing elements once with a few scalars.

Signals:
	•	max/min
	•	running total
	•	best-so-far
	•	one local decision per element

State:
	•	current
	•	best
	•	running sum
	•	min-so-far / max-so-far

Flow:
	•	initialize
	•	scan left to right
	•	update local summary
	•	update global answer

Typical cost:
	•	O(n) time, O(1) space

⸻

Protocol 2 — Hash lookup

Use when the present element needs fast information about the past.

Signals:
	•	“have I seen…”
	•	complements
	•	frequency
	•	last seen index
	•	grouping by normalized key

State:
	•	hash map / set
	•	key and payload must be precise

Flow:
	•	derive lookup key
	•	query map/set
	•	act on hit or miss
	•	update structure

Typical cost:
	•	O(n) average time with hash-based lookup. Hashing is widely used in LeetCode problem solving.  ￼

⸻

Protocol 3 — Sliding window

Use when the problem is about a contiguous subarray/substring and the window’s validity can be maintained incrementally.

Signals:
	•	substring / subarray
	•	longest / shortest valid window
	•	“at most K”
	•	“contains all”
	•	fixed-size window

State:
	•	left, right
	•	window summary: counts, distinct count, deficits, etc.

Flow:
	•	expand right
	•	update window state
	•	shrink left while invalid or while optimizable
	•	record answer

Typical cost:
	•	often O(n) because each boundary moves monotonically. Sliding window is one of the most common LeetCode techniques.  ￼

⸻

Protocol 4 — Two pointers

Use when ordering lets you move boundaries intelligently.

Signals:
	•	sorted array/string
	•	pair relation
	•	reverse / palindrome
	•	merge-like process
	•	remove duplicates

State:
	•	two indices or pointers

Flow:
	•	initialize boundaries
	•	compare current pair/state
	•	move one side based on monotone logic

Typical cost:
	•	usually O(n) after any needed preprocessing

⸻

Protocol 5 — Binary search

Use when the answer space or array is monotone.

Signals:
	•	sorted input
	•	“find smallest/largest valid”
	•	feasibility changes once from false to true
	•	large search range with monotone predicate

State:
	•	left, right, mid

Flow:
	•	test mid
	•	discard half safely
	•	continue until boundary found

Typical cost:
	•	O(log n) or O(log range × check_cost)

A common LeetCode heuristic is that if you need to “find x” or optimize x under large constraints, binary search may be the right protocol.  ￼

⸻

Protocol 6 — Prefix / cumulative summary

Use when repeated range or prefix information is needed.

Signals:
	•	range sum
	•	subarray sum conditions
	•	cumulative parity / balance
	•	repeated aggregate over prefixes

State:
	•	running prefix
	•	prefix array or prefix map

Flow:
	•	update cumulative summary
	•	derive needed prior summary
	•	count / compare / query

Typical cost:
	•	often O(n)

⸻

Protocol 7 — Monotonic stack

Use when each element wants its nearest greater/smaller unresolved partner.

Signals:
	•	next greater/smaller
	•	daily temperatures
	•	histogram rectangle
	•	nearest previous/next relation

State:
	•	stack of unresolved candidates, usually indices

Flow:
	•	while current resolves stack top, pop
	•	write answers for popped items
	•	push current

Typical cost:
	•	O(n) amortized because each item is pushed once and popped at most once

⸻

Protocol 8 — Monotonic deque

Use when a moving window needs its max/min efficiently.

Signals:
	•	sliding window max/min
	•	best candidate in active interval
	•	stale + dominated candidates

State:
	•	deque of candidate indices

Flow:
	•	expire out-of-window front
	•	pop dominated back
	•	push current
	•	front is current optimum

Typical cost:
	•	O(n) amortized

⸻

Protocol 9 — Heap / priority frontier

Use when you repeatedly need the current best candidate among many active candidates.

Signals:
	•	top K
	•	kth largest/smallest
	•	merge K sorted streams
	•	weighted shortest path
	•	dynamic frontier ranking

State:
	•	min-heap or max-heap

Flow:
	•	push candidate states
	•	pop highest-priority state
	•	expand / consume / update

Typical cost:
	•	usually O(log n) per heap event; heap-based protocols are common in LeetCode.  ￼

⸻

Protocol 10 — BFS

Use when shortest path is in an unweighted graph/state space, or when expansion naturally occurs in layers.

Signals:
	•	minimum steps
	•	level order
	•	spread/propagation
	•	nearest source
	•	implicit graph of states

State:
	•	queue
	•	visited
	•	sometimes distance/time

Flow:
	•	seed frontier
	•	pop queue
	•	inspect neighbors
	•	push undiscovered neighbors

Typical cost:
	•	O(V + E) in explicit graphs

⸻

Protocol 11 — DFS

Use for structural exploration, components, recursion over trees, and exhaustive traversal when shortest-path guarantees are not needed.

Signals:
	•	connected components
	•	subtree properties
	•	existence/path exploration
	•	tree recursion

State:
	•	recursion stack or explicit stack
	•	visited if graph can revisit

Flow:
	•	enter node/state
	•	recurse into children/neighbors
	•	combine results or mark completion

Typical cost:
	•	O(V + E) in explicit graphs

⸻

Protocol 12 — Topological / dependency processing

Use when a directed acyclic dependency structure exists.

Signals:
	•	prerequisites
	•	build order
	•	DAG dependencies
	•	schedule tasks with constraints

State:
	•	indegree or DFS color/state
	•	queue / stack for ready nodes

Flow:
	•	identify dependency-free nodes
	•	process them
	•	release dependent nodes

Typical cost:
	•	O(V + E)

⸻

Protocol 13 — Backtracking

Use when you must explore combinations/permutations/placements under constraints.

Signals:
	•	generate all
	•	choose/not choose
	•	permutations
	•	combinations
	•	placements
	•	constraint satisfaction

State:
	•	current path
	•	used markers / board state

Flow:
	•	choose
	•	recurse
	•	undo

Typical cost:
	•	exponential or factorial, often acceptable only for small n

Backtracking is one of the core algorithmic techniques used in LeetCode-style problems.  ￼

⸻

Protocol 14 — Top-down DP (memoization)

Use when recursion has overlapping subproblems.

Signals:
	•	“answer from here”
	•	repeated recursion states
	•	optimize/count/decide over a state
	•	sparse reachable state space

State:
	•	memo key = subproblem state

Flow:
	•	define recursive function on state
	•	base case
	•	recurse to smaller states
	•	memoize result

Typical cost:
	•	number of unique states × transition cost

Memoization is a standard DP technique frequently used for LeetCode problems.  ￼

⸻

Protocol 15 — Bottom-up DP (tabulation)

Use when the dependency order is explicit and iterative fill is cleaner than recursion.

Signals:
	•	state table is clear
	•	smaller states build larger states
	•	dense state space
	•	recurrence easy to order

State:
	•	DP array/table

Flow:
	•	initialize base cases
	•	fill in legal dependency order
	•	read final state

Typical cost:
	•	states × transition cost

⸻

Protocol 16 — Greedy

Use when a local choice can be proven globally safe.

Signals:
	•	intervals
	•	scheduling
	•	one-pass decision with irrevocable choices
	•	exchange-argument feel
	•	sort + choose

State:
	•	current best feasible choice
	•	minimal metadata needed for the choice rule

Flow:
	•	sort or iterate
	•	take safe local action
	•	never revisit discarded options

Typical cost:
	•	often O(n) or O(n log n)

Greedy is a standard major algorithm family in LeetCode-style preparation.  ￼

⸻

Protocol 17 — Divide and conquer

Use when the problem splits cleanly into subproblems that combine well.

Signals:
	•	split in half
	•	solve left/right
	•	combine summaries
	•	tree-like recursive decomposition

State:
	•	subproblem boundaries

Flow:
	•	divide
	•	recurse
	•	combine

Typical cost:
	•	depends on recurrence, often O(n log n)

⸻

Protocol 18 — Union-Find / DSU

Use when the core operation is merging and querying connected components.

Signals:
	•	repeated unions
	•	connectivity
	•	same group/component?
	•	merge accounts/nodes/sets

State:
	•	representative parent
	•	rank/size

Flow:
	•	find representatives
	•	union if different
	•	answer component questions by representative

Typical cost:
	•	near-linear overall with path compression/rank heuristics

⸻

Protocol 19 — Trie / prefix tree

Use when shared prefixes must be represented explicitly.

Signals:
	•	dictionary words
	•	prefix search
	•	many repeated prefix queries
	•	word search with dictionary

State:
	•	prefix tree nodes
	•	terminal markers

Flow:
	•	insert words
	•	traverse by characters
	•	branch by prefix

Typical cost:
	•	proportional to processed characters

⸻

Protocol 20 — Sweep line / event processing

Use when interval or event overlap can be understood by ordered endpoints/events.

Signals:
	•	meetings/intervals
	•	overlaps
	•	event starts/ends
	•	active counts over a line/time axis

State:
	•	sorted events
	•	active count/set

Flow:
	•	sort events
	•	process in order
	•	update active state on start/end

Typical cost:
	•	often O(n log n)

⸻

Protocol 21 — In-place structural mutation

Use when the structure itself can serve as working memory.

Signals:
	•	reverse linked list
	•	rotate array
	•	partition array
	•	mutate matrix
	•	no extra space preferred

State:
	•	pointers / indices / temp references

Flow:
	•	preserve needed references
	•	mutate locally
	•	maintain structure validity

Typical cost:
	•	often O(n) time, O(1) extra space

⸻

Protocol 22 — Design / object-state protocol

Use when the problem is not one-shot computation but maintaining fast operations over time.

Signals:
	•	implement class
	•	support operations in O(1) / O(log n)
	•	cache/history/stack/min/max/browser/feed behavior

State:
	•	multiple synchronized structures

Flow:
	•	each API call performs a local state transaction
	•	invariants must hold after every operation

Typical cost:
	•	per-operation target dominates analysis

⸻

Protocol 23 — Math / formula / combinatorics

Use when brute-force structure can be collapsed into arithmetic, combinatorial counting, or number theory.

Signals:
	•	direct count/formula
	•	gcd/lcm
	•	modular arithmetic
	•	parity
	•	pattern derivation
	•	bit tricks

State:
	•	usually small scalars

Flow:
	•	transform to formula or number-theoretic relation
	•	compute directly

Typical cost:
	•	often O(1) or O(log n)

⸻

4. Directional protocols

These are not separate algorithms, but important solving directions.

Top-down

Start from the full problem and recurse into smaller needed states.

Bottom-up

Start from smallest known states and build upward.

Left-to-right

Prefix-driven iteration.

Right-to-left

Suffix-driven iteration.

Outside-in

Shrink boundaries inward.

Inside-out

Expand from a center or seed state.

These directional choices matter a lot in LeetCode-style reasoning.

⸻

5. Operational protocols

These describe when computation happens.

Offline protocol

You know all data/queries first, so you can reorder or preprocess before answering.

Online protocol

You must answer as data arrives.

Amortized protocol

Some single operations can be expensive, but average cost stays low over a sequence.

These are especially important in design, query, and advanced data-structure questions.

⸻

6. Hybrid protocols

Most medium/hard problems are hybrids.

Examples:
	•	sliding window + hashing
	•	DFS + memoization
	•	graph + heap
	•	DP + prefix sum
	•	sort + greedy
	•	design + hashmap + doubly linked list

The right way to think about hybrids is:

Primary engine

What drives progress?

Support protocol

What makes the engine efficient?

Example:
	•	Dijkstra: primary = frontier expansion, support = heap + distance cache
	•	Longest substring without repeats: primary = sliding window, support = last-seen/hash map
	•	LRU cache: primary = object-state maintenance, support = hashmap + linked list

⸻

