All types of labelling in all leetcode question 



Here is the master system of labelling for all LeetCode questions.

If formulation tells you what the problem really is, then labelling tells you:
	•	how to tag it
	•	how to classify it
	•	how to retrieve similar problems
	•	how to predict approach
	•	how to group mistakes
	•	how to build a taxonomy over all 3872 questions

So labelling is not one thing.
It is a multi-axis classification system.

A single LeetCode question should never have only one label.

It should have many labels at different depths.

⸻

1. What labelling really means

Labelling means assigning structured tags to a question so the question can be understood, grouped, searched, taught, and solved more systematically.

A good label should answer one of these:
	•	what is the input object?
	•	what is the output type?
	•	what is the core relation?
	•	what is the search space?
	•	what is the algorithm family?
	•	what is the state type?
	•	what is the invariant type?
	•	what is the difficulty source?
	•	what common mistakes happen?
	•	what extension family does it belong to?

So labels are really dimensions of identity.

⸻

2. Why one label is never enough

Example: Two Sum

If you label it only as:
	•	array

that is too weak.

If you label it only as:
	•	hashing

that is still incomplete.

A fuller label set is:
	•	object: sequence
	•	objective: search
	•	relation: pair sum/complement
	•	search space: all pairs
	•	optimization family: hash-assisted scan
	•	state type: prefix cache
	•	invariant type: processed-prefix map
	•	anti-pattern: destructive sort without index preservation
	•	difficulty source: recognizing complement lookup
	•	extension family: k-sum / pair relation

That is real labelling.

⸻

3. The master axes of labelling

All LeetCode questions should be labelled across these axes:

Axis A — Surface labels

What words/story appear in the statement?

Axis B — Structural labels

What computational object/problem is it really?

Axis C — Objective labels

What kind of answer is required?

Axis D — Search-space labels

What brute-force universe exists?

Axis E — Approach labels

What solving style fits?

Axis F — State labels

What memory/state is central?

Axis G — Proof labels

What proof style justifies it?

Axis H — Complexity labels

What growth class does it live in?

Axis I — Difficulty-source labels

Why do people fail this problem?

Axis J — Extension labels

What family does it generalize into?

That is the full master labelling framework.

