All about properties of all leetcode question 

Here is the master framework of properties of all LeetCode questions.

A “property” is any stable characteristic a question has that helps you:
	•	understand it
	•	classify it
	•	formulate it
	•	choose an approach
	•	predict complexity
	•	predict bugs
	•	predict extensions

So “properties” are deeper than tags.

A LeetCode question has many kinds of properties at once.

⸻

1. What a property is

A property is a feature that remains meaningfully true about the problem.

Examples:
	•	it is order-sensitive
	•	it has overlapping subproblems
	•	it is contiguous
	•	it has monotonicity
	•	identity matters
	•	duplicates matter
	•	the state is small
	•	the graph is acyclic
	•	the answer is output-sensitive

These are all properties.

So the full study of LeetCode questions is really the study of their properties.

⸻

2. The master categories of properties

All LeetCode questions can be described using these main property families:

A. Surface properties

How the problem is worded.

B. Structural properties

What the problem really is underneath.

C. Objective properties

What kind of answer is required.

D. Search-space properties

What brute force would enumerate.

E. Constraint properties

What restrictions shape the solution.

F. State properties

What information must be remembered.

G. Transition properties

How state changes.

H. Invariant properties

What remains true during execution.

I. Complexity / tractability properties

How growth behaves.

J. Proof properties

What style of reasoning justifies the algorithm.

K. Implementation properties

What makes coding easy or dangerous.

L. Extension properties

How the problem generalizes.

That is the full master map.

⸻

3. Surface properties

These are the outer, statement-level properties.

They are shallow, but still useful.

3.1 Story disguise property

Many questions are dressed in story language.

Examples:
	•	robber
	•	island
	•	ladder
	•	oranges
	•	meetings
	•	courses

Property:
	•	the statement may hide the structural object behind a domain metaphor

This matters because good solvers strip surface story early.

⸻

3.2 Domain vocabulary property

A question may sound like:
	•	finance
	•	scheduling
	•	geometry
	•	strings
	•	board game
	•	networking
	•	social feed
	•	caching

But the real computational property may be completely different.

⸻

3.3 Example-guided property

Some problems become clear only after reading examples, because examples reveal:
	•	identity
	•	ordering
	•	duplicates
	•	intended structure
	•	hidden assumptions

⸻

4. Structural properties

These are the deepest identity properties.

⸻

4.1 Object property

What kind of object is central?

Possible values:
	•	sequence
	•	string
	•	interval
	•	grid
	•	tree
	•	graph
	•	linked list
	•	state space
	•	design object
	•	multiset
	•	matrix
	•	parser stream

This is one of the most fundamental properties.

⸻

4.2 Relation property

What relation defines the problem?

Possible relation properties:
	•	pair relation
	•	tuple relation
	•	prefix relation
	•	suffix relation
	•	adjacency relation
	•	connectivity relation
	•	dependency relation
	•	recurrence relation
	•	path relation
	•	matching relation
	•	containment relation
	•	interval overlap relation
	•	transformation relation

This often matters more than the surface domain.

⸻

4.3 Structure depth property

How much nested structure exists?

Examples:
	•	flat sequence
	•	2D grid
	•	hierarchical tree
	•	arbitrary graph
	•	recursive state graph
	•	multi-structure design object

More structure usually means more sophisticated state and invariants.

⸻

5. Objective properties

What type of answer does the question want?

Possible objective properties:
	•	decision
	•	search
	•	optimization
	•	counting
	•	enumeration
	•	transformation
	•	verification
	•	reconstruction
	•	simulation
	•	design/API behavior

These heavily affect tractability and approach.

⸻

5.1 Single-answer vs multi-answer property

Does the question want:
	•	one answer
	•	best answer
	•	count of answers
	•	all answers

This changes everything.

Examples:
	•	one pair
	•	maximum value
	•	number of ways
	•	all combinations

⸻

5.2 Value vs structure output property

Does it return:
	•	numeric result
	•	boolean
	•	indices
	•	modified array
	•	linked structure
	•	list of lists
	•	path / sequence of choices

This affects implementation and state reconstruction.

⸻

6. Search-space properties

This is one of the most important families.

Every LeetCode question has an implicit brute-force universe.

⸻

6.1 Candidate-space property

What would brute force enumerate?

Possible values:
	•	all pairs
	•	all triples
	•	all windows
	•	all subarrays
	•	all substrings
	•	all subsequences
	•	all subsets
	•	all assignments
	•	all paths
	•	all partitions
	•	all states
	•	all subproblems
	•	all operation histories

This property determines the raw combinatorial pressure.

⸻

6.2 Explosion property

How does brute force blow up?

Possible values:
	•	quadratic
	•	cubic
	•	exponential
	•	factorial
	•	pseudo-polynomial
	•	output-sensitive

This is the root of optimization.

⸻

6.3 Redundancy property

What repeated waste exists?

Possible values:
	•	repeated lookup
	•	repeated range aggregation
	•	repeated state solving
	•	repeated path exploration
	•	repeated candidate comparison
	•	repeated connectivity testing
	•	repeated structure rebuilding

This is the main bridge to a better algorithm.

⸻

7. Constraint properties

These are extremely important.

⸻

7.1 Identity property

Do specific instances/positions matter?

Examples:
	•	return indices -> yes
	•	duplicates with different positions -> yes
	•	only values matter -> maybe no

This affects sorting, grouping, deduplication, etc.

⸻

7.2 Order property

Does order matter?

Possible values:
	•	original order matters
	•	relative order matters
	•	sorted order matters
	•	no order significance

This is a foundational property.

⸻

7.3 Contiguity property

Does the valid answer have to be:
	•	contiguous
	•	non-contiguous
	•	connected
	•	arbitrary subset
	•	arbitrary sequence of states

This strongly predicts:
	•	sliding window
	•	subsequence DP
	•	graph traversal
	•	backtracking

⸻

7.4 Adjacency property

What counts as neighboring?

Possible adjacency:
	•	next index
	•	previous index
	•	parent-child
	•	grid direction
	•	graph edge
	•	same component
	•	edit-distance neighbor
	•	parser-token successor
	•	next unresolved greater element

This is a deep property of the problem world.

⸻

7.5 Duplicates property

Are duplicates:
	•	allowed
	•	important
	•	dangerous
	•	irrelevant
	•	grouped
	•	needing deduplication

Duplicate semantics often control both correctness and implementation.

⸻

7.6 Weighted vs unweighted property

Especially for graphs, intervals, choices, and DP.

Weighted property usually changes:
	•	BFS -> Dijkstra
	•	simple counting -> optimization
	•	unweighted recurrence -> weighted recurrence

⸻

7.7 Online vs offline property

Can all data be known in advance, or must answers be updated live?

This matters in:
	•	query problems
	•	design problems
	•	streaming extensions

⸻

7.8 In-place requirement property

Does the solution prefer or require:
	•	no extra memory
	•	mutation of original structure

This often changes implementation strategy.

⸻

8. State properties

The state is the heart of algorithmic solution.

⸻

8.1 State existence property

Does the problem need explicit maintained state beyond loop indices?

Some simple problems barely do.
Many do.

⸻

8.2 State family property

Possible state types:
	•	scalar state
	•	prefix state
	•	window state
	•	frontier state
	•	component state
	•	path state
	•	subproblem state
	•	structural mutation state
	•	synchronized object state
	•	metadata state
	•	parser state
	•	bitmask state

This is one of the strongest labels a question can have.

⸻

8.3 State dimension property

How many axes does state have?

Examples:
	•	1D: dp[i]
	•	2D: dp[i][j]
	•	3D: (i, k, holding)
	•	bitmask + node
	•	interval (l, r)

State dimension strongly affects complexity.

⸻

8.4 State compressibility property

Can full state be reduced to:
	•	two scalars
	•	rolling row
	•	prefix summary
	•	representative root
	•	active frontier only

This is crucial for optimization.

⸻

8.5 State stability property

Does the same state always mean the same future answer?

If yes:
	•	memoization is possible

If no:
	•	hidden mutable context may break cache reuse

This is a subtle but powerful property.

⸻

9. Transition properties

How does the algorithm move?

⸻

9.1 Transition locality property

Does a state depend on:
	•	immediate previous state
	•	a few neighbors
	•	all previous states
	•	children only
	•	all split points
	•	active frontier

This predicts complexity and implementation style.

⸻

9.2 Transition cost property

Per-state transition may be:
	•	O(1)
	•	O(log n)
	•	O(k)
	•	O(n)
	•	all-splits
	•	all-neighbors

This is central to runtime.

⸻

9.3 Reversibility property

Do transitions need undo?

Examples:
	•	backtracking yes
	•	BFS no
	•	DP fill no
	•	sliding window partially reversible
	•	in-place rewiring generally permanent

⸻

9.4 Monotone progress property

Does execution only move forward?

Examples:
	•	left/right pointers
	•	topological order
	•	BFS layers
	•	binary search interval shrink
	•	monotonic stack candidate elimination

If yes, huge optimizations often become possible.

⸻

10. Invariant properties

Every strong LeetCode problem has an invariant shape.

Possible invariant properties:
	•	processed prefix is summarized correctly
	•	current window state matches exact window
	•	queue holds current BFS frontier
	•	stack holds unresolved monotone candidates
	•	dp state is fully solved
	•	current recursion path matches chosen decisions
	•	representative root matches component identity
	•	cache and list stay synchronized
	•	search interval still contains answer

The invariant property is one of the deepest properties a question can have.

⸻

11. Complexity properties

Now the runtime/space side.

⸻

11.1 Growth-class property

Possible values:
	•	O(1)
	•	O(log n)
	•	O(n)
	•	O(n log n)
	•	O(n²)
	•	O(n³)
	•	pseudo-polynomial
	•	exponential small-n
	•	factorial small-n
	•	output-sensitive

⸻

11.2 Tractability property

Possible values:
	•	fully tractable
	•	tractable only for medium n
	•	tractable only for small n
	•	target-bounded tractable
	•	output-size bounded
	•	parameter-bounded tractable

⸻

11.3 Dominant-resource property

What really dominates:
	•	time
	•	memory
	•	state count
	•	transition cost
	•	output size
	•	recursion depth

⸻

11.4 Amortization property

Does the runtime require amortized reasoning?

Examples:
	•	monotonic stack
	•	monotonic deque
	•	union-find
	•	some design problems

⸻

12. Proof properties

What reasoning style fits the problem?

Possible proof properties:
	•	induction
	•	contradiction
	•	exchange argument
	•	monotonicity
	•	recurrence correctness
	•	exhaustive coverage
	•	invariant preservation
	•	frontier optimality
	•	dominance elimination
	•	component coverage

A problem often has a natural proof property matching its main algorithm family.

⸻

13. Implementation properties

These describe coding behavior, not just theory.

⸻

13.1 Boundary sensitivity property

Does correctness depend heavily on:
	•	loop endpoints
	•	half-open vs closed intervals
	•	grid bounds
	•	left < right vs left <= right

⸻

13.2 Update-order sensitivity property

Is line order crucial?

Examples:
	•	query before insert
	•	shrink after expand
	•	pop stale before using heap top
	•	save next before rewiring
	•	undo after recursion returns

Many LeetCode problems have this property.

⸻

13.3 Mutation-risk property

Does the problem involve dangerous mutation?

Examples:
	•	linked lists
	•	in-place arrays
	•	design state sync
	•	backtracking with undo

⸻

13.4 Sentinel / initialization sensitivity

Examples:
	•	DP base cases
	•	memo “uncomputed” marker
	•	infinity values
	•	empty structure handling

⸻

13.5 Duplicate-sensitivity property

Some implementations break only on duplicates.

This is a recurring property.

⸻

14. Difficulty properties

Instead of only easy/medium/hard, classify why it is hard.

Possible difficulty properties:
	•	disguised pattern
	•	state hard to define
	•	transition hard to derive
	•	invariant hard to see
	•	greedy proof hard
	•	monotonicity hidden
	•	recursion state explosion
	•	duplicate semantics tricky
	•	stale state handling tricky
	•	recurrence design hard
	•	interval reasoning hard
	•	pointer mutation risky
	•	extension reasoning hard

This is a much more useful property family than just difficulty rating.

⸻

15. Extension properties

How does the problem generalize?

Possible extension properties:
	•	k-generalizable
	•	weighted version exists
	•	online version exists
	•	counting version exists
	•	reconstruction version exists
	•	all-solutions version exists
	•	circular version exists
	•	tree version exists
	•	graph version exists
	•	dynamic-update version exists
	•	streaming version exists
	•	distributed version exists

This property tells you how the problem sits inside a larger family.

⸻

16. Meta-properties shared by huge groups of questions

Now the really deep universal properties.

⸻

16.1 Compressibility property

Can brute force be compressed into a smaller summary/state?

This is one of the most important universal properties.

Examples:
	•	prefix sum
	•	hash cache
	•	rolling DP
	•	DSU representative
	•	frontier only
	•	monotone candidate stack

⸻

16.2 Overlap property

Do smaller subproblems repeat?

If yes:
	•	memoization / DP may apply

⸻

16.3 Monotonicity property

Does a once-invalid or once-dominated region stay that way?

If yes:
	•	binary search
	•	two pointers
	•	monotonic structures
	•	greedy discarding

⸻

16.4 Frontier property

Is there a small active subset of useful states at a time?

If yes:
	•	queue
	•	heap
	•	deque
	•	stack
	•	topological ready-set

⸻

16.5 Reversibility property

Must decisions be undone?

If yes:
	•	backtracking
	•	reversible state management

⸻

16.6 Locality property

Can the next answer/state be computed from nearby information only?

If yes:
	•	iterative scans
	•	rolling DP
	•	local updates
	•	windows
	•	linear recurrences

⸻

16.7 Reusability property

Can a solved state remain valid later?

If yes:
	•	caching / memoization / tabulation / metadata storage

⸻

17. Universal property template for any LeetCode question

Use this template.

Surface properties

