And you want a clean architecture for solving any question.

That means:

1. What system-level thinking means for LeetCode

System-level thinking means you treat every question as a small computational system.

Not:
	•	“write loop”
	•	“use hashmap”
	•	“do DFS”

But:
	•	what is the system receiving?
	•	what internal state does it maintain?
	•	what operations are needed?
	•	what data flows through it?
	•	what constraints does it obey?
	•	what output contract must it satisfy?
	•	what subcomponents exist?
	•	how can the solution be decomposed cleanly?

So system-level thinking is:

model the problem as a pipeline of responsibilities, not as random lines of code.

⸻

2. What clean architecture means here

For LeetCode, clean architecture means:
	•	separate problem understanding from algorithm choice
	•	separate state model from execution engine
	•	separate core logic from edge handling
	•	separate data representation from transition rules
	•	separate proof/invariant layer from implementation layer
	•	separate testing/validation from the main algorithm

So instead of writing tangled code, you think in layers.

⸻

3. The master clean architecture for all LeetCode questions

Every question should be handled through these layers:

Layer A — Contract layer

What exactly is the input/output contract?

Layer B — Domain model layer

What is the true computational object?

Layer C — State layer

What must the system remember?

Layer D — Policy layer

What decision rules solve the problem?

Layer E — Execution layer

How are those rules applied step by step?

Layer F — Verification layer

How do we know the state remains correct?

Layer G — Extension layer

How would this system adapt if the problem changed?

That is the full architecture.

⸻

4. Layer A — Contract layer

This is the external interface of the problem.

Ask:
	•	what is the input type?
	•	what is the output type?
	•	what does “correct answer” mean?
	•	are there guarantees?
	•	are there edge-case obligations?
	•	what is forbidden?
	•	are duplicates allowed?
	•	can input be empty?
	•	are values bounded?

Examples:
	•	return indices, not values
	•	return one answer, not all
	•	return maximum value only
	•	modify in place
	•	preserve order
	•	use each element once
	•	graph may be disconnected
	•	exactly one solution exists

This is the API contract of the question.

If you misunderstand this layer, the whole system is wrong.

⸻

5. Layer B — Domain model layer

Now translate the story into the true internal system model.

Examples:
	•	Two Sum -> indexed sequence + complement relation
	•	Number of Islands -> grid graph + connected components
	•	House Robber -> linear value sequence + adjacency exclusion
	•	Course Schedule -> directed dependency graph + cycle property
	•	LRU Cache -> synchronized key-node-recency system
	•	Edit Distance -> alignment over prefix states
	•	Sliding Window Maximum -> active interval + dominant frontier

This is the core domain abstraction.

Clean architecture demands that you identify this before picking code.

⸻

6. Layer C — State layer

This is the heart of the system.

Ask:
	•	what internal state does the system need?
	•	what is persistent?
	•	what is temporary?
	•	what is computed?
	•	what is derived?
	•	what must stay synchronized?

Possible state families:

Scalar state
	•	current sum
	•	best
	•	carry
	•	parity
	•	remaining budget

Prefix state
	•	seen values
	•	prefix sum
	•	last seen index
	•	cumulative count

Window state
	•	left/right
	•	counts
	•	satisfied constraints

Frontier state
	•	queue
	•	stack
	•	heap
	•	deque

Component state
	•	visited
	•	parent
	•	representative
	•	indegree

Subproblem state
	•	dp[i]
	•	dp[i][j]
	•	memo(mask, i)

Path state
	•	current recursion path
	•	used markers
	•	board placements

Structural state
	•	linked list pointers
	•	bucket lists
	•	node references

Synchronized object state
	•	hashmap + doubly linked list
	•	freq map + ordered buckets
	•	min stack plus actual stack

This layer is the system’s memory architecture.

⸻

7. Layer D — Policy layer

This is where the algorithmic intelligence lives.

Policy means:
	•	what rules does the system follow to make progress?

Examples:

Hash policy

If needed complement already exists, answer found; else cache current.

Window policy

Expand until valid/invalid, then shrink under rule.

DP policy

Solve state from already solved smaller states.

Greedy policy

At each point choose locally safest best candidate.

BFS policy

Explore frontier in layers.

Dijkstra policy

Expand smallest current tentative distance first.

Backtracking policy

Choose, recurse, undo.

DSU policy

Merge representatives, not raw nodes.

This is the decision engine of the solution.

You can think of it as the “business logic” of the problem.

⸻

8. Layer E — Execution layer

Now we ask:
	•	how does the system operationally run?

This is the compute engine.

Possible execution styles:

Scan engine

for-loop / linear pass

Boundary engine

two pointers / sliding window

Frontier engine

while queue/heap/deque not empty

Recursive engine

DFS / divide-and-conquer / backtracking

Table-fill engine

bottom-up DP

Event engine

sweep line / sorted events

API engine

sequence of operations mutating internal state

This layer is about:
	•	control flow
	•	ordering
	•	step sequencing

A key system-level rule:

keep the policy separate from the execution skeleton.

Example:
	•	policy = monotone candidate elimination
	•	execution = for each element, pop dominated, push current

⸻

9. Layer F — Verification layer

This is the correctness layer.

Clean architecture means the system is designed around verifiable truths.

Ask:
	•	what invariant must always hold?
	•	what preconditions/postconditions does each step maintain?
	•	what makes each subsystem trustworthy?

Examples:

Hashing invariant

Map summarizes all relevant processed prefix information.

Sliding window invariant

Counts match exactly the active window.

Monotonic stack invariant

Stack contains unresolved candidates in monotone order.

BFS invariant

All dequeued nodes have finalized shortest unweighted distance.

DP invariant

Every filled state is correct when used.

LRU invariant

Map and list agree on key ownership and recency ordering.

Linked-list invariant

All nodes remain reachable and correctly rewired.

This layer is what prevents architecture from degenerating into hacks.

⸻

10. Layer G — Extension layer

System-level thinking always asks:
	•	what if requirements change?

This matters even in LeetCode because many hard questions are extensions of easier ones.

Examples:

Two Sum
	•	one answer -> all pairs
	•	array -> stream
	•	static -> multiple queries
	•	2-sum -> k-sum

House Robber
	•	linear -> circular -> tree

Shortest path
	•	unweighted -> weighted -> negative edges

Window problems
	•	one constraint -> multiple constraints
	•	exact distinct -> at most K distinct

LRU
	•	recency only -> recency + frequency (LFU)

A clean architecture makes extension easier because:
	•	state meaning is explicit
	•	contracts are clear
	•	decision rules are isolated

