1. Arrays / direct scan architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	array / sequence

Output:
	•	scalar answer, index, transformed array, or boolean

Domain model

A linear ordered sequence where each new element can be processed relative to a summary of what came before.

State

Usually small:
	•	current value
	•	best value
	•	running sum
	•	min/max so far
	•	answer accumulator

Policy

For each element:
	•	update local running state
	•	update global answer if improved

Execution engine
	•	single for loop
	•	sometimes two directional passes

Invariant

After processing index i, the maintained state correctly summarizes the prefix 0..i.

Main risks
	•	wrong initialization
	•	all-negative/all-zero edge cases
	•	off-by-one on bounds
	•	mixing “current” and “best” semantics

Extensions
	•	scalar -> prefix/suffix
	•	one pass -> two pass
	•	value only -> return indices / range
	•	linear -> circular array variants

⸻

2. Hashing architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	sequence or stream
Output:
	•	existence, pair, count, group, or location

Domain model

Current element needs fast access to information about previously seen elements or grouped keys.

State
	•	hash map / hash set
	•	key
	•	payload

Examples:
	•	value -> index
	•	value -> count
	•	normalized_form -> group

Policy

At each step:
	•	derive key/query
	•	lookup prior info
	•	act on hit or miss
	•	update cache

Execution engine
	•	single scan
	•	sometimes plus preprocessing normalization

Invariant

The hash structure summarizes exactly the relevant information from processed elements.

Main risks
	•	wrong key choice
	•	wrong payload meaning
	•	overwrite policy wrong
	•	duplicate semantics broken
	•	using “contains value” when earliest/latest occurrence matters

Extensions
	•	static array -> stream
	•	one answer -> all answers
	•	exact lookup -> grouped lookup
	•	single key -> composite key

⸻

3. Prefix / cumulative architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	sequence
Output:
	•	range aggregate, count, feasibility, or optimized statistic

Domain model

Many questions depend on cumulative facts about prefixes rather than raw elements.

State
	•	running prefix
	•	prefix array
	•	prefix count map
	•	cumulative min/max

Policy

Convert repeated range logic into prefix relation logic:
	•	range = prefix difference
	•	condition = relation between current prefix and earlier prefix

Execution engine
	•	one pass with cumulative update
	•	optional prefix preprocessing

Invariant

At position i, cached prefix summaries are correct for all processed positions up to i.

Main risks
	•	wrong prefix base initialization
	•	forgetting empty-prefix case
	•	integer overflow in cumulative sum
	•	using wrong difference direction

Extensions
	•	1D -> 2D prefix
	•	sum -> xor/parity/balance/count
	•	static queries -> query service object

⸻

4. Sliding window architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	array/string
Output:
	•	longest, shortest, count, or existence over contiguous region

Domain model

The answer lives on an active contiguous interval whose summary can be updated incrementally.

State
	•	left, right
	•	frequency map / counts
	•	validity metrics
	•	current best answer

Policy
	•	expand right
	•	incorporate new element
	•	while rule says shrink, move left
	•	record answer at the correct stage

Execution engine
	•	nested while inside single pass, but both pointers monotone

Invariant

The maintained state matches the exact current window [left, right].

Main risks
	•	shrink at wrong time
	•	record answer before validity established
	•	decrement/removal bugs
	•	misunderstanding “at most” vs “at least” vs “exactly”

Extensions
	•	one constraint -> many constraints
	•	fixed-size -> variable-size
	•	longest -> shortest
	•	distinct-count -> weighted deficit/surplus

⸻

5. Two pointers architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	usually ordered sequence or structure with directional semantics
Output:
	•	pair, partitioned array, merged result, or relation verdict

Domain model

Two moving boundaries or roles gradually narrow/transform the search space.

State
	•	left, right
	•	or slow/fast pointers
	•	or read/write pointers

Policy

At each step:
	•	evaluate current pointer relation
	•	move one or both pointers according to monotone rule

Execution engine
	•	while (left < right) or similar monotone pointer loop

Invariant

Everything outside the active pointer region is either resolved, discarded, or already placed correctly.

Main risks
	•	wrong movement rule
	•	pointer cross condition wrong
	•	infinite loop
	•	duplicate skipping errors
	•	forgetting sortedness requirement

Extensions
	•	opposite ends -> partition pointers
	•	array -> linked list fast/slow
	•	static -> merge two streams

⸻

6. Binary search architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	ordered search space or monotone predicate
Output:
	•	exact position, first/last valid, boundary, or optimized threshold

Domain model

The answer is embedded in an ordered domain where half the space can be discarded after each check.

State
	•	low, high, mid
	•	monotone predicate or compare target

Policy
	•	evaluate mid
	•	discard one half by monotonicity
	•	continue until boundary semantics resolve

Execution engine
	•	while (low < high) or while (low <= high) depending on convention

Invariant

The answer remains inside the maintained search interval.

Main risks
	•	closed vs half-open interval confusion
	•	wrong return after loop
	•	infinite loop on boundary updates
	•	predicate not actually monotone

Extensions
	•	direct search -> answer-space search
	•	static array -> feasibility threshold
	•	1D -> nested binary search with secondary check

⸻

7. Monotonic stack architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	sequence
Output:
	•	nearest greater/smaller, span, rectangle, or unresolved relation answer

Domain model

Each element cares about unresolved earlier candidates; dominated candidates can be discarded forever.

State
	•	stack, usually of indices
	•	sometimes auxiliary answer array

Policy

For each element:
	•	pop while stack top is resolved/dominated
	•	write effects for popped elements if needed
	•	push current index

Execution engine
	•	one forward or backward pass

Invariant

The stack remains monotone and contains only unresolved candidates still relevant to the future.

Main risks
	•	wrong comparison (< vs <=)
	•	storing values when indices needed
	•	misunderstanding direction (next vs previous)
	•	forgetting unresolved leftovers

Extensions
	•	next greater -> previous greater
	•	greater -> smaller
	•	one pass -> circular-array variants

⸻

8. Monotonic deque architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	sequence plus active interval/window
Output:
	•	window max/min or dynamic best candidate

Domain model

Need the best candidate in a moving region while expired or dominated candidates should be removed.

State
	•	deque of indices
	•	window boundaries

Policy

At each step:
	•	remove expired front
	•	remove dominated back
	•	push current
	•	front is current optimum

Execution engine
	•	single scan

Invariant

Deque is monotone and all stored indices are valid members of current or future windows.

Main risks
	•	expiry before use vs after use
	•	dominance inequality wrong
	•	off-by-one on window start

Extensions
	•	max -> min
	•	fixed window -> bounded online window
	•	use inside DP transition optimization

⸻

9. Heap / priority architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	collection of candidates / weighted frontier
Output:
	•	repeated best candidate, top-k, or weighted shortest/optimal progression

Domain model

At any time, many candidates exist, but only the currently highest-priority one should be processed next.

State
	•	min-heap or max-heap
	•	priority definition
	•	optional auxiliary maps/arrays for stale detection

Policy
	•	push candidate states
	•	pop best-priority state
	•	expand/update as needed
	•	ignore stale if policy allows duplicates

Execution engine
	•	while heap not empty

Invariant

Heap contains the active frontier ordered by the chosen priority rule.

Main risks
	•	comparator reversed
	•	stale entries mishandled
	•	forgetting tie semantics
	•	not bounding heap for top-k

Extensions
	•	static top-k -> streaming top-k
	•	shortest path -> best-first search variants
	•	heap + hash for mutable-key design problems

⸻

10. BFS architecture

Contract

Input:
	•	graph, grid, or implicit state space
Output:
	•	shortest unweighted distance, reachability layers, propagation time, or component discovery

Domain model

State space expands in concentric layers from one or more sources.

State
	•	queue
	•	visited
	•	optional distance/time/level

Policy
	•	initialize source frontier
	•	pop current state
	•	inspect neighbors
	•	enqueue undiscovered neighbors

Execution engine
	•	queue-driven loop

Invariant

States are processed in nondecreasing layer distance; discovered states are never rediscovered unnecessarily.

Main risks
	•	visited marking too late
	•	level counting errors
	•	neighbor bounds mistakes
	•	using BFS where weights invalidate shortest-step guarantee

Extensions
	•	single-source -> multi-source
	•	explicit graph -> implicit state graph
	•	shortest path -> reconstruct path with parent map

