So all type of search space in depth





Here is the full in-depth system of search space for LeetCode.

This is one of the deepest topics.

Because every LeetCode question secretly contains a search space, even if the final optimal solution never explicitly explores it.

If you understand search space, you understand:
	•	what brute force would do
	•	why it explodes
	•	what is being avoided
	•	what is being compressed
	•	what the optimized algorithm is really replacing

So this is foundational.

⸻

1. What search space means

A search space is:

the full universe of candidate possibilities that could, in principle, be explored to solve the problem.

That universe may contain:
	•	candidate answers
	•	intermediate states
	•	decision sequences
	•	paths
	•	partitions
	•	subproblems
	•	transformations
	•	operation histories

So search space is not always:
	•	“all final outputs”

Sometimes it is:
	•	all ways of getting to an output

That distinction matters a lot.

⸻

2. Why search space matters

Search space tells you:

A. What brute force is really searching

Not just “nested loops,” but what conceptual candidates those loops represent.

B. Why a problem is hard

Because the search space may be:
	•	quadratic
	•	exponential
	•	factorial
	•	infinite-looking until constrained

C. What optimization must remove

Good algorithms do not magically solve problems.
They exploit structure to avoid searching the entire raw space.

D. What the problem family is

A problem about:
	•	all subarrays
is different from one about
	•	all subsets
even if both use “array” input

So search-space identity is deeper than object identity.

⸻

3. The master definition

For any LeetCode problem, search space should be defined as:

the set of all candidate configurations that a correct solution might need to distinguish among, directly or indirectly.

That means search space can be:
	•	explicit
	•	implicit
	•	direct
	•	transformed
	•	compressed
	•	pruned
	•	represented as states instead of outputs

⸻

4. The 3 main levels of search space

This is very important.

Every problem has at least one of these, often several.

Level 1 — Answer search space

All possible final answers.

Examples:
	•	all pairs
	•	all substrings
	•	all subsets
	•	all paths
	•	all partitions

Level 2 — Decision search space

All possible sequences of choices that could construct an answer.

Examples:
	•	choose / skip at each position
	•	place queen in any column
	•	take edge transitions through graph
	•	cut or not cut partition point

Level 3 — State search space

All distinct computational states reachable during solving.

Examples:
	•	(i, j) in DP
	•	(node, mask)
	•	current BFS node
	•	active window boundaries
	•	parser mode/state
	•	heap frontier entries

Modern efficient solutions often stop searching over full answers and instead search over compressed states.

This is one of the deepest insights.

⸻

5. Direct vs indirect search space

Direct search space

The algorithm explicitly explores candidates.

Examples:
	•	backtracking over subsets
	•	DFS over paths
	•	BFS over state graph
	•	permutation generation

Indirect search space

The algorithm does not enumerate answers directly, but still reasons over them through compressed structure.

Examples:
	•	DP over subproblems
	•	binary search over ordered answer space
	•	greedy over feasible candidates
	•	prefix/hash compression replacing pair checks

Example:
Two Sum brute force searches all pairs directly.
Hashing does not explicitly search all pairs, but it still solves the same answer space indirectly.

⸻

6. Finite search-space families across LeetCode

Now the main taxonomy.

⸻

7. Pair search space

Definition

All unordered or ordered pairs of elements/positions.

Examples
	•	Two Sum
	•	container with most water
	•	max profit pair
	•	many interval-pair problems

Raw size
	•	O(n²)

Structure

Candidates are:
	•	(i, j)

Sometimes with:
	•	i < j
	•	or all ordered pairs

Typical optimization
	•	hashing
	•	sorting + two pointers
	•	prefix summary
	•	monotonic reasoning

Core difficulty

Pair explosion is quadratic.

Deep note

Many sequence relation problems are really pair-space problems in disguise.

⸻

8. Triple / k-tuple search space

Definition

All triples or k-sized tuples from input.

Examples
	•	3Sum
	•	4Sum
	•	k-Sum
	•	tuple relation tasks

Raw size
	•	O(n³), O(n⁴), O(n^k)

Structure

Candidates are:
	•	(i, j, k, ...)

Typical optimization
	•	sorting
	•	recursive reduction
	•	meet-in-the-middle
	•	pruning
	•	dedup structure

Deep note

As k grows, tuple search becomes combinatorial very quickly unless extra structure exists.

⸻

9. Subarray search space

Definition

All contiguous subarrays.

Examples
	•	maximum subarray
	•	subarray sum equals k
	•	min-size subarray
	•	range aggregate problems

Raw size
	•	O(n²) subarrays

Structure

Each candidate is defined by:
	•	(left, right)

with contiguity mandatory.

Typical optimization
	•	prefix sums
	•	sliding window
	•	monotonic deque
	•	DP / Kadane
	•	hash on prefix relation

Deep note

Subarray search space is much smaller than subsequence space, but still too large for brute force at scale.

⸻

10. Substring search space

Definition

All contiguous substrings of a string.

Examples
	•	longest substring without repeats
	•	minimum window substring
	•	longest palindromic substring
	•	repeated-pattern substring problems

Raw size
	•	O(n²)

Structure

Also boundary-defined:
	•	(left, right)

Typical optimization
	•	sliding window
	•	center expansion
	•	DP
	•	suffix/prefix structures
	•	hashing/last seen

Deep note

Substring problems often become window-state or interval-state problems.

⸻

11. Subsequence search space

Definition

All not-necessarily-contiguous subsequences.

Examples
	•	subsequence checks
	•	LCS
	•	longest increasing subsequence variants
	•	counting subsequences
	•	distinct subsequences

Raw size
	•	O(2^n)

Structure

Each element may be:
	•	included
	•	excluded

Typical optimization
	•	DP
	•	memoization
	•	greedy + binary search in special structured cases like LIS
	•	counting recurrences

Deep note

Subsequence search is fundamentally much larger than substring search.

This distinction is one of the most important in LeetCode.

⸻

12. Subset search space

Definition

All subsets of a collection.

Examples
	•	Subsets
	•	partition problems
	•	subset sum
	•	can partition
	•	bitmask DP

Raw size
	•	O(2^n)

Structure

Binary choice per item:
	•	take / skip

Typical optimization
	•	backtracking
	•	DP
	•	bitmasking
	•	meet-in-the-middle
	•	pseudo-polynomial compression when target bounded

Deep note

Subset search space is one of the canonical exponential spaces.

⸻

13. Permutation search space

Definition

All orderings of elements.

Examples
	•	permutations
	•	next permutation
	•	arrangement problems
	•	assignment-order problems

Raw size
	•	O(n!)

Structure

At step k, choose one unused item.

Typical optimization
	•	backtracking
	•	lexicographic construction
	•	factorial number system
	•	pruning

Deep note

Permutation space is much larger than subset space.

Because:
	•	subset = choose membership
	•	permutation = choose both membership and order

⸻

14. Combination search space

Definition

All size-k selections, or all unordered selections under some restriction.

Examples
	•	combinations
	•	k-combination sum
	•	choose k numbers

Raw size
	•	O(C(n,k)) or more generally binomial family

Typical optimization
	•	backtracking
	•	pruning with remaining-capacity bounds
	•	combinatorial indexing

Deep note

Combination search is smaller than full subset search if k is fixed/small.

⸻

15. Partition search space

Definition

All ways to split an object into segments/groups.

Examples
	•	palindrome partitioning
	•	word break
	•	restore IP addresses
	•	partition array/string problems

Raw size

Often exponential.

For string of length n:
	•	cut or not cut between adjacent positions
	•	often about 2^(n-1) possible cut patterns

Typical optimization
	•	DP
	•	memoization
	•	backtracking + pruning

Deep note

Partition space is boundary-choice space.

⸻

16. Assignment search space

Definition

All ways of assigning resources, labels, tasks, or matches.

Examples
	•	N-Queens
	•	task assignment
	•	matchings
	•	colorings
	•	Sudoku filling
	•	graph coloring-like search

Raw size

Often exponential or factorial.

Typical optimization
	•	backtracking
	•	branch and bound
	•	bitmask DP
	•	matching algorithms when structure is special

Deep note

Assignment spaces are broader than permutations because the mapping may be partial, constrained, or many-to-one.

⸻

17. Path search space

Definition

All possible paths through a graph, tree, grid, or state graph.

Examples
	•	path sum
	•	all paths source to target
	•	maze/path existence
	•	shortest path if brute-forced naively
	•	word search

Raw size

Can be:
	•	exponential
	•	potentially huge even in moderate graphs

Typical optimization
	•	BFS/DFS with visited
	•	DP on DAGs
	•	shortest path algorithms
	•	pruning
	•	memoization on acyclic state spaces

Deep note

Path space is often one of the largest and most dangerous spaces.

⸻

18. State-transition search space

Definition

All reachable states of a dynamic process.

Examples
	•	BFS over lock combinations
	•	sliding puzzle
	•	word ladder
	•	game states
	•	parser automata
	•	stock DP state machines

Raw size

Depends on state dimensions.

Can be:
	•	polynomial
	•	exponential
	•	very large but sparse

Typical optimization
	•	BFS
	•	memoization
	•	DP
	•	graph search
	•	visited compression

Deep note

Many advanced problems are better understood as state-space search than as answer-space search.

⸻

19. Subproblem search space

Definition

All distinct subproblems needed by a DP/memoized solution.

Examples
	•	edit distance states (i, j)
	•	interval DP (l, r)
	•	mask DP (mask, i)
	•	coin change (i, rem)

Raw size

Defined by number of unique states.

Examples:
	•	O(n)
	•	O(n²)
	•	O(n·target)
	•	O(n·2^n)

Typical optimization
	•	memoization
	•	bottom-up DP
	•	rolling compression
	•	transition optimization

Deep note

DP does not remove search.
It changes the search space from huge recursive trees to a smaller state graph.

⸻

20. Interval search space

Definition

All intervals or interval relationships.

Examples
	•	merge intervals
	•	interval scheduling
	•	interval DP
	•	longest palindromic substring
	•	burst balloons

Raw size
	•	O(n²) intervals
	•	often more if you consider split points too

Typical optimization
	•	sorting
	•	greedy
	•	boundary scans
	•	interval DP

Deep note

Interval search is a special boundary-defined family with strong ordered structure.

⸻

21. Window search space

Definition

All active contiguous regions considered as movable windows.

This is related to subarrays/substrings, but operationally different.

Examples
	•	min window substring
	•	at most K distinct
	•	fixed-size window max

Raw size

Still O(n²) possible windows in raw form.

Typical optimization
	•	sliding window
	•	deque
	•	hashing

Deep note

Window space is a maintainable subarray/substring search space.

The distinction is:
	•	subarray space = all boundary pairs
	•	window protocol = efficient traversal of a special subset/order through that space

⸻

22. Range-answer search space

Definition

All possible numeric/ordered answers in some bounded interval.

Examples
	•	binary search on answer
	•	smallest feasible capacity
	•	minimum speed to arrive on time
	•	kth-threshold style problems

Raw size

Potentially huge numeric domain.

Typical optimization
	•	binary search if predicate monotone

Deep note

This is not searching over input objects, but over answer values.

Very important distinction.

⸻

23. Parse search space

Definition

All valid or possible interpretations of a token/string under grammar rules.

Examples
	•	regex matching
	•	wildcard matching
	•	decode ways
	•	arithmetic parsing
	•	expression generation

Raw size

Often exponential if parsed naively.

Typical optimization
	•	DP
	•	memoization
	•	parser stacks/state machines
	•	automata-like methods

Deep note

Parse space is interpretation space, not subset/pair/path space.

⸻

24. Reconstruction search space

Definition

All possible parent/choice chains that could produce a final optimal/valid result.

Examples
	•	reconstruct LCS
	•	recover path
	•	decode actual segmentation
	•	output actual choices after optimization

Raw size

Can be large, especially if many optimal solutions exist.

Typical optimization
	•	parent pointers
	•	stored predecessor choices
	•	one-path reconstruction vs all-path reconstruction

⸻

25. Operation-history search space

Definition

All possible sequences of operations applied to a mutable object.

Examples
	•	design problems
	•	browser history
	•	cache evolution
	•	stack/queue process simulation
	•	operation minimization problems

Raw size

Can be very large, especially online.

Typical optimization
	•	maintain internal state incrementally
	•	use invariants so full history need not be replayed

Deep note

Design problems often live here.

⸻

26. Search space by answer type

Another very powerful classification.

⸻

Decision search space

Need only decide if at least one valid candidate exists.

Examples:
	•	Word Break
	•	Jump Game
	•	Path Sum
	•	regex feasibility

This often allows:
	•	early exit
	•	boolean DP
	•	pruned search

⸻

Search / witness search space

Need one valid witness.

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
	•	find path
	•	return one pair
	•	restore one structure

Often smaller than full enumeration.

⸻

Optimization search space

Need best candidate under an objective.

Examples:
	•	max subarray
	•	min path sum
	•	longest valid substring
	•	shortest path

This changes search because:
	•	local pruning may require bounds or monotonicity
	•	DP / greedy become common

⸻

Counting search space

Need the number of valid candidates.

Examples:
	•	decode ways
	•	unique paths
	•	distinct subsequences

This usually requires:
	•	aggregating over many candidates, not just finding one

⸻

Enumeration search space

Need all valid candidates.

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	all paths
	•	all partitions

This is often output-sensitive and inherently huge.

⸻

27. Search space by compressibility

This is one of the deepest classifications.

⸻

Low-compressibility search space

Very hard to reduce without strong constraints.

Examples:
	•	all permutations
	•	all assignments
	•	arbitrary path enumeration

Often requires:
	•	pruning
	•	small n
	•	output-sensitive acceptance

⸻

Medium-compressibility search space

Can often be reduced using ordering, caching, or monotonicity.

Examples:
	•	all pairs
	•	all windows
	•	many path existence problems
	•	many state graphs

⸻

High-compressibility search space

Huge raw space, but strong structure collapses it.

Examples:
	•	repeated recursion -> DP
	•	pair search -> hash lookup
	•	subarray sums -> prefix relation
	•	interval overlap -> sweep line
	•	graph shortest path -> BFS/Dijkstra instead of all paths

This is where most beautiful LeetCode optimizations live.

⸻

28. Search space by explicitness

⸻

Explicit search space

You can list the candidates directly.

Examples:
	•	all pairs
	•	all subarrays
	•	all subsets
	•	all intervals

⸻

Implicit search space

Candidates are generated through transitions rather than direct listing.

Examples:
	•	BFS state graph
	•	puzzle states
	•	regex parse states
	•	recursive decision trees

These are often better understood as graph/state spaces.

⸻

29. Search space by dimensionality

⸻

1D search space

Examples:
	•	index i
	•	answer boundary
	•	single running state

⸻

2D search space

Examples:
	•	(i, j)
	•	window boundaries
	•	grid positions
	•	interval boundaries

⸻

3D+ search space

Examples:
	•	(day, transactions_left, holding)
	•	(node, mask, fuel)
	•	(i, j, mode)

Higher dimension usually means:
	•	more complexity
	•	bigger state space
	•	stronger need for compression

⸻

30. Search space by symmetry

Some spaces contain many equivalent candidates.

Examples:
	•	duplicate values
	•	permutations of identical elements
	•	symmetric board placements
	•	interchangeable components

This allows:
	•	deduplication
	•	pruning
	•	canonical ordering

Symmetry is a critical search-space property.

⸻

31. Search space by monotonicity

If candidates can be ordered so that invalidity/optimality changes once, search becomes easier.

Examples:
	•	binary search on answer
	•	two pointers on sorted arrays
	•	monotonic stacks/deques
	•	interval boundary elimination

Monotonicity is one of the most powerful search-space simplifiers.

⸻

32. Search space by locality

Some spaces can be explored with local updates.

Examples:
	•	sliding window
	•	rolling DP
	•	single-pass scans
	•	local pointer shifts

This is what enables O(n) over spaces that naïvely look O(n²).

⸻

33. Search space by output burden

This is crucial.

If output itself is huge, then large search is unavoidable.

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	all palindrome partitions
	•	all paths

This is called output-sensitive behavior.

The search space may be huge, but that may be acceptable because the answer itself is huge.

⸻

34. Search space by tractability class

⸻

Polynomial search spaces
	•	pairs
	•	intervals
	•	many DP grids
	•	graph traversal states

⸻

Pseudo-polynomial search spaces
	•	target-based DP
	•	knapsack
	•	subset-sum by value range

⸻

Exponential search spaces
	•	subsets
	•	partitions
	•	many path families
	•	recursive choices

⸻

Factorial search spaces
	•	permutations
	•	orderings
	•	assignment orders

This tells you how dangerous the raw universe is.

⸻

35. Search space vs state space

This distinction is one of the most important.

Search space

All raw candidates/choices/answers

State space

All distinct meaningful states needed to reason about those candidates efficiently

Example:
LCS

Raw search space:
	•	all subsequence pairings

Efficient state space:
	•	(i, j)

Example:
Word Break

Raw search space:
	•	all partitions of string

Efficient state space:
	•	index i meaning “can suffix starting at i be segmented?”

Example:
Two Sum

Raw search space:
