All about recurrence in all 3872 leetcode question 


Here is the master framework of recurrence for all 3872 LeetCode questions.

Recurrence is one of the deepest ideas in the whole LeetCode universe.

Because recurrence is not only “DP formula.”

It is the rule:

how a larger problem depends on smaller solved structure.

So recurrence appears in many forms:
	•	dynamic programming
	•	recursion
	•	divide and conquer
	•	tree aggregation
	•	parser state transitions
	•	greedy local update in disguised form
	•	rolling-state scans
	•	even some monotonic and graph formulations have recurrence-like state transitions

If you understand recurrence deeply, you understand:
	•	how to formulate subproblems
	•	how to compress search space
	•	how to define state
	•	how to justify transitions
	•	how to convert top-down to bottom-up
	•	how to optimize memory
	•	how to generalize problems

⸻

1. What recurrence really is

A recurrence is:

a rule that defines the answer for a state in terms of smaller, earlier, or simpler states.

Examples:
	•	Fibonacci: f(n) = f(n-1) + f(n-2)
	•	House Robber: dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], dp[i-2] + nums[i])
	•	Edit Distance: dp[i][j] from nearby cells
	•	Tree height: height(node) = 1 + max(height(left), height(right))

That is the standard view.

But more generally:

Recurrence means:
	•	how information flows
	•	what dependencies exist
	•	what must already be known
	•	what smaller building blocks define the current answer

So recurrence is the dependency law of the solution.

⸻

2. Why recurrence matters for all LeetCode questions

Across all 3872 questions, recurrence helps answer these questions:

A. What is the subproblem?

What smaller unit is meaningful?

B. What must be remembered?

What state is necessary?

C. How does the problem grow?

By one element? one boundary? one level? one decision?

D. What are the transitions?

What smaller states combine into this one?

E. Can the recursive explosion be compressed?

If yes, DP/memoization becomes possible.

So recurrence is one of the main bridges from:
	•	brute force
to
	•	optimized solution

⸻

3. The universal recurrence equation

For almost every recurrence-based LeetCode problem:

State meaning

Define what Solve(state) means.

Base case

Define smallest states with immediate answers.

Transition

Express current state from smaller states.

That is the full recurrence architecture.

So recurrence always has 3 parts:
	•	state
	•	base
	•	transition

If any of these are vague, the recurrence is weak.

⸻

4. Recurrence is bigger than DP

Many people think recurrence = DP only.

That is too narrow.

Recurrence appears in:

A. Pure recursion

Tree traversal, divide-and-conquer, backtracking

B. Memoized recursion

Top-down DP

C. Bottom-up DP

Tabulation

D. Structural recursion

Trees, lists, graphs/DAGs

E. Incremental scan recurrences

Kadane, stock, prefix updates, rolling state

F. Greedy local-update recurrences

Some greedy problems can be phrased as recurrence with a proof that only one branch matters

So recurrence is the dependency skeleton behind many solution families.

⸻

5. The 10 master recurrence families across LeetCode

This is the most important section.

⸻

Family 1 — Linear-prefix recurrence

Shape

State depends on one or a few earlier prefix states.

Examples:
	•	Fibonacci
	•	Climbing Stairs
	•	House Robber
	•	Max Subarray
	•	many stock DP problems
	•	decode ways

General form:
	•	dp[i] from dp[i-1], dp[i-2], etc.

Core property

Problem grows one index at a time.

Typical state
	•	prefix ending at i
	•	suffix starting at i
	•	best up to i

Common transition styles
	•	choose/skip
	•	take/not take
	•	extend/restart
	•	merge last step choices

Complexity

Usually:
	•	O(n)
	•	maybe O(k·n) if more prior states used

Compression

Often reducible to:
	•	O(1) scalars
	•	rolling arrays

This is one of the most common recurrence families.

⸻

Family 2 — Two-dimensional alignment recurrence

Shape

State depends on neighboring positions in a 2D grid.

Examples:
	•	LCS
	•	Edit Distance
	•	Distinct Subsequences
	•	Interleaving String
	•	many string alignment / sequence relation problems

General form:
	•	dp[i][j] from nearby states like
	•	dp[i-1][j]
	•	dp[i][j-1]
	•	dp[i-1][j-1]

Core property

Two sequences or two indices evolve jointly.

Typical meaning
	•	answer for prefixes/suffixes of two strings
	•	match feasibility/count/optimum for two coordinates

Complexity

Usually:
	•	O(nm)

Compression

Often:
	•	rolling rows
	•	rolling columns
if dependency is local enough

This is the classic sequence-alignment family.

⸻

Family 3 — Interval recurrence

Shape

State is defined on a subinterval (l, r).

Examples:
	•	Longest Palindromic Subsequence
	•	Burst Balloons
	•	Matrix Chain-like problems
	•	palindrome partition related DP
	•	many substring/interval DP problems

General form:
	•	dp[l][r] depends on:
	•	shrinking interval
	•	splitting interval at k
	•	both

Core property

Subproblem is not prefix-based, but boundary-based.

Typical transitions

Shrink recurrence
	•	dp[l][r] from dp[l+1][r], dp[l][r-1], dp[l+1][r-1]

Split recurrence
	•	dp[l][r] = combine(dp[l][k], dp[k+1][r])

Complexity
	•	O(n²) states
	•	O(n³) often if all split points tested

Fill order

Usually:
	•	shorter intervals -> longer intervals

This family is very important and often considered harder.

⸻

Family 4 — Grid-path recurrence

Shape

State at cell depends on neighboring cells.

Examples:
	•	Unique Paths
	•	Unique Paths II
	•	Minimum Path Sum
	•	Triangle
	•	some matrix DP problems

General form:
	•	dp[r][c] from top/left or other local neighbors

Core property

Movement rules define dependency neighborhood.

Typical transitions
	•	sum counts from parents
	•	take min/max among parents
	•	block with obstacle = zero/unreachable

Complexity
	•	O(rows × cols)

Compression

Often:
	•	one row
	•	one column
	•	in-place grid overwrite

This is one of the cleanest recurrence families.

⸻

Family 5 — Tree recurrence

Shape

Answer for a node depends on answers from its children.

Examples:
	•	tree depth
	•	balanced tree
	•	diameter
	•	path sum variants
	•	House Robber III
	•	max path sum

General form:
	•	solve(node) = combine(solve(left), solve(right), node.val, extra_state)

Core property

Tree structure gives natural recursive decomposition.

Typical state
	•	subtree answer
	•	tuple return values
	•	node + mode/flag

Examples:
	•	return height
	•	return (balanced, height)
	•	return (take, skip)
	•	return best downward path gain

Complexity

Usually:
	•	O(n)

Deep point

Tree recurrence is structural, not index-based.

⸻

Family 6 — DAG / graph-state recurrence

Shape

State depends on neighbors in a DAG or acyclic dependency graph.

Examples:
	•	Course Schedule-style DAG DP
	•	longest path in DAG
	•	DFS + memo on state graph
	•	some game/state search problems

General form:
	•	solve(u) = combine(solve(v) for v in outgoing_neighbors)

Core property

Dependencies form an acyclic graph or can be memoized safely.

Typical transitions
	•	max over neighbors
	•	sum over neighbors
	•	any/all over neighbors

Complexity
	•	number of states + transitions

Deep point

This is recurrence on a graph, not on an array/grid.

⸻

Family 7 — Decision-tree recurrence

Shape

State branches by choices.

Examples:
	•	subsets
	•	combination sum
	•	partitioning
	•	many recursive search problems
	•	stock with branching decisions

General form:
	•	solve(state) = combine(solve(choice_1), solve(choice_2), ...)

Core property

Each state has several possible next decisions.

Typical transitions
	•	choose / skip
	•	use / don’t use
	•	cut / don’t cut
	•	place in one of many positions

Complexity

Without memoization:
	•	often exponential

With memoization:
	•	depends on how many unique states remain

This is one of the most important recurrence families because many exponential recursions start here.

⸻

Family 8 — Bitmask / subset-state recurrence

Shape

State includes a subset mask and sometimes an endpoint or extra coordinate.

Examples:
	•	Traveling Salesman style
	•	assignment problems
	•	minimum path cover variants
	•	visiting-state problems
	•	some BFS/DP hybrids

General form:
	•	dp[mask][i]
	•	solve(mask, last)

Core property

State represents “which items are already used/visited/chosen.”

Typical transitions
	•	add one new bit/item
	•	transition to next endpoint

Complexity

Usually:
	•	O(n·2^n)
	•	O(2^n · transitions)

Deep point

This is recurrence over subset-state space, not just over indices.

⸻

Family 9 — Partition / segmentation recurrence

Shape

State at index depends on valid cut points.

Examples:
	•	Word Break
	•	Palindrome Partitioning
	•	Decode Ways
	•	Restore IP Addresses style counting/decision variants

General form:
	•	dp[i] from trying cuts j < i
	•	or solve(i) from all valid next segment endpoints

Core property

Current answer is built by splitting the sequence into valid segments.

Typical transitions
	•	for all valid segment ends:
	•	combine answer of suffix/prefix remainder

Complexity

Often:
	•	O(n²)
with validity precomputation or pruning

Deep point

This is a very common string recurrence family.

⸻

Family 10 — Rolling local-update recurrence

Shape

Current state updates from current input and small local state, often without explicit DP table.

Examples:
	•	Kadane
	•	best time to buy/sell stock
	•	running minima/maxima
	•	some greedy scans that still obey recurrence form

General form:
	•	state_i = update(state_{i-1}, input_i)

Core property

Recurrence is present but fully scalarized.

Examples

Kadane
	•	best ending here from previous best ending here

Stock I
	•	best profit from min-so-far and current price

Deep point

These are recurrence-based even if people do not call them DP.

⸻

6. The four most important recurrence styles

Across all 3872 questions, most recurrences are one of these four:

Style A — Extend / restart

Example:
	•	max subarray
	•	longest valid ending here
	•	build current from prior, maybe restart fresh

Style B — Take / skip

Example:
	•	House Robber
	•	subsets
	•	knapsack-like logic
	•	stock choices

Style C — Match / don’t match

Example:
	•	LCS
	•	edit distance
	•	regex/wildcard-like families
	•	subsequence counting

Style D — Split / partition

Example:
	•	interval DP
	•	word segmentation
	•	matrix chain-like reasoning
	•	palindrome partitions

These 4 styles cover a huge fraction of recurrence thinking in LeetCode.

⸻

7. Recurrence by objective type

Recurrence changes depending on what the problem asks for.

⸻

A. Decision recurrence

Answer is true/false.

Examples:
	•	Word Break
	•	can reach end
	•	regex match
	•	interleaving validity

Transition often uses:
	•	OR / AND logic
	•	any / all conditions

⸻

B. Counting recurrence

Answer is number of ways.

Examples:
	•	Unique Paths
	•	Decode Ways
	•	Distinct Subsequences
	•	coin change counting variants

Transition often uses:
	•	sum of valid smaller states

⸻

C. Optimization recurrence

Answer is min/max/best value.

Examples:
	•	House Robber
	•	Edit Distance
	•	Min Path Sum
	•	max path sum
	•	stock profit problems

Transition often uses:
	•	min / max over candidate transitions

⸻

D. Construction / reconstruction recurrence

Need actual solution, not just value.

Examples:
	•	reconstruct LCS
	•	path reconstruction
	•	partition reconstruction

Transition often stores:
	•	predecessor
	•	choice
	•	parent pointer

⸻

8. State meaning is the soul of recurrence

The most important skill is:

define exactly what the state means.

Examples:

Good

dp[i] = best answer for prefix [0..i]

Good

dp[i][j] = edit distance between first i chars of s and first j chars of t

Good

solve(node) = max downward path sum starting at this node

Bad

dp[i] = answer somehow around i

If state meaning is vague, recurrence will be vague.

If recurrence is vague, implementation and proof collapse.

⸻

9. Base cases in recurrence

Every recurrence depends on correct base cases.

Base cases represent:
	•	smallest solvable states
	•	empty structure
	•	exhausted input
	•	impossible state
	•	exact success state

Examples:

Linear
	•	dp[0]
	•	dp[1]

Grid
	•	first row
	•	first column

String alignment
	•	empty prefix vs non-empty prefix

Tree
	•	null node

Interval
	•	l > r
	•	l == r

Bitmask
	•	full mask reached
	•	empty mask

Many bugs come from weak base cases, not bad transitions.

⸻

10. Transition design in depth

A recurrence transition must answer:
	•	from which smaller states can this one be built?
	•	how are they combined?
	•	are all possibilities needed?
	•	is there symmetry or pruning?
	•	is the recurrence complete?

Typical transition operators:

max

best among choices

min

cheapest among choices

sum

count all valid ways

OR

existence of one valid way

tuple combine

return multiple pieces of info simultaneously

Examples:
	•	(balanced, height)
	•	(take, skip)
	•	(ways, cost)
	•	(best_down, best_anywhere)

Tuple recurrence is extremely important in tree and advanced DP problems.

⸻

11. Recurrence direction

A recurrence can be written in multiple directions.

⸻

Prefix direction

Build answer for first i items.

Suffix direction

Build answer from index i to end.

Interval direction

Build answer for segment (l, r).

Subtree direction

Build answer for subtree rooted at node.

Mask direction

Build answer for chosen/remaining subset.

Reverse direction

Sometimes easier to solve from target backwards.

Good recurrence design often depends on choosing the cleanest direction.

⸻

12. Top-down vs bottom-up recurrence

Same recurrence can often be implemented two ways.

⸻

Top-down
	•	think from full question downward
	•	recurse into needed smaller states
	•	memoize

Strength:
	•	natural derivation
	•	sparse-state friendly

Weakness:
	•	recursion overhead
	•	stack depth issues

⸻

Bottom-up
	•	start from base states
	•	fill upward in dependency order

Strength:
	•	explicit order
	•	easier memory compression
	•	no recursion stack

Weakness:
	•	fill order may be tricky
	•	may compute unused states

The recurrence is the same.
Only execution direction changes.

⸻

13. When recurrence is hidden

Some problems have a recurrence even when it is not obvious.

Examples:

Kadane

Looks like greedy scan, but really:
	•	best ending at i depends on best ending at i-1

Stock problems

Often presented as greedy or state machine, but many are DP recurrences.

Sliding window

Not classic recurrence in table form, but window summary updates follow a local state transition rule.

Monotonic stack

Operational rather than table-like, but unresolved relation state evolves by a deterministic rule.

So recurrence exists on a spectrum:
	•	explicit table recurrence
	•	structural recursion
	•	local state update law

⸻

14. The most common recurrence mistakes

⸻

Mistake 1 — Wrong state meaning

State does not fully determine future answer.

⸻

Mistake 2 — Oversized state

Includes irrelevant history, making recurrence too expensive.

⸻

Mistake 3 — Missing transition

Not all valid predecessor/smaller states considered.

⸻

Mistake 4 — Double counting

Especially in counting recurrences.

⸻

Mistake 5 — Wrong base case

Most common in strings, intervals, and recursion.

⸻

Mistake 6 — Wrong dependency order

Bottom-up fill uses unsolved states.

⸻

Mistake 7 — Transition cost ignored

States may be fine, but each transition loops too much.

⸻

Mistake 8 — Hidden symmetry not exploited

Duplicate states or choices inflate recurrence unnecessarily.

⸻

15. Recurrence optimization across the whole set

Once recurrence is derived, the next global task is optimization.

Major recurrence optimizations:

A. Memoization

Solve each state once.

B. Bottom-up tabulation

Avoid repeated recursion.

C. Rolling compression

Keep only recently needed states.

D. Transition optimization

Reduce cost from “all previous states” using:
	•	prefix min/max
	•	deques
	•	heaps
	•	monotonicity
	•	precomputed validity

E. State compression

Replace rich state with smaller sufficient summary.

F. Bitmask compression

Pack combinatorial state compactly.

These are universal recurrence optimizations across the full set.

⸻

