All recurrence formulas

Here is the master sheet of recurrence formulas for LeetCode.

Not as 3872 disconnected formulas, but as the full formula language from which most LeetCode recurrences are built.

That is the only scalable way to understand “all recurrence formulas.”

Because across the whole set, the formulas mostly come from a finite number of recurrence families.

⸻

1. Master recurrence template

Every recurrence has this shape:

\text{State} = \text{Combine}(\text{smaller states})

More explicitly:

F(s) =
\begin{cases}
\text{base answer}, & \text{if } s \text{ is base}\\
\text{Combine}\big(F(s_1), F(s_2), \dots, F(s_k)\big), & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

Where:
	•	s is the current state
	•	s_1, s_2, \dots are smaller states
	•	Combine is usually one of:
	•	sum
	•	max
	•	min
	•	OR
	•	AND
	•	tuple merge

That is the universal recurrence formula.

⸻

2. The 8 core combine operators

Most LeetCode recurrences use one of these.

2.1 Counting recurrence

dp[s] = \sum_{\text{valid } t \to s} dp[t]

Used for:
	•	number of ways
	•	counting paths
	•	counting decodings
	•	counting subsequences

⸻

2.2 Minimum recurrence

dp[s] = \min_{\text{valid } t \to s} \big(dp[t] + \text{cost}(t,s)\big)

Used for:
	•	min path sum
	•	edit distance
	•	coin change
	•	cuts / partitions

⸻

2.3 Maximum recurrence

dp[s] = \max_{\text{valid } t \to s} \big(dp[t] + \text{gain}(t,s)\big)

Used for:
	•	House Robber
	•	LIS
	•	max path sum
	•	stock profit
	•	longest subsequence

⸻

2.4 Boolean OR recurrence

dp[s] = \bigvee_{\text{valid } t \to s} dp[t]

Used for:
	•	can partition
	•	word break
	•	regex matching
	•	reachability

⸻

2.5 Boolean AND recurrence

dp[s] = \bigwedge_{\text{required } t \to s} dp[t]

Less common, but used where all child conditions must hold.

⸻

2.6 Choice recurrence

dp[s] = \text{Combine}(\text{take branch}, \text{skip branch})

Usually:
dp[s] = \max(\text{take}, \text{skip})
or
dp[s] = \text{take} + \text{skip}

Used everywhere.

⸻

2.7 Split recurrence

dp[l][r] = \text{Combine}_{k \in [l,r)}\big(dp[l][k], dp[k+1][r]\big)

Used for:
	•	interval DP
	•	partition DP
	•	matrix chain style
	•	palindrome cuts
	•	burst balloons type structure

⸻

2.8 Tuple recurrence

dp[s] = (a(s), b(s), c(s), \dots)

Used when one state must return multiple values together.

Examples:
	•	balanced tree returns height + balancedness
	•	tree robber returns take + skip
	•	max path style returns local best + global best contribution

⸻

3. Linear one-dimensional recurrence formulas

These are the most common.

⸻

3.1 Fibonacci form

dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2]

Examples:
	•	Climbing Stairs
	•	many count-step problems

Base:
dp[0]=1,\quad dp[1]=1

Variant:
dp[i] = \sum_{k \in \text{allowed steps}} dp[i-k]

⸻

3.2 Take / skip form

dp[i] = \max(dp[i-1],\ dp[i-2] + value[i])

Examples:
	•	House Robber
	•	weighted non-adjacent choices

General count/boolean versions also exist.

⸻

3.3 Extend / restart form

dp[i] = \max(a[i],\ dp[i-1] + a[i])

Examples:
	•	Maximum Subarray (Kadane)

And final answer:
ans = \max_i dp[i]

⸻

3.4 Prefix best form

dp[i] = \max(dp[i-1],\ \text{candidate using } i)

Generic for:
	•	LIS-like one-dimensional optimized variants
	•	stock problems
	•	prefix optimum tracking

⸻

3.5 Stock state-machine form

For one transaction style:
hold_i = \max(hold_{i-1},\ -price_i)
sell_i = \max(sell_{i-1},\ hold_{i-1}+price_i)

For multiple transactions, cooldown, fees, etc., states expand.

⸻

3.6 Decode ways form

If single digit valid:
dp[i] += dp[i-1]
If two-digit valid:
dp[i] += dp[i-2]

Equivalent suffix form:
dp[i] =
\begin{cases}
0, & s[i]='0'\\
dp[i+1] + dp[i+2]\ \text{if two-digit valid},\\
dp[i+1], & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

⸻

4. Two-dimensional sequence recurrence formulas

These dominate string DP.

⸻

4.1 Longest Common Subsequence

dp[i][j] =
\begin{cases}
dp[i-1][j-1] + 1, & s[i-1]=t[j-1]\\
\max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]), & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

⸻

4.2 Edit Distance

dp[i][j] =
\begin{cases}
dp[i-1][j-1], & s[i-1]=t[j-1]\\
1 + \min(dp[i-1][j],\ dp[i][j-1],\ dp[i-1][j-1]), & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

Base:
dp[i][0]=i,\quad dp[0][j]=j

⸻

4.3 Distinct Subsequences

dp[i][j] =
\begin{cases}
dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j], & s[i-1]=t[j-1]\\
dp[i-1][j], & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

Meaning:
number of ways first i chars of s form first j chars of t

⸻

4.4 Interleaving String

dp[i][j] =
\big(dp[i-1][j] \land s_1[i-1]=s_3[i+j-1]\big)
\;\lor\;
\big(dp[i][j-1] \land s_2[j-1]=s_3[i+j-1]\big)

⸻

4.5 Wildcard matching

Typical form:
dp[i][j] =
\begin{cases}
dp[i-1][j-1], & p[j-1]='?' \text{ or } s[i-1]=p[j-1]\\
dp[i][j-1]\lor dp[i-1][j], & p[j-1]='*'\\
false, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

⸻

4.6 Regex matching (. and *)

dp[i][j] =
\begin{cases}
dp[i-1][j-1], & p[j-1]=s[i-1]\ \text{or}\ p[j-1]='.'\\
dp[i][j-2]\ \lor\ \big(\text{match}(s[i-1],p[j-2]) \land dp[i-1][j]\big), & p[j-1]='*'\\
false, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

⸻

5. Grid recurrence formulas

⸻

5.1 Unique Paths

dp[r][c] = dp[r-1][c] + dp[r][c-1]

Base:
first row / first column = 1

⸻

5.2 Unique Paths with Obstacles

dp[r][c] =
\begin{cases}
0, & obstacle[r][c]=1\\
dp[r-1][c] + dp[r][c-1], & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

⸻

5.3 Minimum Path Sum

dp[r][c] = grid[r][c] + \min(dp[r-1][c],\ dp[r][c-1])

⸻

5.4 Triangle minimum path sum

Bottom-up:
dp[r][c] = triangle[r][c] + \min(dp[r+1][c],\ dp[r+1][c+1])

⸻

5.5 Maximum / minimum falling path variants

Typical:
dp[r][c] = value[r][c] + \min/\max(dp[r-1][c-1], dp[r-1][c], dp[r-1][c+1])

depending on rules.

⸻

6. Interval recurrence formulas

⸻

6.1 Longest Palindromic Subsequence

dp[l][r] =
\begin{cases}
1, & l=r\\
2 + dp[l+1][r-1], & s[l]=s[r]\\
\max(dp[l+1][r], dp[l][r-1]), & s[l]\ne s[r]
\end{cases}

⸻

6.2 Palindrome table

pal[l][r] =
\begin{cases}
true, & l=r\\
s[l]=s[r], & r=l+1\\
(s[l]=s[r]) \land pal[l+1][r-1], & r-l\ge 2
\end{cases}

Used as helper for partitioning.

⸻

6.3 Minimum palindrome cuts

dp[i] = \min_{0 \le j \le i,\ pal[j][i]} \big(1 + dp[j-1]\big)

with suitable base convention.

⸻

6.4 Generic interval split DP

dp[l][r] = \min/\max_{k=l}^{r-1} \big(dp[l][k] + dp[k+1][r] + cost(l,k,r)\big)

This is the master formula for:
	•	matrix chain multiplication style
	•	merge cost style
	•	partition optimization style

⸻

6.5 Burst Balloons

With virtual boundaries:
dp[l][r] = \max_{k \in (l,r)} \big(dp[l][k] + dp[k][r] + nums[l]\cdot nums[k]\cdot nums[r]\big)

where l,r are outside boundaries of open interval.

⸻

7. Tree recurrence formulas

⸻

7.1 Height / depth

height(node) =
\begin{cases}
0, & node=null\\
1 + \max(height(left), height(right)), & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

⸻

7.2 Balanced tree tuple

solve(node) = (balanced,\ height)

with
height = 1+\max(h_L,h_R)
balanced = balanced_L \land balanced_R \land |h_L-h_R|\le 1

⸻

7.3 Diameter of tree

If returning height:
height(node)=1+\max(h_L,h_R)
Global:
diameter = \max(diameter,\ h_L+h_R)

⸻

7.4 House Robber III

take(node)=node.val + skip(left)+skip(right)
skip(node)=\max(take(left),skip(left))+\max(take(right),skip(right))

Final:
ans = \max(take(root), skip(root))

⸻

7.5 Binary Tree Maximum Path Sum

Return best downward gain:
gain(node)=node.val+\max(0,gain(left),gain(right))

Global update:
ans = \max(ans,\ node.val+\max(0,gain(left))+\max(0,gain(right)))

⸻

7.6 Path Sum counting style

Prefix-sum or DFS accumulation usually not classic DP recurrence, but recursive accumulation:
remaining' = remaining - node.val

and recurse to children.

⸻

8. DAG / graph recurrence formulas

⸻

8.1 Longest path in DAG

dp[u] = \max_{(u,v)\in E} \big(1 + dp[v]\big)

or with weights:
dp[u] = \max_{(u,v)\in E} \big(w(u,v) + dp[v]\big)

Base:
sink nodes.

⸻

8.2 Path counting in DAG

dp[u] = \sum_{(u,v)\in E} dp[v]

with base at destination or sinks.

⸻

8.3 Reachability in DAG/state graph

dp[u] = \bigvee_{(u,v)\in E} dp[v]

⸻

9. Partition / segmentation recurrence formulas

⸻

9.1 Word Break

dp[i] = \bigvee_{j < i} \big(dp[j] \land s[j:i]\in dict\big)

Or suffix form:
solve(i) = \bigvee_{j \ge i} \big(s[i:j]\in dict \land solve(j+1)\big)

⸻

9.2 Word Break II

sentences(i) = \bigcup_{j \ge i,\ s[i:j]\in dict} \{ s[i:j] + \text{sentence} : \text{sentence} \in sentences(j+1)\}

Structurally recurrence-based, but output-sensitive.

⸻

9.3 Restore IP Addresses

solve(i, parts) = \bigcup_{j=i}^{i+2} \text{if segment valid } s[i:j]

Recursive segmentation with bounded branching.

⸻

9.4 Generic partition recurrence

dp[i] = \text{Combine over all valid next cuts } j

This is the universal segmentation formula.

⸻

10. Subset / choice recurrence formulas

⸻

10.1 Generic choose / skip

solve(i, \text{state}) = \text{Combine}(solve(i+1,\text{skip}),\ solve(i+1,\text{take}))

This is the master recurrence for:
	•	subsets
	•	knapsack-like families
	•	partition-style search
	•	many backtracking and DP problems

⸻

10.2 0/1 Knapsack

dp[i][w] =
\begin{cases}
dp[i-1][w], & weight_i > w\\
\max(dp[i-1][w],\ dp[i-1][w-weight_i] + value_i), & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

⸻

10.3 Subset sum feasibility

dp[i][s] = dp[i-1][s] \lor dp[i-1][s-a_i]

if a_i \le s

⸻

10.4 Partition equal subset sum

Same subset-sum feasibility with target = total/2.

⸻

10.5 Coin Change (minimum coins)

dp[x] = \min_{coin \le x}(dp[x-coin]+1)

or 2D formulation depending on item reuse model.

⸻

10.6 Coin Change II (count ways)

dp[x] += dp[x-coin]

with loop order determining combinations vs permutations.

⸻

11. Bitmask recurrence formulas

⸻

11.1 Traveling Salesman style

dp[mask][i] = \min_{j \in mask,\ j\ne i} \big(dp[mask \setminus \{i\}][j] + dist[j][i]\big)

⸻

11.2 Visit-all state recurrence

solve(mask, last) = \min/\max_{\text{next not in }mask} \big(cost(last,next) + solve(mask \cup \{next\}, next)\big)

⸻

11.3 Count assignments

dp[mask] = \sum_{\text{valid next choices}} dp[mask \setminus bit]

depending on formulation.

⸻

12. Backtracking recurrence formulas

These are not always memoized, but they are still recurrence formulas.

⸻

12.1 Subsets

solve(i, path) =
\begin{cases}
emit(path), & i=n\\
solve(i+1, path),\\
solve(i+1, path \cup \{a_i\})
\end{cases}

⸻

12.2 Permutations

solve(used, path) = \bigcup_{i \notin used} solve(used \cup \{i\}, path + a_i)

⸻

12.3 N-Queens

solve(row) = \bigcup_{\text{valid col}} solve(row+1)

with board constraints in state.

⸻

13. Scan / rolling recurrence formulas

These are often overlooked as recurrences.

⸻

13.1 Kadane

bestEnd[i] = \max(a[i], bestEnd[i-1]+a[i])

Compressed:
bestEnd = \max(x,\ bestEnd+x)

⸻

13.2 Best time to buy and sell stock I

minPrice_i = \min(minPrice_{i-1}, price_i)
best_i = \max(best_{i-1}, price_i - minPrice_i)

⸻

13.3 Prefix sum

prefix[i] = prefix[i-1] + a[i]

This is a recurrence too.

⸻

13.4 Running min/max

mn_i = \min(mn_{i-1}, a[i])
mx_i = \max(mx_{i-1}, a[i])

⸻

14. Parse / pattern recurrence formulas

⸻

14.1 Decode Ways

Already given:
dp[i] = (\text{1-digit valid})\cdot dp[i-1] + (\text{2-digit valid})\cdot dp[i-2]

⸻

14.2 Expression-style partition

Generic:
solve(l,r) = \text{Combine over all operator split points }k

For “different ways to add parentheses” type problems:
solve(l,r) = \bigcup_{k \in ops} \{ combine(x,y,op_k) : x\in solve(l,k-1), y\in solve(k+1,r)\}

⸻

15. The master formula catalog

Here is the compact catalog.

Count

dp[s] = \sum dp[prev]

Boolean

dp[s] = \bigvee dp[prev]

Min

dp[s] = \min(dp[prev] + cost)

Max

dp[s] = \max(dp[prev] + gain)

Take / skip

dp = combine(take,\ skip)

Match / mismatch

dp[i][j] =
\begin{cases}
match\ branch\\
mismatch\ branch
\end{cases}

Split

dp[l][r] = \text{Combine}_{k}(dp[l][k], dp[k+1][r])

Child combine

solve(node) = combine(solve(child_1), solve(child_2), \dots)

Subset-state

dp[mask][i] = combine(dp[mask \setminus bit][j])

Rolling local update

state_i = update(state_{i-1}, input_i)

These are the true master recurrence formulas.

⸻

16. Base case formulas

Base cases are part of the formula system too.

Common base patterns:

Empty prefix / suffix

dp[0]=...
\quad\text{or}\quad
dp[n]=...

Empty string alignment

dp[i][0]=...
,\quad
dp[0][j]=...

Single interval

dp[l][l]=...

Null tree

solve(null)=...

Full mask / empty mask

dp[0]=...
,\quad
dp[(1<<n)-1]=...

⸻

17. Optimization formulas on top of recurrences

After the base recurrence, many problems use optimized equivalent formulas.

⸻

17.1 Rolling compression

If:
dp[i] = f(dp[i-1], dp[i-2])
then keep only two scalars.

⸻

17.2 Row compression

If:
dp[i][j] \text{ depends only on row } i-1 \text{ and current row}
then keep 1–2 rows.

⸻

17.3 Prefix transition optimization

If:
dp[i] = \min_{j < i}(dp[j] + cost(j,i))
and cost has structure, use prefix minima / deque / convexity-like tricks conceptually.

⸻

18. How to derive the formula

For any LeetCode problem, derive recurrence like this:

Step 1

Define state meaning in one exact sentence.

Step 2

Write smallest base states.

Step 3

Ask:
“What last choice / previous smaller structure could lead here?”

Step 4

Write all valid predecessors.

Step 5

Choose combine operator:
	•	sum
	•	min
	•	max
	•	OR
	•	tuple

Step 6

Check completeness and no double counting.

That is how all recurrence formulas are born.

⸻

19. Final condensed “all formulas” sheet

Here is the minimal master sheet:

F(s)=base
or
F(s)=\sum F(prev)
or
F(s)=\min(F(prev)+cost)
or
F(s)=\max(F(prev)+gain)
or
F(s)=F(a)\lor F(b)
or
F(s)=\max(\text{take},\text{skip})
or
F(l,r)=\text{Combine over split }k
or
F(node)=combine(F(children))
or
F(mask,i)=combine(F(mask\setminus bit,j))
or
state_i=update(state_{i-1}, input_i)

That is the full recurrence language behind LeetCode.

⸻

20. Final sentence

The deepest truth is:

there are not 3872 unrelated recurrence formulas; there are a small number of recurrence families, and each LeetCode problem is an instance of one or more of those families with a specific state, base case, and combine rule.

The best next step is a master recurrence formula table with columns:
	•	family
	•	formula
	•	state meaning
	•	base case
	•	combine operator
	•	example questions
	•	common bugs



Procedure of visit in all leetcode 

“Procedure of visit” across LeetCode means:

the exact order in which the algorithm touches, revisits, skips, or finalizes elements, states, nodes, windows, subproblems, or candidates.

This is a very deep idea.

Because two algorithms may use the same data structure but differ entirely in:
	•	visit order
	•	revisit policy
	•	finalization rule
	•	skip rule
	•	expansion rule

And that difference is often the whole algorithm.

So this topic is really about the visitation protocol of problems.

1. What “visit” means

A visit is any moment the algorithm focuses on a unit of work.

That unit may be:
	•	array index
	•	character
	•	window boundary
	•	pair candidate
	•	DP cell
	•	tree node
	•	graph node
	•	edge
	•	subset state
	•	interval
	•	parser state
	•	heap candidate
	•	queue element

So visiting means:
	•	inspect
	•	process
	•	update from
	•	branch from
	•	finalize
	•	expand neighbors from

A LeetCode problem is often solved by choosing the right visit procedure.

⸻

2. The 8 major visit questions

For any problem, ask:

1. What is the visit unit?

Element, node, state, interval, subset, etc.

2. In what order are units visited?

Left to right, BFS layers, topological order, recursion, heap order, etc.

3. Can a unit be revisited?

Never, sometimes, many times, until improvement stops?

4. When is a unit considered complete?

After one pass, after children processed, after best cost fixed, after all transitions considered?

5. What neighboring units get scheduled next?

Adjacent cells, child states, next interval, next mask, etc.

6. What units are skipped?

Dominated, stale, duplicate, invalid, already visited, already solved?

7. What metadata controls visitation?

Visited set, indegree, distance, stack state, memo, window counts?

8. What invariant is true when a visit happens?

This is the real correctness layer.

⸻

3. The master categories of visit procedure

All LeetCode visit procedures mostly fall into these families:
	•	linear visit
	•	boundary visit
	•	layered visit
	•	depth visit
	•	dependency visit
	•	priority visit
	•	recursive state visit
	•	exhaustive choice visit
	•	interval visit
	•	subset visit
	•	event visit
	•	service-operation visit

Now the deep breakdown.

⸻

4. Linear visit procedure

Meaning

Visit units in simple sequence order.

Typical objects
	•	arrays
	•	strings

Order
	•	left to right
	•	right to left
	•	sometimes two passes

Revisit policy

Usually no revisit.

Completion rule

An index is complete once its contribution is folded into state.

Examples
	•	max/min scan
	•	prefix sum
	•	Kadane
	•	stock one pass
	•	last word length

Invariant

Processed prefix/suffix is summarized correctly.

Core idea

History is compressed as you move.

⸻

5. Boundary visit procedure

Meaning

Visit regions by moving boundaries.

Typical objects
	•	sorted arrays
	•	windows
	•	intervals

Order
	•	outside in
	•	left/right shifting
	•	expand/shrink

Revisit policy

Boundaries move monotonically, but regions conceptually change.

Completion rule

A boundary position is complete once it is permanently excluded or absorbed.

Examples
	•	two pointers
	•	sliding window
	•	binary search interval
	•	merge intervals

Invariant

Everything outside active boundaries is resolved or irrelevant.

Core idea

Do not visit all candidates explicitly; visit only evolving boundaries.

⸻

6. Layered visit procedure

Meaning

Visit states by distance/step layer.

Typical objects
	•	graphs
	•	grids
	•	implicit state spaces

Order
	•	level by level

Revisit policy

Usually no revisit after visited marking.

Completion rule

A node is complete when dequeued and expanded under the BFS model.

Examples
	•	shortest unweighted path
	•	rotting oranges
	•	level order traversal
	•	Word Ladder

Invariant

All nodes in the queue belong to current or future BFS layers.

Core idea

Visit in minimum-step order.

⸻

7. Depth visit procedure

Meaning

Visit one branch deeply before siblings.

Typical objects
	•	trees
	•	graphs
	•	recursive structures
	•	search spaces

Order
	•	descend fully, then backtrack

Revisit policy

Trees: no revisit naturally
Graphs: revisit blocked by visited
Backtracking: revisit different branches structurally

Completion rule

A node/state is complete after all children/branches are processed.

Examples
	•	tree traversals
	•	component DFS
	•	path existence
	•	subtree aggregation

Invariant

Current recursion stack matches current active branch.

Core idea

Depth-first structure discovery or subtree solving.

⸻

8. Dependency visit procedure

Meaning

Visit only after prerequisites are ready.

Typical objects
	•	DP tables
	•	DAGs
	•	topological problems
	•	interval DP
	•	parser/state dependencies

Order
	•	smallest to largest
	•	topo order
	•	short interval to long interval
	•	previous row to current row

Revisit policy

Usually no revisit after state solved.

Completion rule

A state is complete when all its dependencies are already final.

Examples
	•	bottom-up DP
	•	topo sort
	•	edit distance
	•	interval DP

Invariant

Every visited state only depends on already-solved states.

Core idea

Correct visit order is everything.

⸻

9. Priority visit procedure

Meaning

Visit the most important candidate first.

Typical objects
	•	heaps
	•	weighted graphs
	•	top-k streams
	•	best-first search

Order
	•	by min/max key
	•	by tentative cost
	•	by priority score

Revisit policy

Sometimes yes, with stale-state skipping.

Completion rule

Depends on algorithm:
	•	Dijkstra: first finalized pop under valid assumptions
	•	top-k: pop until enough
	•	merge streams: pop smallest next

Examples
	•	Dijkstra
	•	merge k lists
	•	kth largest
	•	top k frequent

Invariant

Frontier is ordered by priority rule.

Core idea

Visit order is determined by value, not position.

⸻

10. Recursive state visit procedure

Meaning

Visit abstract states through recurrence.

Typical objects
	•	memoized DP
	•	top-down recursion
	•	DAG state graph
	•	parser problems

Order
	•	demand-driven
	•	visit only needed states

Revisit policy

Raw recursion revisits a lot
Memoized recursion solves each state once

Completion rule

A state is complete after all recursive dependencies are computed and combined.

Examples
	•	coin change memo
	•	word break memo
	•	regex matching
	•	interval memo
	•	tree DP with flags

Invariant

Memoized value means exact answer for that state.

Core idea

Visit is driven by the recurrence graph, not by physical input order.

⸻

11. Exhaustive choice visit procedure

Meaning

Visit all choices from a partial state.

Typical objects
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	N-Queens
	•	combination sum
	•	Sudoku

Order
	•	branch recursively through choices

Revisit policy

Same structural position may be revisited under different partial choices.

Completion rule

A branch is complete when:
	•	full valid solution formed
	•	or pruned / dead-end reached

Examples
	•	backtracking families

Invariant

Current mutable state exactly reflects current partial choice path.

Core idea

Visit tree of decisions, often with undo.

⸻

12. Interval visit procedure

Meaning

Visit subproblems by interval size or split.

Typical objects
	•	substrings
	•	range DP
	•	matrix chain style
	•	palindrome DP

Order
	•	short intervals first
	•	longer intervals later
	•	or recursive split

Revisit policy

DP: each interval once
Recursion without memo: repeats badly

Completion rule

An interval is complete after all smaller required intervals or split points are processed.

Examples
	•	longest palindromic subsequence
	•	burst balloons
	•	palindrome partitioning DP

Invariant

Any smaller interval needed by current interval is already correct.

Core idea

Boundaries define visit units.

⸻

13. Subset / bitmask visit procedure

Meaning

Visit states defined by selected-set membership.

Typical objects
	•	subset DP
	•	assignment problems
	•	TSP-like problems
	•	visit-all-state searches

Order
	•	by increasing mask size
	•	or recursive mask expansion
	•	or BFS over state graph

Revisit policy

Usually each (mask, extra_state) once in DP/memo

Completion rule

State complete after all predecessor or successor masks considered.

Examples
	•	bitmask DP families

Invariant

Mask exactly represents chosen/visited set.

Core idea

Visit combinatorial states in compact encoded order.

⸻

14. Event visit procedure

Meaning

Visit start/end/change events in sorted order.

Typical objects
	•	intervals
	•	sweep line
	•	scheduling
	•	timeline systems

Order
	•	sorted by coordinate/time/key

Revisit policy

No revisit of processed event

Completion rule

Event complete after active structure updated

Examples
	•	meeting room overlap
	•	skyline-type thinking
	•	sweep line families

Invariant

Active structure matches all events processed so far.

Core idea

Visit changes, not objects.

⸻

15. Service-operation visit procedure

Meaning

Visit not data positions, but incoming operations on a persistent object.

Typical objects
	•	LRU
	•	LFU
	•	Min Stack
	•	Browser History
	•	design questions

Order
	•	real-time operation sequence

Revisit policy

Object state evolves across operations

Completion rule

An operation is complete when all internal structures are synchronized and API contract satisfied.

Examples
	•	design category

Invariant

All internal views of the object agree after each call.

Core idea

Visit order is the request stream.

⸻

16. Visit procedures for trees specifically

Trees have especially important visit procedures.

Preorder visit

Visit node before children.

Use when:
	•	need root-first construction
	•	serialization
	•	clone/build prefix logic

Inorder visit

Visit left, node, right.

Use when:
	•	BST sorted order matters
	•	anomaly detection in BST
	•	kth smallest in BST

Postorder visit

Visit children before node.

Use when:
	•	subtree answer depends on child answers
	•	delete/free tree
	•	bottom-up tree DP

Level-order visit

Visit by depth.

Use when:
	•	per-level output
	•	minimum depth with BFS
	•	next-right links sometimes

The tree problem often reduces to choosing the right visit protocol.

⸻

17. Visit procedures for graphs specifically

Graphs usually use one of these.

BFS visit

For:
	•	shortest unweighted distance
	•	minimum transformations
	•	layer propagation

DFS visit

For:
	•	component discovery
	•	cycle detection
	•	topological DFS
	•	subtree-like graph reasoning

Dijkstra-style priority visit

For:
	•	weighted shortest path with nonnegative edges

Topological dependency visit

For:
	•	DAG order
	•	course schedule
	•	DAG DP

DSU indirect visit

Not traversal-heavy; visit is merge/query oriented instead of path exploration.

⸻

18. Visit procedures for DP specifically

DP is entirely about visit order.

Top-down visit

Visit only states asked by recursion.

Good when:
	•	state space sparse
	•	recurrence natural

Bottom-up visit

Visit all needed states in dependency order.

Good when:
	•	state space dense
	•	fill order clear

Row-wise visit

Common in sequence/grid DP

Diagonal visit

Common in interval/string DP

Mask-size visit

Common in bitmask DP

Topological visit

Common in DAG DP

Wrong visit order in DP means wrong algorithm.

⸻

19. Visit procedures for sliding window

This deserves its own view.

Units visited:
	•	right boundary
	•	left boundary
	•	current window state

Procedure:
	1.	visit new right element
	2.	update state
	3.	while invalid or optimizable, visit left removal
	4.	record answer at right moment

This is not just index visiting.
It is window-state visiting.

Important property:
	•	each element usually enters once
	•	each element usually leaves once

That is why it becomes linear.

⸻

20. Visit procedures for monotonic structures

Monotonic stack

Visit each new element.
While it resolves old unresolved elements:
	•	pop them
	•	write their answers
Then push current.

Important:
Some elements are visited twice in operational terms:
	•	once on push
	•	once on pop

But total remains linear.

Monotonic deque

Visit each new element.
	•	expire stale front
	•	remove dominated back
	•	push current
	•	read front as answer

These are controlled revisit procedures.

⸻

21. Visit vs revisit vs finalize

Very important distinction.

Visit

Touch/process a unit.

Revisit

Come back to same unit/state again.

Finalize

Know no better/newer information can change its answer.

Examples:

Array scan

Visit once, finalize immediately.

BFS

Visit/discover once, finalize distance effectively on first discovery in unweighted graph.

Dijkstra

May push many tentative candidates, but finalize node cost when valid minimum pop occurs.

Memoization

State may be requested many times, but actually solved/finalized once.

Backtracking

Structural position revisited under different path states; no global finalization until whole search over.

This distinction is central.

⸻

22. Main revisit policies across LeetCode

Never revisit

Typical for:
	•	simple scans
	•	many in-place transforms
	•	prefix arrays

Revisit allowed until best-known improves

Typical for:
	•	relaxation algorithms
	•	some dynamic frontier problems

Revisit structurally but not state-identically

Typical for:
	•	backtracking
	•	combinatorial recursion

Revisit prevented by memo

Typical for:
	•	top-down DP

Revisit prevented by visited set

Typical for:
	•	BFS/DFS graph traversal

Understanding revisit policy often tells you the whole algorithm family.

⸻

23. Visit scheduling rules

A schedule decides what gets visited next.

Common scheduling rules:

Positional schedule

Next index

Boundary schedule

Next left/right boundary move

Queue schedule

FIFO frontier

Stack schedule

LIFO branch expansion

Priority schedule

Best-key-first

Dependency schedule

Only when prerequisites solved

Recursive schedule

Call-tree driven

Event schedule

Sorted event order

Each family corresponds to a major LeetCode protocol.

⸻

24. Visit metadata

Visitation is controlled by metadata.

Common metadata:
	•	visited
	•	dist
	•	parent
	•	indegree
	•	memo
	•	dp
	•	in_stack
	•	used
	•	left/right
	•	min/max so far
	•	heap key
	•	stack monotonic order
	•	deque freshness
	•	last seen index
	•	frequency counts

This metadata answers:
	•	visited already?
	•	safe to process now?
	•	finalized already?
	•	stale?
	•	valid?
	•	dominated?
	•	prerequisite satisfied?

So visitation is really “data + metadata + schedule.”

⸻

25. Procedure of visit by major problem family

Arrays

Usually:
	•	linear visit
	•	boundary visit
	•	monotonic visit

Strings

Usually:
	•	linear visit
	•	window visit
	•	DP dependency visit
	•	parse-state visit

Grids

Usually:
	•	BFS layered visit
	•	DFS depth visit
	•	DP cell visit

Trees

Usually:
	•	preorder / inorder / postorder / level order

Graphs

Usually:
	•	BFS / DFS / topo / priority / DSU-style operation visit

DP

Usually:
	•	top-down recursive state visit
	•	bottom-up dependency visit

Backtracking

Usually:
	•	exhaustive branch visit with undo

Design

Usually:
	•	operation-stream visit

⸻

26. Universal visit template for any LeetCode question

Use this:

1. What is the visit unit?

Index, node, state, interval, mask, event, operation?

2. What schedule visits units?

Loop, queue, stack, heap, recursion, topo order?

3. What makes a unit eligible to visit?

Unvisited, dependency-ready, popped from heap, valid branch, in current window?

4. What happens during a visit?

Read, update, relax, merge, recurse, emit, mutate?

5. When is the unit complete?

Immediate, after children, after all transitions, after first discovery, after min-pop?

6. Can it be revisited?

Never, until improvement, under different path state, memoized once?

7. What invariant is true at visit time?

This is the correctness core.

That is the master “procedure of visit” framework.

⸻

27. Final compressed summary

All LeetCode questions use some visitation protocol over units like:
	•	indices
	•	windows
	•	intervals
	•	tree nodes
	•	graph nodes
	•	DP states
	•	subset masks
	•	parser states
	•	events
