All type of code operation and data structure representation after it for all 3872 leetcode question 


Here is the master framework of all types of code operations and the data structure representation after them across the LeetCode universe.

This is a very deep layer.

Because solving a LeetCode problem is not only:
	•	choose algorithm
	•	choose data structure

It is also:
	•	understand what operations the code performs
	•	understand how each operation changes representation
	•	understand what the data structure looks like after each operation
	•	understand which operations are cheap, expensive, reversible, destructive, monotone, cached, or state-expanding

So this topic is really:

operation semantics + representation evolution

⸻

1. What this means

For any LeetCode problem, code does operations like:
	•	read
	•	write
	•	compare
	•	swap
	•	insert
	•	delete
	•	push
	•	pop
	•	merge
	•	split
	•	traverse
	•	recurse
	•	memoize
	•	relax
	•	union
	•	compress
	•	backtrack
	•	rebuild
	•	normalize

After each operation, the data structure is in a new representation state.

Example:

Two Sum

Operation:
	•	seen[value] = index

Representation after operation:
	•	hash map now represents processed prefix summary

Reverse Linked List

Operation:
	•	curr->next = prev

Representation after operation:
	•	processed prefix is now reversed and detached from unprocessed suffix

BFS

Operation:
	•	enqueue neighbor and mark visited

Representation after operation:
	•	queue represents current/future frontier
	•	visited set represents discovered states

So we need both:
	•	operation type
	•	post-operation representation meaning

⸻

2. The master categories of code operations

Across almost all 3872 questions, code operations fall into these families:

A. Access operations

Read/query/check state

B. Update operations

Change stored values or metadata

C. Structural operations

Change the shape of a structure

D. Traversal operations

Move across structure/state space

E. State-transition operations

Move from one computational state to another

F. Constraint operations

Validate, prune, reject, or normalize

G. Aggregation operations

Combine many small facts into one summary

H. Reversible operations

Do + undo

I. Scheduling operations

Decide what gets processed next

J. Finalization operations

Freeze answer or mark state complete

Now the deep breakdown.

⸻

3. Access operations

These do not mutate the structure directly.
They inspect.

3.1 Index access

Examples:
	•	nums[i]
	•	grid[r][c]
	•	dp[i][j]

Representation after access:
	•	unchanged
	•	but the algorithm now holds a local view of one unit

Semantic meaning:
	•	current focus is this indexed cell/element/state

⸻

3.2 Pointer/reference access

Examples:
	•	node->left
	•	curr->next
	•	iterator dereference

Representation after access:
	•	unchanged
	•	but current traversal cursor moves conceptually

⸻

3.3 Membership check

Examples:
	•	set.count(x)
	•	map.contains(k)
	•	visited[node]

Representation after access:
	•	unchanged

Meaning after operation:
	•	algorithm learns whether representation already includes summary/state/item

Common in:
	•	hashing
	•	graph traversal
	•	duplicate control
	•	memoization

⸻

3.4 Boundary check

Examples:
	•	i < n
	•	r >= 0 && r < rows
	•	left <= right

Representation after access:
	•	unchanged

Meaning:
	•	protects structural validity of next step

⸻

3.5 Compare operation

Examples:
	•	a < b
	•	height[left] < height[right]
	•	s[i] == t[j]

Representation after access:
	•	unchanged

Meaning:
	•	determines next branch / update / pointer move

⸻

4. Update operations

These mutate stored values but do not necessarily change structure shape.

4.1 Scalar overwrite

Examples:
	•	best = max(best, curr)
	•	carry = sum / 10
	•	min_price = min(min_price, price)

Representation after operation:
	•	scalar summary now represents all processed information up to this point

Meaning:
	•	history compressed into a smaller value

This is one of the most common operations in LeetCode.

⸻

