⸻

Master list of all primary step-table types

1. Scalar Scan Table

Use when the algorithm processes input linearly and maintains a few scalar summaries.

Best for:
	•	simple array scans
	•	running min/max
	•	Kadane-like logic
	•	stock one-pass logic
	•	greedy scans

Core progress unit:
	•	one index / one element per step

⸻

2. Prefix Summary Table

Use when each step updates a cumulative summary of everything seen so far.

Best for:
	•	prefix sums
	•	suffix sums
	•	cumulative counts
	•	balance/parity scans
	•	prefix extrema

Core progress unit:
	•	one new element added to summary

⸻

3. Hashmap / Cache Table

Use when each step is defined by:
	•	query cache
	•	update cache
	•	cache hit/miss
	•	cached state expansion

Best for:
	•	Two Sum
	•	frequency maps
	•	grouping
	•	last seen index
	•	memo maps
	•	clone maps

Core progress unit:
	•	one lookup/update event

⸻

4. Sliding Window Table

Use when the active object is a moving contiguous interval.

Best for:
	•	longest substring without repeat
	•	min window substring
	•	at most K distinct
	•	fixed window problems
	•	contiguous validity problems

Core progress unit:
	•	expand / shrink / record

⸻

5. Two-Pointer Boundary Table

Use when progress comes from moving two boundaries or two coordinated cursors.

Best for:
	•	sorted pair problems
	•	palindrome scans
	•	container with most water
	•	merge scans
	•	partition scans
	•	binary-partition logic

Core progress unit:
	•	left/right movement decision

⸻

6. Monotonic Stack Table

Use when unresolved candidates are stored in stack order and popped when resolved/dominated.

Best for:
	•	next greater element
