7. Representing one thing in the form of another

This is the deepest part.

A lot of LeetCode is about converting one representation into another.

⸻

7.1 Pair search -> complement lookup

Original form

Find (a, b) such that a + b = target

Transformed form

For current a, search target - a

Benefit

Quadratic pair search becomes linear hash lookup.

This is Q1.

⸻

7.2 Subarray sum -> prefix relation

Original form

Check sum of interval (l, r)

Transformed form

prefix[r] - prefix[l-1]

Benefit

Range sum becomes constant-time arithmetic.

⸻

7.3 String partition -> index state

Original form

All ways to cut a string

Transformed form

State dp[i] or solve(i) means answer from index i

Benefit

Exponential partition search becomes indexed DP state graph.

⸻

7.4 Path search -> graph traversal

Original form

All possible moves

Transformed form

Graph nodes and edges

Benefit

Generic traversal tools apply.

⸻

7.5 Repeated recursion -> memo table

Original form

Huge recursive decision tree

Transformed form

Finite state cache

Benefit

Same subproblem solved once.

⸻

7.6 Set -> bitmask

Original form

Subset of elements

Transformed form

Integer bit pattern

Benefit

Fast subset operations, compact memory.

⸻

7.7 Sequence -> monotone frontier

Original form

All previous elements matter

Transformed form

Only undominated candidates matter

Benefit

Linear-time monotonic stack/deque solutions.

⸻

7.8 Connectivity -> DSU forest

Original form

Need to know whether elements belong to same component

Transformed form

Parent links to representative

Benefit

Fast merge/find.

⸻

7.9 Tree recursion -> postorder return values

Original form

Need subtree properties

Transformed form

Return summary tuple from each node

Benefit

Bottom-up solution.

⸻

7.10 Output relation -> parent pointers

Original form

Need actual path/string/sequence, not only value

Transformed form

Store predecessor relation

Benefit

Reconstruction becomes simple backward walk.

