3. Tree represented as array

This has multiple meanings.

3.1 Binary heap tree as array

Logical object: complete binary tree
Storage: array

Encoding

For 0-indexed array:
	•	parent(i) = (i - 1) / 2
	•	left(i) = 2i + 1
	•	right(i) = 2i + 2

Figure

Array index:   0   1   2   3   4   5   6
Value:        [A] [B] [C] [D] [E] [F] [G]

Tree:
            A(0)
         /       \
      B(1)       C(2)
     /   \       /   \
   D(3) E(4)   F(5) G(6)

Why this works

Because the tree is complete / near-complete, so no explicit pointers are needed.

Easy operations
	•	parent/child navigation
	•	heap push/pop
	•	cache locality

Hard / bad for
	•	sparse arbitrary trees
	•	many missing nodes

⸻

3.2 General binary tree as array (level-order with nulls)

Logical object: arbitrary binary tree
Storage: array with placeholders

Encoding

Store nodes in breadth-first order, keeping nulls where children are missing.

Figure

Tree:
      1
     / \
    2   3
     \
      5

Level-order array:
[1, 2, 3, null, 5]

Meaning

This is common in LeetCode serialization.

Good for
	•	input/output
	•	visualization
	•	reconstruction

Weakness
	•	sparse trees waste space
	•	not ideal for heavy mutation

⸻

3.3 Tree as parent array

Logical object: rooted tree
Storage: parent[i]

Encoding

Each node stores its parent index.

Figure

parent = [-1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2]

Meaning:
0 is root
1,2 are children of 0
3,4 are children of 1
5 is child of 2

Good for
	•	ancestry
	•	reconstruction
	•	DSU-like reasoning
	•	rooted tree metadata

Weakness
	•	child iteration needs reverse map / adjacency list

⸻

3.4 Tree as adjacency list

Logical object: tree
Storage: graph adjacency list

Figure

0: [1, 2]
1: [0, 3, 4]
2: [0, 5]
3: [1]
4: [1]
5: [2]

Meaning

A tree is a special graph with n-1 edges and connectedness.

Good for
