All about matrix indepth in all 3872 leetcode question 


Matrix in LeetCode is not just “2D array.”

It is a whole universe of representations, operations, invariants, traversal systems, DP states, graph conversions, geometry models, and memory layouts.

So “all about matrix” across all 3872 questions should be organized as a master atlas.

1. What a matrix is in LeetCode

A matrix is usually one of these:
	•	a 2D container of values
	•	a grid of positions
	•	a graph in disguise
	•	a DP table
	•	a spatial world
	•	a constraint board
	•	a prefix-sum surface
	•	a binary image
	•	a cost landscape
	•	a state transition space

So the first rule is:

never ask only “is this a matrix?”
ask “what role is the matrix playing here?”

2. The major matrix roles

A. Storage matrix

The matrix is just where values live.

Examples:
	•	search in 2D matrix
	•	set matrix zeroes
	•	rotate image

B. Grid-position matrix

Each cell is a position you can move through.

Examples:
	•	number of islands
	•	shortest path in binary matrix
	•	rotten oranges

C. DP-state matrix

Each cell is not a world cell, but a subproblem.

Examples:
	•	edit distance
	•	LCS
	•	distinct subsequences

D. Prefix / aggregate matrix

Each cell summarizes a region.

Examples:
	•	2D prefix sum
	•	range sum query 2D

E. Constraint board matrix

Each cell participates in rules.

Examples:
	•	Sudoku
	•	N-Queens board view
	•	valid board configurations

F. Image / geometry matrix

The matrix is treated visually or spatially.

Examples:
	•	rotate image
	•	spiral matrix
	•	flood fill

G. Binary matrix

The matrix stores true/false or 0/1 structure.

Examples:
	•	maximal rectangle
	•	maximal square
	•	islands
	•	shortest path on binary grid

3. The 12 most important matrix interpretations

1. Matrix as table of values

Cell (r,c) just stores data.

2. Matrix as coordinate plane

Cell (r,c) is a location.

3. Matrix as graph

Each cell is a node, neighbors are edges.

4. Matrix as DP state space

Cell (i,j) means an answer for a subproblem.

5. Matrix as region map

Rectangles/submatrices matter.

6. Matrix as image

Rotation, symmetry, connectivity, shapes matter.

7. Matrix as binary mask surface

1 means active, 0 means inactive.

8. Matrix as layered dependency structure

Some cells depend on earlier cells.

9. Matrix as simulation board

Agents, tokens, or processes move through cells.

10. Matrix as histogram source

Rows or columns can be converted into heights.

11. Matrix as constraint lattice

Local/global restrictions define legality.

12. Matrix as compressed state transition system

Sometimes matrix coordinates encode state pairs.

4. Matrix memory representation

At machine level, a matrix is usually represented as:
	•	vector of vectors
	•	flat 1D array with index mapping
	•	static 2D array
	•	sparse map of coordinates
	•	bitset rows for binary structure

Standard row-major view

matrix[r][c]

Logical view:

(r,c)
(0,0) (0,1) (0,2)
(1,0) (1,1) (1,2)
(2,0) (2,1) (2,2)

Flattened 1D representation

id = r * cols + c
r = id / cols
c = id % cols

This is very important for:
	•	DSU on grids
	•	graph conversion
	•	BFS/DFS state storage
	•	memory optimization

5. Matrix neighbor systems

A huge amount of matrix logic comes from neighbor definition.

4-direction neighbors

Up, down, left, right.

    U
L   X   R
    D

Used for:
	•	islands
	•	flood fill
	•	shortest grid path
	•	BFS/DFS grids

8-direction neighbors

Includes diagonals.

UL  U  UR
 L  X   R
DL  D  DR

Used for:
	•	shortest path in binary matrix
	•	image region variants
	•	king-move style problems

Custom moves

Knight moves, jumps, portals, weighted moves.

So one of the most important matrix questions is:

what is the legal adjacency model?

6. Matrix traversal families

These are core across LeetCode.

Row-major traversal

Left to right, top to bottom.

Column-major traversal

Top to bottom by column.

Reverse row-major

Bottom-right backward.

Diagonal traversal

Process by r + c or r - c.

Spiral traversal

Outer ring inward.

Zigzag traversal

Alternating direction per row or diagonal.

BFS traversal

By layer from one or more sources.

DFS traversal

Deep region exploration.

Dependency traversal

Only visit when prerequisites are solved.

That means matrix questions are often about choosing the right traversal order.

7. Matrix as graph

This is one of the deepest conversions.

A matrix cell becomes a graph node.

node = (r,c)
edges = legal neighbor moves

Then you can apply:
	•	BFS
	•	DFS
	•	Dijkstra
	•	DSU
	•	topo-style reasoning in special cases

This converts grid problems into graph problems.

Examples:
	•	number of islands -> DFS/BFS/DSU on grid graph
	•	rotten oranges -> multi-source BFS on grid graph
	•	shortest path -> BFS or Dijkstra on grid graph

8. Matrix as DP table

Another huge universe.

In these problems, the matrix is not a world. It is a set of subproblems.

Examples:
	•	dp[i][j] = edit distance up to i,j
	•	dp[i][j] = LCS up to i,j
	•	dp[r][c] = min path sum to cell

So matrix in DP has different meaning from matrix in grid BFS.

That distinction is critical.

Grid DP matrix

Cells correspond to physical positions and DP states simultaneously.

Example:
	•	unique paths
	•	min path sum

String DP matrix

Rows/columns represent prefixes of two sequences.

Example:
	•	edit distance
	•	LCS
	•	interleaving string

9. Matrix as region / rectangle system

Many matrix problems are really about submatrices.

Important region types:
	•	single cell
	•	row segment
	•	column segment
	•	rectangle
	•	square
	•	prefix rectangle
	•	suffix rectangle
	•	band / strip
	•	boundary ring

This creates operations like:
	•	rectangle sum
	•	maximal rectangle
	•	maximal square
	•	rectangle updates
	•	region validity checks

10. 2D prefix sum

One of the most important matrix tools.

Define:

prefix[r][c]

to mean sum of rectangle from (0,0) to (r,c).

Then rectangle sum becomes constant time.

This is the 2D analogue of prefix sums in arrays.

Core idea:
	•	region query becomes arithmetic on summaries

This appears in:
	•	range sum query 2D
	•	many optimization/counting problems
	•	image/block computations

11. Binary matrix universe

Binary matrices are especially common.

Cells are often:
	•	land/water
	•	1/0
	•	obstacle/free
	•	valid/invalid
	•	occupied/empty

This enables several important transformations.

A. Binary matrix -> connected components

For islands and flood fill.

B. Binary matrix -> shortest path graph

For pathfinding.

C. Binary matrix -> histogram rows

For maximal rectangle.

D. Binary matrix -> square-growth DP

For maximal square.

So binary matrices are often a bridge between:
	•	geometry
	•	graph
	•	DP
	•	histogram logic

12. Matrix -> histogram conversion

A very important advanced pattern.

For each row, compute heights of consecutive 1s above it.

Example:
if current cell is 1:
	•	height[c] += 1
else:
	•	height[c] = 0

Then each row becomes a histogram.

This is used in:
	•	maximal rectangle

This is a major representation conversion:
	•	matrix -> row-wise histograms -> monotonic stack problem

13. Matrix rotation and symmetry

Common operations:
	•	transpose
	•	horizontal reverse
	•	vertical reverse
	•	rotate 90°
	•	rotate 180°
	•	diagonal reflection

These are really coordinate transforms.

For an n x n matrix, many rotation problems are about mapping:
	•	(r,c) to (c, n-1-r) or similar transforms

So matrix geometry questions are often secretly coordinate mapping questions.

14. Matrix boundary / ring representation

Used in:
	•	spiral matrix
	•	border traversal
	•	layer peeling
	•	ring rotations

A matrix can be viewed as nested rectangular shells.

outer ring
 inner ring
  inner ring

This is useful whenever processing goes layer by layer.

15. Matrix invariants

For matrix problems, invariants often look like this:

Traversal invariants
	•	all cells before current row are finalized
	•	current BFS queue is exactly the frontier
	•	visited cells won’t be revisited

DP invariants
	•	dependencies of current cell are already solved
	•	dp[r][c] means exact answer for its defined subproblem

Geometry invariants
	•	boundary pointers enclose the remaining unprocessed region
	•	rotated segments preserve previously fixed regions

Constraint invariants
	•	no duplicate in row/col/box so far
	•	placed cells satisfy all local rules

Understanding matrix problems often means stating the right invariant.

16. Matrix operations taxonomy

These are the major operation families on matrices.

Access operations
	•	read cell
	•	read neighbors
	•	read row/column
	•	read rectangle summary

Update operations
	•	write cell
	•	mark visited
	•	accumulate DP value
	•	reset state

Structural operations
	•	transpose
	•	reverse rows
	•	rotate
	•	flatten

Traversal operations
	•	row scan
	•	column scan
	•	diagonal scan
	•	BFS/DFS expansion

Region operations
	•	query rectangle
	•	expand square
	•	compare submatrix
	•	peel ring

Conversion operations
	•	flatten to 1D
	•	convert to graph
	•	convert to histogram
	•	convert to prefix table

