All type of logical view mapping in all leetcode question 


Yes — this is the right deep question.

“Logical view mapping” across LeetCode means:

how a problem is re-seen from one logical form into another logical form that is easier to reason about, optimize, or implement.

This is broader than data structure conversion.

It includes mappings like:
	•	pair problem -> complement problem
	•	substring problem -> active window problem
	•	recursion tree -> DP state graph
	•	connectivity problem -> component problem
	•	path problem -> graph traversal problem
	•	subset problem -> bitmask problem
	•	range query problem -> prefix-sum problem
	•	matrix problem -> graph problem
	•	merge problem -> order maintenance problem

So the right answer is a master atlas of logical view mappings.

⸻

1. What logical view mapping means

A problem has many views.

For example:

Surface view

“Find two numbers adding to target.”

Logical view 1

Pair-relation search.

Logical view 2

Complement lookup.

Logical view 3

Processed-prefix memory problem.

All three describe the same problem, but one is much easier to solve.

So logical view mapping is:

old view -> new view

with the goal of making:
	•	state smaller
	•	transitions clearer
	•	invariants simpler
	•	complexity lower

⸻

2. The universal mapping template

For any question, write:

Layer	Description
original view	how it first appears
mapped view	the more useful computational view
why mapping helps	what difficulty it removes
new state carrier	what memory/state now matters
new invariant	what becomes easy to maintain

This is the master framework.

⸻

3. The master families of logical view mapping

Across the LeetCode universe, most mappings fall into these families:
	1.	relation -> lookup
	2.	search space -> compressed state
	3.	range -> summary
	4.	sequence -> interval
	5.	interval -> boundary process
	6.	repeated recursion -> memo/DP
	7.	structure -> graph
	8.	graph -> component partition
	9.	set -> bitmask
	10.	unordered candidates -> ordered frontier
	11.	local decisions -> invariant-preserving process
	12.	topology -> pointer state
	13.	object behavior -> synchronized internal structures
	14.	geometric world -> coordinate transitions
	15.	string structure -> automaton / prefix structure
	16.	output problem -> predecessor reconstruction
	17.	raw data -> canonical key
	18.	many candidates -> undominated frontier
	19.	region problem -> event/prefix difference problem
	20.	tree recursion -> subtree summaries

Now the full atlas.

⸻

4. Relation -> lookup mapping

Core idea

Instead of searching directly for a relation between two or more objects, transform it into a lookup question.

Examples

Two Sum
	•	original: find pair (a,b) with a+b=target
	•	mapped: for current a, lookup target-a

Contains Duplicate
	•	original: check whether two equal values exist
	•	mapped: membership check in seen set

Isomorphic / bijection-style problems
	•	original: check relation consistency
	•	mapped: mapping lookup consistency

Why it helps

Turns repeated scanning into constant-time memory access.

⸻

5. Search space -> compressed state mapping

Core idea

The brute-force candidate universe is huge, but many candidates collapse into the same state.

Examples

Climbing Stairs
	•	original: all step sequences
	•	mapped: dp[i] = ways to reach i

Word Break
	•	original: all segmentations
	•	mapped: solve(i) or dp[i]

Edit Distance
	•	original: all edit scripts
	•	mapped: dp[i][j]

Why it helps

Exponential trees collapse into finite reusable states.

⸻

6. Range -> summary mapping

Core idea

Instead of recomputing over a range each time, represent the range by a summary.

Examples

Prefix sum
	•	original: sum over [l..r]
	•	mapped: prefix[r] - prefix[l-1]

2D prefix sum
	•	original: rectangle sum
	•	mapped: inclusion-exclusion over prefix surface

running extrema
	•	original: best over prefix
	•	mapped: scalar prefix summary

Why it helps

Range operations become O(1) or cheaper than rescanning.

⸻

7. Sequence -> interval mapping

Core idea

Instead of thinking of the data as only individual elements, think in terms of contiguous regions.

Examples

substrings/subarrays
	•	original: many candidate substrings
	•	mapped: interval (l, r)

palindromes
	•	original: string object
	•	mapped: interval validity / interval state

subarray optimization
	•	original: sequence optimization
	•	mapped: active or candidate interval

Why it helps

Makes windowing, interval DP, and range reasoning possible.

⸻

8. Interval -> boundary process mapping

Core idea

Instead of treating intervals as static, see them as moving boundaries.

Examples

Sliding window
	•	original: all valid substrings
	•	mapped: one live interval with moving L,R

Two pointers
	•	original: pair or range search
	•	mapped: shrink active boundaries

Binary search
	•	original: ordered search space
	•	mapped: low/high active interval

Why it helps

Transforms huge candidate enumeration into monotone shrink/expand process.

⸻

9. Repeated recursion -> memo / DP mapping

Core idea

A recursive expansion tree is actually a DAG of repeated states.

Examples

Fibonacci / stair problems
	•	recursion tree -> 1D DP

regex matching
	•	recursion tree -> dp[i][j]

interval recursion
	•	repeated range states -> interval DP

Why it helps

Avoids repeated work, makes dependencies explicit.

⸻

10. Structure -> graph mapping

Core idea

Many problems are really about states and transitions, which is a graph.

Examples

grid -> graph

cells become nodes, moves become edges

word ladder

words become nodes, one-letter transitions become edges

puzzles / locks

configurations become nodes, legal moves become edges

dependency systems

items become nodes, prerequisite links become edges

Why it helps

Unlocks BFS, DFS, topo sort, shortest-path logic.

⸻

11. Graph -> component partition mapping

Core idea

Sometimes you do not need the full graph, only which nodes belong together.

Examples

connectivity questions
	•	original: full graph exploration
	•	mapped: components / DSU representatives

account merge
	•	original: graph of linked accounts/emails
	•	mapped: equivalence classes

number of connected groups
	•	graph -> component counting

Why it helps

Compresses many paths into representative-based membership.

⸻

12. Set -> bitmask mapping

Core idea

A subset can be encoded as bits.

Examples

subset DP
	•	chosen items -> mask bits

visited-state BFS
	•	visited special nodes -> mask

assignment problems
	•	assigned workers/tasks -> mask

Why it helps

Compact storage, fast transitions, hashable states.

⸻

13. Unordered candidates -> ordered frontier mapping

Core idea

Not all candidates matter equally; re-view them as an ordered frontier.

Examples

Heap problems
	•	candidates -> priority queue

Dijkstra
	•	tentative states -> min-priority frontier

top-k
	•	collection -> keep best frontier only

Why it helps

Always process the most relevant candidate next.

⸻

14. Local decisions -> invariant-preserving process mapping

Core idea

Instead of “guessing greedily,” see the algorithm as preserving a strong invariant.

Examples

two pointers
	•	not “move random pointer”
	•	mapped: discard impossible region while preserving existence of optimum

sliding window
	•	not “just expand and shrink”
	•	mapped: maintain smallest/largest valid active region

monotonic stack
	•	not “store elements”
	•	mapped: preserve only unresolved undominated candidates

Why it helps

Turns heuristic-looking behavior into a correctness-driven system.

⸻

15. Topology -> pointer-state mapping

Core idea

For linked structures, the real state is not values but connectivity.

Examples

reverse linked list
	•	original: sequence reversal
	•	mapped: pointer rewiring process

merge lists
	•	original: sorted merge
	•	mapped: tail attachment and source pointer advancement

cycle problems
	•	original: detect revisit
	•	mapped: pointer-speed relation

Why it helps

Makes mutation visible and safe.

⸻

16. Object behavior -> synchronized internal structures mapping

Core idea

Design problems are best viewed not as individual method logic, but as maintaining agreement among internal representations.

Examples

LRU Cache
	•	mapped view: hashmap + doubly linked recency list must stay synchronized

LFU
	•	mapped view: frequency buckets + key metadata + min-frequency tracker

MinStack
	•	mapped view: value stack + minimum-summary stack

Why it helps

Design correctness becomes consistency between structures.

⸻

17. Geometric world -> coordinate-transition mapping

Core idea

Spatial problems can be seen as state transitions on coordinates.

Examples

spiral matrix
	•	mapped: shrinking boundaries

rotate image
	•	mapped: coordinate transform

robot simulation
	•	mapped: position + direction state machine

Why it helps

Makes movement rules algebraic or graph-like.

⸻

18. String structure -> automaton / prefix structure mapping

Core idea

Strings are often better seen as:
	•	token streams
	•	prefix structures
	•	parser states
	•	interval families

Examples

valid number / atoi
	•	string -> parser state machine

dictionary prefix problems
	•	string set -> trie

regex-like logic
	•	text/pattern -> state transition system or DP grid

anagrams
	•	string -> frequency signature

Why it helps

Avoids raw character-by-character ad hoc logic.

⸻

19. Output problem -> predecessor reconstruction mapping

Core idea

Sometimes computing the value is different from recovering the actual solution.

Examples

shortest path
	•	value phase: distances
	•	mapped reconstruction view: parent pointers

LCS
	•	value phase: length table
	•	reconstruction view: backtrack path through DP table

partition reconstruction
	•	value phase: cut feasibility/cost
	•	reconstruction view: predecessor cut choice

Why it helps

Separates optimization from answer recovery.

⸻

20. Raw data -> canonical key mapping

Core idea

Different raw objects can be transformed into the same canonical signature if they are equivalent for the problem.

Examples

group anagrams
	•	string -> sorted string or frequency vector

duplicate subtree
	•	subtree -> serialization key

normalize coordinate/set states
	•	raw arrangement -> canonical ordered tuple

Why it helps

Grouping/equality becomes key comparison.

⸻

21. Many candidates -> undominated frontier mapping

Core idea

A huge set of historical candidates can be reduced to only those that might still matter.

Examples

monotonic stack
	•	previous values -> unresolved monotone frontier

monotonic deque
	•	window candidates -> live undominated deque

convexity-like optimizations conceptually
	•	candidate set -> only promising frontier

Why it helps

Massively compresses history while preserving correctness.

⸻

22. Region problem -> event / difference representation mapping

Core idea

Instead of reasoning directly over whole intervals/regions, reason over changes at boundaries.

Examples

interval overlaps
	•	intervals -> start/end events

range updates
	•	interval add -> difference array boundary deltas

sweep line problems
	•	regions -> sorted event stream

Why it helps

Global region behavior becomes local event accumulation.

⸻

23. Tree recursion -> subtree summary mapping

Core idea

A subtree can be represented by a compact summary returned upward.

Examples

balanced tree
	•	subtree -> (balanced, height)

House Robber III
	•	subtree -> (take, skip)

max path sum
	•	subtree -> downward gain + global best update

Why it helps

Avoids carrying full subtree details upward.

⸻

24. Matrix / grid -> other logical views

Matrices are especially rich.

Matrix -> graph

for BFS/DFS/pathfinding

Matrix -> DP surface

for min path / unique paths / edit-like 2D states

Matrix -> histogram

for maximal rectangle

Matrix -> prefix-sum surface

for rectangle queries

Matrix -> coordinate transform system

for rotation / symmetry

So matrix questions often require choosing the correct mapped view first.

⸻

25. Tree / BST -> sorted order mapping

Examples

BST -> inorder sorted sequence

Used for:
	•	kth smallest
	•	validate BST reasoning
	•	closest values

sorted array -> balanced BST

Used for construction questions.

This is a deep bridge between hierarchical view and ordered sequence view.

⸻

26. Grid / coordinate -> flat id mapping

Core idea

A 2D object can be mapped into 1D ids.

Formula
	•	id = r * cols + c

Used for
	•	DSU on grid
	•	visited arrays
	•	graph nodes
	•	compact storage

Why it helps

Unifies coordinate logic with standard 1D structures.

⸻

27. Tuple state -> hashable key mapping

Core idea

Complex state can be re-viewed as a single key for memoization/caching.

Examples
	•	(i, j) -> DP key
	•	(node, mask) -> memo key
	•	(r, c, k) -> visited/memo key
	•	tuple -> packed integer or string key

Why it helps

Lets associative memory handle complex states.

⸻

28. Collection -> partition-by-key mapping

Core idea

A list of objects can be re-viewed as groups under a shared key.

Examples

group anagrams
	•	strings -> signature buckets

logs/intervals/items
	•	objects -> grouped by property

Why it helps

Turns pairwise grouping into one-pass bucketing.

⸻

29. Candidate enumeration -> recurrence mapping

Core idea

Instead of enumerating raw candidates directly, define a recurrence that implicitly covers them.

Examples

coin change
	•	all coin sequences -> recurrence on remaining amount

partition problems
	•	all cuts -> recurrence on suffix position

stock DP
	•	all action sequences -> state machine recurrence

Why it helps

Enumeration becomes systematic state transition.

⸻

30. Problem -> optimization surface mapping

Core idea

Some problems are better seen as maximizing or minimizing over a structured state space.

Examples

max subarray
	•	array -> best ending-at-i surface

stock
	•	sequence -> profit state machine

edit distance
	•	string pair -> edit-cost surface

Why it helps

The objective becomes attached to states, not raw candidate lists.

⸻

