Step count,units left,cost, etc …all indepth

Yes — this is the measurement layer of problem solving.

You are asking about things like:
	•	step count
	•	units left
	•	cost
	•	work done
	•	work remaining
	•	state count
	•	frontier size
	•	search-space size
	•	memory delta count
	•	transition count
	•	operation count

This is the layer that turns an algorithm from “idea” into a tracked process.

⸻

1. The master idea

For any LeetCode problem, you can track execution with a measurement model:


Continue 

Metric Layer	Meaning
step count	how many logical steps have executed
unit count	how many units exist total
units left	how many remain unresolved/unvisited/unsolved
work done	how much of problem space is already processed
cost per step	expense of one step
cumulative cost	total expense so far
frontier size	how many active future candidates exist
state count	how many states have been created/solved
transition count	how many moves/relaxations/branches were considered
memory footprint	how much live memory is currently being used
answer progress	how close current state is to final answer

This is the quantitative tracking system.

⸻

2. The 4 master measurement questions

For any problem, ask:

1. What is the unit?

Could be:
	•	element
	•	pair
	•	interval
	•	DP state
	•	graph node
	•	edge
	•	recursive call
	•	branch
	•	window move
	•	heap pop
	•	API call

2. What counts as one step?

A step may be:
	•	one loop body
	•	one BFS pop
	•	one DFS entry
	•	one DP fill
	•	one choose/undo cycle
	•	one relax check
	•	one pointer rewrite

3. What is the cost model?

Could be:
	•	O(1) per step
	•	O(log n) per step
	•	amortized O(1)
	•	number of generated states
	•	number of transitions checked

4. What remains?

Could be:
	•	unprocessed suffix
	•	undiscovered nodes
	•	unsolved DP cells
	•	unvisited branches
	•	unpopped frontier items
	•	unresolved candidates

Those 4 questions define the measurement system.

⸻

3. Step count

Step count is the number of logical execution events.

But it depends on what you call a step.

3.1 Loop-step count

For scan problems:
	•	one iteration of the main loop

Example:
	•	Two Sum: one i
	•	Kadane: one element processed
	•	stock: one day processed

3.2 Frontier-step count

For BFS/heap:
	•	one pop
	•	or one layer

3.3 DP-step count
	•	one cell/state fill

3.4 Backtracking-step count

Could mean:
	•	one recursive entry
	•	one choose action
	•	one full choose/recurse/undo cycle

3.5 Micro-step count

At code-sync level:
	•	one sub-expression evaluation
	•	one branch decision
	•	one mutation

So always define the step granularity first.

⸻

4. Unit count

This is the size of the problem objects being reasoned over.

Examples:

Arrays
	•	units = elements
	•	total units = n

Graphs
	•	node units = V
	•	edge units = E

DP
	•	units = states/cells
	•	total units = size of DP state space

Backtracking
	•	units = partial states or full candidate leaves

Intervals
	•	units = interval states
	•	total count often O(n²)

Bitmask DP
	•	units = masks or (mask, extra_state) combinations

This is the “what exists in the space” metric.

⸻

5. Units left

This is one of the most useful thinking tools.

It means:

how much unresolved work remains in the chosen representation?

Examples:

Scan problems

Units left = remaining unprocessed suffix length

processed | current | left-to-process

BFS

Units left = undiscovered nodes + queued frontier

DP

Units left = unsolved states

Backtracking

Units left = unexplored branches from current node + future subtrees

Sliding window

Units left is subtle:
	•	unprocessed right expansions
	•	plus possible left shrinks needed to restore validity

Linked list

Units left = unreversed/unmerged/unprocessed suffix

This is the “distance to done” metric.

⸻

6. Cost

Cost is the expense of processing.

There are multiple cost layers.

6.1 Unit cost

Cost of one primitive operation.

Examples:
	•	compare two ints
	•	increment count
	•	lookup in map
	•	push/pop from stack

6.2 Step cost

Cost of one logical step.

Examples:
	•	one BFS pop + neighbor loop
	•	one DP cell fill
	•	one window expand with some shrinks
	•	one heap pop + pushes

6.3 Total cost

Sum over all steps.

6.4 Worst-case cost

Maximum possible total cost for input size n.

6.5 Amortized cost

Average cost per operation over a whole sequence.

Examples:
	•	monotonic stack
	•	sliding window
	•	dynamic array push_back

6.6 Opportunity cost / discarded work

What work is avoided by the chosen representation.

Example:
	•	complement lookup avoids pair rescanning
	•	prefix sum avoids range rescanning
	•	memo avoids repeated recursion

⸻

7. Work done vs work left

A powerful decomposition:

Metric	Meaning
work done	already processed/resolved/summarized
work left	not yet processed/resolved
active work	currently in frontier / current branch / current interval

This gives a 3-zone model.

Example: BFS
	•	work done = visited and fully expanded nodes
	•	active work = queue frontier
	•	work left = undiscovered nodes

Example: DP
	•	work done = solved cells
	•	active work = current fill frontier
	•	work left = unsolved cells

Example: window
	•	work done = prefix before L
	•	active work = current [L..R]
	•	work left = suffix after R

This is a very strong analysis lens.

⸻

8. Frontier size

Frontier size matters in many patterns.

What is a frontier?

The set of active candidates that may be processed next.

Examples:
	•	queue in BFS
	•	stack in DFS simulation
	•	heap in Dijkstra/top-k
	•	deque in monotonic window
	•	recursion call stack
	•	current branch set in backtracking

Why it matters

It tells you:
	•	active memory pressure
	•	how many futures are alive
	•	branching intensity
	•	sometimes time-per-phase behavior

Typical frontier metrics
	•	current frontier size
	•	max frontier size
	•	average frontier size
	•	frontier growth/decay rhythm

⸻

9. State count

This is central in DP and graph/state problems.

Meaning

How many distinct states exist or are actually visited.

Examples:

1D DP
	•	n states

2D DP
	•	n*m states

interval DP
	•	n(n+1)/2 intervals

bitmask DP
	•	2^n masks
	•	maybe n * 2^n paired states

BFS on state graph
	•	number of discovered states

memo recursion
	•	number of cache entries filled

State count often directly gives time complexity.

⸻

10. Transition count

A state is not enough; how many transitions are considered from states?

Examples

Graph
	•	transitions = edges explored

DP
	•	transitions = recurrence candidates tried

interval DP
	•	transitions = split points checked

backtracking
	•	transitions = branch choices attempted

sliding window
	•	transitions = expand/shrink events

parser
	•	transitions = token-state moves

Often:
	•	total time = state count × transitions per state

⸻

11. Branching factor

Important in recursion/backtracking/search.

Meaning

How many next choices can arise from a state.

Examples:
	•	subsets: branching factor ≈ 2
	•	permutations: branching factor decreases from n down to 1
	•	Sudoku: cell-dependent branching
	•	graph BFS/DFS: degree-based branching

Why it matters

It controls:
	•	search tree width
	•	explosion risk
	•	pruning value

⸻

12. Depth / levels left

Important in recursion, BFS, interval decomposition, and decision trees.

Examples

recursion
	•	depth left to base case

BFS
	•	layers left until target maybe reached

interval recursion
	•	interval length left

subsets
	•	elements left to decide

This is another version of “units left,” but along hierarchical depth.

⸻

13. Search-space size

This is the brute-force universe.

Examples:

All pairs
	•	O(n²)

All substrings
	•	O(n²)

All subsets
	•	2^n

All permutations
	•	n!

All interval states
	•	O(n²)

All paths in graph

Potentially exponential or huge

This metric is important because optimization often means:

keep the same answer space, but avoid enumerating all of it explicitly

⸻

14. Solved-state count

Particularly useful in DP/memo and weighted graph algorithms.

Meaning

How many states are finalized, not just discovered.

Examples:

DP

A written cell is solved.

memo

A cached state is solved.

Dijkstra

A finalized node has permanent shortest distance.

tree DP

A node after child combination is solved.

This is stronger than visited count.

⸻

15. Active memory count

This measures how much live memory is currently needed.

Examples:

Sliding window
	•	frequency map size
	•	current window length

BFS
	•	queue size + visited size

DFS recursion
	•	recursion depth

heap
	•	heap size

backtracking
	•	path length + used markers + recursion depth

DP
	•	full table size or rolling rows only

This tells you not just asymptotic space, but live space profile.

⸻

16. Delta count

This is very useful for trace-heavy reasoning.

Meaning

How many meaningful changes happened.

Examples:
	•	number of map inserts
	•	number of stack pops
	•	number of window shrinks
	•	number of DP writes
	•	number of edge relaxations
	•	number of branch prunes

This often reveals hidden amortization.

⸻

17. Amortized view

Many LeetCode patterns require “global count,” not per-step naive count.

Sliding window

Right pointer moves n times
Left pointer moves at most n times
So total boundary moves = O(n)

Monotonic stack

Each element:
	•	pushed once
	•	popped once
Total stack ops = O(n)

Dynamic arrays

Push may occasionally cost more, but average is constant

So always ask:

does a step seem expensive locally, but globally each unit can only pay that cost a small number of times?

⸻

18. Cost models by major LeetCode family

Linear scan
	•	units = elements
	•	steps = n
	•	cost/step = O(1)
	•	units left = suffix length

Hash map
	•	units = elements
	•	steps = n
	•	lookup/update = O(1) average
	•	cost includes hash ops

Sliding window
	•	units = elements
	•	steps = expand + shrink events
	•	total pointer moves = O(n)
	•	units left = suffix + pending shrink work

Two pointers
	•	units = positions
	•	steps = pointer moves
	•	total moves often O(n)
	•	discarded region grows monotonically

Monotonic stack/deque
	•	units = elements
	•	each pushed once, popped once
	•	total ops O(n)

BFS
	•	units = nodes
	•	transitions = edges
	•	steps = queue pops
	•	cost = O(V+E)

DFS
	•	units = nodes
	•	transitions = edges
	•	cost = O(V+E) or state-graph equivalent

DP
	•	units = states
	•	cost = transitions per state
	•	total = number of states × average transition count

Backtracking
	•	units = search-tree nodes
	•	cost = branching factor × depth structure
	•	pruning reduces realized node count

Heap-based
	•	units = pops/pushes
	•	per step = O(log frontier)
	•	total depends on number of pushes/pops

DSU
	•	units = find/union ops
	•	amortized near constant

Linked list
	•	units = nodes
	•	steps = pointer rewires / traversals
	•	cost often O(n)

⸻

19. Best measurement table

For almost any problem, this works:

Step	Active Unit	Step Cost	Work Done	Units Left	Frontier Size	State Count	Answer Progress


And for DP/search-heavy problems, use:

State	Transition Count	Cost per Transition	Total Cost So Far	Solved States	Unsolved States


And for backtracking:

Depth	Branching Factor	Choices Tried	Choices Left	Pruned?	Active Path Length



⸻

20. Universal measurement sentence

At any point, describe the algorithm like this:

We have completed ___ steps, processed ___ of ___ units, have ___ units left, the active frontier is size ___, this step costs ___, total cost so far is ___, and the invariant still says ___.

That is the strongest “process tracking” sentence.

⸻

21. Example: Two Sum

Metrics
	•	unit = array element
	•	step = one loop iteration
	•	total units = n
	•	units left at step i = n - i - 1
	•	cost per step = one lookup + maybe one insert
	•	total cost = O(n) average
	•	frontier size = map size = processed prefix size
	•	answer progress = not found -> found

Table

Step	i	Processed Units	Units Left	Map Size	Step Cost	Total Cost So Far
0	0	1	n-1	1	lookup + insert	O(1)
1	1	2	n-2	2	lookup + maybe return	O(2)


⸻

22. Example: Sliding Window

Metrics
	•	unit = element entering/leaving window
	•	expand count ≤ n
	•	shrink count ≤ n
	•	total pointer moves ≤ 2n
	•	frontier = current window
	•	units left = suffix not yet expanded

This is why sliding window is linear.

⸻

23. Example: DP

For dp[i][j] style:
	•	unit = one state
	•	total units = n*m
	•	units left = unsolved cells
	•	cost/state = recurrence transition count
	•	total cost = states × transition cost

Interval DP:
	•	units = intervals = n(n+1)/2
	•	transitions = split points per interval

⸻

24. Example: Backtracking

For permutations of size n:
	•	unit = search-tree node or recursive frame
	•	units left = unresolved suffix choices
	•	branching factor = remaining unused items
	•	active frontier = recursion stack depth
	•	cost = node visits + legality checks
	•	pruning lowers realized node count

⸻

25. The deepest compressed model

All LeetCode execution can be measured with:

Total Work
= (# units processed)
× (cost per unit)
× (transitions checked per unit)
+ overhead of state maintenance

And progress can be tracked as:

Progress = work done / total work

with:
	•	total work exact in DP/state problems
	•	approximate in search problems
	•	amortized in frontier/stack/window problems

⸻

26. Final compressed summary

The core measurement concepts are:
	•	step count
	•	unit count
	•	units left
	•	work done
	•	work left
	•	active frontier size
	•	state count
	•	solved-state count
	•	transition count
	•	branching factor
	•	depth left
	•	cost per step
	•	cumulative cost
	•	amortized cost
	•	live memory count
	•	delta count
	•	answer progress

And the right way to analyze any LeetCode problem is:
	1.	define the unit
	2.	define the step
	3.	define the cost per step
	4.	define the units left
	5.	define the frontier/state growth
	6.	define the invariant
	7.	compute total cost using the right model

That is the full deep framework for step count, units left, cost, and related measurements across the LeetCode universe.




All about representation and its types

Representation is the core of problem solving.

A lot of LeetCode, algorithms, and even programming itself is really about this:

take something in one form, and express it in another form that is easier to store, reason about, compare, traverse, optimize, or prove.

So “all about representation and its types” should be organized as a full framework.

1. What representation means

Representation is:

how an object, state, relation, process, or problem is expressed so it can be understood or manipulated.

The same thing can have many representations.

Example:
A subset can be represented as:
	•	a list of elements
	•	a boolean array
	•	a set
	•	a bitmask
	•	a recursion path
	•	a sorted tuple key

All represent the same logical object, but each changes:
	•	what is easy
	•	what is hard
	•	what is visible
	•	what can be optimized

2. The master law of representation

Every representation answers 4 questions:

Question	Meaning
what is being represented?	object / state / relation / process / answer
what medium is used?	array / graph / map / bits / tree / formula / table
what is the encoding rule?	how parts of the original map into the representation
what operations become easy?	lookup, update, merge, compare, traverse, optimize

That is the universal template.

3. The major domains of representation

Representation appears in many domains.

A. Object representation

How a thing is stored or modeled.

Examples:
	•	array
	•	tree
	•	graph
	•	string
	•	linked list
	•	matrix

B. State representation

How the current algorithm state is captured.

Examples:
	•	(i, j)
	•	current window [L, R]
	•	dist[node]
	•	mask
	•	dp[i][j]

C. Relation representation

How relationships between things are modeled.

Examples:
	•	edges in graph
	•	parent array
	•	value -> index map
	•	interval overlap events

D. Process representation

How evolution over time is represented.

Examples:
	•	queue frontier
	•	recursion stack
	•	event timeline
	•	state machine

E. Answer representation

How the final solution is expressed.

Examples:
	•	scalar
	•	list of pairs
	•	path
	•	tree
	•	reconstructed sequence
	•	boolean

4. The core types of representation

Now the main taxonomy.

5. Physical representation

This is how something exists in memory or storage.

Examples:
	•	array in contiguous memory
	•	linked list as nodes with pointers
	•	tree as parent/child pointers
	•	heap as array
	•	graph as adjacency list

This is the lowest level.

It answers:
	•	where is it?
	•	how is it laid out?

6. Logical representation

This is the abstract structure of the thing.

Examples:
	•	sequence
	•	hierarchy
	•	graph of relations
	•	set of elements
	•	interval
	•	subset
	•	partition
	•	frontier
	•	state graph

Logical representation is often more important than physical representation in algorithm design.

Example:
A matrix can logically be:
	•	a grid
	•	a graph
	•	a DP table
	•	an image
	•	a cost surface

Same physical object, different logical representation.

7. Semantic representation

This is what the structure means in the current problem.

Examples:
	•	hash map as “seen prefix summary”
	•	queue as “BFS frontier”
	•	stack as “unresolved candidates”
	•	parent array as “component representative system”
	•	bitmask as “visited-set encoding”

This is crucial.

A data structure is not enough by itself.
Its semantic role matters more.

8. Operational representation

This is representation viewed through supported operations.

Examples:
	•	array: O(1) index access
	•	hash map: O(1) average lookup
	•	heap: best candidate extraction
	•	DSU: merge/find equivalence classes
	•	prefix sum: O(1) range query after preprocessing

This is the performance view of representation.

9. Structural representation

This focuses on shape.

Examples:
	•	linear sequence
	•	tree
	•	DAG
	•	cyclic graph
	•	grid
	•	ring/layer
	•	partition into groups
	•	interval family
	•	nested structure

This is common in algorithm visualization.

10. State-space representation

This is one of the deepest types.

It represents the problem as a space of states.

Examples:
	•	state = index i
	•	state = (i, j)
	•	state = (node, mask)
	•	state = (r, c, k)
	•	state = current window
	•	state = current parser mode

This is the key representation behind:
	•	DP
	•	BFS over implicit states
	•	memoization
	•	automata
	•	puzzles

11. Search-space representation

This represents the full brute-force candidate universe.

Examples:
	•	all pairs
	•	all substrings
	•	all subsets
	•	all paths
	•	all partitions
	•	all permutations
	•	all intervals

Optimization often comes from mapping:
	•	search-space representation
into
	•	compressed state representation

12. Summary representation

This is when a big region/history/object is replaced by a smaller summary.

Examples:
	•	prefix sums
	•	subtree return values
	•	running max
	•	rolling hash
	•	frequency map
	•	DP table cell
	•	component representative

Summary representation is central to efficient algorithms.

13. Encoded representation

This is when something is compactly encoded in another form.

Examples:
	•	subset -> bitmask
	•	coordinates -> flattened id
	•	tuple -> hash key
	•	tree -> serialized string
	•	interval updates -> difference array boundaries

Encoding is often used for:
	•	compactness
	•	hashing
	•	memoization
	•	fast operations

14. Canonical representation

This is a normalized form where equivalent things become identical.

Examples:
	•	sorted string for anagrams
	•	normalized interval ordering
	•	subtree serialization
	•	ordered tuple for state key
	•	reduced rational form conceptually

Canonical forms are used for:
	•	grouping
	•	deduplication
	•	equality testing
	•	caching

15. Derived representation

This is built from the original to enable easier queries.

Examples:
	•	prefix sums from array
	•	2D prefix sums from matrix
	•	height histogram from binary matrix
	•	indegree array from graph
	•	parent pointers from traversal
	•	sparse table/segment tree from sequence

This is preprocessing-based representation.

16. Implicit representation

Sometimes the full object is not stored explicitly.

Examples:
	•	implicit graph in Word Ladder or lock problem
	•	heap tree shape implied by array indices
	•	search tree implied by recursion choices
	•	state graph implied by transition rules

Implicit representation is huge in LeetCode.

17. Explicit representation

Everything is stored directly.

Examples:
	•	adjacency list
	•	full DP table
	•	full queue contents
	•	explicit list of intervals
	•	full tree nodes

This is simpler but sometimes heavier.

18. Static representation

Does not change while solving.

Examples:
	•	input array
	•	sorted input
	•	immutable graph structure
	•	fixed constraints table

19. Dynamic representation

Evolves during execution.

Examples:
	•	queue frontier
	•	visited set
	•	current window
	•	stack
	•	heap
	•	DP fill region
	•	linked-list topology after rewiring

Most problem solving happens through dynamic representation change.

20. Local representation

Captures only a small part of the problem at a time.

Examples:
	•	current index
	•	current node
	•	current interval
	•	current branch
	•	current cell

21. Global representation

Captures whole-problem structure.

Examples:
	•	full graph
	•	full DP table
	•	full prefix surface
	•	all components
	•	canonical grouping map

Good algorithms combine local and global views.

22. Exact representation

Preserves full relevant information.

Examples:
	•	storing all values
	•	storing full path
	•	storing exact DP answer in state
	•	explicit graph edges

23. Approximate / relaxed representation

Less common in standard LeetCode, but conceptually important.

Examples:
	•	keeping only best-so-far
	•	keeping only undominated frontier
	•	discarding impossible regions
	•	greedy compressed state

This is not “wrong”; it is selective representation justified by invariants.

24. Reversible representation

Can be converted back easily.

Examples:
	•	flattened id <-> (r,c)
	•	bitmask <-> subset
	•	parent pointers <-> recovered path
	•	inorder sorted array <-> BST construction directionally

25. Irreversible / lossy representation

Loses some information.

Examples:
	•	frequency map loses original order
	•	set loses duplicates
	•	sorted order loses original indices unless stored
	•	subtree summary loses full subtree shape

Lossy representations are often useful, but you must know what was lost.

26. Representation by major object families

27. Sequence representations

A sequence can be represented as:
	•	array
	•	linked list
	•	deque
	•	stack/queue in restricted access view
	•	prefix summary
	•	interval family
	•	monotone frontier
	•	sorted sequence
	•	circular sequence

28. Set representations

A set can be represented as:
	•	hash set
	•	tree set
	•	boolean array
	•	bitmask
	•	sorted vector
	•	DSU component class
	•	canonical key collection

29. Graph representations

A graph can be represented as:
	•	adjacency list
	•	adjacency matrix
	•	edge list
	•	parent tree after traversal
	•	DSU components for connectivity
	•	implicit transition rules

30. Tree representations

A tree can be represented as:
	•	node pointers
	•	parent array
	•	adjacency list
	•	level-order array with nulls
	•	complete-tree array
	•	subtree summaries
	•	Euler tour / inorder style sequence views conceptually

31. Matrix representations

A matrix can be represented as:
	•	2D array
	•	flattened array
	•	grid graph
	•	DP table
	•	image
	•	cost surface
	•	binary mask
	•	prefix-sum surface
	•	row histograms

32. String representations

A string can be represented as:
	•	char sequence
	•	frequency vector
	•	trie path
	•	parser token stream
	•	automaton input
	•	suffix/prefix family
	•	interval family

33. Subset representations

A subset can be represented as:
	•	explicit list
	•	boolean vector
	•	bitmask
	•	recursion choice path
	•	sorted tuple key

34. Interval representations

An interval can be represented as:
	•	pair (l, r)
	•	active window boundaries
	•	event endpoints
	•	difference array updates
	•	interval DP state
	•	merged interval family

35. Problem-to-representation mappings

This is the most important layer for algorithms.

Many problems become easy only after changing representation.

Pair problem -> lookup problem

Two Sum

Range problem -> prefix summary problem

Prefix sums

Recursion tree -> DP state table

Memoization / tabulation

Grid -> graph

BFS / DFS on matrix

Connectivity -> component representatives

DSU

Subset -> bitmask

Subset DP

Region updates -> boundary deltas

Difference arrays

Binary matrix -> histogram

Maximal rectangle

Tree details -> subtree summary

Tree DP

Output recovery -> predecessor chain

Path reconstruction

36. Representation and invariants

Every good representation has a meaning that must stay true.

Examples:
	•	dp[i][j] = exact answer for state (i,j)
	•	queue = current BFS frontier
	•	map = processed prefix summary
	•	window = current valid/repairable interval
	•	stack = unresolved monotone candidates
	•	parent[root] = representative of component

Representation without invariant is just storage.
Representation plus invariant is algorithm state.

37. Representation and cost

Changing representation changes what is cheap.

Examples:
	•	array -> O(1) index
	•	hash map -> O(1) average membership
	•	heap -> O(log n) best extraction
	•	prefix sum -> O(1) range sum after preprocessing
	•	bitmask -> O(1) set ops on small universes
	•	DSU -> near-constant merge/find

This is why representation choice is often the algorithm.

38. Representation tradeoffs

Every representation helps something and hurts something.

Examples:

Sorted array

helps:
	•	binary search
hurts:
	•	original order unless stored separately

Frequency map

helps:
	•	multiplicity comparisons
hurts:
	•	original sequence order

Bitmask

helps:
	•	compact subset ops
hurts:
	•	hard to interpret manually for large universes

Linked list

helps:
	•	rewiring
hurts:
	•	random access

DP table

helps:
	•	reuse subproblems
hurts:
	•	memory if too large

Tradeoff awareness is essential.

39. The universal representation stack

For any question, you can analyze representation like this:

Layer	Ask
surface representation	how is the problem phrased?
logical representation	what abstract object is it really?
brute-force representation	what does naive search enumerate?
compressed state representation	what smaller state is enough?
memory representation	what stores that state?
semantic representation	what does that memory mean?
invariant representation	what must stay true?
output representation	how is the answer expressed/recovered?

This is the full stack.

