Like linked representation

Yes — linked representation is one major type of representation.

You’re pointing to a category like:
	•	linked representation
	•	array representation
	•	indexed representation
	•	hierarchical representation
	•	graph representation
	•	bitmap representation
	•	table representation

So let’s do this properly.

1. What linked representation means

A linked representation means:

objects are represented by connections/references/links between units, instead of only by physical position.

So the important thing is not “where it sits in memory,” but:
	•	what it points to
	•	what comes next
	•	what is connected to what

That is why linked representation is fundamentally about topology.

⸻

2. Core idea

Compare:

Array representation

Order comes from index position

Index:  0   1   2   3
Value: [A] [B] [C] [D]

Linked representation

Order comes from links

[A] -> [B] -> [C] -> [D] -> null

In arrays:
	•	order = physical/index order

In linked representation:
	•	order = traversal through links

That is the deepest distinction.

⸻

3. Main properties of linked representation

1. Connectivity defines structure

Not index.

2. Local rewiring is powerful

You can change structure by changing a few links.

3. Random access is weak

To reach the 10th element, you may need to traverse through earlier links.

4. Shape is flexible

Can represent:
	•	chain
	•	tree
	•	graph
	•	cycles
	•	skip structures
	•	multiple relations

5. Semantic meaning often lives in links

Example:
	•	parent-child
	•	next node
	•	random pointer
	•	neighbor relation

⸻

4. Types of linked representation

Now the important taxonomy.

⸻

A. Singly linked representation

Each node points to the next node.

[node] -> [node] -> [node] -> null

Node shape

struct ListNode {
  int val;
  ListNode* next;
};

Meaning

A sequence represented by single forward connectivity.

Used in LeetCode for
	•	reverse linked list
	•	merge two sorted lists
	•	remove nth node
	•	cycle detection
	•	add two numbers

⸻

B. Doubly linked representation

Each node points:
	•	forward
	•	backward

null <- [A] <-> [B] <-> [C] -> null

Node shape

struct Node {
  int val;
  Node* prev;
  Node* next;
};

Meaning

Bidirectional linked sequence.

Advantages
	•	move both ways
	•	delete node in O(1) if node given
	•	useful for recency ordering

Used in LeetCode for
	•	LRU Cache
	•	Browser History
	•	design questions

⸻

C. Circular linked representation

Last node links back to first or another earlier node.

[A] -> [B] -> [C]
 ^             |
 |-------------|

Meaning

No natural null end.

Used for
	•	circular queue/list concepts
	•	Josephus-style logic
	•	cycle problems

⸻

D. Multi-linked representation

A node has multiple link fields.

Examples:
	•	left, right
	•	next, random
	•	prev, next, child

Figure

[node]
  | next
  v
[node]

[node] --random--> [other node]

Used for
	•	copy list with random pointer
	•	multilevel doubly linked list
	•	trees
	•	graph-like custom objects

⸻

E. Tree-linked representation

Nodes linked hierarchically.

        [root]
        /    \
     [L]    [R]

Node shape

struct TreeNode {
  int val;
  TreeNode* left;
  TreeNode* right;
};

Meaning

Hierarchy via links.

This is also a linked representation

Because structure comes from pointers, not indices.

⸻

F. Graph-linked representation

Nodes linked to many neighbors.

[A] --> [B]
 | \      |
 v  \     v
[C] --> [D]

Meaning

Arbitrary relation network.

Usually implemented as:
	•	adjacency list
	•	neighbor vectors
	•	node pointers

This is also a generalized linked representation.

⸻

G. Indexed-linked representation

Very important.

Instead of pointers, links are stored as indices.

Example

value: [10, 20, 30]
next : [ 1,  2, -1]
head = 0

This means:
	•	node 0 points to node 1
	•	node 1 points to node 2
	•	node 2 ends

Meaning

Still linked logically, but stored in arrays.

This is a huge bridge between:
	•	linked representation
	•	array representation

⸻

5. Linked representation vs array representation

Aspect	Array representation	Linked representation
order comes from	index	link
access by position	fast	slow
insertion/deletion in middle	costly unless shifting tolerated	link rewiring can be cheap
memory layout	contiguous	scattered or logically linked
traversal	index arithmetic	pointer following
best mental model	storage by slots	storage by connectivity

This comparison is fundamental.

⸻

6. Linked representation in LeetCode

Linked representation appears far beyond “linked list” questions.

Directly
	•	reverse linked list
	•	merge linked list
	•	remove node
	•	reorder list
	•	copy random list

As trees
	•	all binary tree questions
	•	BST problems
	•	subtree problems

As graphs
	•	node-neighbor models
	•	graph cloning
	•	traversal with explicit nodes

As design structures
	•	LRU uses doubly linked representation
	•	LFU often uses doubly linked lists inside buckets

So linked representation is a huge family, not one topic.

⸻

7. What linked representation is good at

1. Dynamic structural changes

Changing shape by updating links.

2. Stable local editing

Insert/remove near known node.

3. Natural recursive structures

Trees and graphs fit linked representation naturally.

4. Semantic relationships

Links can mean:
	•	sequence
	•	child
	•	parent
	•	random reference
	•	neighbor
	•	dependency

⸻

8. What linked representation is bad at

1. Random access

No cheap node[i] style access unless indexed wrapper exists.

2. Cache locality

Nodes may be scattered.

3. Simpler bulk operations

Sorting/searching by direct index is less natural.

4. Debugging topology bugs

Wrong links can:
	•	lose nodes
	•	create cycles
	•	break chains

⸻

9. Representation conversions involving linked representation

This is one of the deepest parts.

⸻

A. Linked list -> array

