10. The deep types of “link”

A link can mean many different things.

Link type	Meaning
next link	sequence continuation
prev link	reverse sequence navigation
child link	hierarchy descent
parent link	upward navigation
neighbor link	graph adjacency
random link	arbitrary cross-reference
representative link	DSU parent/root chain
skip link	jump shortcut
threaded link	traversal shortcut

This is very important:
linked representation is not only next.

⸻

11. Linked representation as topology

This is the deepest mental model.

A linked structure is really a topology:
	•	which objects are reachable from which
	•	in what order
	•	through what field names
	•	whether cycles exist
	•	whether null ends exist
	•	whether multiple routes exist

So for linked representation, always ask:
	1.	what are the nodes?
	2.	what are the links?
	3.	what does each link type mean?
	4.	what shape do the links create?
	5.	what invariants must the topology satisfy?

⸻

12. Topology invariants in linked representation

Examples:

Singly linked list
	•	each node has at most one next
	•	chain ends in null
	•	no accidental cycle unless intended

Doubly linked list
	•	node->next->prev == node
	•	node->prev->next == node
	•	head prev = null
	•	tail next = null

Tree
	•	children belong to correct parent relation
	•	no invalid cycles
	•	subtree boundaries respected

Graph clone
	•	cloned links preserve original adjacency semantics

These are representation invariants.

⸻

13. Linked representation tracing

When working with linked representation, the best trace is not value-only.

You should trace:

Step	Pointer/Node	Link Before	Operation	Link After	Meaning


Example for reverse list:

Before:
prev = null
curr = A
A -> B -> C

Rewrite:
A.next = prev

After:
A -> null
curr = B

This is how linked representation should be tracked.

