3. Input-output meaning

Input meaning

The input is not just an array.

It is:

an ordered sequence of values
+
a target relation to satisfy

Output meaning

The output is not the values.

It is:

the original positions of the two values

So the problem is:

value relation
→ position output

That is very important.

⸻

4. Original logical representation

The raw logical view is:

Find a pair of indices (i, j)
such that nums[i] + nums[j] = target

This is a pair-relation problem.

⸻

5. Brute-force logical representation

The naive view is:

input
  ↓
all possible index pairs
  ↓
test each pair sum
  ↓
return matching pair

Search space:

(i, j) for all i < j

This is why brute force is O(n²).

⸻

6. Optimized logical representation

We transform the pair-relation problem into a lookup problem.

Core conversion

nums[i] + nums[j] = target

becomes

if current value is x,
needed value = target - x

So the mapped view is:

pair search
→ complement lookup

This is the main representation shift.

⸻

7. Best algorithmic pattern

The best pattern is:

one-pass hash map complement lookup

This means:
	•	scan left to right once
	•	for each value, ask whether its needed partner already appeared
	•	if yes, answer found
	•	if no, store current value

⸻

8. Memory representation

Use a hash map:

std::unordered_map<int, int> seen_index_by_value;

Meaning:

key   = value already seen
value = index where it was seen

So memory is representing:

processed prefix summarized as
value -> index


⸻

9. State representation

At any step i, state is:

State(i) =
(
  i,
  current_value = nums[i],
  needed_value = target - nums[i],
  seen_index_by_value
)

This is the live computational state.

⸻

10. Invariant representation

Before processing index i:

the hash map contains all values from indices [0 .. i-1]
mapped to valid earlier indices

So when you process nums[i]:
	•	if needed_value is in the map, answer exists now
	•	otherwise insert current value and continue

This is the central invariant.

